<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION DOUSE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Revolution's youth movement could be paying off.
They held off the Chicago Fire, 1-0, and finished the night tied
for first place in the Eastern Division with a lineup averaging 25
years old.
</P>
<P>
   They again used a set play, which is becoming their best
offensive weapon, to provide the difference as Wolde Harris headed
in a Mauricio Ramos corner kick in the 31st minute, then held off a
desperate Chicago attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution kept their composure and remained compact as they
protected the lead, in sharp contrast to last Wednesday, when they
squandered a two-goal advantage in a 4-3 loss to Colorado. They
also benefited by the absence of Hristo Stoitchkov, who made a
92d-minute unofficial appearance by running onto the field in his
warmup jacket and receving a caution from referee Kevin Stott, and
Lubos Kubik, who left with a left knee strain in the seventh
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we needed to do,'' Revolution coach Fernando
Clavijo said. ``We needed to minimize their space and minimize our
mistakes. We made four crucial mistakes against Colorado and they
cost us. If they score on a great play, fine, but we wanted to make
sure we didn't give away anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was solid. As the visiting team, the Revolution
absorbed pressure in an attempt to frustrate the home team. They
did so with a three-man back line of Brian Dunseth, 23, Joe
Franchino, 24, and Rusty Pierce, 20. Defensive midfielders Mike
Burns, 29, and Ivan McKinley, 30, who took the places of Leonel
Alvarez (left ankle sprain) and John Harkes (calf), held the Fire's
Peter Nowak in check.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago controlled the pace and kept possession for most of the
first half, but had two goals disallowed for offside, and Jeff
Causey made a solid save on a breakaway by Dema Kovalenko in the
20th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution scored against the run of play as Harris's
dribbling set up a loose ball in the penalty area, and he slammed a
shot off C.J. Brown, who was standing in the goal area. Ramos then
curled a corner kick to the near post, and Harris headed it past
Jesse Marsch, who appeared to step to his right, vacating the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost whoever was marking me just by running around,'' Harris
said. ``And I was wide open for the header.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played to the last second of the game and we were aware of
what was going on. After watching 2 1/2 hours of video of the last
game, we knew what to do when we took the lead. And with 15 minutes
left, we knew we had to kill the clock and kill the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we surprised ourselves because we knew we could
do this. We might have surprised some people but this shows the
depth of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good mix of youth and experience and we had
experienced players in the middle of the pitch. Mike Burns and Ivan
McKinley worked really hard to win the ball back and they stayed
pretty compact.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution again failed to play through midfield, but this
time Mauricio Ramos remained on the field until the final minutes.
And, though Ramos was seldom involved in the offense, he and
McKinley made some vital touches to keep possession in
counterattack. Imad Baba and Ted Chronopoulos neutralized the
Fire's outside threats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 0000EDT &QL; 
