<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLD WAR STILL RED HOT IN
 ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Commissar Hull:
</P>
<P>
   Excuse, please. I mean to say, of course, Governor Hull. I write
now to be telling you that I am pleased as borscht that in state of
Arizona the law still treats communists in a way to make late Sen.
Joseph McCarthy most proud.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a teacher I never met before is showing me loyalty
oath dat each person employed by gov ernment in Arizona must sign,
no matter if they are working for state or city or county or
schools or commissions or even Politburo. Ex cuse, please. I mean
to say, of course, governor's staff.
</P>
<P>
   This oath goes, ``I do solemnly swear that I will support the
Constitution of the United States and the Consti tution and laws of
the State of Arizona; that I will bear true faith and allegiance to
the same, and defend them against all enemies, foreign and domestic
. . .'' And so on.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher is telling me that she asks comrade bosses what law
this oath comes from and they say it is Arizona Revised Statutes
38-231.
</P>
<P>
   Is most bee-utiful law I'm seeing since Bolsheviks decided to
rewrite books in Russia back in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Paragraph E describes for workers what oath means and what
happens to them if oath they sign is violated.
</P>
<P>
   Person signing oath cannot ``commit or aid in the commission of
any act to overthrow by force or violence the government of this
state or any of its political subdivisions . . .''
</P>
<P>
   (Excuse, please, but this causes me wondering why Rep. Karen
Johnson from Mesa, who introduced bill to secede from union, has
not been arrested and banished. Or, is ``Mesa'' English translation
for ``Si beria''?)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here is best part.
</P>
<P>
   Law also says person violates oath if he or she ``knowingly
becomes or remains a member of the Communist Party of the United
States or its successors or any of its subordinate organizations .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Even better, law says violation is ``Class 4 felony'' and
``employee shall be deemed discharged.''
</P>
<P>
   This means it is still possible in this state to send Cossacks
and have political dissident dragged to gulag.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, teacher is telling me she has trouble signing oath. She
is saying it is difficult to sign when her job is teaching children
that, in America, free persons can join any political party they
choose. She says this is kind of oath communists force peo ple to
sign.
</P>
<P>
   She asks me if I tink she should sign. Being good American, I
say, ``Quit your Stalin and Trotsky over to boss' office and
sign.'' (Is leetle communist humor.)
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, I call Kremlin _ excuse, please, I mean state Capitol
_ to congratulate fearless leaders on keep ing witch hunt law on
books. Only, instead of responding to me with courage they give me
Chicken Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why bring this up?'' they ask. And, ``Nobody enforces it.''
And ``It's just holdover from a bygone era.''
</P>
<P>
   Law is on books, I remind them. Some people say it is
unnecessary. Some say it is evil. Some even ask what will be next
political party Arizona makes illegal? Democrats? (Or are they
outlawed already?)
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong, comrades. I'm no refusenik. I'm no Red. When
people call me ``pinko,'' is only because I am blushing with pride
to be livink in land of free, home of brave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
