<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS' PLAN WORKS _ SORT OF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some say the Portland Trail Blazers have 10
players who could start, and sometimes Saturday it seemed like all
10 of them were on the court together.
</P>
<P>
   How else to account for a triple-team on Shaquille O'Neal and a
simultaneous double-team on Kobe Bryant?
</P>
<P>
   The strategy produced mixed results for the Blazers. They held
down Bryant to just 13 points in Game 1 - his lowest output of the
postseason - but O'Neal still scored 41.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' role players used the extra breathing room to hit a
barrage of outside jumpers in the Lakers' 109-94 win.
</P>
<P>
   The double-teams on O'Neal are expected, but it's rare to see
teams smother Bryant the way the Blazers did, often using 6-11
Rasheed Wallace to crowd him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that they had to do that, because if they didn't, you
have Kobe down low on the block with (5-10) Damon Stoudamire on
him,'' said the Lakers' Brian Shaw. ``So when they were doubling,
Kobe was doing a good job of kicking the ball back out, finding the
shooters on the perimeter, and guys were knocking down the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bryant also collected six assists, tying his
postseason high. Foul trouble also limited him, and Bryant took
just nine shots, making four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've faced every different kind of way that you can play us
throughout the year,'' Shaw said, ``so it just depends on if we're
hitting the shots. Today they pretty much gambled and said, `Hey,
we're going to see if these guys are hitting shots.' Robert (Horry)
came out and started hitting them right away, and that opened it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Turn back the clock: Lakers coach Phil Jackson referred to
Portland's hack-a-Shaq tactics, which produced 25 O'Neal free
throws in the fourth quarter, as ``dredge'' and ``dreariness'' but
didn't question the strategy behind it.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't profit from fouling,'' he said. ``That's
basically what basketball is about. And in the original rules by
our god who created this game, (James) Naismith, the player that
fouled had to go out and sit out of a basketball game when he
fouled. So he had to leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that was what fouling was all about when basketball
started. But the game has changed, and you foul for profit now, and
that's an interesting aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheaper than airfare: The Lakers are inviting fans to view Games
3 and 4, televised from Portland, at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Free tickets will be distributed beginning Monday at 10 a.m. at
the Staples Center box office and Ticketmaster outlets located at
the Wherehouse, Tower Records, Robinson's May and Ritmo Latino. No
tickets will be distributed via the Ticketmaster phone center or
online.
</P>
<P>
   The two games will be played May 26 and May 28 at the Rose
Garden, and Staples Center will broadcast them on the four
Diamondvision scoreboard screens and 1,200 television monitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
