<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
 
SCIOSCIA HAS BEEN IN DiSARCINA'S POSITION 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Gary DiSarcina is still mulling over a course
of action to remedy his sore left shoulder. MRIs have shown nothing
outside the normal wear and tear, but the Angels shortstop is
contemplating surgery that would end his season.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia said he understands what DiSarcina is
going through.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, after coming to the Padres, he tore the rotator cuff in
his right shoulder on the first day of spring training. An MRI
revealed little damage, so he tried rehab for six to eight weeks
before eventually deciding to undergo surgery during which doctors
discovered a large tear.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia tried to play the next season with the Rangers, but
never did and retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough, tough decision,'' Scioscia said of undergoing
surgery. ``It had to be done, but it was tough to get the words
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference, Scioscia noted, is that he was in the twilight
of his career, while DiSarcina is 32 and figures to have several
productive seasons left.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think you can play three or four more years, it's
easier to sacrifice one year. The tough thing is he already feels
like he missed a year last year (when he missed nearly three months
with a broken arm.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult situation for all of us. We can give him
all kinds of advice, but Gary has to make the decision. He's talked
to a number of doctors and athletes. It's all where he wants to be
a year from now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have four starting pitchers on the disabled list (Ken
Hill, Tim Belcher, Jason Dickson and Kent Mercker) and another in
the minors (Ramon Ortiz) as the organization's pitching depth has
been stretched near its limits.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that won't get stretched, Scioscia said, is its
patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it takes a lot of discipline not to react on need,''
the manager said. ``But we're not going to bring Ortiz back or rush
Belcher (or Dickson). I don't think you can rush a player (back
from injury) or take him out of a developmental situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Belcher, who's recovering from off-season elbow surgery,
threw for 15 minutes in the Angels bullpen before Saturday's game
and pitching coach Bud Black said the 38-year-old right-hander
reported no discomfort during the 50-pitch workout.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, on the 60-day disabled list retroactive to March 27,
will throw again Tuesday in Minnesota. If all goes well, he'll
could make a rehab assignment in 10 days, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Mercker, hospitalized for the past 10 days since he was
diagnosed as having a cerebral hemorrhage, could be released from
the hospital early this week, Scioscia said. But whether the
left-hander pitches again this season is a matter the manager isn't
even willing to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get him healthy,'' Scioscia said. ``Right now, he's
getting stronger. We'll take it one step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: Chris Fussell (3-2, 4.24) vs. Kent Bottenfield
(3-4, 3.92), 1:05 p.m. TV: Fox Sports Net. Radio: KLAC/570 AM,
XPRS/1090 AM.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
