<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS ROUT MARLINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI - Carlos Perez started, so it meant the Dodgers were going
to score runs. The real question was whether Perez was going to
make the lead hold up.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that always the question with Perez?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Perez did his part and got the kind of support to which
he's accustomed as the Dodgers, led by Gary Sheffield's grand slam,
whacked the Florida Marlins 12-6 Saturday at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Every Dodgers starter, save Perez, had at least one hit and
scored a run as they battered starter Brad Penny (3-6) and the
Marlins bullpen for 15 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the batting order) flows really well,'' right fielder
Shawn Green said. ``It seems likes there's always guys on base. It
all feeds off each other. Not only are guys in front going to get
hits and guys behind you going to get hits, but you have to worry
about guys stealing and that opens holes. There's so many different
levels it helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, always teetering on the brink of being yanked from the
starting rotation, is 4-3 and tied with Chan Ho Park for the team
lead in wins. That Perez gets 8.62 runs of support per nine innings
is an enormous help, but he's already doubled his win total of last
season in half the starts (eight).
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the Dodgers (23-17) have won four straight and
six of seven, have secured a winning road trip (6-4) with today's
game remaining and are six games over .500 for the first time since
the final game of the 1997 season, when they finished 88-74.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good as a starting pitcher when you see your team wake-up
early and get runs,'' said Perez, who's ERA dropped to 5.74. ``I
kept throwing a first-pitch fastball for a strike, and when you
have the first pitch for a strike you can control the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive assault continued from the potent middle of the
order. Sheffield, booed by many in the crowd because of his days
with the Marlins, had his seventh career grand slam, a 442-foot
blast to center field in the seventh inning, which made it 12-3.
</P>
<P>
   Green was a homer short of the cycle and scored three times;
Eric Karros hit his 12th homer, a two-run shot, and walked twice;
and Todd Hundley singled in a run and scored.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are averaging 7.2 runs per game during the road
trip, and that foursome is doing most of the damage. They're a
combined 48 for 136 (.353) with 13 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheff took a little frustration out on that one ball,''
manager Davey Johnson said. ``He unloaded on that one. He had a
little frustration building. That was about the hardest hit ball
I've seen in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Green had two chances to become the first Dodger in 30 years to
hit for the cycle, but walked on four pitches and then struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Green finished 3 for 4 with an RBI and three runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Parker remains the lone Los Angeles Dodger to hit for the
cycle. He did it May 7, 1970, and at the time it ended a 21-year
drought. Before Parker, Brooklyn's Gil Hodges did in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The feat has been accomplished eight times in franchise history.
By comparison, there are have been 20 no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to hit one out,'' Green said. ``The last at-bat,
I had a good pitch and missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense is customary for Perez, but he had to fight to
survive six innings. Perez allowed three runs on nine hits, and the
Marlins either scored or had a runner in scoring position in each
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Perez was able to get the big out when he needed it
until the Dodgers broke it open with three runs in the fifth off
lefty reliever Ron Mahay. Karros' two-run homer and Alex Cora's
RBI-single increased the Dodgers' lead to 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Perez) kept us in the ballgame, pitched out of a few jams,''
Karros said. ``He's struggled in the first inning, and we put some
runs up for him.''
</P>
<P>
   DODGERS VS. FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10:05 a.m., at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Channel 5; 1150-AM, KWKW-AM (1330 Spanish).
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: The longest road trip of the season, covering four
cities and lasting two weeks, ends with Dodgers right-hander Kevin
Brown (2-1, 2.49 ERA) pitching against the club he led to the `97
World Series title. Brown is 20-8 with a 2.17 ERA here. He held the
Marlins to one run in eight innings in his only outing against them
a year ago. Brown is second in the N.L. in opponents' batting
average (.197) and ERA. Marlins lefty Jesus Sanchez (4-2, 5.98)
makes his seventh appearance against the Dodgers. He's 3-0 with a
4.43 ERA against L.A., but has pitched mostly in relief. Back in
the rotation, the 25-year-old has allowed a team-leading 11 homers.
</P>
<P>
   -Brian Dohn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
