<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COUPLES-SPECTATOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLES' SHAKEN AFTER TEE SHOT ON NO. 7 HITS SPECTATOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Fred Couples split eight of Colonial's 14
fairways and _ unfortunately _ one unsuspecting spectator's
forehead during Saturday's third round of the MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Couples prevailed despite his wayward blows from the tee, but
the errant drive on No. 7 shook the former Dallas resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never hit anyone and drawn blood, and it happened to be a
lady, which makes it even worse,'' Couples said. ``I don't know
why, but I'd rather it been a boyfriend or husband at 6-foot-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Garber was treated and released at Harris Methodist Fort
Worth, but this was no purple bruise where ``you kind of walk away
and actually don't feel bad,'' Couples said after shooting a
2-under-par 68.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lady is lying on the ground, not blood everywhere, but
there's enough blood to make you kind of feeling like quitting,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vision lingered, and Couples settled for a bogey at No. 7
despite the ball caroming into the fairway for his approach shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say it was the cause for a bogey because it
wasn't an easy second shot, but I hit it just off the green and
chipped to about 4 feet,'' Couples said of his only bogey. ``I was
thinking about it on the second shot, the chip shot and the putt,
but then I also thought about it on a lot of other holes, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples recorded three birdies before and none after his errant
drive at No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was walking down the street and some guy called me a name
and I slugged him in face,'' Couples said, ``I wouldn't think about
it for another second _ unless he went and got six of his friends.
But when you're out there and hit somebody, I just couldn't shake
that off.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples, though, made his charge before No. 7 and will begin
Sunday's final round trailing the leader, Stewart Cink, by five
strokes after birdies at Nos. 1, 5 and 6. Couples reached the par-5
No. 1 in two and two-putted from 30 feet, and he later drained
putts of 20 and 10 feet at Nos. 5 and 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very nice thing to be under par after five holes, and
the fifth hole is the hardest hole that maybe we play on tour,''
Couples said. ``I've gone par, birdie, birdie. So I don't know what
to expect (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's rain forced Couples to resume his second round on No.
8, but it allowed him to play 29 holes under ideal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have that many people to leapfrog, but it's going to
take a very good round _ better than a 66 _ I think,'' Couples said
of a potential victory. ``If the weather stays like this, I feel
like I can do it.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
