<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1404 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-COLONIAL-TOMS-TEX     05-21 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-TOMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMS' FAST START QUICKLY GIVES WAY TO FADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ David Toms began a 31-hole day Saturday at
the MasterCard Colonial believing he would be among those chased.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Toms finished 13 holes to complete a postponed
second round from Friday, he was neck-and-neck with tournament
leader Davis Love III. Toms' afternoon start for the third round
began strong, and he was among the favorites.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, he ambled into the clubhouse as the one doing the
chasing.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in the final group proved difficult for Toms, who went
from leading at 8 under after seven third-round holes to the last
man showing on the board at 5 under. Toms' 72 that followed rounds
of 67 and 66 ties him with four others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky to get in at 2 over,'' Toms said. ``I had a couple
of three-putts. Maybe I got tired. It just wasn't a very good day.
I had no rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Toms couldn't find the beat beginning at Nos. 3, 4 and 5 _ the
hallowed Horrible Horseshoe. After finishing his delayed second
round with four birdies and adding another to begin Round 3, Toms
bogeyed Nos. 3 and 5.
</P>
<P>
   On the latter, his uphill-lie bunker shot stayed in the sand,
but he recovered nicely on a second try to avoid a double bogey.
From there, Toms fought back to 8-under with birdies on Nos. 6 and
7.
</P>
<P>
   As Love kept pace, Stewart Cink went on a back-nine tear that
saw him move to 11 under for the tournament lead.
</P>
<P>
   Toms said that as Love and Cink stayed their course, he became
less focused on what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're playing with Davis and he's just bombing it,'' Toms
said. ``I started pressing. You're walking up every fairway and
people are going crazy for them, and they deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Toms said he attempted to ``block out'' the day his partners
were having. The more he struggled, the more it was difficult to do
so, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Toms bogeyed five of the last 11 holes, finishing with birdies
on Nos. 16 and 17 to salvage a share of eighth place. He wasn't the
only hopeful to fall off in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson (5 under) and Rocco Mediate (6 under) both sat in
second place at some point in the day. Mediate gained a stroke on
the day but would lose two over the final four holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was off to the races,'' Toms said. ``Even after
the bogey at 5, one shot and one hole should have no bearing with
13 left. Cink was out there a long time (31 holes) too, and he did
a good job. I've got to find something tomorrow that will work.''
</P>
<P>
   More than likely Toms will do a lot less looking over his
shoulder when he begins Sunday's final round. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
