<HEADLINE>
WITHIN STRIKING DISTANCE, LOVE'S ON FAMILIAR GROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Davis Love III is no stranger to the top of
a leader board.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he has been on them almost his entire professional
career, recording 106 top-10 finishes since joining the PGA Tour in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed familiar with the leader board during Saturday's third
round of the MasterCard Colonial. In fact, he yo-yoed up and down
the board, seeing basically every position on it before finishing
with a 1-under-par 69.
</P>
<P>
   That put the second-round co-leader at 8-under-par 202 for the
event, three strokes back of leader Stewart Cink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's not where I want to be,'' Love said. ``I made
four bogeys from the middle of the fairway, two on the front and
two on the back, and those really killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   What hurt Love most was inconsistency. His roller-coaster ride
began with a birdie on the par-5 No. 1 and continued with bogeys at
Nos. 3 and 5, two of Colonial's toughest holes. He did answer with
a birdie on No. 6, getting through the front nine at even par.
</P>
<P>
   But that's when his round really got interesting. Starting at
No. 12, Love went from 7 under to 9 under in two holes, only to go
back to 7 under on the next two before getting back to 8-under with
a birdie on the par-3 No. 16. For the confused, that's a stretch of
birdie, birdie, bogey, bogey, birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not hitting the ball close to the hole when I have
opportunities,'' he said. ``It makes it frustrating. I hit two good
shots at 12, a good shot at 13, two good shots at 15, a good shot
at 16, and I make two bogeys in there. That just kills you.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of his ride, Love is anything but out of this
tournament _ something else with which he is familiar. Just a week
ago, he was leading entering the final round before finishing
second in a playoff at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic. He trailed by
three strokes entering Sunday at the MCI Classic on April 16 and
finished tied for third behind Cink. He also finished second at the
Bay Hill Invitational and has three fourth-place finishes this
year.
</P>
<P>
   He's there again. And if he can put up five birdies, this time
without the four bogeys, he might just get his first victory since
the 1998 MCI Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what I wanted,'' he said, ``but no one else, except
Stewart, made much of a move.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
