<HEADLINE>
AS USUAL, KITE MAKES CUT AT COLONIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES AND JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tom Kite's record of making cuts at Colonial
remained perfect after his second-round 72 left him with a 1-over
141 for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Kite has made 28 cuts in 28 years at Colonial. His first was as
an amateur, so he will receive an earnings check in Fort Worth for
the 27th consecutive year, though he has never won the event.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Kite was poised to finish the second round at 1 under
or better until he bogeyed two of his last three holes following
tree trouble along two fairways. His third-round 73 put him at 4
over for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Despite finishing in the money the most times at Colonial, Kite
is 46th all-time on the event's earnings list with $153,675. Corey
Pavin ($737,833) is No. 1. MISSED THE CUT
</P>
<P>
   Defending MasterCard Colonial champion Olin Browne led a list of
notable golfers who missed yesterday's cut (3 over), set shortly
before the delayed third round began.
</P>
<P>
   Browne finished 4 over with a two-round 144 (71-73) but did
share $5,000 with Peter Jacobsen after the pair teamed to win the
Colonial Shootout on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a defending champion missed since 1995
champ Tom Lehman failed in '96, when he also missed by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Other notables to miss the cut included Lee Janzen (6 over),
Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks (6 over), Gary Nicklaus (7 over),
past Colonial champions Bruce Lietzke (8 over), Corey Pavin (9
over) and Ben Crenshaw (10 over), and amateur and Fort Worth
resident Hunter Haas (9 over). ACE FOR APPLEBY
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Appleby recorded the 17th hole-in-one in tournament
history since Colonial began play in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby aced No. 13, a par-3, 178-yard hole with a 7-iron. The
ace put him at even par before he bogeyed No. 14 to slip to 1-over.
Brad Faxon recorded Colonial's previous ace, in 1996 at No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask my caddie,'' Appleby said when asked the last time he aced
a hole. ``I don't remember.'' It was at the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby's fortune went sour a hole later when his approach found
a muddy groove between the cart path and grass. His drop landed on
a sprinkler head, so he dropped again.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby's chip rolled to within 5 feet. About to putt for par,
he backed off when a mosquito bit his hand; he then two-putted for
bogey. REALLY HORRIBLE
</P>
<P>
   Holes 3, 4 and 5 at Colonial have been dubbed the ``horrible
horseshoe'' for obvious reasons _ it's easily the toughest stretch
on the course with Nos. 3 and 5 being monster par-4s and No. 4
being a 246-yard par-3.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch was especially difficult for Phil Mickelson
yesterday. The tour's most famous left-hander entered No. 3 at
6-under-par and walked off No. 5 green 2-under after two bogeys and
one double bogey. IT'S A BEACH
</P>
<P>
   David Toms, who had to take two shots out of a greenside bunker
at No. 5, said Colonial's reconditioned sand traps are ``definitely
a hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   Toms bogeyed the hole after back-to-back bunker shots and later
said ``80 percent of the balls that fly into'' Colonial's traps are
``plugging in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sand's too deep,'' he said. ``They keep getting buried in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For the tournament, Toms has made 6 of 9 sand saves. He made 2
of 4 in the third round. COUPLES' BACK BETTER
</P>
<P>
   Fred Couples' ailing back prevented him from competing during
last week's GTE Byron Nelson Classic in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK, but I could get on a plane flight or hit one shot,
and then it will stiffen up to where I can't really do anything,''
he said. ``I just felt like if I went to Dallas, I would play and
would probably really do something bad. So, I just let it rest, and
that's why I think I'm feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples said his back began troubling him while carrying luggage
upstairs after returning from the Compaq Classic of New Orleans. It
prevented him from playing for four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say it doesn't dictate my golf,'' Couples said,
``but a lot of times, if I don't feel well, I don't play.'' NICE
BREAK
</P>
<P>
   For once, Colonial Country Club actually gave a player an extra
chance rather than taking one away.
</P>
<P>
   Irving's Joel Edwards, in the middle of his 5-under-par 65, hit
his worst shot of the day on the tee of the 470-yard, par-4 No. 5.
The shot was going well right, headed for the Trinity River, but
somehow stayed in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably in somebody's boat at one time,'' Edwards
said. ``But it hit something and came out in the fairway. It was in
the river, it was well in there, but I got a break.'' FAMILIAR
POSITION
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sluman is lurking near the top of the MasterCard Colonial
leader board _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Sluman fired a 3-under-par 67 yesterday and is 6 under for the
tournament, tied for fourth with three other players. Last year, he
shot a final-round 66 to tie for second, a stroke behind winner
Olin Browne, with four other players.In 1998, Sluman finished
third, four strokes back of winner Tom Watson. COURSE DRAINS WELL
</P>
<P>
   After about three-fourths of an inch of rain Friday afternoon,
Colonial course superintendent Scott Johnson said water wasn't a
problem on the course yesterday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The bunkers, which had new drainage systems installed in the
more than $3.5 million renovation the past year, had no standing
water, and Johnson said the sand didn't wash away from the tops of
the traps.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, he said, the traps just needed raking to get them
ready for the morning rounds when 53 golfers had to complete second
rounds that were delayed because of rain and lightning.
</P>
<P>
   He said the greens were dry enough to mow after the morning
competitors finished and before the third round began at 12:30 p.m.
EXTRA WORK NO PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   David Toms tied Davis Love III for the second-round lead at 7
under after resuming his round yesterday morning and playing his
remaining 12 holes in 3 under par to finish with a 66.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was no big deal to have to play so many holes in the
morning and then come back in the afternoon to play 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to be here all day, so I went to bed early
and tried to get a good night's sleep. It's no big deal. We're
supposed to be athletes, aren't we?'' CITY CHAMPS CADDYING
</P>
<P>
   Andy Fuller and Phil Dyson, former Fort Worth Men's City Golf
champions, are caddying this week. Fuller is toting Brian Watts'
bag, and Dyson is carrying Brandt Jobe's clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Both have been carrying the bags for several years, here and in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be back here,'' Dyson said yesterday. ``It's just
a lot different here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuller said his caddying career might be coming to an end
because he recently married.
Staff writers J. Douglas Foster and Troy Phillips contributed to
this report. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
