<HEADLINE>
BIRTHDAY BOY CINK CASTS EYE ON BIG PRESENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Until Sunday, perchance, the most memorable
birthday of Stewart Cink's life came when he turned 16 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents were out of town,'' Cink confessed. ``And we had a
party _ 40 people, maybe, all under age.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents don't know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Well, they do now.
</P>
<P>
   But if Cink, who turns 27 on Sunday, survives the risky business
of the MasterCard Colonial's fourth round, his best birthday party
figures to come tonight.
</P>
<P>
   With mom, dad and wife Lisa all in attendance, Cink cast a spell
on Colonial's muggy fairways and byways Saturday. Beginning the day
with 13 rain-delayed, second-round holes still to play, Cink picked
a grand day to show his ``best stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he negotiated the course's telltale corner _ holes
3, 4 and 5 _ Cink had made so many birdies in a row, ``The hole
looked like a big bucket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alabama native is not just another young pro with a funny
name. In 1996, Cink _ pronounced ``sink,'' as in kitchen _ was
named the Buy.Com Tour's player of the year. In the very next
season, he was named the PGA Tour's player of the year, the first
to win the honors in successive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Cink won at Hartford in '97 and had what he felt was a
breakthrough weekend at the MCI Classic in Hilton Head, S.C., four
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first victory means a lot,'' Cink explained. ``But the
second one means at least as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes yourself out of the he's-only-won-once group of guys.
It seems there's always something else that the public is ready to
label you as.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cink's case, even before Hilton Head, he was winning money
and being labeled as one of the game's bright young stars. In his
first nine tournament starts this season, Cink finished in the top
10 four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about really everything going in my game right
now,'' Cink said after his third-round 65.
</P>
<P>
   The one stumble in his season may have come after the win at
MCI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took three weeks off and kind of relished the victory,'' he
said. ``And then I realized when I came back that I wasn't as ready
to play as I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Cink shot 70-74 at last week's GTE Byron Nelson Classic and
missed the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good wakeup call for me,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   He opened here, however, with an even-par 70 under gusty
conditions and has been a model of consistency ever since. In 31
holes of golf Saturday, Cink carded exactly one bogey.
</P>
<P>
   So what's his secret?
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm good at,'' Cink answered, ``is that I know myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really tall (6-foot-4), and my swing is a little weird.
But I know what's going to happen. It's something I've had since I
became a decent player _ based more on observation than anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Cink, as it turns out, is a meticulous note-taker. Every shot he
takes, every move he makes, Cink notes for further study.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned it from Ben Hogan and, of course, he was `the man'
here,'' Cink said. ``I never talked to him, but I read about him.
He wrote down every shot he hit. I liked his swing, and I read how
he used to play, and he was a perfectionist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, well, if he did it, it ought to be good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He won't change Sunday, Cink said, even if it is his birthday.
After rounds of 64 and 65, there is no need to change anything, no
need to run scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go out there and think that 18 pars are going to win,
though,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His mom and dad, Rob and Anne Cink, are in town from Florence,
Ala. Shhh _ don't tell them about that 16th birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   But tradition-rich Colonial, with its Wall of Champions, would
be a grand place, Stewart said, to celebrate his 27th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed on the first tee that you can see yourself in the
wall, almost like a mirror,'' he said after his long day of
birdies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to see your reflection in the wall, but it'd be a
lot nicer to see your name on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider it, perchance, a birthday present. It might even beat
turning 16. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
