<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-COCHRAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUY IN A POLO CORSET STARTED IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE COCHRAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Lest we forget, it all really began 59 years
ago with a guy wearing a polo corset winning what the
``Star-Telegram'' modestly touted as ``golfdom's gaudiest
carnival.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Fort Worth's 1941 U.S. Open, the forerunner of the
Colonial National Invitation, now the 2000 MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   The guy was Craig Wood, the gaudy carnival was the first Open
south of the Mason-Dixon line and the long-ago competition included
Ben Hogan, who would eventually put his stamp on Colonial as no
other. That historic field also embraced the likes of Sam Snead,
Gene Sarazen, Byron Nelson, Lloyd Mangrum, Denny Shute, Jimmy
Demaret, Johnny Bulla, Lawson Little, Dutch Harrison, Henry Ransom,
Clayton Heafner and Ralph Guldahl.
</P>
<P>
   Wood hit town that June suffering from a bizarre injury suffered
when he dropped a razor while shaving, then sneezed as he stooped
to pick it up. It dislocated a vertebra. Thus the polo corset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I can make it or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Wood, 39, was golf's reigning bridesmaid, despite
winning a Masters championship. He had lost playoffs in the British
Open to Shute in 1933, the Masters to Sarazen in 1935 and the Open
to Nelson in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing Shute after 36 holes, Wood closed with a pair of
even-par 70s and his 284, although four shots over regulation, was
three better than Shute and five better than Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   The $1,000 payoff was precisely $593,000 less than today's
champion earns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '41 Open was so popular with both players and fans that
Colonial officials vowed to start a tournament of their own,'' said
Dennis Roberson, Colonial historian and tournament manager.
</P>
<P>
   But precisely five months later, the Japanese attacked Pearl
Harbor, and World War II would prevent Colonial from fulfilling
that vow until 1946.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Star-Telegram'' had pronounced the '41 Open the ``greatest
athletic event'' in Fort Worth's history, but Hogan would torpedo
that claim pretty much by himself, starting with the very first
Colonial, in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hogan captivated the city and the event by charging from three
shots back for a thrilling one-stroke victory and $3,000
first-place check,'' Roberson recounted in a 50-year Colonial
reminiscence.
</P>
<P>
   ``His incredible final-round 65 stood as the course record for
24 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan won four of the first seven Colonials and captured his
fifth and final title in 1959, although he would be a legitimate
challenger up until 1967, when he tied for third, three strokes
behind champion Dave Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   The 1959 title was also his last PGA victory. Course founder
Marvin Leonard's pride and joy would become known around the world
as ``Hogan's Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's victory here in 1953 was historically significant,
coming as it did four years after his near-fatal car wreck and
sandwiched between triumphs at the Masters and the U.S. and British
Opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``His remarkable comeback from those life-threatening injuries
would become one of the greatest stories in all of sports
history,'' Roberson recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, there have been countless memorable Colonial
moments, inevitable with a great golf course and a Wall of
Champions decorated with names such as Snead, Middlecoff, Bolt,
Sanders, Nicklaus, Palmer, Crenshaw, Trevino, Boros, Casper,
Crampton, Watson, Souchak, Zoeller, Pavin, Price and on and on and
on.
</P>
<P>
   But Colonial and Hogan are simply inseparable:
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, the Hogan-Snead rivaly was in full bloom, but Snead
eagled the first hole the first day and led from start to finish,
beating Hogan by five shots.
</P>
<P>
   When he won in 1952, Hogan closed with a 67 _ hitting all 18
greens in regulation. That was the year Colonial's plaid jackets
made their debut.
</P>
<P>
   After 36 holes of the 1954 tournament, Hogan was tied for third
but two strokes ahead of eventual winner Johnny Palmer when illness
forced him to withdraw. Ten years later, Palmer set a scoring
record unchallenged to this day. His 87-81-82-79_331 was 51 over
par.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, Arnold Palmer led after the first round, but Hogan was
within a shot of the lead approaching the 18th green Sunday. He
carded an extremely rare double bogey, and Tommy Bolt won by three
strokes. The weather conditions were so horrible that year they
produced one of my favorite all-time Colonial quotes. Byron Nelson
said it after the first round: ``The course is too wet to be muddy,
and somehow, it's the driest wet I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Colonial can do that to you.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
