<DOCNO> NYT20000521.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1409 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-LEDE-TE     05-21 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED BULLET PUTS STOP TO PEGASUS' BID FOR TRIPLE CROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ It looks as though Fusaichi Pegasus slipped up on
his way to the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky Derby winner couldn't get the job done at Pimlico
Race Course on Saturday, which turned out to be the big banana peel
on the way to history. Instead, he let things get away from him in
the final turn and never threatened, while Red Bullet pulled away
in the stretch to win the Preakness Stakes by almost four lengths
at damp Pimlico.
</P>
<P>
   The track was rated as ``good'' after rain showers passed
through Maryland before the races. It was rated sloppy earlier in
the day. The people surrounding Fusaichi Pegasus, who was heavily
favored at odds of 2-5, said the inability of their colt to handle
the track was the reason for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big, heavy horse,'' said jockey Kent Desormeaux, who
held on to second, barely, over Impeachment and Captain Steve.
``He's so heavy going around those turns that he was slipping and
sliding. That certainly could have made the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the track wasn't to his liking. But no one could tell that
before the race. The last time Fusaichi Pegasus and Red Bullet met
each other on the track, Fusaichi Pegasus beat that colt by four
lengths in the Wood Memorial Stakes on a wet track five weeks ago
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus won the Derby two weeks ago over Aptitude,
while Red Bullet skipped the Derby and headed toward the Preakness.
Red Bullet had beaten Aptitude twice, and now he breaks a streak of
71 horses that failed to win the Preakness after skipping the Derby
during the past 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Solis rode Red Bullet in the Wood, and trainer Joe Orseno
believed the rider made a mistake by going out early with the
pacesetter and chasing a fast pace in his first effort around two
turns. So when Hall of Fame rider Jerry Bailey became available
after War Chant departed the Triple Crown chase following the
Derby, Orseno had no trouble convincing him to take the mount.
</P>
<P>
   And he let Bailey do whatever he pleased on the colt. Red Bullet
had only raced four times in his career, and Bailey was aboard for
his second victory in February at Gulfstream Park in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Orseno and owner Frank Stronach talked with each other on what
instructions they should give to Bailey as the race card progressed
at Pimlico. The Preakness was the 10th race on the card.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had out-thought ourselves at that point,'' Orseno said.
``So when we got down there with him and the horse (before the
race), we just told him `Good luck.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet's talent was formidable enough _ he was second in the
wagering at 6-1 _ so maybe the move to Bailey made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet took an awkward step out of the gate _ he actually
jerked his head around seconds prior to the start _ and he was
ahead of one horse heading into the clubhouse turn.
</P>
<P>
   But Bailey put the colt on the move. Before they left the
backstretch, he was on even terms with Fusaichi Pegasus about two
lengths from the lead when the first three-quarters of a mile went
in 1 minute, 11 1/5seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, however, had guided Red Bullet to a path inside of
Fusaichi Pegasus, and Red Bullet was able to avoid traffic trouble
all the way through the turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to wiggle my way through the crowd,'' Bailey said.
Desormeaux ``had to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   It cost him. Red Bullet was running behind Snuck In, but when
jockey Cash Asmussen was able to get Snuck In to make his move,
Bailey followed and was able to pass Hal's Hope and head for the
top of the stretch. Desormeaux had to take Fusaichi Pegasus around
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was no more than a half a length off my flank
turning for home,'' Bailey said. ``But I thought if my horse was
good enough to beat him to that point, I knew he could probably
beat him overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Bullet really showed what he was made of today. He
exploded on that turn, and when we straightened out, he just left
the other horses. He was just a better horse today.''
</P>
<P>
   When the field entered the stretch, Red Bullet was a length in
front. Bailey slapped the colt three times with the stick
right-handed, then put it in his left hand and swatted him twice
more. Mission accomplished, he tucked away the whip and stopped the
clock in 1:56 for the 13/16 miles. That's the slowest winning time
since Tabasco Cat won in 1:562/5 on a fast track in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet and Fusaichi Pegasus have met each other two times
and won one race apiece. It sounds as if they could have a rubber
match in three weeks at the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Drysdale, trainer of Fusaichi Pegasus, said he intends to
send the colt to New York tomorrow. Orseno said he would make a
decision based on how the colt is doing, but did not rule out the
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   When they get there, they could meet up again with Aptitude.
Lexington Stakes winner Unshaded, fifth-place Derby finisher
Wheelaway and Lone Star Derby winner Tahkodha Hills may be a part
of the field, as well.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
