<HEADLINE>
TRAINERS POINT TO BELMONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Unlike pro wrestling, horse racing is not a sport
where threats are exchanged as freely as dot-com stocks on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   But a battle of words might be forming between the people
handling Fusaichi Pegasus and the people handling Red Bullet after
the Preakness Stakes. Maybe the Triple Crown is history, but both
horses are the leading candidates for champion 3-year-old _
possibly Horse of the Year _ now that Fusaichi Pegasus won the
Kentucky Derby and Red Bullet won the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Drysdale, trainer of Fusaichi Pegasus, stopped short of
saying Red Bullet was a better horse despite Red Bullet's victory
of nearly four lengths Saturday in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   And Drysdale, usually a cautious type who wouldn't make a firm
commitment to the Preakness until a week following the Derby, now
appears raring to go. He's already announced plans to leave for New
York tomorrow in order to prepare for the Belmont Stakes on June
10.
</P>
<P>
   He might get a rematch with Red Bullet. It would be a rubber
match because Fusaichi Pegasus defeated Red Bullet by four lengths
in the Wood Memorial prior to the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to be taken away from Red Bullet's victory''
Saturday, Drysdale said. ``But I don't think Fusaichi Pegasus
handled the track. I just feel he was slipping and sliding. He
couldn't go when the other horse came with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The track at Pimlico Race Course was rated as ``good'' after
rain showers passed through the area for two days leading up to the
races. That was a disappointment to Red Bullet trainer Joe Orseno.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping for a sunny day because I knew how well my horse
was training up to this race,'' Orseno said. ``I just wanted to win
the race and not have any excuses from anybody. Red Bullet is a
talented horse, and I wanted the chance to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Orseno blamed the colt's loss to Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood on
the fact he made an early move to chase a fast pace under jockey
Alex Solis. Orseno replaced Solis on Red Bullet with Hall of Fame
rider Jerry Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   But with the approval of owner Frank Stronach, Orseno skipped
the Derby with Red Bullet and pointed for the Preakness. It was a
risky move. In the past 17 years, 71 horses have skipped the Derby,
run in the Preakness and lost.
</P>
<P>
   It looked even more shaky after Fusaichi Pegasus won the Derby
by 11/2 lengths with the sixth-fastest time in the history of the
race. The colt came to Pimlico at odds of 2 to 5, the heaviest
Preakness favorite since Spectacular Bid at odds of 1 to 10 in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought going in (to the Preakness) that there were
seven horses to beat, not just one who happened to be almost 1 to 5
and came to town as the next Triple Crown winner. People thought we
were running for second money, and I didn't believe any of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to have a champion horse, not a one-race
wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they'll figure out who's the one-race wonder at the
Belmont. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
