<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORIOUS TRAINER FLYING HIGH WITH STRONACH'S STABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Life is getting good, real good, for trainer Joe
Orseno. When Red Bullet won the Preakness Stakes on Saturday at
Pimlico Race Course, he became the first trainer since 1996 to
train the winner of the Preakness and the Pimlico Special _ the two
most prestigious races at Pimlico _ in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   People can even ask things of Orseno that they were forbidden to
ask Fusaichi Pegasus trainer Neil Drysdale _ those ``touchy-feely
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, I'll answer those,'' Orseno said. ``I feel great, a
real high. I won't need an airplane to get home.''
</P>
<P>
   A 44-year-old native of Philadelphia, Orseno has been the
leading trainer at Atlantic City Racecourse, Garden State Park,
Meadowlands and Delaware Park. But Orseno thought about getting out
of the game when he no longer was winning training titles.
</P>
<P>
   Orseno became the private trainer for Frank Stronach when
Stronach and Patrick Byrne parted ways following 1999. Byrne
eventually sued Stronach to collect training fees.
</P>
<P>
   Orseno got his hands on some nice horses when Stronach hired
him. Before Orseno was trainer, Stronach had won races such as the
Belmont ('97 with Touch Gold) and the Breeders' Cup Classic ('98
with Awesome Again).
</P>
<P>
   The stable is still powerful. Orseno won the Pimlico Special
with Golden Missile, the Beaugay Handicap with Tap To Music and
other stakes races with Perfect Sting. STRONACH ON RETAMA
</P>
<P>
   Frank Stronach, who owns Red Bullet, has been in talks with
officials at Retama Park near San Antonio about buying that
racetrack. But those talks have bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has a price,'' said Andy Stronach, son of Frank
Stronach and heavily involved in the Stronach business empire.
``Some things fall into place, sometimes they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stronachs would not comment regarding ongoing negotiations.
Several sources contend the owners of Retama's debt have upped
their price. Retama was purchased in 1997 for a price between $12
million and $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Through his Magna Entertainment Corp., Stronach owns Santa Anita
Park, Gulfstream Park, Golden Gate Fields and Remington Park. He
just announced he's buying Bay Meadows Racecourse near San
Francisco. SNUCK IN FIFTH
</P>
<P>
   Snuck In, trained by Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie-based Steve
Asmussen, finished fifth in the eight-horse field of the Preakness.
Asmussen leads the trainer standings at Lone Star, but this was his
first Triple Crown race.
</P>
<P>
   Snuck In, who had won the Rebel Stakes and finished second in
the Arkansas Derby, was battling for the lead heading into the turn
before Red Bullet flew past him. After that, Fusaichi Pegasus,
Impeachment and Captain Steve went past as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good trip. Lovely trip,'' said Cash Asmussen, brother of Steve
Asmussen and Snuck In's jockey. ``He traveled well, happy following
High Yield''toward the final turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the other horse (Red Bullet) quickened next to me, I just
kind of stayed on it.'' TRACK GOT `GREASY'
</P>
<P>
   Kent Desormeaux, rider of Fusaichi Pegasus, has firsthand
knowledge of the racing surface at Pimlico. He rode in Maryland
before he moved to the Southern California circuit. He believes the
surface contributed to Fusaichi Pegasus' loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``This track has a limestone bottom,'' Desormeaux said. ``When
it gets greasy, it's hard for a big, heavy horse like mine to not
slip around on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The base is the part of the track that's built first, then the
other layers of the track _ sand, loam, clay and other materials _
are laid on top of it. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
