<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-POLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD VIBES: RAY TAKES INDY POLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Texan Greg Ray was driving so fast at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Saturday he couldn't see straight.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how Ray won the pole position for the 84th
Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Driving while blind.
</P>
<P>
   Battling a tire vibration problem he said blurred his vision
throughout his 10-mile qualification run, Ray held his breath and
ripped off four consecutive laps of 223-plus mph for an average
speed of 223.471 mph. Ray, the reigning Indy Racing Northern Light
Series champion, relegated rookie Juan Montoya _ reigning champion
of the rival CART FedEx Series _ to No. 2 among the 23 drivers
completing attempts on the first of two days of qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Champions Ray and Montoya will be joined by open-wheel
journeyman Eliseo Salazar in the three-car front row for the race's
traditional flying start May 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the pole here is as big as winning any race anywhere
else,'' said Ray, the Plano resident who had qualified No. 2 for
the previous two Indy 500s. ``After starting second the last two
years, I'd be lying if I said it wasn't a big focus for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya had gotten Ray's attention _ and sent a buzz through the
grandstands _ when he put together a four-lap average of 223.372
mph to take the provisional pole from Salazar (223.231), who is
driving for Texan and four-time Indy 500 champion A.J. Foyt.
Montoya, who warmed up with a screaming lap of 221.626 mph, went
out approximately 10 minutes after Ray had waved-off his first
attempt because of a pushing condition in his car going into Turn 1
of the 2.5-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time by I fully committed to turning into Turn 1 at
233 mph, and the car went straight,'' said Ray, driver of the No. 1
Team Conseco Dallara/Aurora. ``I had to back off the gas to keep it
off the wall, and there was no need to continue that attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya's number stood atop the Speedway's scoring pylon
approximately 21/2 hours. Both Ray and teammate Robby Gordon worked
on their cars during that period before mounting second bids for
the pole. Ray hit the track at 3:50 p.m., facing relatively the
same cloudy and cool conditions he and Montoya had dealt with
earlier in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When Ray warmed up at 218.140 mph, Montoya's speed appeared
safe. But Ray hunkered down for consecutive laps of 223.658,
223.397, 223.503 and 223.325 mph and a time of 2:41.095.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car was definitely on the edge when I practiced,'' said
Ray, who had run off a lap at 224 mph moments before heading out
for his second attempt. ``But I think we slung a (wheel) weight on
the backstraight the first time I accelerated, and there was a huge
vibration in the car. We didn't have a chance to come back in
because that was my second attempt. I just decided to drive it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had sets of tires before where you had a vibration, but
this is the first time at Indy. I just couldn't believe it. I was
almost laughing in the car. Here I am driving this car with
absolutely no downforce, 65-degrees track temperature, it's cold
and slippery and now we've got a vibration. It's like, you just
suck-it-up and go.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said the vibration prevented him from ever shifting into
sixth, or top gear, during the four laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was vibrating so bad, it was fighting itself,'' said Ray,
who nevertheless bagged his third pole in four events this season
and the seventh of his Indy Racing League career. ``It was very
difficult to see because the vibration goes up through the whole
car. You'd see a flat wall one second and then it'd be fuzzy. All I
know was I was happy to see the checkered flag because I could
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I know for a fact that I can hold my breath for 160
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray presented team owner John Menard with his third Indy 500
pole and 16th in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (run) is a testament to Greg's stamina and focus,'' said
Menard, who fielded the cars that the late Scott Brayton put on the
pole here in 1995 and 1996. ``That was a great drive. I can't
remember a more awesome run.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya and his car owner, Chip Ganassi, were fully aware that
Team Menard had the savvy to blast them off the pole late in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought maybe we could get the pole, or front row,'' said
Montoya, the Colombian who qualified his backup No. 9 Target G
Force/Aurora _ and made it look easy. ``I don't think it's easy. I
set it up the way I do my Champ Car. I like the car. It's a really
friendly car. Fast and friendly.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
