<SLUG> BC-REFORM-BUCHANAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN TACKLES STATE
 BORDER WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 BY TESSIE BORDEN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, the presumptive pres idential candidate for the
Reform Party, on Saturday said he supports in theory a work-permit
program that would give some kind of tempo rary legal status to
migrant workers who now cross the border illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not an idea I would throw out on principle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan was in town to address the Arizona convention of the
Reform Party, which elected eight members and eight alternates to
attend the national convention in Long Beach, Calif., in August.
The group of about 250 met at the Chaparral Suites in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The former Republican delivered an impassioned speech that
touched on the main tenets of the Reform Party, including severe
limits to legal immi gration, an end to illegal immigra tion, an
end to campaign soft money and an end to U.S. participation in free
trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where my hand goes up,'' he said to roaring applause, ``The
new world order goes down.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bulk of his message, and of the dialogue through the
rest of the convention, addressed illegal immi gration and the
problems of Arizona border ranchers who have detained thousands of
border crossers they find on their property.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before his speech, Buchanan harked back to a
similar guest worker program called brace ros that allowed Mexican
workers to temporarily work in the United States from 1942 to 1964
and guar anteed them at least minimum-wage salaries and humane
living condi tions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the program we had in the 1950s,'' he said. ``I
wasn't opposed to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would support a similar program today, he said
he might, but he has not yet worked out a detailed proposal. With
this tenta tive support, Buchanan joins the camp of Arizona Gov.
Jane Hull and Douglas Mayor Ray Borane, both of whom have urged the
federal govern ment to work out a new bracero program that they
believe would alleviate the problems caused by thousands of illegal
immigrants who cross the U.S.-Mexican border daily. &QL; 
WANTS BORDER SEALED Still, Buchanan said that before any such
program can become a reality, the United States needs to close its
porous borders. Buchanan suggested bulking up U.S. Border Patrol en
forcement in all high-traffic areas at the same time, rather than
slowly and gradually, as the Border Patrol has done since the early
1990s with operations like El Paso's Hold the Line, San Diego's
Gatekeeper, and Arizona's Safeguard.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he would use troops if necessary to stop illegal
immi grants. The sheriff of Cochise County has twice asked Hull to
send in the National Guard in support and administrative
capacities, but she has resisted.
</P>
<P>
   Use of the military on the border is not new. It last occurred
during the Reagan administration's war on drugs, when Marines
helped the Border Patrol with scouting and reconnaissance work, as
well as actual enforcement of the border. The 240 military
personnel were stationed all along the U.S.-Mexican border, though
most stayed near El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   But the May 20, 1997, killing of Ezequiel Hernandez Jr., a
Redford, Texas, youth, by a Marine brought those efforts to an
abrupt end. Two months later, the Pentagon recalled the soldiers
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he was not aware of the Hernandez shooting. The
main thing to remember, he said, is that the current policy has not
worked.
</P>
<P>
   He said he understands why Mexi can workers cross American
borders in search of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivations of those folks coming over here, there's
nothing wrong with them,'' he said. ``The problem lies with an
administration that is not willing to enforce the laws of this
country.'' &QL; 
SUPPORTS RANCHERSBuchanan criticized U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and U.S. Attor ney General Janet Reno, who con
demned the ranchers and what they called ``vigilante justice'' last
week. Albright made a joint statement with Mexican Foreign
Secretary Rosario Green. Reno pledged to help gather evidence for
possible criminal prose cutions of the ranchers, but later backed
away, saying she merely promised to enforce the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said both are putting their personal relationships with
the Mexi can government ahead of the prop erty rights of American
citizens and of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ranchers simply are protecting their property rights
because the U.S. government has literally abdicated its
responsibilities,'' he said. ``You only have vigilante justice
where real justice doesn't exist.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
