<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LITTLE AL' QUALIFIES FOR INDY 500 AFTER FIVE-YEAR ABSENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Two-time Indianapolis 500 champion Al Unser Jr.
needed 2 minutes, 43 seconds and change to complete some unfinished
business at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after he failed to qualify for the Indy 500 as the
reigning champion, Little Al secured a spot in the 84th edition of
the race that has become his family's birthright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can safely say we're back now,'' said Unser, who will start
18th in the 33-car field after compiling a four-lap qualifying
average of 220.293 mph. ``We're in the show. We definitely had
butterflies we haven't had for five years. There's been a lot of
buildup and hype, and we're officially back now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It relieves a lot of tension that's been festering for five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser and Marlboro Team Penske teammate Emerson Fittipaldi both
failed to make the race in 1995 on speed. The political split
between the Championship Auto Racing Teams and IMS president Tony
George's Indy Racing League has prevented Little Al from competing
here since '95.
</P>
<P>
   The Unsers have enjoyed tremendous success at the Speedway. Al
Unser, Junior's father, is a four-time winner of the Indy 500.
Uncle Bobby won the race three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still `The Greatest Spectacle in Racing,' and it's a
great thing for me, my family and my team,'' said Unser, whose No.
3 ECR Racing Tickets.com G Force/Aurora is owned by Rick Galles.
Unser Jr. and Galles won the 1992 Indy 500, and the longtime
residents of Albuquerque, N.M., reunited in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Unser Jr. said his visit here last May convinced him it was time
to leave CART and Team Penske.
</P>
<P>
   ``You betcha,'' Unser Jr. said. ``What I saw last year on Race
Day looked exactly like I saw in '94. It's the Speedway, and it's
bigger than all of us.'' MONTOYA ANOTHER MANSELL?
</P>
<P>
   Juan Montoya, the reigning CART champion, drew comparisons to
heralded Indy 500 rookie Nigel Mansell after qualifying No. 2 at
223.372 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``That little sucker is pretty quick,'' said Jimmy Vasser, the
1996 CART champion and Montoya's teammate at Target/Chip Ganassi
Racing. ``This isn't the only place he's made look easy. And
believe me, it's not easy. Juan is out there like this (on the
edge), and he's got his car working really good. He's got a lot of
talent, and he's pretty much taken to any place we've gone to. I'm
looking for advice from him half the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansell, the 1992 Formula One World Driving Champion, started
third and finished eighth as an Indy 500 rookie with Newman/Haas
Racing in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Vasser, meanwhile, marked his return to the Speedway for the
first time since the CART-IRL split with a four-lap qualifying
average of 221.976 mph. Vasser will start seventh. FISHER IN THE
SHOW
</P>
<P>
   Teen-ager Sarah Fisher qualified for her first Indy 500 with an
impressive four-lap average of 220.237 mph. She was fourth-fastest
among the five rookies completing attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wide-open on the straightaways, so that was all she
had,'' said Fisher, 19, sounding like a veteran. ``It's been a big
thrill. Al Unser Sr. and I have worked a lot together this month.
He showed me the line around this place, and who better to learn
from than a four-time winner?''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who made her series debut at Texas Motor Speedway in
Fort Worth in October, is driving Derrick Walker's No. 15 Cummins
Special Dallara/Aurora. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
