<HEADER>
A1415 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-T     05-21 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS WILL NEED THEIR SUNDAY BEST TO DIG OUT OF HOLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Tunnel vision doesn't even begin to describe last
season's Stars. They were so hellbent on winning the Stanley Cup,
they didn't need any other motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Well, your 2000 Dallas Stars suffer from a bit of motivational
attention deficit disorder.
</P>
<P>
   They seem to be motivated only after getting embarrassed,
needing their worst to bring out their best. Which is a good thing,
because their worst peeked its ugly head out in Game 3 and their
best needs to make an appearance if they're going to win Game 4 of
the Western Conference Finals at 2 p.m. Sunday at the Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the thing that bothers us a little bit as
coaches. Are we a situation-motivated hockey club? That's what
we've been all year,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We seem to
have to dig ourselves right into a big hole before we dig ourselves
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   If a hole is what the Stars need, they've certainly got one.
</P>
<P>
   They trail the best-of-seven series 2-1. They're playing Game 4
in Denver, where the Avalanche has yet to lose in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, they can't seem to find their offense either. The Stars
have been shut out in two of the first three games. All of their
goals have come from either Mike Modano or Brett Hull. Nary a peep
has been heard from the likes of Joe Nieuwendyk and Jamie
Langenbrunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only line that has really been scoring for us is Mike's
line,'' Langenbrunner said. ``We know as good as anyone it doesn't
work that way. You have to have more than that going.''
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to remedy the situation, Hitchcock juggled his
lines at practice Saturday. He had Scott Thornton on a line with
Modano and Hull. He had Nieuwendyk with Jere Lehtinen and Mike
Keane, while his bottom two lines consisted of Aaron Gavey-Jon
Sim-Grant Marshall and Roman Lyashenko-Kirk Muller-Langenbrunner.
</P>
<P>
   They won't be like this for the game, at least not exactly.
Stars center Guy Carbonneau, who didn't practice, will be in there
somewhere. But Hitchcock said he's likely to play either Sim or
Lyashenko, who have yet to see action in this series, if for no
other reason than to inject some life.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, your attitude is you can either sit and hope you make a
turnaround or you can make it happen. We've always been a group
that's made it happen,'' Hitchcock said. ``We can always go back
right away. But if we're not willing to make changes, if we're not
willing to make adjustments, then we're not trying to get on the
right edge of winning, because right now, when you get shut out two
of three games, you've got to look at yourself in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, we're not going to win with one line scoring.
We're not going to win with one line being dependable defensively.
We're going to need more. We're going to need a lot more. Why not
spread the wealth and see where it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The players seemed impervious to the line changes. The problem,
they insisted, won't be remedied by whom they're playing with,
rather how they are playing.
</P>
<P>
   Which wasn't too well in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically feel that we more or less gave them the game,''
Stars captain and defenseman Derian Hatcher said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars don't believe they played that bad five-on-five. The
problem was they were hardly ever five-on-five. They were in the
penalty box for almost 20 minutes of Game 3. Hitchcock said the
penalties were a symptom of an uninspired performance. Stars winger
Mike Keane thought they were the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what me and Hitch had a talk about,'' Keane said. ``I
think we agreed but disagreed. It's something where, yeah, we had
too many penalties, but we weren't in the game mentally. We had a
talk this morning, a team meeting, and I think you'll see a better
outing (Sunday). We got something out, and we'll be better.''
</P>
<P>
   They usually are. You don't have to look any further than this
series to see that. They were whipped by the Avs in Game 1 and came
back with an inspired performance to win Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for the Stars is they seem to need the bad to get
the good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately for us, we have to have a game like that in
order for us to realize how desperate we have to play and how
mistake-free our game has to be,'' Stars center Mike Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt how desperate the Stars must be now. If they
lose Sunday, they would have to defeat the Avalanche in
back-to-back-to-back games to get back to the Stanley Cup Finals.
Not a likely feat considering how well Colorado goalie Patrick Roy
is playing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Stars aren't willing to say this is a must-win game
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a huge game. I don't want to say it's not,''
Carbonneau said. ``But if we lose, we're not out of the playoffs.
The only game you can't afford to lose in the one that knocks you
out.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
