<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1416 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MEXICO-BORDER-AZR &LR;      05-21 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BORDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER CROSSERS WILL KEEP TRYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARK SHAFFER AND JERRY KAMMER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGUA PRIETA, Sonora _ Cesar Juarez was in a quandary as he
scurried about town Saturday morning, a heavy, dirty backpack slung
over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Juarez, 32, had heard and read the horror stories in the Mexican
media all week as he rode the bus from his home in Morelia,
Michoacan, to this dusty border city with the anticipation of
illegally crossing the border and finding construction work in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Vigilante ranchers in southeastern Arizona were hunting Mexicans
like they were animals. They shot at the feet of some, the heads of
others, and some had been killed. Those that they didn't shoot at,
they were siccing packs of dogs on, the press accounts went.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? There was no turning back now with a wife and two
young children to feed.
</P>
<P>
   Juarez wasn't the only one confused at the end of an eventful
week: The Mexican government had threatened to sue the ranchers
with U.S. lawyers for human rights violations, both governments
condemned ``vigilante justice'' on the Arizona border, the Border
Patrol added 150 agents in southeastern Arizona and the U.S. House
of Representatives approved an amendment seeking the use of
military troops on the border.
</P>
<P>
   Groups of ranchers, saying their land is being ruined by the
human flow northward and the trash it leaves behind, began
patrolling their land with weapons last year and detaining groups
of illegal immigrants for the Border Patrol. Eyebrows were raised
last month when a brochure invited winter visitors to Arizona to
join in the patrolling activities while ranchers allied themselves
with anti-immigrant activists in California.
</P>
<P>
   But Juarez didn't plan on becoming a victim. He had a plan as he
waited for cover of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   He would walk alone, rather than with a group, in an attempt to
avoid detection. He would stay off private property, if he could
make out where it was at night.
</P>
<P>
   He would eat garlic, soak pieces of it in water and splash the
water on his body to try to keep rattlesnakes from biting him. He
would walk 80 miles past farm fields and through the desert
mountains near the community of Dos Cabezas to the train tracks
parallel to Interstate 10.
</P>
<P>
   From there, he would jump a train and catch a ride to Phoenix,
just in case the ranchers also were stopping suspected vehicles of
illegal-immigrant smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   And, if Juarez's luck was bad, he hoped it was the Border Patrol
doing the capturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what the ``migra'' is going to do to you,'' Juarez
said. ``But who knows what these racist gringos with guns would
do?''
</P>
<P>
   Mario Hernandez Olivas, a supervisor at the Mexican office of
migration in Agua Prieta, wonders the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pure racism at its worst,'' Hernandez said. ``All the
Mexicans do is walk on the land. They don't even take bread or
tortillas from those people, yet they are being treated like they
are criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez shook his head at the perceived injustice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has always been a racist country,''
Hernandez said, vigorously typing a visa for a U.S. tourist. ``I
only go there to buy things.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanca Diaz, who owns a new motel across the street from Agua
Prieta's bus station that caters to immigrants, said the ranchers
have been the talk of her cafe for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said a trip to Sonora by Mexican presidential candidate
Vicente Fox on Friday had been closely watched on television by
many of her clients.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said that the ranchers should be prosecuted like criminals
for their ``hunting'' of the immigrants and that the border should
be open for free movement of people in the next five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand this. The United States has a great economy
built on the backs of Mexican workers. But some people full of hate
do things like these to our people,'' Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   But Eduardo Peralta of Jalisco, who said he had immigrated
illegally through Arizona seven times in 10 years and was about to
try again Saturday night, said he couldn't care less about the
ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who worry me are the criminals from Mexico near the
border who steal everything from you,'' Peralta said. ``I was in a
group one time where $1,000 was stolen from one man, $600 from
another and $400 from another. I fear that a lot more than these
ranchers.''
</P>
<P>
   The furor over the ``hunt for illegals'' is receiving enormous
attention in Mexico, where it was front-page news all last week and
has been given dramatic coverage on television.
</P>
<P>
   It was the lead story Thursday on the Televisa network's
national news broadcast, with announcer Joaquin Lopez Doriga
calling it ``one of the most lamentable expressions of racism in
Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Televisa's coverage of trouble on the border included reports of
violence not only in Arizona, but also in Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human-rights organizations agree that the Border Patrol in
California acts with impunity on a daily basis,'' Lopez Doriga
said, introducing a report from California.
</P>
<P>
   That report included an interview with a young Mexican who said
he and several companions were punched and kicked by Border Patrol
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by the Mexican and U.S. governments to calm the rising
tensions along the border were front-page news again Friday. While
most of the coverage was dispassion ate and objective, some of it
expressed the indignation that is widespread here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico demands that the United States stop the hunting of
immigrants,'' one Mexico City daily reported in a front-page
headline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It damages our pride as Mexicans to learn that this is
happening,'' said Juan Ramon Fuentes, 23, a law student in the
southern state of Oaxaca. ``We have heard a lot about the racial
discrimination that Mexicans and other Hispanics suffer in the
United States, and it causes us great concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuentes said he has several friends who have crossed illegally
into the United States, where they have found work that pays them
as much in a day as they can earn in two weeks of work at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to leave, and they don't want to separate
themselves from their families,'' Fuentes said. ``But they are
looking for a way to earn money to help their families. Our
salaries here just don't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   About a half-hour drive west of Oaxaca City, Justino Vasquez
said the news from Arizona would affect his plans for returning in
September to Arizona, where he and his brother have worked in
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't cross the border at Douglas,'' said Justino, 22, who
has spent the past several months at his parents' home in the small
town of Zaachila. He and brother German, 19, worked most of Friday
in their parents' 2-acre field that provides corn in September and
beans in February.
</P>
<P>
   Justino said the $500 he and German sent home every month is
vital to his family's survival in an economy where there is little
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same for a lot of families here,'' he said,
estimating that 45 percent of them depend on the money orders that
flow from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Hunting' is a vulgar word to use about human beings,''
German said. ``It is a word to use about animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Justino said he worries about the outbreak of hostility in
Arizona but said he intends to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some racists, but most of the people there know that
we come only with the intention of working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he is hoping that the U.S. government will grant an
amnesty similar to that which was granted in the 1980s and allowed
millions of Mexicans to legalize their presence in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, Juana Maldonado talked angrily about the border
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it possible that such things can happen to human
beings?'' she said, chopping a slab of beef at the street-side taco
stand where she and two others work all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't they know that Mexicans are human beings?'' she
demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Maldonado, 37, conceded that the United States has a right to
control its borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean that people have the the right to take
the law into their own hands.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
