<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-FORECHECK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS NEED A BETTER FORECHECK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER_ There is a reason the defending Stanley Cup champions
have three goals in three games.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado goalie Patrick Roy has something to do with it.
Penalties have something to do with it. The Stars' forecheck, or
it's untimely disappearance, has almost everything to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the problem,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``The
forecheck is one thing. But, the forecheck is no good if you don't
have proper positioning. Our positioning was terrible (Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   In a series where goals have been sparse, the Stars need to
forecheck better to begin scoring and win Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it all starts with our forecheck,'' Stars
defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``We have to dump the puck better.
Game 2 we had a great forecheck and got opportunities. We didn't
have that going (in Game 3), and defensively we were out of
position a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   For four periods, the third in Game 1 and all of Game 2, Dallas
had its forecheck going. During that stretch, they outshot
Colorado, 47-24, and spent 42 percent of the time in the Avs zone.
As a result, the Stars were scoring, and winning: Three goals and
one win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our forwards allowed them too much speed; we weren't
skating,'' former Stars and current Avs forward Dave Reid said.
``We were standing around, and we let them blow by us on
dump-ins.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a key because for the other five periods, the first two in
Game 1 and all of Game 3, Colorado had its forecheck going. The Avs
enjoyed a plus-24 shooting margin and had the puck in the Dallas
zone 45 percent of the time. The result was four Avalanche goals
and two wins.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Colorado playing without Adam Foote, its most physical
defenseman who could return Sunday, the Stars were outshot, 40-21,
in Game 3. Of course, the Stars serving almost 20 minutes in
penalties had something to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have to start staying out of the penalty box, too,
so we can get into that flow of getting a good first-man forecheck
and bottling them up in their own end,'' Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk said. ``That's going to be a big key (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   More telling than penalties, however, was the way Colorado
prevented Dallas from dumping the puck in, chasing defenders and
pressuring Roy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did to us what we want to do to them,'' Stars defenseman
Richard Matvichuk said. ``They clogged the neutral zone very well.
When you are slowing guys down like (Mike) Modano and Nieuwendyk,
they have to get the puck in.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, when you are held up, it's tough to get the forecheck
going. In Game 2, we got the puck deep, we had room to skate, and
it was going, and we were banging and hitting, and it makes a big
difference. ... Penalties are the big deal. You can't get any
momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but history has shown that this isn't always penalties.
And, the Stars know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts with our competitive level and us playing better,''
Stars captain Derian Hatcher said. ``It's a lot like Game 1. We
weren't playing well. But, it's hard to get a forecheck going when
you are in the box for 20 minutes.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
