<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AX-DEATH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
79-YEAR-OLD MAN ARRESTED AFTER WIFE IS SLAIN WITH AX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES F. BOSTWICK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LITTLEROCK, Calif. _ A 71-year-old woman, long physically
abused by her husband, was found Saturday beaten to death with an
ax in her bed, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles County sheriff's deputy called the case a
``terrible case of domestic violence'' after arresting her husband,
79-year-old Hollis Medford, on suspicion of murder.
</P>
<P>
   After Medford called authorities to report he had assaulted his
wife, deputies found Vonia Medford bludgeoned to death in her home
in north Los Angeles County about 4:30a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we understand there has been a history of abusive
behavior,'' said Lt. Tom Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Vonia Medford had confided some of her marriage history to
friend and neighbor Audrey Rose, who lives near the couple's
single-story stucco home in the 8800 block of East AvenueT-2.
</P>
<P>
   Rose said Medford told her about five years ago she wanted to
leave her husband but that she never did. She said she gave Medford
a key to her home and told her to come in whenever she needed to
get away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was scared to death of him,'' said Rose, noting Vonia
Medford would not call the police on her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who cared for the couple's three dogs at her Doggie Wash
grooming shop, said occasionally she would see Medford with bruise
marks on her arm or marks on her face.
</P>
<P>
   When Rose questioned the marks, ``She'd just say, `You know
father and his temperament.' She called him father. He was very
controlling. He wouldn't allow her to have control of any money,''
Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Six or seven weeks ago, Rose said, one of her employees
threatened to call sheriff's deputies on Hollis Medford after he
started screaming and cursing because his dogs weren't ready when
he arrived to pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   After Rose told Vonia Medford her husband was banned from the
shop, he called back to apologize, saying he had had a bad day,
Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Medford's violent death stunned other neighbors in this quaint
city, dubbed the ``Fruit Basket of the Antelope Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   One resident said the Medfords bought a house in Littlerock, a
town of 9,000 people located north of Devil's Punchbowl, 15 years
ago after moving from Santa Clarita. The resident described the
couple as quiet neighbors who waved when they drove by.
</P>
<P>
   ``To meet the guy, you would never in a hundred years believe he
could do that,'' the neighbor said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said Hollis Medford -- also known as Glenn -- had once
been an engineer and later worked in real estate. His wife had been
a registered nurse. The couple had three grown children, none
living locally.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators would not say how large or heavy the ax was or
whether the Medford was killed in her sleep, said Deputy Bruce
Thomas. Thomas did not know whether the victim had ever complained
to authorities in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Medford was being held without bail at the Lancaster sheriff's
station, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
