<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1424 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-21 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSIVE APPROACH ALMOST COSTS LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Was that an eyesore of a quarter or what? Yes,
indeed. There can be no ignoring it.
</P>
<P>
   The way the third quarter unfolded Saturday at the Staples
Center, the Lakers should consider themselves lucky to hold a 1-0
lead over Portland in their best-of-seven Western Conference Final.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand: We wholeheartedly agree the final 12
minutes of the Lakers' 109-94 win over the Trail Blazers was
basketball at its most abominable - ``The NBA: It's Foul-tastic!''
</P>
<P>
   But the Trail Blazers would have thought twice about chasing
Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal all over the court so they could put
him on the foul-line on a dirty dozen possessions in the fourth
quarter if the Lakers had buried the Trail Blazers when they had
the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Any way you look at it, the Lakers pieced together a marvelous
first half, effectively shooting down the Trail Blazers' strategy
of doubling down on O'Neal and Kobe Bryant and daring some bit
player to step up and beat them.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry let it be known he was ready for his close-up. Did
he ever. He made three of four shots from beyond the arc on his way
to 12 points in eight second-quarter minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice also was primed for his star turn. He contributed 10
first-half points. Two of his baskets were three-pointers, which
means in 18 minutes he matched his success from beyond the 3-point
arc in 134 regular-season minutes against the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Horry, who throughout the postseason has been the Lakers' MVP
(Most Valuable Perimeter shooter), scored two more points than all
of the much-ballyhooed Portland bench in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   His fellow Laker reserves Rick Fox and Brian Shaw outscored the
Trail Blazers' starting center Arvydas Sabonis 8-0 and Bryant and
O'Neal each had five assists, one more than Portland starting point
guard Damon Stoudamire, as the Lakers roared to a 63-42 lead at
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission in the second half was clear. It was to take that
21-point lead they had built in the second quarter and grow it like
an Internet stock in a bull market. NBA championship-caliber teams
tend to be awfully bloodless that way. Today's day traders would
appear downright sentimental next to Magic Johnson's Lakers or
Michael Jordan's Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers had taken care of business properly, O'Neal would
have been on the bench in the fourth quarter watching John Salley
log garbage minutes instead of parading to the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, the Lakers are at the ``terrible twelves'' of their
development. That's the phase where you build a big lead and then
turn all undisciplined and impatient for a quarter, just long
enough to give your opponent a boost of confidence and renewed
life.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers grew so enamored of their dazzling 66.7 percent
shooting from beyond the 3-point arc in the first half, they came
out in the third quarter and forgot their offense works best when
they give O'Neal a touch or 20.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, Horry and Bryant all were guilty of taking quick shots
instead of letting the shot clock be their ally. They misfired on
three of four shots from beyond the 3-point arc, their defensive
intensity waned and next thing they knew they had lost the quarter
30-22.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got happy feet,'' Horry said. ``We were trying to shoot
more 3s instead of getting it inside to Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers' path suddenly illuminated by that flicker at
the end of the tunnel, they managed to draw to within nine points
of the Lakers with five minutes remaining before their hack-a-Shaq
strategy blew up in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers forged their comeback without power forward
Rasheed Wallace, who provides a monster of a match-up problem for
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that's consistently been able to stop him is his
own temper. It got the best of him again Saturday when he drew a
second technical foul for glaring at the referee after he had been
warned not to and was ejected with 6:43 remaining in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   How Wallace managed to collect two technicals before Sabonis,
the poor sap strapped with the primary responsibility of stopping
O'Neal, collected his second foul is something for Portland coach
Mike Dunleavy to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   How the Trail Blazers managed to outscore the Lakers 42-36 after
Wallace repaired to the visitors' locker room is something for the
Lakers to think hard about before Monday's Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a huge lead and after that we weren't as aggressive
defensively,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked him about the foul-filled fourth and Fox's eyes
narrowed to the size of an assassin's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pissed us off,'' he said. ``I'm sure it makes the big fella
even more perturbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Perturbed is good. It definitely beats passive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
