<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1425 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-21 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAGON SLAYED BY LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The villagers were terrified, cowering in the
Staples Center, listening for the roar of the nine-headed dragon
that laid waste to Minnesota and Utah on its way to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland Trail Blazers, the monster that ate Kevin Garnett
and Karl Malone, were thundering into town, supposedly to make a
main course of Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   But when they arrived Saturday they looked less like the
creature of NBA myth that we'd heard so much about, and more like
an ill-tempered poodle.
</P>
<P>
   They whined (before the Western Conference Finals series even
began). They nipped at O'Neal's ankles, repeatedly and futilely.
They rolled over at the very point in Game 1 when those nine heads
were expected to come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   With their subs outshot by the Lakers' subs, the Blazers fell 24
points behind in the second quarter and had to employ an ugly
tactic in the fourth to make the 109-94 game interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we don't look forward to doing all the
time,'' Brian Grant said of the decision to foul O'Neal
intentionally 12 times in the final 5 minutes, putting the pressure
on the league's most prolific bad free-throw shooter. ``It might
have worked if we'd put the ball in the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   While O'Neal was making 12 of 24 foul shots, including seven in
a row, to keep the Lakers afloat, the Blazers were missing 7 of 8
shots from the floor, not denting their deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Dunleavy's Hack-a-Shaq strategy seemed to take the
Blazers right out of their offensive flow, or so somebody suggested
to him after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it look like we had any flow (before that)?'' Dunleavy
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, no.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers had let this one get away in the first half, just
when it appeared the Lakers were in for an afternoon-long fight. It
was tied at the end of the first quarter when the benches began to
stir.
</P>
<P>
   The bench was said to be Portland's big edge. The Lakers had two
heads, Shaq's and Kobe's, and the Blazers had nine. That's how they
ended up with the NBA's second-best record, without placing an
individual among the top 40 scorers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the subs came into play Saturday, it was all Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   It was 24-24 when Grant went in for Rasheed Wallace, 26-24
Lakers when Robert Horry replaced A.C. Green, 33-28 when Detlef
Schrempf replaced Arvydas Sabonis and Greg Anthony replaced Damon
Stoudamire, and 35-28 by the time Wallace returned in place of
Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   See a trend?
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher gave Bryant a rest, and Bonzi Wells went in for
Steve Smith when it was 44-28 - and Portland continued to dig its
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had new guys coming in, myself included,'' Grant said,
``and I don't think we were in the flow right away. We wanted to
let Horry show he could make shots, and he made some 3's, and then
everybody got a little 3-crazy. ... It was a momentum thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, our bench didn't play very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The stake through the forehead was delivered by Horry and Rick
Fox, who'd come in for Glen Rice between quarters, with 3-pointers
on either side of Anthony dribbling a ball off his foot at
mid-court. That completed a 14-0 run that made it 44-28.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers had challenged the lesser Lakers to beat them,
double-teaming not only O'Neal but Bryant as well, only to watch
Horry respond with 12 first-half points, Brian Shaw step up with
five first-half assists and the L.A. bench outscore the Portland
bench 15-2 during the pivotal 22-2 run.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers had challenged the officials, too.
</P>
<P>
   During the buildup to this quarterfinal matchup of the NBA's
best teams, Dunleavy had issued a pre-emptive complaint about the
referees' treatment of O'Neal, saying the Lakers center is
``allowed to push guys out of the way'' and to ``zone up'' on
defense. ``I think I counted 57 times,'' Dunleavy said, that O'Neal
should have been whistled for zone defense in one game.
</P>
<P>
   The officials might have responded, just not as the Blazers
hoped. Shaq was called for just two fouls all day despite some of
Sabonis' best flops (one of which looked something like the
backstroke). The Lakers weren't warned for a zone until midway
through the second quarter (56 to go!). And Wallace was hit with
two technical fouls and was ejected midway through the third
quarter, the second T apparently coming because Wallace defied ref
Ron Garretson's warning not to glare at him from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officials seem to be a little quick with him,'' Pippen said of
Wallace. ``He speaks with a different aggression than the average
person.''
</P>
<P>
   He must glare with a different aggression as well.
</P>
<P>
   Prognosticators from here to Portland were taking the Blazers to
win the best-of-seven-game series in six, but you get the
impression they weren't quite so confident.
</P>
<P>
   Fussing, flopping, fouling - that's not the work of a dragon.
</P>
<P>
   The dragon slinked back out of town with its heads down, to work
on a better plan for Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us look at the tapes,'' Pippen said when asked what might
be different next time. ``Right now we'll just be happy to get out
of the building and forget about this game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
