<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLACE'S PLIGHT OF STARES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hey, you looking at me?
</P>
<P>
   Not a good idea, not if you're Rasheed Wallace and have a court
history just this side of Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Not if the one being stared at is Ron Garretson, the official to
last join Lakers' lore when Nick Van Exel tried to toss him over a
scorer's table.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is the Trail Blazers' leading scorer and the NBA's No. 1
hothead. During the regular season, he was ejected by officials a
league-high six times.
</P>
<P>
   Add an overall No. 7 after Wallace was tossed out in the third
quarter of Saturday's playoff opener against the Lakers for ...
drum roll, please ... staring.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's come to this for the wild-eyed, 6-foot-11 forward. He
kept looking at Garretson wrong, which was one of the best things
the Lakers saw all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a first,'' said Blazers forward Brian Grant. ``I ain't
never heard of that before. We'll have to be more conscious of
that, be more careful the way we look at the refs.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace had already drawn a first-half technical for a verbal
outburst, and when he failed to heed Garretson's repeated warnings
to stop staring at him in the third quarter, he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Much to the surprise of many.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised, too,'' said Wallace, in what was about his
only postgame comment.
</P>
<P>
   To Portland's players, it was all very wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those referees just really don't like Rasheed,'' said Blazer
Bonzi Wells. ``I mean, Rasheed is a great guy. He just plays
intense. Just because he look at you don't mean that he's coming at
you, or cussing at you. I could understand that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a look? That's just so petty. I think they're just trying
to put a meaning out there for Rasheed and let him know they're not
going to take it - but I don't think it's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be a swell guy in the locker room, but he has the way
of looking like he should be driving a taxi with Robert DeNiro to
officials.
</P>
<P>
   For Wallace, this is a very old story. In that special land
where Wallace resides, the officials have gotten the call wrong
against him every time.
</P>
<P>
   And too often Wallace can do the one thing the Lakers never can
- stop Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to have him on the floor,'' Blazers
coach Mike Dunleavy said. ``In some point in time, he has got to
understand that. And no matter what the circumstances are - even if
he's right and it's a bad call - it doesn't do us any good, because
he's in the locker room and we're on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say under these circumstances I agree with it, but if
Ronnie Garretson told him not to look at him and he looks at him,
he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone with 11 points in just 16 minutes. Gone without any Laker
even having to bait him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually did that on his own,'' said Lakers guard Brian
Shaw. ``Nobody really did get into a pushing match with him or a
verbal confrontation. That was just between him and the referees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 0216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
