<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ HURT, BUT GALAXY WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Considering he arrived from Monterrey, Mexico 24
hours earlier, hadn't trained a lick with his new Galaxy teammates,
Mexican superstar Luis Hernandez's MLS debut was going smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   That is until Hernandez walked out after 72 minutes holding his
right shoulder in pain. Hernandez fell to the turf earlier after a
collision with D.C. United's Carlos Llamosa. It didn't appear
serious, but MLS' biggest foreign acquisition, whom the league paid
nearly $5 million to purchase his contract from Tigres, was taken
to St. Luke's Hospital in Pasadena. It turned out to be only a
scare. He was diagnosed with an A.C. joint strain of his left
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feet came out from underneath me,'' said Hernandez. ``I
have a little pain, it hurts when I move it.''
</P>
<P>
   But before he left, Hernandez showed a glimpse of why the Galaxy
parted with nearly a third of their starting lineup to acquire him.
Hernandez played a big part in both goals that gave the Galaxy a
2-1 victory over MLS champion D.C. United in front of 40,303 at the
Rose Bowl -- the biggest crowd of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez chased Carrey Talley on a Mauricio Cienfuegos pass
deep in United territory. Hearing Hernandez give chase, Talley
accidentally headed in an own goal to give the Galaxy a 1-0 lead in
the 35th minute.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, a three-touch combination from Cienfuegos to
Hernandez to Jones, forced United defender Carlos Llamosa to foul
Jones from behind in the penalty box. Greg Vanney converted the
penalty, giving the Galaxy a 2-0 lead in the 75th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's touch was off a little, but he was pleased overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking into consideration not having practiced with the team,
it went well,'' said Hernandez. ``Once I train they will understand
me better. They will know when I run up the sideline or take a
cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Judah Cooks scored for United in the 75th minute, but the Galaxy
held on to improve to 6-0-5 while United dropped their fourth
straight to fall to a league-worst, 2-9-1.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Hernandez, the Galaxy received more disheartening
news when captain Robin Fraser turned his ankle sliding into
United's Jeff Agoos. He will miss Wednesday's game with New England
and is listed day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Hernandez was scheduled to miss Wednesday's game and
fly back to Mexico to take care of personal issues and check on his
wife, who is seven months pregnant. His injury, however, leaves him
day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was a big win, and a better-than-expected debut from
Hernandez, but it came with a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reading a story saying what would happen if Luis gets
injured and is out for a long time,'' said Schmid. ``I hope that's
not a predictor. And with Robin, he's out for Wednesday, so it's
just a further test of our character and depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering everything, Schmid was pleased with Hernandez's
debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing him in the locker room before the game, you saw the
adrenalin build up in him as the game got closer,'' said Schmid.
``Even after the introductions, you see him sort of ball his fists
together and say c'mon let's go'.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was also obvious his touch was off a little bit. He
hasn't played the last two weeks. But as we move forward, we're
going to see better and better things from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Danny Pena had mixed emotions about the victory.
With Fraser out and Hernandez already off to Mexico, he's worried
about the constant lineup changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in serious trouble if we lose Robin for an extended
period of time,'' said Pena. ``He's our captain and our voice back
there. Now, Hernandez will not be here for a midweek game. It's
frustrating. I was hoping when he got here he was here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a tough road ahead, we are losing all kinds of
national team players with World Cup qualifying commitments in a
few weeks. We're going to be a serious depleted team. We have to do
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
