<HEADLINE>
STARS PLAYERS NOT HAPPY ABOUT DAY GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD, CHAREAN WILLIAMS AND MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Dallas Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said just about
everything that needed to be said after Friday's loss in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated one particular point before practice Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said this to the players this morning, we wasted a helluva
effort by a goaltender,'' Hitchcock said of Ed Belfour, who
finished with 38 saves in Game 3. ``You don't want to waste those,
but we did. That's what's frustrating for us. We needed our
goaltender to be great for us to win on the road, and he was, and
we didn't give ourselves a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour will have to buck a personal trend to deliver another
such performance Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The key word is Sunday. Belfour, a self-admitted night person,
isn't exactly good at day games. The Stars played eight of them
this season. He played in seven, going 2-3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour isn't the only Stars player not so crazy about the day
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go through 82 games playing at 7 or 7:30 (p.m.), you do it
all year and TV comes in and gets to pick and choose when you get
to play,'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``I guess that is
where the money is but I think it's a joke.'' WHERE'S THE POWER?
</P>
<P>
   Penalties, lack of scoring _ there are many things that could be
pointed to as the culprits for the Stars being behind 2-1 in their
best-of-seven series with the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Don't the forget power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were 0-for-3 with a man advantage in Game 3, including
failing to capitalize on two early power plays. They're 1-for-13 in
the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we'd like to have our power play a little better,''
Stars center Guy Carbonneau said. ``Power plays and penalty killing
will be important parts of the game. We have to take advantage of
our power play, especially on the road.'' PLAY TIME
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said Jon Sim and Roman Lyashenko could
play Sunday. Sim has yet to make his playoff debut, while Lyashenko
has played in eight playoff games but has been a healthy scratch
for all three games of the Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's on the agenda,'' Hitchcock said. ``One or both are
going to come in (Sunday). Obviously, Lyashenko is a real physical
player, very strong on the puck, which looks like it's what's
needed in this series. Sim is an offensive threat. He's a guy who's
hungry around the net. He's a guy who will do anything to score a
goal. We're probably looking like we're going to need some of that
jump right now.'' HOME ICE
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche, who are 7-0 at Pepsi Center in the playoffs, used
their home-ice advantage in Game 3, according to the Stars. The
Stars talked about Colorado ``playing the rink'' better than they
did.
</P>
<P>
   But with a game under their belts, the Stars expect to ``play
the rink'' better Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rink is a 200-foot surface, but it doesn't play as a
200-foot surface,'' Hitchcock said. ``The corners come up very
quickly. They use the glass to their advantage here.
</P>
<P>
   ``...They play this rink very well. They're smart. They know
this rink, and they did a terrific job in playing it the right
way.'' MORROW SKATING
</P>
<P>
   Only eight days after fracturing his right ankle in Game 1 of
the Western Conference Finals, Stars rookie winger Brenden Morrow
was back on the ice Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can put a little bit of weight on it, but it's different in
a skate,'' Morrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow, who was injured when he got tangled with Colorado's Dave
Andreychuk late in Game 1, recently was told that his ankle doesn't
require surgery. There is a remote chance that if the Stars advance
to the Stanley Cup Finals, he could play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I want to reinjure for just being stupid
and trying,'' he said. ``But, if it feels really good (Sunday)
we'll see.'' GAME 4 QUESTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Game 4s have been good to the Stars in the playoffs. They are
2-0 so far. In their franchise history, they are 21-19 in the
fourth game.
</P>
<P>
   As added reference, they were 1-3 in the 1999 Stanley Cup
playoffs, including losing Game 4, 3-2, at Colorado in last
season's Western Conference Finals. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
