<HEADLINE>
AVS' SAKIC QUIETLY GETTING JOB DONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ If Joe Sakic isn't scoring goals, he's spending his
off-ice time answering why.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's his own fault. Maybe he has been so good over his 12
NHL seasons that he has spoiled his critics. Maybe his 18 goals to
lead all playoff scorers, and 34 points, during the Avs' 1996
Stanley Cup run that earned him the Conn Smythe Trophy as playoff
MVP, set the bar entirely too high.
</P>
<P>
   Through 13 playoff games, the Avs are two wins away from a
return trip to the Stanley Cup Finals. Yet, Sakic has only two
goals, and everyone wants to know, ``Where's Joe?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't worry outside the dressing room, the talking that
goes on,'' Sakic said. ``You just have to try your best and help
the hockey team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as he did in a myriad of ways in Game 3, a 2-0 victory that
gave the Avs a 2-1 series lead heading into Sunday's Game 4 of the
Western Conference Finals. He remained goalless in the series, but
Sakic is a major reason the Avs lead the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Joe Sakic is not scoring goals,'' linemate Dave Andreychuk
said, ``he's doing a lot of other things.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3, Sakic dominated in the faceoff circle, the biggest
coming with almost 15 minutes elapsed in the second period with the
Avs on the power play and trying to build on a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   He outdueled Stars center Guy Carbonneau, getting the puck to
defenseman Martin Skoula at the point. Skoula launched a shot that
Adam Deadmarsh redirected at the top of the crease and into the net
for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   He won 20 of 29 faceoffs, including key victories late in the
third period when the Stars played desperately in the Avs' zone. He
also turned up the offensive heat. His eight shots in Game 3
doubled his output in the first two games and he led all forwards
in ice time, playing 24 minutes, 29 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we wanted to get more pucks on net and be more
assertive in the offensive zone,'' Sakic said of his line. which
had one-fourth of the Avs' total shot output with 10. ``It's
something we talked about, and we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   On a team loaded with goal scorers, Sakic's greatest asset too
often goes unheralded. Like his Stars counterpart, Mike Modano, he
unselfishly sacrifices
</P>
<P>
   offense for defense. He goes up against the opposition's top
centers. Against Phoenix in the first round he checked Jeremy
Roenick. Against Detroit he faced Steve Yzerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This round it's got to be either (Joe) Nieuwendyk or (Mike)
Modano,'' Avs coach Bob Hartley said. ``His role hasn't changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano and Nieuwendyk were no-shows in Games 1 and 3. And should
Sakic start finding the back of the net again, it makes the
explosive Avs even tougher to defend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe wants to make plays, Joe wants to get points, Joe wants to
score goals, Joe wants to take great pride in his defensive game
and penalty killing,'' said assistant coach Bryan Trottier, a
tremendous goal scorer throughout the 1980s for the New York
Islanders. ``He's one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sakic, ``As long as we win hockey games, it doesn't
matter.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
