<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO WON'T TAKE GAME 4 LIGHTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Avalanche failed to eliminate the Stars on two
occasions in last season's conference finals. Entering Sunday's
Game 4, they have the chance to give themselves three cracks at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to take that game lightly; it is a big game
for us,'' goalie Patrick Roy said. ``Now, we are up 2-1 in the
series and we know that we still have to win two more games to win
the series, and they won't be easy games. If Adam (Foote) could be
back, we would be pretty strong.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance the Avs' injured defenseman could be back
Sunday. He practiced Saturday for the second consecutive day
wearing a full visor. Although Foote declared himself ready for
duty, doctors have not yet cleared him to play. The right corner of
his right eye remains red. He was injured in Game 2 when the blade
of Jere Lehtinen's stick caught the corner of his eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``The face shield felt good. I will get evaluated again today
and every day, and they are going to let me play when they feel
it's 100 percent,'' Foote said. ``I want to play. I wanted to play
(Friday) night. I feel like I could have played four days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche coach Bob Hartley continued to toe the company line,
saying he expects Foote to return during the series. Hartley just
doesn't know when.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs fared well without Foote, limiting the Stars to 11 shots
through two periods and keeping the Stars' top two lines quiet.
Whether or not Foote plays, the Avs want to head back to Dallas for
Game 5 leading 3-1 instead of tied 2-2 and handing home-ice
advantage back to the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we said this morning in the room is probably the
same thing that was said in the Stars' room,'' Hartley said. ``We
know the importance of the game. It should be a great matchup.''
BOURQUE FINE DAY AFTER
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Ray Bourque, 39, felt no ill-effects in his left knee
after logging 35 minutes, 35 seconds of action in Game 3, his first
game time since spraining the knee May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good last night, and usually you know you're in trouble
after a game if you're cramping up or whatever,'' Bourque said.
``Last night I felt fine, and I knew waking up I would be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque also returned to quarterback a busy power play and play
on the penalty-kill unit. Avs coach Bob Hartley said he was not
concerned about overplaying Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works so hard to get ready,'' Hartley said. ``There was no
way that I would stop him from running like that. I have said
before I believe a thoroughbred needs to run, and he is one of the
best.'' HOT ROY
</P>
<P>
   Avs goalie Patrick Roy is on top of his game. He has two
shutouts in three games and has stopped 76 of 79 shots. His
goals-against average is a playoff-low 1.52.
</P>
<P>
   He said the biggest key against the Stars has been scoring
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against them it is always key to take the lead. When you play
with the lead it is always a lot easier,'' Roy said. I'm very
pleased with the way the guys are playing right now. The team is
very sharp and very focused.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
