A1434 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-NBA-LOTTERY-TEX     05-21 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LOTTERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS' PICK RESTS WITH BOUNCE OF PINGPONG BALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SECAUCUS, N.J. _ Don Nelson always has fun with the NBA Draft
Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   When he was coaching the Golden State Warriors, the team urged
fans to send their lucky charms so Nelson could carry them to New
York for the lottery. In 1993, Nelson wound up taking a bag full of
trinkets to the Big Apple, but there was one item that stood out
the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one that I carried in my pocket that year was a good luck
charm that a farmer's cow had swallowed,'' Nelson recalled while
laughing. ``It was a big old piece of metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow they cut it out of the cow's belly, and the cow
survived and they sent me that as a lucky charm. That's when we
went from six to three.''
</P>
<P>
   That year, Nelson used his lottery luck to draft Penny Hardaway
with the third pick overall. He subsequently traded Hardaway on
draft day to the Orlando Magic for Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cuban, the Dallas Mavericks' billionaire owner, hopes to be
so lucky when he represents the Mavericks in the 2000 Draft Lottery
on Sunday during halftime of Game 7 in the New York-Miami Eastern
Conference semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban won't divulge his lucky charms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I am superstitious,'' Cuban said. ``And no, you will
never know what (the lucky charms) are unless they work.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban, buoyed by the Mavs' 16-5 record during the last six weeks
of the season, is not holding out hope that his team will beat the
odds and win Sunday's lottery. And it might not matter where the
team selects.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous lotteries, there is no consensus prize player
available in this year's draft. The top prospects include
Cincinnati power forward Kenyon Martin, Texas center Chris Mihm and
Iowa State forward Marcus Fizer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks didn't even keep their past two No. 1 draft
choices. Nelson dealt Robert Traylor in 1998 and Kelvin Cato in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have a much better team next year whether we
get the No. 1 pick or the No. 13 pick,'' Cuban said. ``So we expect
to get some help, and we will go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA went to a lottery system in 1985, after repeated
complaints from then-Mavericks coach Dick Motta about the
possibility of the Houston Rockets ``tanking'' games late in the
season in order to receive a favorable draft position.
</P>
<P>
   Before the lottery, the last-place team in the Western
Conference flipped a coin with the last-place in the Eastern
Conference. The winner received the top pick, and the loser
selected No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets won coin flips in 1983 and '84, and capitalized by
selecting Ralph Sampson and Hakeem Olajwuon, respectively. After
that, the lottery was born, although some purists still favor the
previous system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather do (the coin flip) where the worst team gets (a
50-50 shot) at the No. 1 pick,'' Nelson said. ``But the league was
worried about teams not trying to win toward the end of the season,
so this is a pretty fair alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   The 13 teams that failed to make the playoffs qualify for the
lottery. The Mavericks, seeded 12th among the 13 lottery teams,
have a 6-in-1,000 chance of winning the No. 1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   In 15 years of the lottery, the highest the Mavericks finished
was second in 1994. The Mavericks drafted Jason Kidd after the
Milwaukee Bucks, who won the lottery, selected Glenn Robinson No.
1.
</P>
<P>
   The highest other lottery finishes for the Mavericks occurred in
1993 and '94, when they drafted fourth overall both years and
selected Jim Jackson and Jamal Mashburn, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The league has restructured the lottery system in favor of the
teams with the worst records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to draft 12th, and if something crazy happens
it'll be great,'' said Nelson, who will watch the lottery from his
North Dallas home. ``If we do win it I'll get awful excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I sent all of those lucky charms back to the (Warriors')
fans, so I don't have that lucky charm. If I had it, I'd give it to
Mark.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 0251EDT &QL; 
