<HEADER>
A1435 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-REEVES-INSIDERS-COLUM     05-21 1708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-INSIDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE EXTRA PUDGE ADDS WEIGHT TO DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Confession time: At spring training in March, I took
one look at Pudge Rodriguez's _ ahem _ spreading posterior and
quietly wondered if this would be the year the slide would begin.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, he's sliding all right. Sliding right into such elite
status that it's not at all unusual to hear talk show callers and
hosts debating whether he might be the greatest catcher of all
time.
</P>
<P>
   Or even the greatest player of all time.
</P>
<P>
   I should have known, having seen Rodriguez's dedication to his
workout regimen, that if his tail looked bigger _ as many a
catcher's do after years of squatting behind the plate _ in his
case it was more likely added muscle.
</P>
<P>
   To this point, Rodriguez has given us a glimpse of what may be a
season for the ages. Just when you think he can't get any better,
he takes his game to yet another, higher level.
</P>
<P>
   Now folks are kicking his name around with the greatest ever:
Ruth, Aaron, Mays, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, all that may be somewhat premature, but the fact is, there
have been few players in the history of the game who possessed his
combination of pure, natural hitting ability and incredible
defense.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be the best ever _ only time will tell _ but he has
certainly earned the right to be mentioned with them.
</P>
<P>
   As far as being the best catcher ever, only Johnny Bench is even
close and he's losing ground daily. LUDS TO FORT WORTH?
</P>
<P>
   Former Dallas Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig is on the Fort Worth
Brahmas' short list of head coaching candidates, and _ considering
his long relationship with former Stars teammate Andy Moog, one of
the franchise owners _ it's safe to say the job is his if he
decides he wants it.
</P>
<P>
   There's a holdup, however, while Ludwig considers other options
that might arise with the Stars. He could wind up as part of the
coaching staff at the team's new minor-league affiliate in Utah
(Kalamazoo is shutting its operation).
</P>
<P>
   The Brahmas would love to have a high-profile former NHL star as
their coach, so they'll wait on Ludwig, who probably won't announce
his decision until after the Stars are either eliminated from the
playoffs or win a second consecutive Stanley Cup. GIVE HIM A RAISE
</P>
<P>
   Note to Texas Rangers owner Tom Hicks: Hitting coach Rudy
Jaramillo deserves a hefty bonus and right now. He has the Rangers
leading the league in hitting and on-base percentage despite losing
two-time MVP Juan Gonzalez and the fact that new right fielder Gabe
Kapler was scraping along under .200 before injuring his right
quadriceps muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo has been patient with youngsters Mike Lamb and Ruben
Mateo, and he helped second baseman Luis Alicea pull out of an
early season slump. They've all been hotter than a downtown Fort
Worth sidewalk in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy has done a great job,'' manager Johnny Oates said, ``and
the players have been willing to work at it. Lamb and \RTom Evans\S
have actually added a new dimension for us by being able to
hit-and-run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, we don't run a lot. Why would you want to run
into an out when you've got a three-run homer a batter away?''
LIARS LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche had injured defenseman Adam Foote on the ice
Friday morning, wearing a full face shield to protect his injured
right eye, even though they had said he wouldn't skate in Game 3
Friday night. Of course, we all know by now that NHL actually
stands for National Hockey Liars.
</P>
<P>
   This might be the only sports league in North America where it's
considered A-OK to stand up in front of the media and tell
bald-faced lies about injuries and whether or not a player might
actually play.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, you can't believe anything you're told and only about half
of what you see.
</P>
<P>
   But consider this: the Stars' Darryl Sydor missed two weeks with
what was apparently an injury very similar to Foote's. With this
kind of eye injury _ though the Avs certainly haven't given details
on just what kind of injury Foote has _ the player cannot afford to
get his blood pressure too high without fear of rupturing a blood
vessel in the eye and risking permanent loss of vision.
</P>
<P>
   There's a good chance Foote won't play again in this series.
</P>
<P>
   That means, of course, he'll probably be back Sunday afternoon
for Game 4. In the NHL, it's all about subterfuge, trickery and
misdirection.
</P>
<P>
   And if the media and fans get faked out in the process, too bad.
MAKE GOALIES FAIR GAME
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion to the NHL: Remove the invisible force field from
goaltenders and make them fair game if they stray out of the
crease. That'll cut down on some of the Meryl Streep theatrics we
keep seeing whenever another player so much as looks in their
direction.
</P>
<P>
   It's really simple: Stay in the crease and nobody is allowed to
touch them. Come out of the crease to play the puck _ like the
Stars' Eddie Belfour and Colorado's Patrick Roy like to do _ and
they take their chances with the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   It only seems fair _ goalies wear more armor than a medieval
knight _ but Stars coach Ken Hitchcock says they still need
protection, even out of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in a playoff series where I've lost a goaltender
\Rto injury\S and it's very traumatic,'' Hitchcock said. ``You
count on a guy all season and then he's gone. That's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   No, tough is watching a player sit in the penalty box because he
had the audacity to get within 10 feet of the opposing goalie, who
can skate from corner to corner with total impunity. BET THE TREY
</P>
<P>
   TCU has launched a search for a new sports information director
_ Rick Covington is leaving _ and here's a tip for athletic
director Eric Hyman: Don't forget to look under your nose.
</P>
<P>
   Best man for the job, hands down, is Trey Carmichael, longtime
assistant SID, who worked closely and successfully with football
coach Dennis Franchione last year.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael knows the local media and understands the
difficulties and nuances of marketing and publicizing the Frogs in
an avid pro sports market like Fort Worth-Dallas, a daunting
challenge for candidates from your basic College Town, USA, where
the local university team is the biggest story in town. WAS GAILEY
INFLEXIBLE?
</P>
<P>
   Peter King might be slightly overstating the case when he says,
in the latest ``Sports Illustrated'', that former Cowboys coach
Chan Gailey skipped quarterbacks meetings because he got tired of
debating play selection with Troy Aikman and Jason Garrett. Gailey
skipped some meetings because of his coaching duties, not because
he was cowed by his contentious quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   What is true is that the biggest private complaint consistently
heard about Gailey from players last season was his inflexibility
regarding play calling and that he rarely, if ever, used any of the
plays suggested by others.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey insisted, when asked about those whispers, that he did
listen to suggestions regarding play calling and sometimes
implemented those plays.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, there's also no question that the cooling of the
Gailey-Aikman relationship played a large part in Jerry Jones'
decision to fire Gailey after last season.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Gailey, while Cowboys coach, never once to my
knowledge offered any criticism of Aikman, either public or
private. On the contrary, he consistently praised him as one of the
league's best quarterbacks. THE CRYING GAME
</P>
<P>
   Trying to get John Wetteland to complain about his lot in life
is next to impossible, but even the Rangers' closer is disgusted
with baseball's gluttony of offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've still got to deal with it so it doesn't matter what I
think,'' Wetteland said. ``You tell me, when there's seven home
runs every game you stinkin' watch, that the game hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't seem like baseball anymore. There's no
question I'm throwing as well as I did last year. But that doesn't
seem to make a difference in anyone's mind either. I still have to
go out there and deal with it every day and it does no good to
whine about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, you think anything's going to change?''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, John. Not a chance.
</P>
<P>
   REVO'S RIMSHOTS
</P>
<P>
   JUST PARK THE CAR
</P>
<P>
   Stars fourth-line forward Blake Sloan went temporarily
unrecognized by a valet parking attendant one day last week. When
the guy suddenly realized who Sloan was, he was apologetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't recognize you at first,'' the guy told Sloan. ``I think
it was because of this Honda you're driving.''
</P>
<P>
   NO BUNNY HOP
</P>
<P>
   TCU's Heisman Trophy candidate LaDainian Tomlinson is back from
the ``Playboy'' All-American Weekend in Phoenix, where he hung
around with the guys who likely will be his major competitors for
the award, including quarterbacks Michael Vick of Virginia Tech and
Drew Brees of Purdue, and running backs Lamont Jordan of Maryland
and Deuce McAllister of Ole Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson took part in a photo shoot, taped the annual TV show
and had a good time but there was one disappointment: No Playboy
Bunnies.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe disappointment is putting it too lightly.
</P>
<P>
   THE ABC'S OF HOCKEY
</P>
<P>
   Devils winger Claude Lemieux was trying to provoke Philly's Eric
Desjardins last week, so he skated over and asked the Flyers'
captain, ``What's that `C' \Ron Desjardins' sweater\S for,
selfish?''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, spelling is not Lemieux's strong point.
</P>
<P>
   THE POWER OF MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Our Dwain Price had the story and the quote of the week when he
broke the news that Don Nelson, who had insisted that he was
retiring, will instead be returning as the Mavs' head coach next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nellie loves money,'' a source told Price, ``and \RMark\S
Cuban has a lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bingo.
</P>
<P>
   NOT TONYA, PLEASE
</P>
<P>
   Three days in jail for Tonya Harding for assaulting her
boyfriend with a hubcap?
</P>
<P>
   Don't put her in my cell.
</P>
<P>
   HELP! HELP!
</P>
<P>
   Don Baylor's been begging for help for his beleaguered Cubs'
bullpen, now he's got it.
</P>
<P>
   One problem: I think he meant pitchers, not extra security
guards.
</P>
<P>
   LEADERS APPLY HERE
</P>
<P>
   If, as shortstop Royce Clayton charged on his Web site last
week, a part-time bit player like Chad Curtis has poisoned the
Rangers' clubhouse atmosphere, what exactly does that say about
team leadership? nn
</P>
