<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY CRITICS: FOCUS ON PERFORMANCES, NOT CLUBHOUSE THEATRICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What I'm coping with this morning is the failure to find a bad
guy. In case of controversy in the jock kingdom, the first rule of
columnizing-made-easy is to take sides. Identify the rat, set your
trap, then crush the neck. Man, that's fun.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Clayton must have thought so. Royce, all that Web-page
anger _ you got a Bobby Knight complex, or what?
</P>
<P>
   How about Chad Curtis? People don't like you, Chad. Starting
with Royce, apparently. Why don't you lighten up just a notch?
</P>
<P>
   And from the Royce-writes-nasty-things-about-Chad scene at the
ballyard the other day, then comes the latest issue of ``Sports
Illustrated,'' with this quote from an unnamed Dallas Cowboys'
player:
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, Troy's got to make some plays to help us win.
Last year, he was at fault as much as anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wooooo.'' Why was there so much ``wooooo'' being heard locally
over that comment?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, fellows, can't we all get along around here?
</P>
<P>
   Who then is the bad guy? Is it Royce? Not from where I sit. But
one piece of advice for Clayton would be stick to shortstop and
leave the wordy rip jobs to us highly skilled professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Is it Curtis? Absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman? Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who said those things about Troy? No, again. Except why
not use your name, buster? What you said was true. Even Aikman
would agree with that. So why hide, unless your name is Nine-Toed,
and you know your credibility around here is lower than an
armadillo's belly.
</P>
<P>
   Among Clayton, Curtis and Aikman, however, I can't find a weasel
in the bunch. They all play the game the way the game is supposed
to be played. And off the field, they act right and do right, for
those of you who consider that an important part of the jock
kingdom process.
</P>
<P>
   So what was it with a certain segment of local fandom sitting in
the left-field seats on Thursday night at The Ballpark in
Arlington? Why were you people riding Chad Curtis' butt over
something Clayton had said on a stupid Web site? Curtis gives you
nothing but effort, and also production, as he fills in admirably
for the injured Rusty Greer. Leave him alone, and he might also
give you an autographed baseball card.
</P>
<P>
   I got mine the other night. ``Here, take my card,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's not exactly a limited-edition Topps. On the back,
Curtis preaches. His religious message is, well, intense.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball word on Chad Curtis is that playing for six teams
in nine seasons has plenty to do with a religious fervor that grows
tiresome. And also with a combative clubhouse nature when it comes
to ``standards.'' His standards.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know enough about the 31-year-old Curtis to judge. From
afar, however, he seems to be a weird little cat. The flattop. The
laser-beam eyes. On the field, what is there not to like? Off the
field, I might not necessarily agree with one thing Curtis stands
for, but again, I like him. He's definitely unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad, you don't seem to want to make friends in here,'' I say
the other night, meaning among his teammates in the Texas Rangers'
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I do. I really do. That's important to me,'' he answered.
``But at the same time, I made the decision long ago that I will
not compromise my beliefs to do so. Some of that has to do with my
religion, some of that with the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing, Curtis grinned, and added, ``I'm not a regular
person.''
</P>
<P>
   I understand.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis just spent three seasons with the Yankees, two on world
championship teams. He's the guy I thought went too far at the
World Series in humiliating NBC's Jim Gray over the Pete Rose
thing. His manager, Joe Torre, even said so publicly. But Curtis'
teammates had voted almost unanimously to stiff Gray as a show of
support for Rose. Curtis got the first chance to do so, having hit
a game-winning home run. This was Chad Curtis being the good
teammate. And he took the fall for it.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, I'm watching ``SportsCenter'' one night and see
film of a Yankees-Seattle brawl. Except off to the side, the
Yankees' Derek Jeter is clowning with Seattle's Alex Rodriguez. I'm
thinking Jeter was wrong here. And a teammate would be letting him
know just that.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Curtis did. He had words for a New York favorite.
Criticism of Curtis followed. So did an off-season trade to the
Rangers. But Curtis was right in doing what he did. ``Except I took
the brunt of that one,'' he said, believing he was traded for
confronting Jeter. ``But then again, it's also printed that I told
Derek he should have punched Alex. No way. If anything, I'd have
stepped up and taken a punch aimed for Derek. I admire him that
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis also wants to know why his ``music'' argument with
Clayton in the first week of this season was reported by some as a
``shoving'' incident. ``That never happened,'' he said. ``Why can't
I read somewhere that shoves never happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Hardcore _ that's Curtis. But in Port Charlotte this spring,
I've never heard a more eloquent plea for compassion after former
Yankees' teammate Darryl Strawberry went down on a cocaine count
for the umpteenth time. Curtis obviously felt for this loser.
</P>
<P>
   Like I said _ shut up out there in left field. There are no bad
guys in all this. Strange ones, maybe. But it's still all about how
they play the game. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
