<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CORONATION PREMATURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Going into the season, it was clear that the Yankees were the
team to beat. They were the two-time defending champions, had won
the World Series three of the past four years, and had their star
players and pitching staff back for another run at a title.
</P>
<P>
   On Mother's Day, it became clear that the Yanks can be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox pushed the mighty Yankees out of first place a week
ago, defeating the Orioles on the same day their American League
East rivals were losing to the Tigers. That knocked the New Yorkers
out of first place for the first time since last June 8.
</P>
<P>
   The New Englanders, naturally, said all the predictable things
about it being too early and all that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means nothing right now,'' Red Sox outfielder Darren
Lewis said. ``Yeah, we're in first place. That's nice for the fans,
and we're excited about that, but it's still May. We've got to go
out and play good baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox history, though, suggests that the standings in the
middle of May are a pretty good precursor of the standings in early
October. In 1995, the season they won their last division title,
they moved into first place for good with a victory against the
Yankees on May 13. And in 1986, the last time they played in the
World Series, the Sox permanently moved into first place May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Of more importance than the history lesson is how the Red Sox
got to the top of the division and how they held the lead going
into the weekend. They did it with outstanding pitching, clutch
hitting and good defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing well,'' Lewis said. ``When you put everything
together _ the pitching, the hitting and the defense _ it usually
turns into good things.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't enough to get the Red Sox into first, however. The
Yankees did their part by being swept in a three-game series by the
lowly Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit pitchers C.J. Nitkowski, Jeff Weaver and Dave Mlicki
took a combined 1-15 record and 6.44 earned-run average into the
series but went 3-0 with a 1.74 ERA. The Yankees hit a collective
.240 (25-for-104), and didn't get an extra-base hit in the final
two games.
</P>
<P>
   That series wasn't an aberration. Scoring runs has been a
seasonlong problem. The Yankees' .265 batting average heading into
the weekend was 12th in the league, as were their 45 homers. They
had scored 175 runs, more than only one team.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem is at the top of the batting order. Chuck
Knoblauch and Derek Jeter had a combined .415 on-base percentage
last season. This year, it was barely over .300.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominous than the offensive malaise are the rumblings
coming from The Boss, owner George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not seeing some things I'd like to see,'' Steinbrenner
said. ``I'm not happy with the way some of our guys are playing.
I'm not going to get into naming specific people, but they know who
they are. This is a good ballclub. I will be concerned if they
don't start playing better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' struggles are all relative, of course. Virtually
every other team in the league would love to have the Yankees'
problems. They took a 23-14 record into the weekend, second-best in
the AL. Their 3.97 team ERA also was second.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox were first in both categories.
</P>
<P>
   Based on their track record and their talent, the Yankees remain
the team to beat. Their coronation, though, doesn't appear as
inevitable as it once did.
RAISE THE MOUND
</P>
<P>
   A committee of general managers is trying to get the pitching
mound raised from its current height of 10 inches, not necessarily
to curb offense but as a way to reduce injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to throw down from a higher slope,'' Pirates GM
Cam Bonifay said. ``It puts less strain on a pitcher's arm, back
and elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonifay doesn't believe the height will return to 15 inches, as
it was until 1969. He thinks 14 inches is a more realistic target.
He is pushing to experiment with the heightened mound in the
Arizona Fall League and in the low minors, but he also believes the
mound can be raised in time for the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have a problem lowering the mound from one year to
the next,'' he said. ``I think it will gain momentum throughout the
year.'' GARNER NOT BACKING DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Tigers manager Phil Garner was a popular man when his club
visited Cleveland for the first time this season. Garner drew a
crowd because of his spring training comments that the Indians
appeared ``vulnerable'' this season.
</P>
<P>
   Garner admitted he was half wrong. The Indians do appear
vulnerable. They've trailed the White Sox for much of the season
and, after finally climbing back into a tie for first, they've had
to put two of their starting pitchers _ Jaret Wright and Charles
Nagy _ on the disable list.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tigers haven't been able to take advantage. They've got
the worst record in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand where I stood when I first said it,'' Garner said. ``I
didn't say they weren't going to win. I just didn't see it being a
runaway like it has been in the past. As it turns out, the crow I'm
eating is about us. I thought we'd be part of the mix, but we just
haven't played as well as I thought we would.'' LAST LAUGH
</P>
<P>
   It was simply a matter of time before the Mets got rid of Bobby
Bonilla and Rickey Henderson after the two went into the clubhouse
to play cards during a loss to the Braves in the playoffs last
season. Bonilla was released in October, and Henderson got the boot
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The two players, though, are laughing all the way to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla was picked up by the Braves and has been a useful
player. Henderson was signed by the Mariners and will get a chance
to be their leadoff hitter and left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they contribute to their new teams, they will do it
while on the Mets' payroll because they were released and not
traded. The Mets owe Bonilla almost $30 million over the next 25
years and must pay Henderson the remainder of his $1.9 million
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice little irony because the Mets are footing the
bill,'' Bonilla said. ``This is like a gift. I'm ecstatic now. Hey,
I'm doing the Macarena.'' DEFENDING FRANCONA
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Francona is bearing the brunt of Phillies' fans
wrath because of the team's slow start. The boos grow louder every
time he steps out of the home dugout at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   However, GM Ed Wade has given no indication that Francona's job
is in jeopardy, and staff ace Curt Schilling supports the manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't kicked a ball, he hasn't failed to get a runner home
from third base with less than two outs, and he hasn't walked
anybody,'' Schilling said. ``Of all the people who should shoulder
the blame for what has happened, he's probably at the bottom of the
list.'' AROUND THE NL
</P>
<P>
   _ Randy Johnson's first loss of the season brought back bad
memories. Johnson and the Diamondbacks fell to the Expos, 2-0,
Tuesday. He lost four consecutive games in '99 when his team was
shut out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phillies prospect Pat Burrell could make his big-league debut
this week, possibly as soon as Tuesday in Houston. After Rico
Brogna fractured the ulna bone in his left hand, the Phillies
immediately asked Burrell to move from left field back to first
base at Triple-A Scranton/Wilkes-Barre. He had been moved from
first to left to prepare to take Ron Gant's place, but Brogna's
injury changed the position and the timetable.
</P>
<P>
   _ When Pirates strength and conditioning instructor Dr. Warren
Sipp made his annual appearance in an exhibition game against a
minor-league affiliate Monday, team members bribed Double-A Altoona
pitcher John Rosengren to bean him. Rosengren hit Sipp in the
ankle, and after the game the Pirates collected a $300 bounty.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sterling Hitchcock, the Padres' No. 1 starter, was winless
before defeating the Marlins on Tuesday. The victory marked his
first in 11 starts dating to September.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cubs were 35-72, a .327 winning percentage, after June
last season, a collapse that caused manager Jim Riggleman to be
fired. In their first 42 games under new manager Don Baylor they
went 15-27, a .357 winning percentage.
AROUND THE AL
</P>
<P>
   _ Athletics' first baseman Jason Giambi was hitting .314 with 16
homers and 47 runs batted in through Thursday. He was tied with
Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez for the AL home run lead, and led
the league in RBI. However, he isn't satisfied. ``It's where you
end up that really matters,'' Giambi said. ``It's nice what I'm
doing so far, but you've got to keep getting better. You can't ever
be happy with where you're at. Every day is a grind out there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Yankees owner George Steinbrenner has yet to publicly blast GM
Brian Cashman or manager Joe Torre, but he has made it clear that
he was in favor of trading for Jim Edmonds. However, Cashman and
Torre wanted to hold onto left fielder Ricky Ledee and reliever
Ramiro Mendoza. Edmonds is hitting .395 with 13 homers and 34 RBI
for the Cardinals, while Ledee is batting .211 with one homer and
nine RBI.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Indians' Alomar brothers hit for the cycle Wednesday.
Sandy had a homer and a triple. Roberto singled and doubled. ``Just
say Alomar hit for the cycle,'' Roberto said. ``Don't say R. Alomar
or S. Alomar. Just say Alomar.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Keith Foulke has replaced Bobby Howry as the White Sox closer.
He won the job by going 1-0 with a 0.70 ERA and five saves in six
chances and holding opponents to a .163 batting average. ``He is
lights out and has been doing that for the last year and a half,''
Howry said. ``The whole bullpen agrees that we're so versatile it
doesn't matter what role we're in. You can mix and match us any way
you want to. That's what makes our bullpen so good.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The White Sox and the Twins are the only teams in the majors
that haven't used the disable list since Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Angels shortstop Gary DiSarcina is considering having
season-ending surgery on his sore right shoulder. He saw vascular
and orthopedic specialists in Chicago, but the results were
inconclusive. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
