<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRIATHLON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIVE TEXAN PREPARED TO SWIM WITH THE OLYMPIC SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She has survived a family tragedy. She has stayed the course.
She has swum with the sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Who says that the newest athletes of the Olympics, the
triathletes, don't have a little iron in them?
</P>
<P>
   It was less than six years ago that Jennifer Gutierrez, a native
of San Antonio, competed in her first triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're good at this,'' her now-husband, Bob Utberg, announced.
``We've got to get you a bike.''
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a hobby, therefore, soon became Gutierrez's
personal mission _ to stand at the steps of the Sydney Opera House
for the Olympic Games' inaugural triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   She will. She earned her spot on the U.S. team by finishing
seventh in the Sydney World Cup Triathlon last month. The event was
held on the same course _ and in the same shark-visited waters _
where the Olympic triathlon will be staged in September.
</P>
<P>
   Two more women's spots will be at stake Saturday when Irving
hosts the U.S. Olympic team trials in the waters and roads of Las
Colinas. The men's race is scheduled for next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pursued this because it was an Olympic event,'' Gutierrez
said last week during a stopover in Texas. ``I knew it was a
four-year commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   In high school, like a lot of triathletes, she had been a
talented swimmer, good enough to be awarded a college scholarship
to Pepperdine. She earned a master's degree in early childhood
education in 1991 and has been teaching physical education to
handicapped children in the Denver area.
</P>
<P>
   Through the understanding of her school district, Gutierrez was
able to juggle her work schedule when her father, Tiger, was
stricken with cancer. He died last year at age 68.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Gutierrez had been the driving force behind Jennifer's
athletic career. ``The experience showed me that there is so much
more to life than training every day,'' she said. ``Life, I
realized, is full of obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the sharks. Sydney officials plan to employ divers with
sonar devices to keep the sharks at bay during the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really worried about that,'' Gutierrez said. ``They
tell us that sharks won't attack anyone in packs. But when I was
warming up for the World Cup, I was out on the Olympic course and
realized I was out there by myself. I thought, `Hmm, I don't know
if I should be out here.'''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the week, as they say, went swimmingly. During the
running portion of the Sydney triathlon, Gutierrez overtook Barb
Lindquist and became the first American to finish, earning the
Olympic team spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still hasn't hit me yet,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, she said, the event in Sydney will indoctrinate the
world on the real Olympic triathlon _ not the 10-hour, staggerfest
known as the Hawaii Ironman Triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our event is geared more toward the everyday person, to be
honest, the people who don't have 10 hours a day to train,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are going to like seeing this.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
