<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-CANSECO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE FELL FROM TOP OF BOXING WORLD, NOW CURRY SEEKS FIGHTING CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ There was a time when the world was Donald
Curry's playground. As undisputed and undefeated welterweight
champion, he was a perfect contradiction: shy and softspoken with a
choirboy's face and good intentions outside the ring, his
lightning-quick fists and punching power fostered bad intentions
inside it.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the admiration of the people in his hometown of Fort
Worth, Curry helped transform Cowtown into Fight Town during the
mid-1980s. Curry's first world title in February 1983 soon was
followed by those won by his older brother, Bruce Curry, Gene ``Mad
Dog'' Hatcher, ``Little'' Stevie Cruz, Troy Dorsey and more
recently, Paulie Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going to be the best pound-for-pound fighter, the
biggest money-earner, the successor to Sugar Ray Leonard and
Marvelous Marvin Hagler,'' said promoter Bob Arum, who orchestrated
Curry's dizzying trip to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Curry won the World Boxing Association welterweight title in
front of his hometown fans in February 1983 and then unified the
147-pound division when he knocked out World Boxing Council
champion Milton McCrory in the second round in December 1985.
Curry, ``The Lone Star Cobra'' and one-time Texas Golden Gloves
hero, appeared invincible.
</P>
<P>
   But the bright lights of stardom sometimes can blind, and Curry
now confesses he was not prepared to deal with the expectations and
responsibilities that come with being a champion.
</P>
<P>
   At 38, he has returned to Fort Worth from a self-imposed,
three-year exile in Las Vegas. Nearly broke and living at the home
of his mother, Hazel Sample, he is intent upon starting over as a
boxing trainer and re-establishing himself as someone worthy of
trust. Staring into an uncertain future, Curry freely admits to the
foibles of his star-crossed past as a two-time world champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to be whatever people wanted me to be,'' Curry
said in a monotone voice, barely above a whisper. ``Model citizen,
this and that. I tried to be a role model. It was a lot of
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole time I was champion, it wasn't something I enjoyed.
I wasn't being manipulated, I was just ignorant of a lot of things.
A country boy from Fort Worth. It's a fast business, and I trusted
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Donald once told me, `When you're on top ... time flies. It
just blows by you,' '' said publicist Lee Samuels of Top Rank, who
handled most of Curry's national promotions. ``And he said, `When
you're on top, you're never by yourself ... you've got trainers, PR
guys, press conferences all the time.' I think we knew where Donald
was every waking moment. He was a hot guy. When he was on top of
his game, he was unbeatable. He just lost his focus _ like many,
many fighters do.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Curry is focusing on a second career as a trainer. But thus
far, he hasn't had a lot of success. Earlier this year, he
approached Paul Reyes, his longtime trainer, who now works with
Ayala, about starting a boxing team in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Don, I'm too old (61) to start all over again,' ''
said Reyes, who began training Curry when the fighter was 7. ``And
he said he needed people that had money. He had it one time, had
his chance and he blew it. But if he's serious, he could still do
it. He don't need my help. I tried to give him a little pep talk.
He's got the credentials. I told him I wished him the best. He's
still my friend, even though he did me wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry also approached his former business partner Scott Sherman
about rejoining Boxing Management Inc., which manages Ayala, among
other fighters. Sherman also declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with Donald about four years ago, when he was still
with us, and asked him if he would train some of our fighters,''
Sherman said. ``And he laughed at me. He said he wasn't a trainer.
So when Donald came to me (in January), I figured he wasn't
interested before and didn't see any reason to upset the applecart.
We don't need another trainer.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate irony would be if Curry were reunited with his
former manager David Gorman, who he fired after his first
successful title defense in 1986. Gorman has started over in
boxing, with a gym on the city's North Side. And he said he would
consider doing business with his former protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for Don,'' said Gorman, 58. ``I know he needs
some help. I got my feelings hurt over Curry, but I don't hold it
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gorman and Curry were on top, this was not a scenario
either of them would have envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got into this game, you know, one of the things I
did not want to do is what I'm doing now. Start over,'' Curry said.
``I can tell you my fears, and when I made up my mind to turn
professional, what I feared was to do ``this''. And it manifested
itself.'' THE HARD FALL
</P>
<P>
   When he fell, Curry landed with a thud, battered inside and
outside the squared circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was insecure,'' said Curry, who decided Gorman was
ill-equipped to deal with big-time boxing and demoted him in March
1986. ``I was smart enough to be champion, but I wasn't smart
enough to keep my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum once projected Curry among Top Rank's top-five all-time
attractions. Of Curry's downfall, Arum said, ``It's just sad. He
was a tremendous disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own accounting, Curry earned an estimated $5 million
between February 1983 and June 1991. Virtually none of that prize
money remains, much of it consumed when Curry fought to clear his
name in a federal drug conspiracy indictment handed down in April
1994. Some of his fortune was squandered through what he sweepingly
describes as ``bad investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry's reign as undisputed welterweight champion started well
enough. He won the unification bout against McCrory on Dec. 6,
1985, succeeding his hero, Sugar Ray Leonard, as king of the
147-pound division.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he knocked out McCrory, Donald Curry did really look like
the genuine article,'' said Nigel Collins, editor of ``The Ring
Magazine.'' ``He looked like he would dominate the welterweights
and maybe move to the middleweights. There were high hopes
throughout the boxing community, not just from Bob Arum.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry was the toast of Fort Worth when he scored a second-round
KO against Eduardo Rodriguez of Panama on March 9, 1986, before a
standing-room-only crowd of 8,864 at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum.
The first defense of his undisputed title left Curry at 25-0 with
20 knockouts.
</P>
<P>
   But only two days after disposing of Rodriguez, word leaked that
Curry was about to replace Gorman, with whom he had turned pro in
1980, with Akbar Muhammad, who was resigning as executive vice
president of Top Rank, Arum's company.
</P>
<P>
   With his former executive now serving as manager, Arum was
positioning Curry to be the farewell opponent for Hagler, the
undisputed middleweight (160-pound) champion, tentatively planned
for September 1987. But Curry felt that he was being pressured by
Arum to move up in weight and hired attorney Mike Trainer, longtime
adviser to Leonard, who convinced him to remain in the welterweight
division. Infuriated by Curry's decision to remain a welterweight
and Trainer's interference, Arum announced that a potential
Hagler-Curry megabout was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all fell apart when Donald suddenly became this major
business guy, and decided that nobody was going to tell him what to
do,'' Arum said. ``He dumped Gorman and started dumping
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Curry dumped Trainer and welcomed back Muhammad as
his manager.
</P>
<P>
   Curry's camp and career remained in flux until Arum nailed down
the rights to the Curry-Lloyd Honeyghan world title fight for Sept.
27, 1986, in Atlantic City. A listless Curry surrendered his
championship belts when he failed to answer the bell for the
seventh round. Honeyghan, an 8-1 underdog, was credited with a
sixth-round technical knockout.
</P>
<P>
   After the loss, Curry's style and skills began to deteriorate
noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCallum knocked him out in the fifth round for the WBA
junior middleweight title July 18, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   With Muhammad now clearly in charge as Curry's manager/financial
adviser and Top Rank nominally in his corner, Curry enjoyed a brief
revival, winning the World Boxing Council's super welterweight
title by stopping Gianfranco Rosi of Italy, which led to a title
defense against Frenchman Rene Jacquot in Grenoble, France, in
February 1989. Jacquot was little more than a club fighter, but he
won a 12-round decision that stunned even the French fans and
media. With his interest in boxing waning, Curry suffered an
eighth-round technical knockout loss against Terry Norris, then the
World Boxing Council's 154-pound champion, on June 1, 1991, and
announced his retirement. SETBACKS BECOME REAL-WORLD
</P>
<P>
   In December 1990, while still active and world-ranked, Curry
entered the boxing management field with Fort Worth businessmen
Scott Sherman and Jon Brumley. They founded BMI, with the idea of
forging another championship-caliber stable in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Curry was entrusted with signing amateur prospects and
overseeing their development in the gym. To that end, Curry was
dispatched to the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, Spain, on behalf of
BMI. But Curry failed to sign Fort Worth's Sergio Reyes, a
world-rated amateur bantamweight and another graduate of Gorman's
Gym. Later, Curry was fired by BMI for reasons Sherman declined to
specify.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1994, Curry and former Detroit boxers Darrell Chambers
and William ``Stanley'' Longstreet _ friends from their amateur
days _ were named in a federal drug-conspiracy indictment. Curry's
mistake was taking a trip to the Bahamas in September 1992, when
the other men purchased $150,000 of cocaine from undercover U.S.
Drug Enforcement Administration agents.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, who swore he ``never, never, ever had anything to do with
drugs,'' was acquitted by a jury in Detroit after an 11-day trial
in January 1995. In a follow-up news conference in Fort Worth,
Curry said the preceding 10-month ordeal had ``destroyed'' him
financially and emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know how I got there in that situation,'' Curry
said. ``There's good and bad in the world, and I wanted to go see
what the bad looked like. For real. A lot of it was being curious.
I was destructive of myself. I can't blame nobody for where I am
today but myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, Curry was sentenced to a six-month jail term in
Dallas for failing to pay child support for a son born to a Dallas
woman in April 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I know I did wrong,'' said Curry, whose infidelity
prompted his wife, Valerie Cooper, to later file for divorce. She
has custody of their 7-year-old son, Donovan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I never (got) divorced,'' Curry said. ``I still
have a great love for Valerie. At that time, I didn't know love. I
thought I did, but I didn't know what love was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fooled myself. Fooled a lot of people. Disappointed a lot of
people. Disappointed myself, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Arum said Curry easily could have placed in the top five of Top
Rank's greatest fighters _ an elite list headed by former
heavyweight champion Muhammad Ali _ if he had stayed with Gorman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had dreams of instant gratification,'' Arum said. ``And
ended up with nothing. If he would have stayed on the program, he
would have been one of the greats.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arum said he is pulling for Curry to make it as a
trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would recommend fighters to him. Sure. I think he would be
good with some fighters. That's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry said he remains optimistic someone in boxing _ ideally,
someone in the hometown he once ruled as undisputed hero _ will
offer him one more chance to answer the bell. And Curry bristled at
the suggestion that he has gone from perennial title contender to
perennial lost soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you say that I'm lost?'' Curry said. `` `Lost' is
someone who doesn't know what they want to do. I know what I want
to do. I have goals. I feel I have the skills for a trainer _ to go
back and teach boxing _ and to me, that's a piece of cake. When I
finished fighting, yeah, I was `lost' then. Because I didn't know
what I wanted to put my heart into. And I found God. I've found my
God, and that's just everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm past defeat, whether it's financial or athletic. I'm
looking at tradition and legacy. Looking at making tradition and
leaving a legacy.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 0254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
