<HEADER>
A1441 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LBPT     05-21 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN LEADS ANGELS PAST ROYALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ High fever. Severe headaches. Dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the symptoms that kept reliever Mark Petkovsek out of
uniform Saturday night, but it's a pretty accurate diagnosis for
the Angels entire pitching staff right now. Everyone's either sick
or tired --- or both.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, thanks to a two homers by Mo Vaughn and a four-run
seventh, rallied to beat Kansas City, 9-8, before 30,689, but just
how long can their hitting cure all that ails them?
</P>
<P>
   In addition Vaughn's two homers and a pair of big hits by Scott
Speizio and Bengie Molina, the Angels needed seven pitchers and 3
3/4 hours to get away with a win, which was secured when Vaughn dug
out Troy Glaus' poor throw for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven pitchers,'' sighed Angels manager Mike Scioscia after a
game in which the lead changed hands six times. ``I don't know if
there's anyone else I could have used?''
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of guys he could use --- all he has to do is look
at the disabled list, which includes Ken Hill, Kent Mercker, Tim
Belcher and Jason Dickson. Or at Edmonton, where Ramon Ortiz and
Lou Pote are because they failed to deliver on the promise they
showed in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Petkovsek, who isn't expected to be available
today either, sidelined with what team officials described as
``viral syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   It's apparently nothing like the fever Vaughn has. His homers
--- both two-run shots --- were his 14th and 15th of the season. In
the 11-game homestand, the big first baseman is batting .391 with
eight homers and 17 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's done it in clutch situations,'' said Spiezio, who hit
a solo homer, drove in the game-tying run with a two-out, broken
bat single and then raced home on Molina's bloop double that
ricocheted off the knee of diving right fielder David McCarty.
</P>
<P>
   Molina also contributed a big two-out, two-strike hit in the
fourth, when he pulled a breaking ball into left field to score two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the mound, the Angels turned to long reliever Al
Levine, who made the second start of his five-year major league
career. After throwing 53 pitches in the first two innings, he
settled down before leaving in the fifth, trailing 4-3 and having
thrown 81 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   He was followed by a parade of relievers: Mike Fyhrie, Mike
Holtz, Eric Weaver, Shigetoshi Hasegawa, Brett Hinchliffe and
finally Percival, who earned his 11th save. The only arm left in
the bullpen belonged to little-used Derrick Turnbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals managed 12 hits, but they rarely came through in the
clutch, leaving 13 runners on base, most of them early.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa, who gave up a three-run double to Mike Sweeney that
gave Kansas City an 8-5 lead in the top of the seventh, has thrown
49 pitches over the past two nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was OK,'' he said. ``But if I'm a little tired I've got
to talk to the coaches. Everybody's a human. You can't pitch every
day. Sometimes you need a day off.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio says there's no added burden on the offense while the
pitchers are so tattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were healthy, we'd still have the same attitude,''
Spiezio said. ``You can turn it on and off like a switch. If the
pitchers hold them to no runs and we score eight, that's great. If
they don't and we still win, that's great, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said it's incumbent on the three usual starters ---
Kent Bottenfield today, Scott Schoeneweis and Jarrod Washburn to
work deeper into games, certainly into the seventh and hopefully
into the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, the starters have to do that,'' Scioscia said. ``And
these guys will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
