<HEADER>
A1482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0522-COX     05-21 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0522-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forester faces tough choices about Chattahoochee
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Regional U.S. Forester Elizabeth Estill manages 13
million acres of our land and a rainforest in Puerto Rico, but the
biggest test of her leadership may be over the Chattahoochee
National Forest in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Estill became the first woman in the forest service's
95-year history to be appointed to a job that was officially
limited to ``able bodied men'' until after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to being named head of the Southern region in 1997, she
served the Rocky Mountain region where there were three acres of
federally owned forest for every person. ``Here, there are seven
people for every acre, which makes our public lands even more
precious,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question about Estill's acceptance in a man's world,
but there's still uncertainty about whether her policy decisions
will differ from the men she succeeded. She faces two such
decisions that will test her public pronouncements about the need
to emphasize recreational uses of the forest over extraction and
logging uses.
</P>
<P>
   First, she will decide how much additional wilderness there will
be in the Chattahoochee and the other 13 Southern forests she
manages. Then she must decide whether Chattahoochee National Forest
officials will be allowed to weaken environmental impact studies
affecting their forest. Southern Environmental Law Center lawyers
have asked Estill not to allow that.
</P>
<P>
   The larger question, according to George Gay, Southeast director
of the National Wilderness Society, is whether Estill will
implement the vision of U.S. Forest Service Chief Mike Dombeck,
which is more preservation oriented than that of any chief in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Estill has admirers, both inside and outside the forest service.
David Waller, director of the state Wildlife Division, says Estill
listens and considers state concerns. And she receives high marks
for helping other women move up within the male-dominated agency.
(There are two other female regional foresters, one of whom is
Estill's protege.)
</P>
<P>
   It's clear the 52-year-old forester loves her job and loves the
outdoors. As a child, she preferred toads to dolls. She had pet
kangaroo rats, monkeys and snakes. Her first ecology lessons were
at her father's knee, learning to tell poisonous snakes from
harmless ones. She once kept in her backyard what the Washington
Zoo declared to be the largest known green snake. ``I had to feed
him worms by hand,'' she says gleefully, as if wishing to run out
and do it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Estill's father was with the FBI, so she lived all over the
country. Her mother was a traditional Southerner from Chattanooga
with a home economics degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother was always asking what I was doing in the woods with
all of those men,'' she recalls with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   As the forest service enters the last phase of a six-year
planning process, the issue is what will happen to the people's
woods over the next decade. Three constituencies are locked in
battle over the uses of the Chattahoochee National Forest:
environmentalists who want more wilderness; loggers and some
hunters who don't (hunting is allowed in wilderness areas but
motorized vehicles aren't), and state wildlife officials who oppose
more wilderness because they don't want to give up leases where
they have feeding areas to attract game. The state agency receives
some of its money from hunting licenses and gun sales.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Estill has avoided making any of the groups angry, but
that can't last. She went along with the tentative designation of
two noncontroversial wilderness areas for the Chattahoochee. But
according to Gay of the Wilderness Society, when a coalition of
environmental organizations asked Estill to designate an additional
15,000 acres, she put the burden on the environmentalists to make
the argument for adding them _ claiming that was the fair middle
ground.
</P>
<P>
   All Estill is saying for now about the hot seat she's in is
nobody ever said public service was easy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
