<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, May 22:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   BRASSAI-EXHIBIT (Paris) _ With the publication of his first
book, ``Paris de Nuit,'' in 1932, Brassai did more than win
immediate acclaim as a photographer. In what was already a much
photographed city, he created iconic images of nighttime Paris that
redefined how it was seen, almost as if darkness were its natural
condition. In the process he established an artistic trademark
that, if exploited, would have assured him a lifetime of fortune as
well as fame. Brassai, however, was something of a reluctant
photographer. A retrospective look at his work. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEW-SEASON (Undated) _ A Reporter's Notebook on the new TV
season. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ Louise Erdrich is the author of
this segment of the Writers-On-Writing series.
</P>
<P>
   VERTIGO-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Richard Eder reviews
``Vertigo,'' by W.G. Sebald.
</P>
<P>
   TV-EASTMAN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Neil Genzlinger reviews a PBS
American Experience episode: ``The Wizard of Photography: George
Eastman.''
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-ASSESS (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission plans
to go to Congress this week to seek tough new privacy rules for
Internet businesses. But the FTC, the nation's consumer protection
agency, is likely to encounter skepticism from key Republicans and
from industry groups about whether the government can impose
regulations without stifling the innovation that is feeding the new
economy. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TALENT-AGENT (Undated) _ Michael Ovitz, who made his
name and career as the superagent, is now involved in an Internet
venture. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   LATAM-INTERNET (Sao Paolo, Brazil) _ Assessing the ambitions and
struggles of Starmedia, the New York-based Internet portal for a
Latin American audience. By Jennifer L. Rich.
</P>
<P>
   SERVICE-PROVIDERS (San Francisco) _ Application service
providers _ companies that remotely supply and maintain the basic
office computing software used in modern business _ are finding a
growth market among small business customers. By Laurie J. Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The New Economy column: Dot-com
mania drove up the salaries law firms felt compelled to keep their
best young lawyers. So now that the stock-market bubble has burst,
are the lawyers willing to work for less? By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: Most
e-commerce companies are too busy keeping their heads above water
to expand into other countries, but there are exceptions. Sites
like Dell, Schwab and Amazon are running headlong into the global
fray, in hopes of winning first mover advantage in countries that
are getting more heavily wired. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PROPERTY (Washington) _ The law meant to protect
intellectual property on the Internet needs to be updated, a
Democratic Party think tank recommends in a report to be released
on Monday. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   ALTEON-WEB (Undated) _ Alteon Websystems intends to announce
this week that it has enlisted two powerful allies: Lucent
Technologies and Akamai Technologies. By Seth Schiesel
</P>
<P>
   MAYAN-OPTICAL (Undated) _ Judging by sheer buzz, there is
nothing in the technology world hotter these days than
``next-generation optical networking.'' And the temperature may
increase just a bit on Monday, when Mayan Networks Inc., a start-up
company based in Sunnyvale, Calif., plans to announce availability
of its first product. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   COURAGE-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Advertising column: To the
British, it is a brand of alcoholic beverage. To fans of John F.
Kennedy, it is the subject of profiles. To the Cowardly Lion, it is
reason to see the Wizard. And to Land Rover North America, it is
the centerpiece of a revamped advertising and marketing campaign,
the first created by the company's new agency, GSD&AMP;M in Austin,
Texas. The subject? Courage, of course. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column: two inventors
have won MIT-Lemelson prizes for their contributions to modern
life. By Teresa Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Short news items about computers.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SCHLESSINGER-MEDIA (Undated) _ Paramount Television is
introducing a syndicated talk show featuring Dr. Laura
Schlessinger, the conservative advice maven whose radio audience
has listened to her stern declarations that homosexuality is a
deviation from the biological norm and incompatible with biblical
scripture. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-DEAL-MEDIA (Undated) _ Why is the bestselling Mary Higgins
Clark _ a self-described ``tough broad'' from the Bronx _ worth the
$15 million-a-book deal she just signed with Simon &AMP; Schuster? By
Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   AP-KOREA-MEDIA (Undated) _ On Sept. 29, 1999, The Associated
Press provided extensive evidence that GIs killed a helpless group
of civilians in the early days of the Korean War. Since then, its
report of the incident at No Gun Ri, 17 months in the making, has
became a media personality in its own right. It has been praised.
It has been followed. It has been honored with journalism's top
prizes. More recently, it has been pilloried. Some wonder if AP
deserved a Pulitzer for the story? A look at the criticism and the
defense. (News Analysis.) By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   HARRY-POTTER-MEDIA (London) _ Get ready for a Harry Potter
blitz. The new book is arriving in July, and the publishers have a
game plan including a whistlestop train tour by the author in
England, and a campaign targeting summer resorts and camps in the
U.S. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ Short news items about the media
business.
</P>
