<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1538 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-VIOLENCE-0522     05-21 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-VIOLENCE-0522-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    BARAK RECALLS NEGOTIATORS AFTER RIOTS; LAUNCHES ATTACKS IN
LEBANON
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    475&AMP;Add
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After a week of riots and the severe burning of a
2-year-old Israeli girl in a firebomb attack, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak Sunday called back negotiators from peace talks
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian rioting appeared to be tailing off Sunday as
Palestinian police restrained protesters. But, Barak delayed a
scheduled land hand-over to the Palestinian National Authority and
closed the West Bank to travel by Israelis and tourists _ a warning
blow to the Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, Israel also announced that its air force
struck at a Syrian-allied Palestinian group in southern Lebanon.
That was apparently a signal that Barak demands a peaceful northern
border after he removes his troops from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has promised to remove troops from Lebanon by July 7, but
with the increased fighting he is under pressure to do so sooner.
The Israeli-paid South Lebanon Army reportedly abandoned three
outposts near the Israeli border Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   To tend to the matters Barak, who serves as his own defense
minister, also cancelled a trip to Washington, where he was
supposed to meet with President Clinton to discuss the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   The moves came after a bloody week that saw Israel confronting
violence on two fronts in Arab territories that it occupies _ the
West Bank and southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has occupied most of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip
since capturing them in the 1967 Middle East war. It is withdrawing
from them slowly under terms of the Oslo peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Israel has occupied southern Lebanon since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   For several days in a row, Palestinians have marched in protest
of the continued detention by Israel of about 1,650 prisoners.
Though many attacked Israeli civilians, Palestinians consider them
prisoners of war and say they should be released in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   The marches frequently turned into riots against Israeli
soldiers and, on several occasions, erupted into gunfights between
Israeli soldiers and the Palestinian police they are supposed to be
working with in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   About six Palestinians were killed and hundreds injured,
including a 16-year-old boy who reportedly died Sunday from wounds
suffered last week.
</P>
<P>
   Several Israeli troops had also been injured, including one
soldier shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Palestinians hurled firebombs at dozens of
Israeli cars traveling in the West Bank, home to more than 190,000
Israeli settlers amid more than 1.5 million Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   One firebomb hit an Israeli car near Jericho, critically burning
the 2-year-old girl who, relatives said, was trapped in her car
seat.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Barak put the peace process on hold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADDS FOLLOW &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with members of his cabinet Sunday morning, Barak
announced he was closing the West Bank to travel by Israelis or
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The closure, an unusual move, could be meant to put a scare into
the Palestinian economy. Palestinian Bethlehem depends on tourist
dollars and Jericho's Oasis Casino, owned in part by the
Palestinian Authority, makes millions of dollars a month off
Israeli gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   Barak demanded that the Palestinians, led by President Yasser
Arafat, control the riots and investigate the police who fired on
Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
   He also called back the two Israeli officials who were meeting
with Palestinian negotiators in peace talks in Sweden. The talks
were meant to help draft a framework for resolving all the
remaining issues between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators have already missed a self-imposed deadline last
week. Barak had planned to hand over three small Arab villages near
Jerusalem Sunday to ease growing Palestinian frustration. That was
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, Barak was responding to stepped up attacks against
Israeli troops, and their allied Lebanese militia, by the Hezbollah
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   While Israel has been pulling out of its hilltop forts in
Lebanon, handing them over to the Israeli-paid and trained South
Lebanon Army, Hezbollah has been attacking with mortars and
rockets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to attacking Hezbollah, Israeli planes this weekend
destroyed 10 tanks that belonged to a Palestinian group allied with
Syria. Syria largely controls Lebanon and Israelis fear it could
encourage attacks over the border
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Barak's office said the attacks were meant to
show Israel's ``future retaliatory ability against whoever might
attack it.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli papers reported that the Palestinian group might have
supplied a tank to Hezbollah and Israel meant to warn Syria not to
supply weapons to Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow can be e-mailed at: larryk(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this story)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
