</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP-KOREA-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: PRESS IS DIVIDED ON ACCOUNTS OF KOREAN WAR MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sept. 29, 1999, The Associated Press provided extensive
evidence that GIs killed a helpless group of civilians in the early
days of the Korean War. Since then, its report of the incident at
No Gun Ri, 17 months in the making, has became a media personality
in its own right. It has been praised. It has been followed. It has
been honored with journalism's top prizes. More recently, it has
been pilloried.
</P>
<P>
   On May 12, 2000, U.S. News &AMP; World Report published a 10-page
report on its Web site, four weeks in the making, whose skeptical
gist was summed up in the headline ``Doubts About a Korean
`Massacre,''' followed by ``American soldiers allegedly slaughtered
hundreds of innocent refugees at a place called No Gun Ri. A new
review of the facts challenges that claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Its work relied on archival documents and some interviews with
the GIs quoted by The Associated Press, many of whom, it said, ``do
not support the thesis of the AP story.''
</P>
<P>
   Have U.S. News and other critics seriously undermined AP's
report? Sorting through the various accounts offers a window on how
news judgments about controversial events are made. The evidence
available about No Gun Ri is sometimes contradictory, all the
editors and reporters involved agree. What sets the accounts apart
are editorial choices: how long the reporting should last; how many
people should be interviewed, and in what depth; how the relative
importance of documents should be evaluated; and when it comes to
writing, how the final account should be framed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the world learned of No Gun Ri from AP's report. It led
to widespread coverage, which tended to emphasize the horror of the
killings and the conflicted feelings of some GIs about their role.
Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered an investigation of the
accusations. Until then, the military had denied responsibility,
rejecting the claims of South Koreans who sought reparations.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-April, the wire service's report was awarded this year's
Pulitzer Prize for investigative reporting. Not long afterward,
military affairs writers at three news organizations _ U.S. News,
The Baltimore Sun and the military journalism Web site stripes.com
_ began looking into the background of one of the AP's sources,
Edward L. Daily.
</P>
<P>
   This recent and skeptical coverage of No Gun Ri was set off and
framed by documents that came to light indicating that Daily had
embellished his military record and was not at No Gun Ri. Daily had
told the AP and other news organizations that he had fired on the
refugees under direct orders.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Seymour Topping, the administrator of the Pulitzer
Prizes, said the Pulitzer board had re-examined and reaffirmed its
award. ``The board has reviewed all the documentation and is
up-to-date on all that has been published, he said. ``The board is
taking no further action. There has been no expression of concern
by any member of the board.''
</P>
<P>
   But the round of skeptical reports has left confusion about key
questions in the case. Confusion, in fact, is to be expected when
the source of information is memories and documents that date back
half a century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with a story like this is, when all is said and
done you have a lot of gray,'' said Tom Bowman, the military
affairs reporter for The Sun, who was among those journalists
pursuing the new evidence about Daily.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the central questions involved in the report, and the
way various news organizations have handled them.
</P>
<P>
   The Events
</P>
<P>
   Did GIs Kill Civilians at No Gun Ri?
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the AP's findings was that these killings did
occur, at the hands of young soldiers. In its original report, the
AP said, ``Six veterans of the 1st Cavalry Division said they fired
on the refugee throng at the South Korean hamlet of No Gun Ri, and
six others said they witnessed the mass killing.'' They went on to
quote nine of these 12.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. News account said in its second paragraph, ``There is
little doubt that something terrible did happen there, in the
confusion of war some refugees were shot by American soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman said, ``Obviously Korean civilians died and U.S. soldiers
are saying they shot them.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department officials on May 12 told The New York Times
they had confirmed that U.S. troops had fired on unarmed civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Duffy, the executive editor of U.S. News, said the
magazine headline ``Doubts About a Korean `Massacre''' was not
intended to undercut the evidence of civilian deaths, but to raise
questions about the scope and circumstances of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   By the South Korean refugees' accounts, the shooting took place
on and off for three days, beginning on July 26, 1950, in the early
weeks of the Korean War. Some general facts are agreed upon by most
witnesses. There had been a panicked retreat of American forces,
including elements of the 7th Cavalry Regiment, and they feared
that the refugees had been infiltrated by North Korean soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Several units, including H Company and F Company, regrouped near
a railroad trestle where the main road curved underneath a railroad
track. Refugees walking along the track were strafed by U.S.
planes. Looking for cover, the refugees ended up under the trestle.
</P>
<P>
   How many were killed there is a matter of dispute. The fourth
paragraph of the AP report said: ``Ex-GIs speak of 100, 200 or
simply hundreds dead. The Koreans, whose claim for compensation was
rejected last year, say 300 were shot to death at the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the article, it again cited the Korean contentions, and
added, ``Some ex-GIs today estimate 100 or fewer were killed. But
those close to the bridge,'' the AP said, ``generally put the total
at about 200.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News reported that James Kerns, a member of H Company, 2nd
Battalion _ the unit of men most directly involved _ ``sharply
disputed the number of refugees in the tunnel.'' However, his
estimate (he said ``there weren't over 125 people in there'') is
within the AP's range.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy said, ``If you read the AP account, it certainly leaves
open the possibility that hundreds were dead.'' Kerns, he said,
``is disputing that possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department officials told The New York Times that
hundreds were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Witness
</P>
<P>
   Was Daily Credible? Was He Even There?
</P>
<P>
   If the Koreans are the least visible witnesses in the U.S.
media, Edward L. Daily was easily the most visible.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks to the AP were vivid _ ``On summer nights, when the
breeze is blowing, I can still hear their cries, the little kids
screaming.'' Still, he was one of 50 sources, American and Korean,
for the wire service; the factual points he made in the report were
corroborated by other, named American sources.
</P>
<P>
   The NBC News program ``Dateline'' relied more heavily on Daily.
The network's half-hour segment helped make the eloquent veteran
the public face of GI guilt over No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   This prominence, in turn, made it more likely that reporters
would pay attention when told that Daily might never have been at
No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bowman; Joseph L. Galloway, the writer of the U.S. News article;
and Ed Offley, the Washington bureau chief of the stripes.com Web
site discovered personnel records flatly contradicting Daily's
assertions about his military service: that he was a prisoner of
war, that he had received certain decorations, and, most important,
that he served with H Company, the unit of the 7th Cavalry Regiment
directly involved in the No Gun Ri incident.
</P>
<P>
   How solid is the new evidence?
</P>
<P>
   It has raised serious doubts among some reporters who trusted
Daily. He has responded to very few questioners. When Galloway
reached him, Daily raised the possibility that his memory had been
affected by emotional trauma or his anti-depressant medication.
</P>
<P>
   Charles J. Hanley, one of the AP reporters, said he originally
found Daily's accounts of events convincing, and trusted his
documentary evidence: a driver's license placing him with the
company in March 1950, a letter home naming his company commander,
and an H Company ceremonial Christmas dinner menu from Dec. 25,
1949. Not until recently did Hanley get documentation of the
conflicting personnel records.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley said this past weekend: ``There is a discrepancy in the
sketchy military record of one of our more than 40 sources. We are
trying to get to the bottom of it. But this source provided no
essential information for our report on No Gun Ri.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question, however, that the newly discovered
personnel records cast doubt on Daily's claims, not only about No
Gun Ri but about his entire military career.
</P>
<P>
   How important is Daily? AP's executive editor, Jonathan Wolman,
said in a statement last week: ``Serious questions involve veteran
Ed Daily. We spoke to soldiers who put him at the scene and have
reviewed the documentation he offered for his role.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If it turns out that he and those records deceived
us, we will be extremely regretful, and saddened for him. But the
tale of No Gun Ri does not fall on the words of Daily.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanley points out that Daily is not quoted until the 56th
paragraph of the original account. And he said that several other
veterans confirmed the basic fact of the killing before Daily did.
</P>
<P>
   However, Stephen G. Smith, the editor of U.S. News, describes
Daily as ``the linchpin'' of the wire service's original report.
``He's the one who ties it all together,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the AP account depends on what Smith calls ``a mosaic of
partial quotes,'' the fact that Daily's three quotes were vivid,
full sentences dealing with the event, the orders and the veterans'
feelings of guilt made him more crucial than the other veterans
interviewed, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Few of those skeptical of the overall report mention the South
Korean witnesses, who are also quoted at some length.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these South Koreans are seeking reparations, a fact
mentioned with some irritation by two veterans interviewed by The
New York Times last week. Few journalists have reinterviewed the
South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   But Hanley bristles at the idea that their quest for reparations
casts doubt on their memories. ``Frankly,'' he said, ``it is
analogous to questioning the right of Holocaust victims to seek
some token of reparation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rules
</P>
<P>
   Amid Fear, Were There Orders to Kill?
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being the public face of No Gun Ri, Daily is also one
of three former soldiers who tell the AP _ either in the original
report or in a video on the wire service's Web site _ that their
commanders on the scene ordered them to fire. He told the AP: ``The
command looked at it as getting rid of the problem in the easier
way. That was to shoot them in a a group.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of orders is crucial to determining whether the
killings were simply lethal overreaction by young soldiers scared
that enemy troops were hidden among the civilians, or whether they
constituted a war crime.
</P>
<P>
   A second soldier from H Company, Eugene Hesselman, was quoted as
saying that the company commander, Capt. Melbourne C. Chandler, had
said: ``To hell with all those people. Let's get rid of all of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News points out that H Company's morning report for July
27, the summary of a unit's activity the day before, listed
Hesselman as having been wounded on July 26. But its attempts to
reach Hesselman proved unsuccessful. Hesselman, in an interview
long before the name of No Gun Ri was widely known, had told the AP
that he had a small shrapnel wound and declined to be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, however, said that the medical battalion's morning
reports indicated that Hesselman had been evacuated to the medical
unit on July 26, the day of the massacre. However, the morning
report of July 27 does not indicate when that transfer occurred _
before or after the shooting, before or after any order might have
been given.
</P>
<P>
   The third veteran to mention orders, George Preece, does so in a
videotaped interview with Hanley. In an interview with The
Lexington (Ky.) Herald-Leader days after the AP released its
original report on Sept. 29, Preece retracted the statement, and he
has since denied that any orders were given.
</P>
<P>
   But Hanley said on Friday that he now has interviews with 10
former GIs confirming that there were direct orders. As for the
retractions and rollbacks of some veterans on the details and even
the existence of the killings, Hanley said he believed that the
former GIs had come under pressure from fellow veterans, or were
worried about possible war-crimes charges.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley also points out that no veteran came to AP volunteering
information for the original article.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``These guys were called cold,'' and remembered details
of the events that in many cases matched the details the South
Koreans had given.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley also says that arguments about on-the-scene orders
overlook two general orders from top commanders. The 1st Cavalry
Division headquarters on July 24 had issued an order saying: ``No
refugees to cross the front line. Fire everyone trying to cross
lines. Use discretion in case of women and children.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News made no reference to these general orders.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would frame his account differently if he had
to do it again, Galloway replied: ``If I had time to do the other
interviews and sit back and ponder, I might have written it
differently. But still, as it stands, not bad. I think we did a
good job in the time that we had. I stand behind it. I think in the
end, when the investigation is over and done, there will be a lot
more holes shot in the AP story.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he meant by ``in the time we had,'' Galloway said he
was trying to get his piece published before Offley and Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the crucial centerpiece of the AP report, the
American soldiers killed at least 100 Korean civilians _ possibly
under direct orders _ has been chipped but hardly shattered by the
latest revelations.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Patterson, a rifleman in the 2nd Battalion, said in an
interview with The New York Times last week: ``Unfortunately, the
incident took place. Numbers are not known exactly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
