<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-DAD-NYT &LR;      05-21 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S FATHER'S JOURNEY: POSSUM HOLLOW, TENN., TO THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE-BIO, GORE-BIO-ABRIDGED) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Albert Arnold Gore of Tennessee never ran a negative
campaign. In his first senatorial race, against an octogenarian
incumbent, Kenneth McKellar, in the Democratic primary of 1952, he
told friends it would be unseemly to make an issue of his
opponent's age.
</P>
<P>
   That season's hot tag lines: ``Thinking feller, vote for
McKellar'' vs. ``Think some more, and vote for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore won that race, and 18 years later his political career also
ended on the high road. In that last losing race, against Bill
Brock, a Republican, in 1970, he never aggressively answered a
whole range of attacks, including the untrue accusation that he had
personally benefited by routing Interstate 40 through land he
owned, and the unfair suggestion that he had forgotten his roots
while chasing after the Kennedys at Georgetown dinner parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Watergate investigation later showed that Nixon operatives
had poured illegal campaign funds into the race. Some of the money
came from Richard Mellon Scaife, the same conservative who later
spent millions on anti-Clinton investigations and activities.
</P>
<P>
   And the man who defeated Gore eventually apologized for the
divisive tone of the campaign. His slogan, designed to appeal to
disaffected whites supporting George Wallace, was ``Bill Brock
believes in the things we believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Born poor in the remote settlement of Possum Hollow, Tenn., Gore
lived through the worst of the Depression and spent seven years
working his way through college by teaching in a one-room school _
he would spend one year earning money, then the next year spending
it on his studies.
</P>
<P>
   He loved music, played a mean fiddle, and always said he ran for
office because as a kid he had seen the picture of a cousin who was
running for the state Legislature on a utility pole and liked the
idea of seeing his own face up there.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also moved by ideas, and was a committed free trader
and New Dealer who believed that, as he said, ``nothing cures
poverty like money.'' He married a strong woman, a fellow lawyer,
Pauline LaFon, and spent much of his career defending unpopular
stands, like his opposition to American involvement in Vietnam and
his refusal to sign Sen. Strom Thurmond's Southern Manifesto, which
encouraged southerners to defy court decisions on desegregation.
(He did, however, vote against the Civil Rights Act in 1964 _ an
election year for him _ and wrote in his memoirs that that vote was
an enduring regret.)
</P>
<P>
   He felt no Southerner had a real chance at his party's
presidential nomination but hoped to serve as vice president, and
he campaigned hard against Sen. John F. Kennedy of Massachusetts
and a fellow Tennessean, Sen. Estes Kefauver, in an effort to
become Adlai Stevenson's running mate in 1956. Kefauver won.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was hopeful again in 1960, but Kennedy chose Lyndon B.
Johnson. At Gore's funeral, his son joked about the senator's
longtime longing for the No. 2 job: ``Now that's humility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000521.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LABOR-CHINA-NYT &LR;      05-21 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR LEADERS WARN DEMOCRATS ON CHINA TRADE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related CLINTON-CHINA) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In lobbying House Democrats to vote against the China trade
bill, the nation's labor leaders are warning of political perils
for the Democrats if the bill passes.
</P>
<P>
   In blunt terms, they are warning that Vice President Al Gore and
other Democratic candidates are likely to fare worse in the
November elections if the China trade bill passes because union
members will be so angry.
</P>
<P>
   But if the House rejects the trade bill, labor leaders say,
union members will quickly forget the episode and will forgive
those Democrats who backed the bill, which would grant permanent
normalized trade relations to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel different if you win a vote _ you're ready to move
on,'' said Steve Rosenthal, the AFL-CIO's political director. ``But
if we lose, it's going to be tougher to put the pieces back
together. It's an emotional issue right now, and it has the
potential of really causing a major problem as we get closer to the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the bill's backers predicting that they will narrowly
triumph in the vote scheduled for this week, some Democratic Party
leaders said union officials were exaggerating the extent of a
labor backlash to make Democratic lawmakers afraid to support the
trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders have repeatedly warned that the China trade fight
could set back the Democrats the way labor's anger over Congress'
approval of the North American Free Trade Agreement hurt the
Democrats in the 1994 congressional elections. After the
Republicans won control of the House that year, many labor leaders
said the Democrats lost largely because many union members,
normally dependable Democrats, stayed home out of anger over NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   The fear that enraged union members will again sit out this
year's election is greatest in the large industrial swing states of
the Midwest, including Pennsylvania, Ohio, Illinois and Michigan.
These are states that Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, may
well need in order to win in November. The three unions lobbying
hardest against the China bill, the Teamsters, the Steelworkers,
and the Auto Workers, are especially strong in these states.
</P>
<P>
   If union members do not vote, or back the Republicans, that
could tip some of those states toward the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush and make it harder for
Democrats to regain control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats need a net gain of six seats to control the House.
Among the Democratic House members that union leaders say will be
more vulnerable this November because they supported the trade bill
are Lois Capps of California, David Moore of Kansas, and Jay Inslee
of Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after Capps endorsed the bill, William D. Elder, the
secretary-treasurer of a Teamsters' local in Ventura, Calif., wrote
her, saying his union was reassessing its support of her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But some Democratic officials asserted that labor's dismay with
the China trade bill would hardly hurt Gore and the Democrats.
These officials predicted that union members would largely forget
the China fight by November and would instead be focusing on issues
like Social Security and a patient's bill of rights that would
persuade them to vote Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, members of labor disagree with the vice president
and some members of Congress on this,'' said David J. Leland,
chairman of the Ohio Democratic Party. ``But overall, these union
members understand that working families are better served by
making sure that Al Gore is the next president.''
</P>
<P>
   One undecided Democratic House member, Gregory Meeks of New
York, said that he was angered at a recent meeting when a labor
leader warned Charles Rangel, the ranking Democrat on the House and
Ways and Means Committee, that the China fight might prevent him
from becoming the committee's chairman because disgruntled union
members might not vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most labor leaders I spoke to don't feel that way,'' Meeks
said. ``They know they'll be cutting off their noses to spite their
face. Once this is all over _ there's a lot of passion for sure _
we'll have to work out a plan together to work together to take
back the House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
