<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1550 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DRUG-MONEY-FEDS-KAN &LR;      05-21 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-MONEY-FEDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT A HINDRANCE, NOT A HELP, ON FORFEITURE LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN DILLON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The U.S. Department of Justice is far more
than a silent partner in the mass evasion of state laws by local
police and state patrols. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Justice Department is the main culprit, The Kansas
City Star has found. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department invented the system that allows police to
keep most of the drug money they seize contrary to most state laws.
It then trained police how to use the system and fought efforts to
reform it, The Star found. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The chief sponsor of the 1984 law that created a partnership
between federal agencies and police now wishes he had never opened
the door. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never envisioned that the feds would circumvent state
law,'' says former U.S. Rep. William J. Hughes, a New Jersey
Democrat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials say they never have encouraged
police to avoid their own laws. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A real motivation on the federal side is to reward the help we
get from our brother and sister law enforcement,'' said Jerry
McDowell, head of the Justice Department's money laundering and
asset forfeiture division. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The real motivation here is to knock the socks off the
criminal gangs.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the hand-offs are possible only because the Justice
Department twisted the 1984 law, which simply allowed federal
agencies to share forfeitures with local police who helped in a
joint investigation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to addressing joint investigations, the Justice
Department wrote guidelines that established an ``adoption''
procedure, allowing federal agencies to adopt forfeitures from
local cases when they weren't even involved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even as they were writing the guidelines, Justice Department
officials had in hand a study showing that adoptions would conflict
with state laws, most of which made some effort to keep seized
money from going directly back to police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The study showed more than half the states specifically
designated the money to go somewhere else, such as to a state
fund. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Justice attorneys determined that state laws did not
specifically prohibit police from turning over a seizure to a
federal agency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State and local law enforcement quickly began taking their
seizures to the federal government, said David Smith, who worked
with forfeitures in the Justice Department in the early 1980s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody ever anticipated that it would be as
wildly successful as it was in getting the police motivated to do
more forfeitures,'' said David Smith, who left the department in
1986 and now co-chairs a committee on forfeiture abuse for the
National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:Not a hard sell &QL; 
 &LR; tx:The quick launch of the adoption program came thanks to
training seminars that the Justice Department put on to show police
how to take advantage of it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brad Cates, then-director of the department's Office of Asset
Forfeiture, pointed out in 1988 that training was going especially
well in California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like 500 police chiefs and whatnot have attended,''
Cates told a House judiciary subcommittee hearing that year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond training, federal officials sometimes have recruited
police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, just a few days after the Missouri Supreme Court ruled
that state forfeitures had to go to education in most cases, the
U.S. attorney for the Western District of Missouri wrote a letter
to state and local law enforcement agencies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that all of you in law enforcement are in desperate
need for additional financial resources,'' wrote Jean Paul
Bradshaw. He explained that police could bring seizures to a
federal agency even if the agency had no involvement in the case. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As most of you know, the money we share through our forfeiture
program goes directly to the state or local law enforcement
agency,'' he wrote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not that the federal program has ever been a hard sell to
police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, the North Carolina State Highway Patrol was
reluctant to expand its role and step up seizures from traffic
stops _ until a DEA agent presented the federal forfeiture program
during a meeting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Then everybody's eyes lit up,'' the head of North Carolina's
Department of Crime Control and Public Safety told congressmen in
1989. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In two years, the Justice Department returned more than $117
million in adoptive and joint forfeiture proceeds to state and
local departments across the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But police were circumventing state laws to take part in the
federal program. For example, in California, where federal agencies
were focusing their program, state law at that time required
forfeited money to go to a mental health fund. But police
themselves got $48 million in just one year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We receive a case which is in every aspect a local case, been
worked on pretty much by the local agencies all the way from
beginning to end, and we put our cover on it,'' Joe Whitley, deputy
assistant attorney general, told the House judiciary subcommittee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then-U.S. Rep. Lawrence J. Smith, a Florida Democrat, was
shocked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are telling me basically is that the federal
government is complicit with the law enforcement agencies in
California in trying to, in essence, subvert the California state
law,'' Smith said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such revelations led Hughes in 1988 to sponsor an amendment to
prohibit federal agencies from overriding state forfeiture laws.
Congress passed the amendment, which was to take effect Oct. 1,
1989. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Justice and law enforcement lobbied against it. And
unbeknownst to many members of Congress, a repeal of the amendment
had been slipped into a large defense appropriations bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not know about that (provision) until after it was
approved,'' Hughes says today. ``We were all surprised.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Hughes and others say they don't know who was
responsible for the measure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Hughes, the issue was dead. He said he wrote then-U.S.
Attorney General Richard Thornburgh to request a meeting about the
forfeitures but never got a response. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a very serious effort to try to stem what looked like
would become a pretty regular practice of circumventing state
law,'' Hughes said. ``The power of law enforcement was too much.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thornburgh, who is now a Washington lawyer, for the past six
months did not return a reporter's telephone calls requesting an
interview. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Edwin Meese III, who was U.S. attorney general during the
early years of the federal program, said he is worried about the
direction of adoptions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious problem,'' said Meese, who is now with the
Heritage Foundation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for law enforcement leaders not to allow the
money to be the tail wagging the dog.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even Bradshaw, the former U.S. attorney in Kansas City, now
questions the adoption program. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me it is getting far afield from what it was
intended, from what perhaps the federal role ought to be,''
Bradshaw said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
