<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SCHLESSINGER-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAMOUNT SWIMS AGAINST TIDE BY PUTTING SCHLESSINGER ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A humorous television commercial for the Kia Spectra automobile,
which began running this month, ends with a truck driver asking his
male passenger, ``So you're a Pisces, too, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, viewers of ``Dawson's Creek'' on the WB network
will see what is being billed as the first romantic kiss between
two male characters in a prime-time TV entertainment series.
</P>
<P>
   Come the fall, the linchpin of the NBC Must See TV Thursday
prime-time lineup will be ``Will and Grace,'' a sitcom centered on
a buttoned-down gay man and his life with a straight woman and a
gay pal.
</P>
<P>
   And Fox Broadcasting has high hopes for a sitcom for the
2000-2001 season called ``Don't Ask,'' featuring John Goodman as a
divorced father who is gay.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, Paramount Television is introducing a
syndicated talk show featuring Dr. Laura Schlessinger, the
conservative advice maven whose radio audience has listened to her
stern declarations that homosexuality is a deviation from the
biological norm and incompatible with Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   With timing being a crucial factor in the success of television
programming, a question arises: How confident are Paramount
executives about their abilities to swim against the tide?
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Paramount remains fully committed to the Schlessinger
TV program, saying it has no intention to contribute to ``an
environment of hurt, hate or intolerance.'' In a statement last
week, the company described commercial sales as ``strong.''
</P>
<P>
   However, times have changed and the statement may not be enough
to soothe the offended sensibilities of an increasingly diverse
audience. ``Offending gay people is not acceptable the way it may
have been even five years ago,'' said Paul Poux, principal at the
Poux Co. in New York, an agency specializing in marketing to gay
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers are becoming more aware of all their customers,''
he added, ``so maybe standards for talking about gay people are
being brought into line with those for other groups.''
</P>
<P>
   One advertiser making its position clear is Procter &AMP; Gamble,
which sells packaged goods mainstays like Tide, Bounty and Charmin.
It canceled plans to advertise on the TV program, citing the
controversy generated by increasingly angry protests against
Paramount and Schlessinger by gay advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   Other advertisers like More.com, Toysrus.com and Xerox have
either withdrawn from her radio program, announced they would not
sponsor her TV program or both.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Procter &AMP; Gamble, the nation's second-largest
advertiser, is a hurdle for the TV program to overcome because many
advertisers ``would not go below the standards'' of a marketing
giant like P&AMP;G, said Gene DeWitt, chairman and chief executive at
Optimedia International U.S. in New York. His media services
agency, formerly DeWitt Media, is owned by Publicis.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a hit syndicated talk show can generate enormous
profits. It is estimated that ``The Oprah Winfrey Show'' earns $300
million annually for King World Productions. And according to The
Hollywood Reporter, ``The Jerry Springer Show'' was being shopped
around last year for $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems sensible to seek a TV talk show host from the ranks
of popular radio talk show hosts. Schlessinger's radio ratings _
second highest among all national talk programs _ suggests she has
loyal followers across the country. Indeed, in its statement last
week, Paramount Television said it would ``expect that the fans of
Dr. Laura will express their disappointment'' with P&AMP;G for
withdrawing its advertising ``without ever having seen the show or
judging it on its own merits.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, radio stars like Rush Limbaugh and Howard Stern, with
legions of loyal fans, have found television tougher than their
regular gigs. Schlessinger, in a recent appearance on ``Larry King
Live'' on CNN, seemed strident and untelegenic.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Paramount executives would suspend production of
the show at this point, DeWitt replied, ``Not if they can still
make money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Morality may have moved as far west as Cincinnati,'' he added,
referring to the headquarters of Procter &AMP; Gamble, ``but it hasn't
made it to the coast yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
