<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRY-POTTER-MEDIA-1195(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHERS USE SECRECY IN HARRY POTTER PROMOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Mystery and magic are the magnets that draw fans to
Harry Potter, the fictional British
schoolboy-cum-literary-phenomenon who has made millions of pounds
and dollars for its author and publishers. And now the book series'
publicists are trying a little sorcery themselves, casting a spell
of secrecy that they hope will conjure up the book-selling event of
the year, if not the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth volume in the Harry Potter series is set to be
published on July 8 in both Britain and the United States _ unlike
the last three, in which the American releases came several months
after the British. And this time, a substantial degree of effort is
going into ensuring that as little as possible is known about the
book's contents in advance.
</P>
<P>
   There will be, for instance, none of the advance copies that
usually land on reviewers' desks a few months before publication.
No one is promoting prepublication interviews with the author, J.K.
Rowling. Indeed, according to the U.S. and British publishers,
Rowling will be giving no interviews at all until publication day.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is a secret. So is the cover design. Even the title is
supposed to remain closely guarded. All that the British publisher,
Bloomsbury, is prepared to acknowledge is that this fourth and
latest in a planned seven-book series will be a whopping 600 pages
_ twice the length of previous Harry Potters. (The U.S. publisher,
the Arthur A. Levine Books imprint of Scholastic Books, says its
version will be closer to 700 pages because of a different layout
and illustrations.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This book is really under wraps,'' said Judy Corman, a
spokeswoman for Scholastic.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bloomsbury in London, the reason for the secrecy is
the author's wish that children's enjoyment of the book not be
spoiled by advance word about the plot. ``The author was very
concerned about this,'' said Rosamund de la Hey, head of children's
books sales and marketing at Bloomsbury. Both publishers said that
only a handful of people at either house had been given a peek of
the text itself.
</P>
<P>
   But one result of the secrecy, of course, is to stoke the
fevered imaginations of countless children _ and not a few adults _
about a book that is already in such demand that advance Internet
orders kept it near the top of Amazon.com's best-seller list last
week. (It had earlier been No. 1, but was bumped to second place by
advance orders for a thriller to be released on Tuesday by Tyndale
House, ``The Indwelling: The Beast Takes Possession,'' by Tim F.
Lahaye and Jerry B. Jenkins.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is quite a classic marketing ruse,'' Rita Clifton, chief
executive of Interbrand, Newell &AMP; Sorrell, a brand consultancy,
said of the Harry Potter campaign. ``It's like launching a new car.
There is quite obsessive secrecy. All the news is kept under strict
control. And you create a sense of expectation and anticipation.
Any leaks would dilute the excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but Bloomsbury's soaring stock price may benefit,
too. ``Having a lot of Harry Potter razzmatazz all helps,'' said
Louise Barton, a media analyst with the brokerage firm of Investec
Henderson Crosthwaite, even though the Harry Potter books are an
important but not dominant part of Bloomsbury's attraction for
investors. From a one-year low of 2.55 pounds ($3.79) before the
Harry Potter phenomenon zoomed into the stratosphere last year,
Bloomsbury's stock has risen to a close of 7.35 pounds on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The British and American publishers are clearly calculating that
when the floodgates of pent-up demand burst on July 8 the supply
will be there to meet the expected clamor for a book whose
predecessors have sold a combined 20.8 million copies in the United
States and an additional 7 million in Britain and the rest of the
English-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomsbury's first print order is for a million copies,
retailing at 14.99 pounds ($22.50). Scholastic's is for 3.8
million, selling at $25.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the third book in the series _ ``Harry Potter and the
Prisoner of Azkaban'' _ had first-print runs of 900,000 in the
United States and 275,000 in Britain and the rest of the
English-speaking world, which includes markets like Canada, South
Africa and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   When the moment of publication arrives, the secrecy is to give
way to what the publishers plan as an explosion of stunts to
provide what Clifton called ``the dry ice, the puffs of smoke to
heighten the drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Newton, Bloomsbury's chief executive, said that a train
with a steam locomotive would be waiting at a mock-up of the
fictional platform _ platform 9} _ at Kings Cross Station in
London, where, in all four books, Harry Potter slips between the
real and the magical worlds to travel to the Hogwarts boarding
school.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for four days or so, the train will tour several British
cities: Oxford, Birmingham, Manchester, York, Newcastle and Perth.
``That was supposed to be a secret,'' Newton said in an interview
at Bloomsbury's offices in Soho Square.
</P>
<P>
   The train itself _ the oldest in Britain, Newton said, with cars
dating to 1891 and 1912 _ will figure into a marketing maneuver
that some young readers might recognize from Roald Dahl's ``Charlie
and the Chocolate Factory,'' in which children compete furiously
for scarce golden candy wrappers that gain access to Willie Wonka's
magical chocolate factory.
</P>
<P>
   Booksellers will have vouchers to give to the first children in
their shops to buy the new ``Harry Potter,'' Newton said. The
vouchers will buy access to the train when it halts in the stations
along the route, with the author, Rowling, on board to sign copies.
</P>
<P>
   The handouts could very well create the same kind of stampede
for first copies of the book as happened last year, when the third
book in the series was timed for release at 3:45 p.m. in Britain,
just when schools let out.
</P>
<P>
   Newton said the cost of chartering the train was a secret,
though ``less than you might think.'' A spokesman for the company
that rents it out _ both the train and the company are called the
Queen of Scots _ said the usual price was around $22,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   While both the British and the American publishers deny it,
there does seem to be an element of competition worthy of Harry
Potter's fictional game of quidditch over who gets to sell the
books first.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Corman at Scholastic said, many
booksellers are planning to open at midnight on July 7 to cope with
the anticipated rush. Doing so would give the U.S. publishers a
six-hour start on Bloomsbury, which had initially intended to
publish the books at 11 a.m., London time (6 a.m., Eastern Standard
Time). Bloomsbury is now trying to decide when the bookstore doors
should be thrown open, de la Hey said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Scholastic is running a sweepstakes through its
own magazines to provide 5,000 winners with a copy of the new book
delivered on the day of publication. Corman said planes would tow
Harry Potter fliers above U.S. beaches, and at midnight on July 7 a
Harry Potter news ticker will illuminate Times Square. Packs of
promotional materials are being sent to 15,000 U.S. bookstores.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With the books being published on the same day in the United
States and Britain, the publishers hope to pre-empt the kind of
Internet arbitrage that erupted last year when frustrated American
buyers went to British Web sites to buy the third ``Harry Potter''
book before the release of the U.S. edition two months later.
</P>
<P>
   The title, whatever it is, will be the same in both countries,
too _ unlike the first book, which was called ``Harry Potter and
the Philosopher's Stone'' in Britain but ``Harry Potter and the
Sorcerer's Stone'' in the United States. But the American edition,
according to both publishers, will be more lavishly illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   For Bloomsbury, the publication will be a high point along a
trail of planned events that the company hopes will keep its sales,
and stock, aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. is planning to release the first Harry Potter movie
next year. Bloomsbury has an expanding list of new and established
authors of literary novels. It has signed a talent-spotting deal
with the Creative Artists Agency in Hollywood. And Bloomsbury's
reference division is developing a series of databases, including a
recently introduced ``Business Bible'' for executives and
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pipeline is very full of major new projects,'' Newton
said, ``and I think the market has recognized that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
