<P>
   &UR; THE CARE AND TREATMENT OF THE DERRIERE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The cartoon on the cover of  &UR; Richard Stengel &LR; 's new book,
``(You're Too Kind) A Brief History of Flattery'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster; $25) pictures a posterior emblazoned with a lip print.
Stengel provides not only a history of flattery and an analysis of
its uses but also a list of flattering do's and don'ts. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   ``Never offer a compliment and ask a favor at the same time,''
``Don't be afraid to flatter people you think already get
enough,''``Never give the same compliment to different people,''
``Never be candid when a person asks you to be candid'' and
``Locate a weakness and praise its opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who are catching rather than pitching, the author
gives a handy set of directions for answering flattery, including
deconstruction of the following responses:
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you'll speak at my funeral'' (acknowledges the
compliment but shows you don't take it too seriously), silence
(``as aggressive as one gets in rebuffing flattery''), ``You
flatter me'' (thanks the giver, &LR;  but at the same thing accuses him
of an ulterior motive).
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Twist magazine reports that  &UR; Doreen Cott &LR; , who went to the
home of  &UR; Tommy &LR;  and  &UR; Pamela Anderson Lee &LR;  some time ago to give one
of them a massage, is suing both of them, claiming that the bite
their rottweiler inflicted on her butt caused her nerve damage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEARST TAKES ACTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Patty Hearst &LR; , who will be a witness when former SLA member
 &UR; Kathleen Soliah &LR;  (now  &UR; Sara Jane Olson &LR; ) goes on trial in August,
told Talk magazine about her practical way _ heiress' privilege _
of dealing with what she doesn't like.
</P>
<P>
   She was only a little disturbed, she said, when she first
learned of PattyHearst.com, a site that was selling T-shirts and
posters. ``It was pretty unsavory. But it was just something you
could ignore. When it changed into the Free Kathy Soliah link,
that's when I completely flipped. I find everything about it
offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a problem that Hearst believed could have been solved
by lawyers. So she bought the site and shut it down.
``PattyHearst.com is closed'' is all that's there now cq &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - The Professional and Administrative Staff Association of the
Museum of Modern Art in New York has been on strike since April 28,
reports artnet.com, causing the cancellation of 65 percent of the
museum's educational programs. The Village Voice has refused to run
listings while the strike continues, and union truckers are
refusing to make pickups and deliveries there.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Princess Eugenie &LR; , 10-year-old daughter of the  &UR; Duke  &LR; and
 &UR; Duchess of York &LR; , has a new hairstyle, which is the subject of an
item in People magazine (and here). Meanwhile, the BBC's
announcement that it would not televise the pageant honoring the
 &UR; Queen Mother &LR; 's 100th birthday this summer angered Conservative
newspapers _ ``sad and surprising,'' said the Daily Telegraph _ and
Prime Minister  &UR; Tony Blair &LR; , who told Parliament last week that he
thought ``everyone would like to see'' the event. An hour later,
ITV, the commercial British network, announced that it would step
in and do the job.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Don Imus &LR;  pledged to African American journalist  &UR; Clarence &LR; 
 &UR; Page &LR;  on his show last week that he will not allow black parodies
and other offensive material on his program.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAUSE TO BEHAVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Reading about the renaming of Parkside Elementary School in San
Francisco after Sen.  &UR; Dianne Feinstein &LR; ,  &UR; Michael Jarvis  &LR; warns the
honoree ``you must live up to new standards and not get busted for
morals issues or fishing without a license.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis recalls that a Southern California junior high school
``adopted the Dodgers,'' renamed the school after star  &UR; Steve &LR; 
 &UR; Garvey &LR; , naming the home economics room after Garvey's then-wife
and the library after  &UR; Tommy Lasorda &LR; . Whereupon Garvey went to
another team, got divorced and ended up making infomercials and
being the target of several paternity suits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is a game of failure. You (mess) up seven times out
of 10. And if you do even that well, you're a god. So because of
the pressure, you have to have an outlet. Not that you have to be a
party animal. But what are you going to do, sit around and (vulgar
solo activity) in your hotel room? It's only natural to want to go
out. ... It's as close to being a rock star as you can get. You can
have women all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   - Oakland A's slugger  &UR; Jason Giambi &LR; , whom Gear magazine
describes as ``baseball's most jocular jock, a hearty partyer and
irreverent orator.''
</P>
