<HEADER>
A1563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PRIVACY-ASSESS-925(2T     05-21 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-ASSESS-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FATE UNCLEAR FOR FTC'S PRIVACY PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Mass., Va.)   By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission plans to go to
Congress this week to seek tough new privacy rules for Internet
businesses. But the nation's consumer protection agency is likely
to encounter skepticism from key Republicans and from industry
groups about the government's ability to impose regulations without
stifling the innovation fueling the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the opposition began mustering its arguments as soon as
the FTC reversed its previous policy by voting on Friday to ask
Congress for new powers to control the ways Internet companies
collect and use information about consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, when the performance of Web sites was rated less
favorably than they are currently being rated, the commission voted
against legislation,'' said Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of
the House Commerce Subcommittee that oversees Internet privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, with the finding that Web sites have improved
dramatically their privacy policies, they are now recommending
legislation,'' he said. ``It seems to be a contradiction that needs
to be understood.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet while high-technology industry groups continue to insist
that any new rules are unwarranted and premature, companies
themselves have differing views on whether new laws are warranted
and, if so, what type.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft insists that no legislation is needed. EBay, the
auction giant, indicated that it could support some sort of minimal
regulation if that curtailed states' rights to impose a patchwork
of differing rules. Bell Atlantic said baseline rules could be
useful.
</P>
<P>
   The only common theme expressed by Internet businesses over the
weekend seemed to be that if Congress proceeds with legislation to
regulate consumer privacy protections online, it should do so
cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all sensitive to this issue,'' said Robert Levitan,
chief executive of Flooz.com, which deals in online gift
certificates. ``We know we are in the spotlight and we are going to
be held to a higher standard.''
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick, which places advertising on Web sites on behalf of
other companies, became a lightning rod for online privacy issues
after it disclosed a plan _ since deferred _ to combine consumer
information gathered online with personal data gathered offline
through direct-mail databases and other means.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to think that industry could self-regulate, but I
think we all have accepted the fact that there will be some
regulation,'' Levitan said. ``We're not jumping up and down
complaining about regulation. We're just saying: Let's do it
wisely.''
</P>
<P>
   If caution means going slowly, companies are likely to get their
wish. Given the complexity of election-year politics and the
fast-changing medium involved, most lawmakers agreed that the
chances of passing Internet privacy legislation this year were all
but nil. But this year's debate could set the stage for action in
the next session.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Internet privacy issue in Congress does not split
along party lines, Rep. Ed Markey, D-Mass., who supports strong
privacy regulation, predicted on Friday that Republicans would
block the consumer protections.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., co-chairman of the House Internet caucus,
responded with the implication that the administration was behind
the FTC move. ``This is an election year, and I think sometimes the
direction they get from up high is to stir this up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it remained unclear over the weekend whether the White
House would back the FTC effort, which comes after the recent
completion of a survey by the commission that found that only about
20 percent of major companies on the Internet had adequate
standards for protecting the privacy of Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the Clinton administration has pushed a
laissez-faire approach to the Internet. And just last week, a top
Commerce Department official told a House hearing on privacy that
self-regulation appeared to be working.
</P>
<P>
   With both parties trying to attract the support _ and dollars _
of the technology industry, the issue could become a tricky one
politically for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the FTC's survey findings and its legislative
proposal will not be released until the agency conducts briefings
around Washington on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But a government official who has seen the 60-page
recommendation said it would suggest only moderate legislation to
set baseline rules that could be used in conjunction with
self-regulation efforts like the seal programs that are used by
some Web sites to certify that they follow their stated privacy
practices.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of monitoring the progress of privacy on the
Internet, the official said, the FTC had not seen enough protection
to avoid regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one step forward, not a massive leap into a highly
regulated, draconian bureaucratic structure,'' said the official,
who predicted that Tauzin and others would be less critical after
seeing the details of the Web survey and the FTC's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   But industry groups began pre-emptive strikes over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Direct Marketing Association released its own
survey of Web sites showing that 93 percent of major Web sites
posted privacy policies and that most of those gave customers
notice of how that information was used and the opportunity to keep
that information from being transferred to third parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, self-regulation has taken hold with lightning
speed,'' said H. Robert Wientzen, president and chief executive of
the association.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Information Technology Association of America issued a
statement from its president, Harris Miller, who called the FTC
report ``a first step down the slippery slope of government
regulation of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet company executives, meanwhile, seemed most concerned
about the effect that new regulations might have on innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the FTC voted on Friday, Microsoft and several
other companies were demonstrating technologies that are being
developed to protect consumers at a weekend privacy retreat in
Leesburg, Va., that was sponsored by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce's
National Chamber Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Purcell, director of corporate privacy for Microsoft,
pointed to efforts to incorporate privacy protection technologies
into Web-browsing software. ``This is not the proper time to stop
or chill that very substantial effort that is being made,'' Purcell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, DataTreasury Corp., showed lawmakers technology
that allows consumers and businesses to conduct all of their online
transactions through DataTreasury's secure system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever regulations are implemented today may not be relevant
tomorrow,'' said Michael Hershman, chairman of Decision Strategies
Fairfax International, a security company in Fairfax, Va. ``This
technology creates an entirely different mode of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to predict how these regulations might be written
and how they might be enforced,'' he added. ``Once you start down
that road, you are never sure where you might end up. I've seen
many regulations written that you think say one thing and do
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Tauke, an executive with Bell Atlantic, said some action
might be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be steps taken in public policy that can be very
helpful in creating a climate in which businesses can flourish and
consumers' privacy can be protected,'' Tauke said. ``I don't think
that Congress should slow down in the privacy area. I think
Congress should get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies said baseline federal legislation was better
than the patchwork of laws being considered by states.
</P>
<P>
   Tod Cohen, public policy director for eBay in Washington, said,
``We would work with the FTC, Congress and the administration to
develop a national standard'' _ provided it pre-empted further
action by states to regulate Internet privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan agreed. ``We need a uniform code across the country,''
he said. ``We need a standard law on privacy and taxation. But
let's do it wisely and make it easy for Internet companies to
comply.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
