<P>
   NATIONAL _ James Truchard was reading at home one night last
winter when a TV news program in the background caught his
attention. A device developed at MIT was being used to enable
paralysis victims to use thought to move their arms. Though the
program didn't mention it, Truchard immediately realized that
National Instruments' technology was part of the MIT device. But
the company founded by three UT grads in the 1970s will make sure
its carefully selected job recruits hear about the technology,
because making a contribution is one of the lures it employees to
hire and retain young engineers and others. Little known even in
Austin, National Instruments has built a reputation of innovation
among scientists around the world. But the company's carefully
managed growth and stability is being challenged by the Internet,
and Wall Street would be happier if it grew faster. (Mahoney,
Austin American-Statesman). 24.
