<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      05-21 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 HONORED FOR BALLOON CATHETER AND WIRELESS COMMUNICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the eighth grade in the late 1940s, Thomas J. Fogarty, in
order to help his widowed mother make ends meet, went to work at
Good Samaritan Hospital in Cincinnati, cleaning medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he got to high school, the hospital promoted him to
scrub technician. ``So at a very early age I saw a lot of
surgery,'' said Fogarty, who often witnessed the complications
arising from blood clots, which surgeons struggled to remove with
forceps after a large part of an artery had been cut open.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Fogarty was awarded the annual Lemelson-MIT Prize to
inventors for his Fogarty Embolectomy Catheter, an invention that
revolutionized vascular surgery after he published a paper
describing the device in 1963. Still the world's most widely used
catheter for blood-clot removal, the Fogarty balloon catheter was
the progenitor of a family tree of balloon catheters used for a
wide range of surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty, 66, envisioned his balloon catheter while still a
student at the University of Cincinnati Medical School. Working in
his attic, he fashioned a prototype by snipping the pinkie finger
off a surgical glove and then _ using fly-tying knots he had
learned while fishing as a boy _ attaching it to a catheter.
</P>
<P>
   With Fogarty's invention, surgeons make small incisions and
insert the catheter, with the balloon not yet inflated, into the
artery. After threading the catheter down the artery so that the
balloon passes the clot, the balloon is inflated and retracted,
pulling the clot along with it.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty, of Portola Valley, Calif., is a professor of surgery at
Stanford University and a practicing surgeon. He is also a
successful entrepreneur who develops medical devices through his
company, Fogarty Engineering, and a venture capitalist who funds
budding medical companies through Three Arch Partners. He also owns
a 325-acre eponymously named vineyard west of Palo Alto that
produces 15,000 cases of wine annually.
</P>
<P>
   The Lemelson-MIT prize, which comes with a $500,000 purse, is
awarded by the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and the
Lemelson Foundation. The prize is named for the late Jerome H.
Lemelson, a prolific inventor whose mechanisms were used in the fax
machine, the supermarket checkout scanner, the Sony Walkman and
other devices.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty _ who credits his childhood deprivation with much of his
entrepreneurial drive _ said he planned to give the prize money to
charity. It is the award itself that is important, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that this award is being given to a physician,
particularly one who is in practice, is meaningful,'' said Fogarty,
noting that such awards are usually given to academics who conduct
basic research. ``You can spend your whole life in a basic research
lab,'' he said, ``but until something is implemented and used by
people, it doesn't bring real social value.''
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS COMMUNICATIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another inventor, Al Gross, 82, received the Lemelson-MIT
Lifetime Achievement Award for Invention. And last week the Federal
Communications Commission sent him a letter of commendation.
</P>
<P>
   Gross, a pioneer in wireless communications, has received
patents over the years for technologies that anticipated inventions
ranging from garage door openers to cell phones and paging systems.
Alas, he notes, the patents expired before any of those devices
came into common use. ``Otherwise I'd be as rich as Bill Gates,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gross was introduced to radio transmissions at age 9, when his
parents took him on a Lake Erie steamer cruise. The ship's wireless
operator beckoned him to come into the communications room and give
a listen. He was hooked. By the time he was 12, he had patched
together his own ham radio from junkyard parts. At age 16, he
earned his amateur radio operator's license. But Gross was restless
being anchored to the desk-bound ham radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be able to walk around and talk to other hams,''
Gross said. He experimented with a hand-held radio that made use of
unexploited frequencies above 100 megahertz. By 1938 he had created
a mobile ham radio that worked. He dubbed it the ``walkie-talkie.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon came World War II, and Gross, then 22, was invited down to
Washington to demonstrate his walkie-talkie in front of William J.
Donovan, the founder of the Office of Strategic Services _ the
precursor to the CIA. ``Donovan liked the idea,'' Gross said. ``He
recruited me and converted me from a civilian to a captain.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross' top-secret mission in the OSS was to develop a two-way
air-to-ground voice communications system so that spies in enemy
territory could transmit information to allied pilots flying
overhead. By 1941, Gross had perfected such a system. The Joint
Chiefs of Staff later said the project, code-named
``Joan-Eleanor,'' was among the Allies' ``most successful wireless
intelligence-gathering operations, saving millions of lives by
shortening the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the end of the war, Gross demonstrated the OSS
walkie-talkie to the Federal Communications Commission's chairman,
E.K. Jett, who was so impressed he wrote an article for the
Saturday Evening Post titled ``Phone Me By Air.'' The article
announced the creation of a Citizens' Radio Communications Service
that would allow for private, short-range radio transmissions. In
it, Jett marveled at the possibilities of what he referred to as
``handie-talkies.''
</P>
<P>
   A staged photo accompanying the article featured a milkman
talking into a radio that, minus the antenna, somewhat resembles a
modern-day cell phone, except that it is about the size of a large
loaf of bread. ``Handie-talkies may result in a civilian world
seething with airborne languages,'' the caption predicts. ``Even
the milkman can be reached en route and told to go back and leave
an extra quart of Grade-A for Ramsay.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross, who left the OSS to form his own electronics company, was
the first to get a citizens' band license from the FCC. His target
market was not milkmen but farmers who, while they were in the
fields on their tractors, wanted to keep in touch with their wives
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was developing new ideas, among them a paging system for
doctors that he introduced in 1949, according to Gross, who long
ago gave up running his own company but is still working, as a
staff engineer for the Orbital Sciences Corp. in Chandler, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The pager apparently was an idea way before its time. ``The
doctors hated it,'' Gross said. ``They complained that it would
interrupt their golf games.''
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
