<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000521.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-HAITI-ELECTIONS-0522-     05-21 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-ELECTIONS-0522-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    AMID DELAYS AND MIX-UPS, HAITIANS HOLD NATIONAL ELECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ This troubled nation lurched toward
recovering its pride and a functioning government Sunday as
national elections were held for the first time in several years.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was marred by delays and bureaucratic mix-ups,
prompting angry criticism from opposition leaders who feared the
results would be tainted by fraud.
</P>
<P>
   A Haitian radio station reported that a policeman was shot and
killed by supporters of a minor party candidate who had been
arrested on election fraud charges, but the report could not be
immediately confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   It was also too early to draw any conclusions about the success
of the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Voting was postponed indefinitely in one of Haiti's nine
jurisdictions because of party squabbling. And with most ballots to
be counted by hand, there was no way to tell what percentage of
registered voters participated or whether the election was free of
widespread irregularities. A firm tally wasn't expected for days.
</P>
<P>
   But after three postponements in the past six months left many
questioning whether Haiti could hold an election at all, some
observers were heartened simply by the sight of people lining up at
polling places and casting their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been lots of complications, but it's a big
improvement over the past,'' said Anne Marie Issa(cq), general
manager of one of the country's radio stations, which had a team of
reporters monitoring the voting. ``The security is good and the
people want to vote very badly. The problem is in the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls were scheduled to open at 6 a.m., but dozens of stations
didn't open until hours later, with some not receiving their
ballots until mid-morning. There were scattered reports of poll
workers refusing to show up because they had not been paid, and
that election monitors from some of the political parties were
barred from watching the proceedings at several polling sites.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leader Gerard Pierre-Charles(cq) called the delays
``sabotage,'' and told reporters that banning monitors from polling
sites could lead to fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   In the teeming slum of Cite Soleil near the Port-au-Prince
waterfront, Beaugil Fenel(cq) waited nearly seven hours to vote,
standing with hundreds of others before a dilapidated fisherman's
hall that served as the polling site. The stench of raw sewage from
scum-filled ditches filled the air, and the decrepit building
swarmed with people, many shouting and pushing, holding their voter
registration cards over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I arrived here at 5 a.m. and they didn't open until about 10
a.m.,'' said Fenel, who finally cast his ballot around 1 p.m.
``Everyone wants to vote because this election is important for
Haiti. Maybe this vote will bring change, and help improve our
economy. But it has been very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Soleil district is a hotbed of support for former Haitian
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide, the country's most powerful
politician. His Lavalas Family Party was backing hundreds of
candidates for seats in Parliament and local governments, hoping to
pave the way for Aristide's re-election as president in the coming
fall election.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders have charged Aristide's cronies with trying
to manipulate the vote through violence and intimidation. Some 15
people were murdered in the months leading up to the election, with
most of the victims coming from opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   Aristide and his supporters have denied the charges, and police
have been unable to solve any of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of international election observers fanned out across the
country to monitor the proceedings, although they weren't expected
to make any conclusive statements until they had a chance to
discuss their impressions after the polls closed.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Leo, an observer from the Caribbean island of Guadeloupe,
checked several dozen polling stations by mid-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the stations started late because they didn't have the
ballots,'' he said. ``But everything has been calm and there
haven't been any problems with security, so far.''
</P>
<P>
   During Haiti's tumultuous 1987 election, more than 30 people
were killed, some gunned down in the streets and their bodies left
there for hours. The country's most recent election in 1997 was
tossed out after widespread fraud tainted the results.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti has had no functioning Parliament since early 1999, and
has lost about $500 million in international aid because donor
nations and groups have been unwilling to send money to a country
with no legislature to oversee its distribution. The country of 8
million is the hemisphere's poorest nation, with an annual per
capita income of $200 to $500, and an estimated illiteracy rate of
80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The current president, Rene Preval _ who took office in 1996 as
Aristide's handpicked successor _ has repeatedly postponed the
elections, ruling the country by decree.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the postponements, some observers held high hopes for
the balloting, partly because a U.S.-backed drive drew millions of
new voters to register.
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear how many of the 4 million registered voters
would actually go to the polls, and the long delays in opening the
stations clearly hampered the proceedings. Downtown Port-au-Prince
was eerily quiet early Sunday, with police blocking off many
streets and the city's ubiquitous small taxis, called Tap-Taps,
banned from the roadways.
</P>
<P>
   Lines of a hundred or more voters stood outside several polling
places, although many didn't get to vote until mid-day because of
the snafus over delivering ballots and opening the sites.
</P>
<P>
   Wigens Joassaint(cq), 22, waited several hours to cast his first
ballot as a voting adult. He hoped the election might bring
positive change, but said Haiti's economy is in such a shambles
that it might take more than a single election to turn things
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the election will really change things because
our leaders have no plan,'' he said. ``There are no jobs here, and
they aren't offering anything to us. I believe the only thing that
can really help Haiti is God.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams may be contacted at Mikew(at)Coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this report)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
