<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, May 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend, daytime temperatures only reached the middle
50s along the Northeast Seaboard as a damp flow of air from the
Atlantic delivered chilly air to the region. Another cool day will
cover the coastal Northeast on Monday with plenty of clouds and the
risk for a few showers as low pressure slides off the New Jersey
coast. Farther south, partial sunshine and humid air will cover the
Southeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably warmer air will reach the Middle West and Ohio Valley
as a warm front passes east across the area. The warmer conditions
may be accompanied by a brief thunderstorm in spots.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the West will stay unseasonably hot with afternoon
readings exceeding 100 degrees across interior California and the
Southwestern deserts.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: OZONE POLLUTION
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, an ``ozone'' watch was posted for portions of
Texas as concentrations of the harmful pollutant were expected to
reach unhealthful levels. Ozone in the upper atmosphere is a gas
that protects humans from the sun's ultraviolet radiation. However,
an increase in ozone near the earth's surface can be the harmful
byproduct of hot weather. Sunlight reacts with hydrocarbons and
carbon monoxide emitted by automobiles and industries to produce
ozone. When winds are light, ozone concentrations can increase to
levels that irritate the eyes and throat and damage vegetation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
