<DOCNO> NYT20000521.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-NATIONAL0522-COX     05-21 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL0522-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National Instruments quietly grows up
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Like many high-tech entrepreneurs, Jim Truchard
dabbled in science as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out to be much more than a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made little crystal radios because we didn't have
electricity,'' said Truchard, who grew up reading by kerosene
lantern. ``My dad just didn't like the idea of electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   What sets Truchard _ who wound up getting a Ph.D. in electrical
engineering from the University of Texas _ apart from many
successful entrepreneurs, however, may not be his background so
much as his company and its culture.
</P>
<P>
   Truchard, 56, is chief executive of National Instruments Corp.,
a test-and-measurement company that had $330 million in sales last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Profitable since its founding in 1976, the company has increased
sales and earnings by at least 20 percent annually 15 of the past
16 years, a time span that would seem like ancient history to many
of today's technology startups. Its stock, which closed at $8.17 on
its first day of trading five years ago, finished at $38 on Friday.
Truchard, like his company, has managed the growth with steadiness
that is winning kudos from employees and industry watchers.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Fortune magazine named National Instruments No. 77
on its list of top 100 companies to work for. Two months later,
Worth magazine listed Truchard No. 32 among the top 50 CEOs for
increasing company success and wealth. The May 29 issue of Forbes
includes National Instruments in a package that names Austin the
No. 1 place to put a business.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is making strides against its competitors. Its
most successful product, called LabView, has become the de facto
standard software for enabling PCs to imitate test-and-measure
equipment that measures sound and electrical waves. It is an
industry long dominated by Agilent Technologies Inc., formerly part
of Hewlett-Packard Co. and a customer of National Instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in a world where ``high tech'' has become a catch-all for
everything from pagers that connect to the Internet to genetic
manipulation, the innovations at National Instruments' Northwest
Austin campus scarcely register beyond a small community of
analysts, scientists and engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Truchard said he was reading at home one night last winter when
a TV news report caught his attention. A national cable channel
showed a paralyzed man who moved his arm with brain waves sent by
wires connected to his skull to equipment strapped to his wrist.
The equipment included National Instruments' technology, yet the
Austin company didn't warrant a mention.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they do,'' said stock analyst Joel Pitt, with Credit
Suisse First Boston, ``is not readily understood by a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   GARAGE STARTUP
</P>
<P>
   What National Instruments does today evolved from a garage in
Austin in the mid-1970.
</P>
<P>
   Truchard and two other scientists, Jeff Kodosky and William
Nowlin, started the company with $3,000 and a $10,000 bank loan.
Kodosky is vice president of research and development. Nowlin
retired in 1996. Both still serve on the company's board.
</P>
<P>
   The three had worked together at the University of Texas Applied
Research Labs, where they measured sound waves and other electrical
signals with Hewlett-Packard oscilloscopes and voltage meters
connected to Hewlett-Packard minicomputers.
</P>
<P>
   H-P's test-and-measurement equipment was the industry standard,
but scientists could only use it with H-P minicomputers. The three
young scientists, working in Truchard's garage, designed a device
that connected H-P's boxes to minicomputers made by Digital
Equipment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   That general-purpose interface bus, or GPIB, is one of about 700
products listed today in National Instruments' 2000 catalog. Most
are manufactured on the company's wooded 20-acre campus in
Northwest Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing Truchard's goal of measured growth, National
Instruments started writing software that could interpret data.
That lead to the introduction of LabView in 1986. Riding in the
wake of Microsoft Corp. and Intel Corp., National Instruments
released LabView for PCs in 1992. Last year, the company adapted
LabView for use in factories to respond to assembly-line problems
immediately without shutting them down.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's a software program, LabView frees scientists and
researchers from writing their own code. They choose the tasks they
want done by pulling down menus on their computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they bring to the table is really a disruptive
technology,'' said Pitt, the analyst, using a phrase from the book
``Innovator's Dilemma,'' a must-read among executives,
entrepreneurs and venture capitalists these days.
</P>
<P>
   Like other ``disruptive technologies,'' LabView has the
potential to force competitors to offer something similar. That is
a major challenge for Agilent, whose business relies heavily on
oscilloscopes and other measurement devices.
</P>
<P>
   But National Instruments is moving too slowly for some. While it
is available on Unix and Macintosh operating systems and the
variety of microprocessors that run them, National Instruments has
focused its efforts on supporting industry standards set by
Microsoft's Windows and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They recognized before long, they were riding the Wintel R&AMP;D
curve,'' said John Barr, an analyst with New York equities firm
Needham &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   That is a shortcoming to some members of the Linux community,
which wants to see more open-source codes from software companies.
</P>
<P>
   Przemek Klosowski is a physicist at the National Institute of
Standards and Technology in Gaithersburg, Md. He's studying neutron
patterns in compounds such as concrete and plastic, which is a way
of understanding their properties and perhaps leading to
improvements in strength, elasticity and durability.
</P>
<P>
   He said researchers using Linux have been frustrated waiting for
National Instruments to release hardware drivers that allow LabView
and the general-purpose interface bus on Linux. Moreover, the
company is reluctant to release code that enables people like
Klosowski to adapt its hardware themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been releasing some information, but not all,'' he
said. As a result, last year he bought a $400 connector from
another company.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always an ongoing challenge in a world with multiple
players,'' said Ron Wolfe, director of strategic marketing for
National Instruments.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company is releasing more drivers for Linux systems,
but it's more profitable to focus on dominant technology such as
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   GROWING TOO SLOWLY
</P>
<P>
   In a time when a high-flying tech company's stock can double or
quadruple in a matter of months, National Instruments has a small
number of shareholders who believe it is growing too slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors tell me, `You're not taking as many risks as you
could,' '' Truchard said. But ``for employees, stability is very
important. We're a safe haven when people look at the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   With annual growth rates of 20 percent or better, National
Instruments already is growing nearly twice as fast as the
test-and-measurement industry, said analyst Barr, who rates the
company a ``strong buy.'' ``They're in it for the long term,'' he
said. ``If it comes down to choosing between even 1 cent (per
share) in earnings, or investing it in R&AMP;D, you can bet they'll put
it in R&AMP;D.''
</P>
<P>
   And with its stock price up some 450 percent since its initial
public offering, there are plenty of happy shareholders _ including
many of the 300 employees who hold options and the scores of former
workers who are now retired.
</P>
<P>
   Retiree Melodie Sommersett met Truchard in 1982 when she was a
22-year-old intern. She started referring to him as Dr. T, a name
that stuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was calling him `Jim.' I felt strange calling him
`Jim,' '' Sommersett recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Now 40, Sommersett directed one of National Instruments'
engineering projects until the company went public in 1995. Her
return from the IPO enabled her to quit and start a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come back once a year for the stockholders meeting,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Dr. T's 13 million shares are worth almost $600
million. Three years ago, he asked the board to freeze his annual
salary at $195,797. He gets a bonus based on the same formula as
his lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way for the boy from Columbus, Texas, who grew up in
a house without electricity and whose mother made the family's
bread in a wood stove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was jealous of the kids who got the fancy store bread,''
Truchard said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
