<HEADLINE>
REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: NETWORKS GIRD FOR BATTLE WITH `MILLIONAIRE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, as the broadcast television networks paraded their
new offerings before their most important constituency, the
advertisers, one question loomed above all others: How much Regis
is too much Regis?
</P>
<P>
   Flush with the staggering and totally unexpected success of its
game show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (a show that was not
even scheduled at this time last year), ABC threw down the gauntlet
to its competitors by spreading ``Millionaire'' and its host, Regis
Philbin, suddenly the biggest star in television, all over its new
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Next fall, ``Millionaire'' will be seen four nights a week, to
the exclusion of most everything else on ABC. The network added
only four new shows, the fewest ever, meaning it had decided to
ride the golden goose of ``Millionaire'' to glory or disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps speaking more from hope than conviction, executives at
the competing networks were whispering a bit more loudly at their
post-announcement parties last week that ``Millionaire'' may have
peaked, that its audience was aging and that some shows, like NBC's
``Frasier,'' were starting to prove that quality programming can
beat it.
</P>
<P>
   The message from ABC's competitors, except CBS, was: the way to
beat ``Millionaire'' is to go for the young viewer. Each network
cited the eye-catching statistic about the median age of the
``Millionaire'' viewer, and how it has edged up from 42, when the
show had its summer run last August, to 51 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Shows are usually considered to be losing their appeal for
younger viewers if the median age climbs by more than one year in a
season. Audience age has always been a closely watched factor with
``Millionaire'' because game shows generally appeal mainly to older
viewers. One reason ``Millionaire'' was dismissed as no threat by
the other networks before it went on the air was for that reason.
</P>
<P>
   But ABC professes to be unconcerned, saying that ``Millionaire''
had maintained its appeal to a remarkable degree and that only the
arrival of Daylight Saving Time has really had an impact on the age
of its audience, because young people tend to stay out later.
</P>
<P>
   Stu Bloomberg, the co-chairman of ABC Entertainment, noted that
the younger audience numbers for other networks had fallen off this
spring far more than the numbers for ``Millionaire.'' ``I'm not
worried at all,'' he said, ``because the 18-to-49-year-old numbers
for this show are still incredibly strong. They may be off from the
show's initial burst, but believe me, I'll take these numbers.'' As
for the first whispered predictions of vulnerability for the show,
Bloomberg was happy to cite how often rumors of demise have been
exaggerated since first evoked by Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting showdown involving ``Millionaire''
will take place on Wednesday nights at 8 next fall. Far from
running from the ABC juggernaut, three networks aim to challenge
the show with new series at that hour. That was unexpected, but
each network has its reasons.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, for example, will introduce ``Titans,'' a steamy new soap
opera from the Aaron Spelling factory, hoping to snare the fans who
are now bereft of ``Beverly Hills 90210.'' Fox is going with
comedy, aiming to steal away younger viewers by bringing back John
Goodman as a gay family man in a show called ``Don't Ask.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS is making perhaps the boldest move by placing its highest
profile new show there, a comedy starring Bette Midler. CBS needs
to get comedy started on a night other than Monday and is convinced
it can establish a beachhead on Wednesday. A number of advertising
and television executives seemed to agree in comments during last
week's round of parties: ``The Bette Show'' was widely cited as one
of the new season's stronger contenders.
</P>
<P>
   As one senior television studio executive _ neutral in terms of
both the show and the network _ put it: ``That was the most
impressive programming play to me. Bette Midler seems like an
electric star who should work big time on television.''
</P>
<P>
   But few shows were receiving consistent support. Among the new
entries that many of the executives seemed to favor were ``Geena,''
an ABC comedy starring Geena Davis, regarded as highly compatible
with the show it is partnered with, ``Dharma and Greg''; ``Gilmore
Girls,'' the latest youth drama from WB, though this one does
feature some adults along with the usual teen-agers; ``The
Fugitive,'' a new take on the television classic, on CBS;
``Fearsum,'' a thriller on Fox from the makers of ``The Blair Witch
Project''; and ``The Street,'' a Fox soap opera about Wall Street
traders, billed as a male ``Sex and the City,'' since it comes from
the same producer.
</P>
<P>
   The network that seemed to inspire the most detractors was
clearly NBC, whose new shows failed to impress. Several of the NBC
shows are already heading back for serious revision, headed by
``The Michael Richards Show,'' which NBC is nevertheless counting
on to start off its Tuesday night schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shows are pretty horrible,'' one senior NBC executive said
in a moment of candor. ``But worst of all they seem totally
unfocused.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive noted that NBC has always been known for smart,
sophisticated, urban comedies, and said it was sorely in need of
new ones right now. But the comedies NBC introduced last week were
mostly broad in style. Several longtime NBC executives reported
that the new schedule stirred some less-than-favorable reviews from
some of the network's top management.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how good or bad the new shows may be, all of them face
the problem of making a successful debut. That is because this fall
will be the first in television history without a specific premiere
week. It will be the first television season in which no new series
will be introduced in September. Instead, the season will start
officially the first week in October. The reason: NBC will fill the
last two and half weeks of September with Olympics coverage from
Australia, and except for ABC and ``Millionaire,'' no network is
going to use new shows to compete against that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we marketed and launched new shows before the Olympics,
we'd probably have to do it all again after they were over,'' said
Sandy Grushow, chairman of Fox Entertainment. ``So it makes more
sense to keep our powder dry.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that October is not going to provide any better
chance for a clean starting week to the season. The very first week
of October will bring the baseball playoffs, which will interrupt
schedules at both Fox and NBC, and Oct. 3 will be the night of the
first presidential debate. The vice presidential debate will
probably be staged the following Sunday, and the Wednesday after
that is expected to bring a second presidential debate.
</P>
<P>
   The big networks will interrupt their schedules for all those
events. After that comes the World Series and a week later the
November sweeps period begins. There will also be an election night
to contend with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nightmare,'' Bloomberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
