<SLUG> BC-MAYAN-OPTICAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSY TIMES FOR OPTICAL SECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judging by sheer buzz, there is nothing in the technology world
hotter these days than ``next generation optical networking.'' And
the temperature may increase today, when Mayan Networks, a start-up
company based in Sunnyvale, Calif., plans to announce the
availability of its first product.
</P>
<P>
   ONI Systems, previously known as Optical Networks, another small
optical communications company, intends to make an initial public
offering of its stock Tuesday. If that offering is successful, it
could throw yet more fuel on the optical sector.
</P>
<P>
   Optical networks convey millions or even billions of bits of
digital information using pulses of light, rather than bursts of
electricity. As demand has increased for these high-speed networks,
dozens of companies have emerged to provide optical communications
gear.
</P>
<P>
   Mayan is nowhere close to an initial public offering, but it has
attracted a blue-chip list of venture capital and private equity
investors, including New Enterprise Associates and Amerindo
Investment Advisors. Intel, as well as Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone of Japan, the world's biggest telecommunications carrier,
have also invested in Mayan.
</P>
<P>
   Mayan's last round of financing, in October, valued the company
at about $200 million, though if the company offers stock to the
public it will almost surely be at a much higher valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Mayan makes complex equipment that helps add flexibility to the
optical networks within cities. The traditional optical networking
format known as sonet, for synchronous optical network, transports
information in ``envelopes'' of 52 million digital bits a second.
Mayan and its competitors hope to crack those envelopes so the
underlying optical communications capacity can be used more
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Mayan's competitors are mostly private companies including
Alidian Networks, Astral Point Communications, Chromatis Networks,
Cyras Systems and Sirocco Systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
