<HEADER>
A1587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TERROR-0522-COX     05-21 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-0522-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BIO-TERROR' ATTACK BECOMES FULL-SCALE 'CRISIS'
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The mock ``bioterrorism attack'' on Denver reached a
full-scale crisis Sunday with 1,314 confirmed cases of deadly
pneumonic plague and 255 ``deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Area airports, bus stations and train depots were closed and the
governor ordered residents of the city to remain in their homes _
all in the fictional context of the congressionally-ordered
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``TOPOFF,'' the exercise is the largest-ever test of the
nation's ability to respond to a terrorist attack with biological
and chemical weapons. A similar drill was taking place in
Portsmouth, N. H.
</P>
<P>
   Although officials running the exercise took pains to constantly
say it was simply a drill, several frightened Denver residents
called the public health department here to ask about the terrorism
epidemic they heard was underway.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which the Justice Department-scripted exercise placed
in overall charge of the ``crisis,'' said it had reviewed ``volumes
of information'' on a suspected terrorist, found dead in a motel
room.
</P>
<P>
   And an official of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention was calling for military support for a local hospital
system which he said was ``at the breaking point.''
</P>
<P>
   As a ``player'' in the make-believe attack, Dr. Scott
Lillibridge, chief of the CDC bioterrorism response unit, arrived
in Denver with 30 other disease investigators from the Atlanta
center Sunday morning, around 36 hours after the first ``cases''
began showing up in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been far later than the CDC would have been
involved had the attack been real, Dr. Lillibridge said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The drill, designed by a contractor selected by the Justice
Department's Office of Justice Programs in Washington, actually
began Friday night when ``10 people with pneumonia'' showed up at
several different Denver hospitals, said Dr. Richard Hoffman, the
Colorado state health officer.
</P>
<P>
   The drill caught no one by surprise. However, constantly watched
by ``controllers,' who served as sort of drill referees, players
such as Drs. Hoffman and Lillibridge, FBI special agent in charge
Mark Mershon and scores of Denver area police and firemen, were
required to respond to the fictional conditions as they unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   At times, their responses were dictated to them.
</P>
<P>
   For example Hoffman said he would have contacted CDC immediately
when he learned of the 10 unexplained pneumonia cases in the
hospital. However, the drill script required him to wait until
Saturday, over 12 hours later, by which time ``we had a cascade of
cases coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Attorney General Janet Reno and Health, Health and Human
Services Secretary Donna Shalala and White House National Security
Advisor Sandy Berger were players in Washington, taking innumerable
conference calls and approving or disapproving different actions.
</P>
<P>
   One set of players was made up of actors posing as reporters for
``VNN,'' the Virtual News Network, who hounded other players with
questions.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief ``walk-through'' Sunday, controllers called a
time-out and allowed players to answer questions from real world
reporters covering the drill. This made for a surreal exercise of
its own, as players sometimes switched back and forth from talking
about the drill to acting it out.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lillibridge broke off an interview to take a telephone call,
during which he put forth his view that the military should be
called in. Some local hospital workers were ``refusing'' to report
for work and the hospitals were overloaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't take action now, we're not just talking about the
city of Denver,'' he said. ``The outer limits of this thing will be
the Colorado state line.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that the Defense Department and the Department of
Veterans Affairs should be asked to ``peel off entire hospital
staffs and bring them here'' to relieve local personnel, and that
military aircraft should be requested to evacuate victims to other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the White House playing in this?'' he asked the player on
the other end of the line. ``Look, we've got to move with this.
Lives are at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   He hung up and turned to a reporter to say that he would have
preferred earlier involvement of CDC in the exercise. Then he moved
to a conference call with Dr. James Hughes, director of the CDC
National Center for Infectious Diseases, and Dr. Jeffrey Koplan,
director of CDC, to talk about his proposal for military
assistance. FBI Agent Mershon and Denver U.S. Attorney Thomas
Strickland avoided giving direct answers about why the drill was
scripted to give the FBI the early advantage of ``good solid
intelligence information'' that a terrorist attack was about to be
launched against Denver and the chance discovery of a dead
terrorist in a ``motel room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you are lucky,'' Strickland said, then turned away
to join a conference call with Reno.
</P>
<P>
   One effect of this particular element of the drill's script was
to involve the FBI _ and the Justice Department _ in the exercise
almost at the outset and place the FBI in control. More was at
stake than which official could make the television announcements.
Analysis of the exercise when it is over could have long term
impact on how America responds to a real terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that in a real-world terrorist attack, a
suspicious body and key intelligence information would be available
before medical laboratories had had time to identify the pathogen
responsible for hospital illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, health officials have warned that a bioterrorism
disease would likely spread over large areas of the country before
anyone realized there was a terrorism link and that an ill-prepared
U.S. public health infrastructure would bear the brunt of the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   CDC has a five-year program underway to upgrade the public
health system, including sending some health officials back to
school to learn about bioterrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, FBI agents and city and fire officials from
suburban Aurora donned ``Class A'' protective suits, complete with
self-contained breathing apparatus, and removed the ``body'' from a
make-believe motel set up on the abandoned campus of Fitzsimmons
Army Medical Center here.
</P>
<P>
   An empty bachelor officers quarters had been converted to the
``Hide-Away Motel'' and a mannequin placed in a room to simulate
the body. Aurora police, who were summoned to the ``motel''
Saturday morning, found the body, amid a great deal of virtual
vomit and some blood. The room also contained equipment that might
be that of a terrorist, said Tom Jacks, a spokesman for the Federal
Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI was called and a four-block area was closed off with
yellow plastic tape. The police who initially entered the room were
``decontaminated.''
</P>
<P>
   During the ``investigation,'' the dead man's ``girlfriend''
appeared and identified him, a chemistry major at a Denver
university. She also led police to her car, where a search revealed
``circuit boards'' in the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how the condition of the corpse, which had
blood around the mouth, sores and a gangrenous toe, related to the
scores of fictitious patients who have been reporting to Denver
area hospitals in the last several days with symptoms that ``might
be pneumonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons was chosen as the location of the ``crime scene''
because its abandoned streets could be closed off without unduly
alarming members of the public, said Jacks.
</P>
<P>
   That decision had its own poignancy. The hospital was closed
under Defense Department base closings brought on by the end of the
Cold War. Now it was being used as a stage prop in an exercise
aimed at helping to prepare America for a new era of post- Cold War
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's email address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
