</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EASTMAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WIZARD OF PHOTOGRAPHY': GEORGE EASTMAN CHANGED PHOTOGRAPHY AND
SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Broadcast notes at end of review. Date, time, channel, are for New
York; please check local listings) 
 By NEIL GENZLINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's possible that people were sticking their fingers
in their ears and going ``naaah'' before 1888. But it's also
possible that this and every other gesture humans muster whenever a
camera is aimed at them can be traced to George Eastman, the man
who in that year transformed photography from an elitist art into
an everyman pastime.
</P>
<P>
   Eastman, whose story is told in ``The Wizard of Photography,''
Monday night's installment of ``The American Experience'' on PBS,
did not invent photography. He did, however, put it within reach of
plain folks when he introduced a simple camera called the Kodak,
thereby dooming thousands of shoe boxes to be filled with millions
of blurry, off-kilter or otherwise amateurish snapshots. One of the
things this interesting program does is remind us that the word
``snapshot'' is a borrowed hunting term that means ``to shoot
without aiming.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Eastman, photography was like portrait painting. Subjects
would sit prim and still while a photographer wielding a bulky
camera, glass plates and assorted chemicals caught the moment. The
moment, though, had to last some seconds to allow for exposure, and
the life captured by these early photographers was one without
spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   Eastman changed all that. Yet he might easily have spent his
life as a bank clerk, which is what he was in 1877 when he decided
to dabble in real estate. He wanted to photograph some land he was
considering buying, purchased a camera to do it with, then found he
had to pay someone to teach him how to use the camera. There
followed the exclamation that fueled so much of the industrial age:
``There must be an easier way.''
</P>
<P>
   What is striking about Eastman is that he did not say this only
once; he found an easier way, then kept searching for even easier
ones. First he replaced the wet-plate process, in which
photographers had to cart chemicals around, with a dry-plate
system, so they could just take along Eastman's precoated glass.
Then he replaced the glass plates with paper film, leading to the
Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   The Kodak, though, was relatively expensive, so he changed the
quest slightly, to ``there must be a cheaper way,'' and in 1900
gave the world the Brownie camera, a boxful of visual memories for
only $1. The name was taken from a storybook character in a
conscious effort to appeal to children, a nonlethal Joe Camel.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the going was rough; the program details various
reversals and near bankruptcies. And, like so many giants of the
age, Eastman had his oddities: an overly meticulous streak and
control-freak tendencies. If ``Wizard of Photography'' has a
shortcoming it is in not letting us hear more about and from the
people who had to work for him. His odd end, by suicide in 1932, is
given a retrained and dignified treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Eastman ultimately made a fortune, and he
transformed Rochester, N.Y., site of his company's headquarters.
What ``The Wizard of Photography'' nicely conveys is how much he
also transformed us, the way we think of and document our own
lives. Today, when the debate in many households is whether to
jettison the old-fashioned camera (i.e., the one that uses film) in
favor of a digital one, it is hard to fathom that countless
generations had no easy way of preserving a visual record of
everyday life. Those shoe boxes go back only a century or so;
before that the slate is, by comparison, an elusive blank.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAN EXPERIENCE: The Wizard of Photography
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Monday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Written, produced and directed by James A. DeVinney; Barbara
Moran, co-producer; Eric Handley, editor; Judith Light, narrator. A
Green Light Productions Inc. film for ``The American Experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Experience'' is produced by WGBH, Boston.
Margaret Drain, executive producer; Mark Samels, senior producer.
David McCullough, series host.
</P>
</TEXT>
