<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANG UP _ YOU WON'T WANT TO KEEP THESE PORK TENDERLOINS ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm not sure my doctors have ever confronted my particular
affliction.
</P>
<P>
   I think my fingers are going to have a nervous breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   For years, soothing voices on radio commercials urged us to drop
out of the commercial rat race. ``Let your fingers do the
shopping,'' we were advised.
</P>
<P>
   My fingers are about to grab somebody by the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping by telephone is akin to volunteering for interrogation
by the New York Police Department. You are asked a series of
incomprehensible and possibly incriminating questions, then ordered
to reply by punching buttons 1, 2, 3, 4 or 44.
</P>
<P>
   Did you punch the right one? You are left to wonder, while the
phone goes whir, click and then begins to play a recording of a
requiem written for dead German kings. It seems that all the
operators (or New York cops) are busy dealing with other criminals
or customers.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what area of industry and commerce is the absolute
worst at communicating with their customers? Right, it's the
companies that deal in communications.
</P>
<P>
   The phone companies don't have enough phone lines and customer
representatives, or else all of their employees are out buying
recordings of requiems for dead German kings.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't do is answer the phone. They ignore you even
before they know what you want. And if you punch the wrong button,
you might as well be trying to communicate by semaphore from McNeil
Island.
</P>
<P>
   The wrong number, in my recent instance, was No. 4 as in: ``If
you wish to discontinue our service, please punch 4.'' After that
recorded phone message, I swear I heard insane laughter in the
background. No way were they going to answer my call.
</P>
<P>
   On the first attempt I hung up after six minutes. The second
time I began to scream at a dead phone line after 12 minutes. The
third time I punched the speakerphone connection in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   I chopped five onions and three green peppers, made a large pot
of chili and put it in freezer containers. By the time my call was
finally answered, the blocks of chili were frozen solid as a Baffin
Bay growler.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I outlasted the sorry sons of Marconi. And the response of
the phone representative when I finally confirmed my intent was,
``Mister Owen, how can I talk you out of this?'' At which point my
neurotic fingers tried to strangle the phone line.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have time to play games with the phone company. I've got
clams to steam, pinto beans to soak, beef briskets to bake,
brownies to burn, pork tenders to tend. And when you have pork
tenders to tend, you can't put them on ``hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Long Distance Loins
</P>
<P>
   4 pork loins (about 1 pound each)
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half-inch hunk of fresh, peeled ginger root
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup rum
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced jalapeno pepper
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons hoisin sauce
</P>
<P>
   Into a food processor or blender dump the garlic, ginger root,
soy sauce, rum, jalapeno and hoisin sauce. Hit the button to create
a sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Plunk the loins into a large plastic bag, pour the sauce over
them, then seal and let sit, refrigerated, all day or overnight,
removing from the cooler once or twice to massage the sauce into
the meat.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, either seal the loins and sauce in a large
piece of heavy aluminum foil and bake in a 350-degree oven for 30
minutes, or barbecue on a grill, turning once, for about 25
minutes. The pork is cooked when it is pink in the middle and
browned on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Sliced, and served with rice, each loin should serve two to
three.
</P>
<P>
   Right Number Rice
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half pounds long-grain rice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   3 large onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 large bell peppers, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 10-ounce cans cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces green pimento olives, sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pineapple juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon seasoned salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon powdered sage
</P>
<P>
   In a large pot boil the rice with water to cover by 1 inch until
almost tender. Don't overcook the rice. It might take less than 10
minutes. Drain rice and fluff it with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a large skillet and saute the onions, peppers
and celery until tender. Remove from heat and add one can soup
mixed with one soup can of water. Add half the olives and all of
the almonds.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl moosh together one cup pineapple juice, the
vinegar, salt, seasoned salt and sage. Combine this muck with the
soup mixture, then pour this whole schmear in with the rice, mix
then transfer to a large oven casserole or dish. Pour the remaining
can of soup mixed with the second cup of pineapple juice over the
top. Distribute the rest of the olives over the top and cook the
rice 45 minutes in a 350-degree oven. This will serve 16.
</P>
<P>
   I'll put you on hold while I figure out how many servings you'll
get if you halve all the ingredients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
