<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VODAFONE TO CONSIDER SALE OF SOME FIXED-LINE ASSETS
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone AirTouch, the world's largest wireless telephone
operator, is considering selling the fixed-line assets it acquired
when it bought Mannesmann and speeding up the sale of Orange, the
British cellular operator, to raise $60 billion, executives close
to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is considering selling Mannesmann's stake in Arcor
of Germany and in Infostrada of Italy, the executives said.
Vodafone is hoping those assets will bring at least (PS)15 billion,
or $22 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ALTEON WEBSYSTEMS IN 2 ALLIANCES
</P>
<P>
   Alteon Websystems, a manufacturer of switches for Internet
communications, intends to announce this week that it has enlisted
two powerful allies: Lucent Technologies and Akamai Technologies.
Lucent has agreed to sell Alteon's gear under the Lucent brand, and
Akamai will sometimes encourage its customers to buy Alteon
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   OPTICAL NETWORK MARKET HEATS UP
</P>
<P>
   Judging by sheer buzz, there is nothing in the technology world
hotter these days than ``next generation optical networking.'' And
the temperature may increase today, when Mayan Networks, a start-up
company in Sunnyvale, Calif., plans to announce its first product.
In addition, ONI Systems, previously known as Optical Networks,
intends to make an initial public offering Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A DOT-COM LEGAL BILL COMES DUE
</P>
<P>
   When fast-growing Internet companies began raiding law firms in
the Bay Area for employees last year, the firms responded by
increasing associates' salary by as much as 40 percent. That set
off a chain reaction at other law firms nationwide, which followed
suit. But at the companies stealing the lawyers, stock prices
stopped rising, bringing the value of millions of stock options
into question. Turnover at many California law firms has returned
to normal, but the firms are still stuck with the bill for the
higher salaries. New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   PATH TO WEB PROFITS SPANS GLOBE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A flood of statistics suggests that to keep their businesses
growing, Internet merchants have to look outside the United States.
And yet, with investors demanding that Web merchants find a
speedier path to profitability, the merchants can hardly justify
the expenses associated with rolling out sites aimed at other
nations.
</P>
<P>
   RENTING-A-COMPUTER DEPARTMENT
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hiring a computing staff to manage a company's
accounting and sales management systems, a lot of small-business
executives are deciding to ``rent'' their main business software
from one of a growing number of Internet companies known as
application service providers, which use the Internet to offer a
range of software and technology-related services. The trend has
caused an explosion of companies specializing in the service.
</P>
<P>
   REPORT CALLS FOR COPYRIGHT UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   The law meant to protect intellectual property on the Internet
needs to be updated, the Progressive Policy Institute, a Democratic
research center, will recommend in a report to be released Monday.
The report proposes outlawing technologies like the Napster
software, which enables Internet users to trade music files with
little regard for copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   MERGER TALKS FOR A CEMENT MAKER
</P>
<P>
   Blue Circle Industries, which earlier this month fought off a
$5.7 billion bid from Lafarge of France, said it had ``early''
merger talks with Southdown, the second-largest U.S. cement maker.
</P>
</TEXT>
