<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HAVE A GRAND TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI - The Florida Marlins opted not to take batting practice
before Sunday's game. They must've known it wouldn't have mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown had one of those days.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander overwhelmed his former organization, retiring
17 straight at one point, and the Dodgers offense was simply
overpowering as Adrian Beltre and Shawn Green hit grand slams in
completing a three-game sweep of the Marlins with a 12-3 win at Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (3-1) continued his mastery in his one-time home park,
winning for the 21st time in 29 decisions. In pitching his first
complete game of the season, Brown allowed six hits, two earned
runs, struck out six and didn't walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   It also allowed the Dodgers to complete a tiresome 11-game road
trip 7-4, quite impressive since it began with three potentially
demoralizing losses to division-leading Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``That incident in Chicago might have brought that team
together,'' Marlins manager John Boles said. ``After the tough year
they had last year, they look like they're getting great chemistry
going over there. When you get great chemistry and talent, you've
got something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre provided Brown and the Dodgers with all the offense
needed. His grand slam, the second by the Dodgers in as many days,
keyed a five-run fifth inning and provided a 5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Green added his third career slam in a seven-run ninth inning
that was nothing more than window dressing for another rout. Gary
Sheffield, who hit a grand slam Saturday, followed Green's homer
with his team-leading 14th homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to not be the one guy to not contribute,'' said
Green, who was 5 for 12 with a homer and five RBI in the series.
``We don't let anything affect the way we go about our approach.
It's a real professional team.''
</P>
<P>
   The two grand slams tied a National League record, and marked
the third time in Dodgers history (1985 and 1901) it's been
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're more complete (as a team),'' Brown said. ``The
way we started off the long road trip, starting off (with three
losses) and coming back, it shows the character on this team. We
turned it around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (24-17) matched a season-high with their fifth
straight win. They haven't won six in a row since a seven-game
winning streak July 25 to Aug. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I hit it good and had a chance when I hit it,'' said
Beltre, who was 2 for 23 (.087) in his career with the bases
loaded. ``The whole lineup was hitting, and with guys always on
base, it's good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense had problems in the first inning that led to Florida
scoring an unearned run on three hits, but that was it for the
Marlins. Of course, Brown's been outstanding since returning from
the disabled list April 25 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brownie got a little frustrated in the first inning and didn't
feel like the ball was moving enough and he was berating himself,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``On offense, you make some
mistakes and don't make good pitches, we have some guys that'll
kill 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida starter Jesus Sanchez (4-3) found that out. He was wild
in his five innings, but it didn't hurt him until the fifth when
the Dodgers scored five times on two hits. Mark Grudzielanek led
off with the second of his four hits on the day, Green was hit with
a pitch and Sheffield and Eric Karros walked to tie it 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, whose two-run double lifted the Dodgers to a win Friday,
hit Sanchez's 1-1 pitch for a towering home run over the left-field
scoreboard to give the Dodgers a 5-1 lead. It was the Dodgers'
fifth grand slam of the season, and the first of Beltre's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you keep getting guys on, and we did, you're eventually
going to get to him,'' Grudzielanek said. ``It's a mater of time.
Too many baserunners, too many good hitting counts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
