<HEADLINE>
A YOUNG PRANKSTER AT HOME ON THE ROOF 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE-BIO, GORE-BIO-ABRIDGED, GORE-DAD) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Up on the roof of the Washington hotel where he grew up, the old
Fairfax, now a much tonier Westin, Vice President Al Gore was
standing at the edge. There is no railing on the roof of the
eight-story building, and Gore was trying to goad a reporter into
following him there. ``I'd catch you,'' he said, and he seemed
amazed that anyone would decline such a sporting challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had taken a reporter and photographer back to his former
home on Massachusetts Avenue, and while the return visit did not
seem particularly emotional _ no Barbara Walters moments, certainly
_ it did bring back memories of how cranky old Sen. John McClellan
of Arkansas would get, in the suite below the Gores', when Al Gore
dribbled his basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the building, Gore gestured toward a door. ``This woman
down here had great Jell-O, so I'd go down and visit with her,'' he
said, as if he were half-hoping that she might still come out and
invite him in.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores' two-bedroom apartment has been totally rebuilt, but
the view from the roof is still mostly unaltered. ``This was a key
escape route,'' he said, taking the stairs up into the open air.
And on the roof, he was reminded of some of the childish tricks he
used to spend hours there perfecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd lay on my belly on the edge'' and lower a toy duck, tied
to a thread, down slowly, trying to bop those walking into the
hotel on the head just as they went through the door, he said. He
also hurled water balloons at cars stopped at the red light below,
and ``I hate to admit this,'' he said, ``but I would scare the
birds up here, with distressing results for the windshields'' of
cars on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Coming back down the stairs, he spied a small indentation in the
wall where he used to hide ``whatever a 10-year-old didn't want
someone to find.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my stuff may still be in there,'' he said. But no, it
had been sealed off and painted over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
