<HEADER>
A1604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VERTIGO-BOOK-REVIEW-N     05-21 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERTIGO-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VERTIGO': EXPLORING A PRESENT THAT IS INVADED BY THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of Proust as the Isaac Newton of memory. Instead of the
possibly apocryphal apple triggering the Universal Law of
Gravitation, a madeleine sets off a universal law of recollection.
</P>
<P>
   Think of W.G. Sebald as memory's Einstein, and his two great
novels, ``The Emigrants'' (1996) and ``The Rings of Saturn''
(1998), as his Special Theory and General Theory, respectively. The
first tells of half a dozen Jews who for one reason or another
escaped the Holocaust; one because he lived before it. (Einsteinian
time runs backwards as well as forward.) All collapse in nightmare
or hallucination after lifetimes of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rings,'' taking the form of a monthslong ramble through the
decayed towns of East Anglia _ interwoven with the narrator's
meanderings through history, literature and his own depression _
makes a more general case. The Holocaust, lethally radiating in
every temporal direction, contaminates in its foreshadowings and
rememberings all human chronicles, not just those of the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Proust, in the seclusion of his famous cork-lined room,
recreated a past free from the interference of the present: a
separate world, mesmeric, endlessly suggestive and utterly
controlled. Sebald, a German writer, has no cork. And his novels,
so very different, give rise to an equivalent sense (I will not say
equal, since weights and measures are for another generation) that
the ground of consciousness has shifted beneath us.
</P>
<P>
   The present that he explores is invaded, governed, sullied and
eroded by the past. In a modern Europe Sebald has created a common
market or free trade zone between memory and the senses, between
then and now, between what we think or do and what the past has
thought and done. There are no boundary markers or customs posts.
</P>
<P>
   Time is not what we employ to measure the distance we have come
or plan to go. It is a mechanism set off in the past and advancing
balefully upon us. It will not simply limit our future _ the
classical notion _ it undoes our present. We resort to futile
devices against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vertigo,'' for example, describes a watchmaker's shop ``in
which a host of long-case clocks, wall-mounted regulators, kitchen
and living room clocks, alarm clocks, pocket and wristwatches were
all ticking at once, just as if one clock on its own could not
destroy enough time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vertigo'' is Sebald's first novel, now rendered into English
by his regular translator, Michael Hulse, whose fine transparency
is the sheerest of silk gloves on the writer's hand. It has some of
the instant bewitchment _ we enter Sebald's discourse like Alice
going down the rabbit hole _ of the other books. Here the
incantations of his style are used for a slighter purpose, as if he
were honing his instruments. The exception may be the last of the
book's four sections; a memoir, beguiling and troubling, of the
Bavarian village where the narrator was raised.
</P>
<P>
   In all of Sebald's writing the narrator's identification with
the author flickers; each leaves the other free. In any case,
identity for Sebald is geological more than personal: the stratum
deposits of history, reading, the imagination and dreams. ``Dream
Is a Life'' would be Sebald's reversal of the title of Calderon de
la Barca's celebrated play.
</P>
<P>
   The first three sections interweave the narrator's travels in
Italy with those of Stendhal, Casanova and Kafka. N (I will call
him) disappears into his subject; at times he is living their
lives, at others it is as if they were living his. None of it makes
a narrative, really; more like a nervous picking up of detail or
incident, as a collector might proceed who is not certain what he
should be collecting. ``Only collect'' could be N's motto; but the
randomness is a statement of human existence.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs are used (as they are to more rending effect in the
other books) to document the uncertainty. The receipt for a park
fee in Verona, a railroad ticket extending the fare when N decides
to go beyond his destination, the snapshot of a boarded-up pizzeria
he once went to (and fled in panic). Life's meaning is uncertain,
but: Look here, I  &UR; have &LR;  been to the park, on the train, at the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The first sketch is delicate but tenuous; a variation on the
memoirs Stendhal wrote years after he went to Italy in Napoleon's
army. More substantial are N's travels touching on Casanova's time
in Venice, where he was imprisoned; and Kafka's visit to Lake Garda
for a hydrotherapy cure.
</P>
<P>
   N makes the stops. At Desenzano he lies down on the grass as
Kafka did; later he has a mild flirtation with the landlady of an
inn on the lake. He gets into an imbroglio with the parents of two
boys he accosts because he thinks they look like Kafka.
</P>
<P>
   He undergoes depressions and fears that seem to mirror Kafka's.
He hallucinates glimpses of Dante, the daughter of James I and mad
King Ludwig of Bavaria. We become what we know, goes the
Aristotelian formulation; and Sebald's N becomes the history and
literature he has read and the paintings he has seen.
</P>
<P>
   In this early book Sebald has not yet found a way to attach his
melancholy and his oddly moving comedy to a convincing vision of
history's fearful workings. ``Vertigo'' floats at times; meanwhile
there is the lovely specificity of the writing: the seen characters
and the unseen wildness, for instance, in the Alpine village where
N grew up. Or the Verona dog.
</P>
<P>
   As N is chasing ghosts: ``A sandy-colored dog with a black mark
like a patch over its left eye, that appeared like all stray dogs
to run at an angle to the direction it was moving in, had attached
itself to me outside the duomo and now kept a steady distance ahead
of me. If I paused to gaze down at the river, it paused as well and
looked pensively at the flowing water.''
</P>
<P>
   N has Kafka and a headful of cloudy connections. The dog has his
modest canine day, and N.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `VERTIGO'
</P>
<P>
   By W.G. Sebald. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Michael Hulse.
</P>
<P>
   263 pages. New Directions. $23.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
