<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-A     05-21 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-ART-695(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST PEACE TALKS HALTED AFTER FIREBOMB ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak recalled his peace
negotiators from Sweden on Sunday after a firebomb seriously
wounded a 2-year-old Israeli girl in a car passing through the
sleepy Palestinian-ruled city of Jericho.
</P>
<P>
   The attack prompted Israel to block entrance to the Palestinian
territories, declaring them unsafe for Israelis and tourists, and
temporarily undercut a year of normalization efforts. The incident
also undermined Palestinian attempts to restore order, although the
Palestinians did clamp down on street fighting for the first time
in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials denounced Barak for pushing away from the
peace table. Calling it an ``irresponsible decision,'' Ahmed Abdel
Rahman, general secretary of the Palestinian Authority, said it
would lead to ``further deterioration and increased tensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, because of surging violence in the West
Bank, Gaza and Lebanon, Barak also canceled a trip to consult with
President Clinton on the U.S.-mediated ``final status'' peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton's advisers said they understood, the
cancellation indicated that Israel was setting its own timetable
despite prodding from administration officials who have devoted two
terms to the Israeli-Palestinian peace effort and feel that their
remaining time is ebbing away.
</P>
<P>
   Middle East peace, however, does not work on anyone's schedule.
Certainly the last two weeks have produced an unpredictable shift
on the ground, in which the Palestinians' frustration with the slow
pace of peace erupted at the same time that officials finally got
down to serious and substantive final-status negotiations in
Stockholm, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators face a September deadline, which is tight even
without timeouts, given that other events will compete for the
Israeli leader's attention. Soon, Barak, who is also the defense
minister, will be forced to focus on the complex and delicate task
of withdrawing Israeli troops from southern Lebanon by July 7. And
analysts believe that the dynamic of the withdrawal is already
affecting Israeli-Palestinian relations.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Arab world see Israel's withdrawal as a defeat to be
celebrated, and as an object lesson that negates the value of peace
negotiations. Fighters from Hezbollah, or the Party of God, are
intensifying their combat to ensure that Israel pulls out under
fire.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, for the first time in years, they attacked an Israeli
outpost at the foot of Mount Hermon, in the Shebaa Farms area that
was Syrian territory when Israel occupied the Golan Heights. Israel
does not plan to withdraw from the Shebaa Farms even though Lebanon
recently claimed the land as Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, which will certify whether Israel's
withdrawal is complete, is unlikely to accept Lebanon's assertion.
This makes the Shebaa Farms a worrisome zone, and Hezbollah sent a
message Sunday that it would keep fighting Israel if the withdrawal
did not include the area.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in the last week, Palestinian youths cited the
Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon as proof that violence ``forces the
Israelis to surrender,'' as one teen-ager said Sunday. ``They are
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that this will be a new intifada,'' Nafez Azzam, a
leader of the Islamic Holy War group in Gaza, said, referring to
the uprising of the late 1980s. ``It should continue as far as
occupation remains. There is no excuse for resumption of talks
under such an atmosphere. This is an atmosphere of war.''
</P>
<P>
   The street violence, which involved sustained gunfire between
Israeli and Palestinian troops last Monday, provoked opposition
forces on both sides to press their leaders to suspend the peace
talks. At Sunday's Israeli Cabinet meeting, Health Minister Shlomo
Benizri of the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party said that Yasser Arafat,
the Palestinian leader, was ``either a dead horse or a deadly
one,'' and he proclaimed the peace effort to be useless.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Stockholm negotiations continued until Sunday, when
Barak halted them ``in light of the situation.'' He also deferred
the transfer of Abu Dis and two other villages abutting Jerusalem
to full Palestinian control.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office said he viewed the incident in Jericho ``with the
greatest concern'' and has demanded that the Palestinian Authority
track down and arrest those responsible. The car in which the
little girl was traveling was passing through Jericho on its way to
northern Israel, a shortcut that many Israelis prefer to the
circuitous bypass road that was constructed so they could avoid
Palestinian-ruled areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Jericho attack unnerved pro-peace Israelis, who have
hesitated to accept that the recent violence could be anything but
a short-lived spurt, because such incidents were coming to be seen
as a thing of the past. Many have touted the normalization of
tourism to and travel through Jericho in particular as an emblem of
successful ``people to people'' peace relations.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a reflection of the successful casino there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We today are not at peace with ourselves when we see what is
happening with the Palestinians,'' said Shlomo Lahat, a former
mayor of Tel Aviv and chairman of a pro-peace forum. ``We are
sensitive people, and we understand their pain _ but to attack
people and shoot at them _ that's the thanks we get? These things
cause us to reconsider whether the road we are on is the right
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, of course, see things differently.
</P>
<P>
   In the last nine days, rubber-coated or live bullets fired by
Israeli troops killed five Palestinians and wounded more than 1,000
others, the Palestinian Red Crescent Society said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian human rights groups said the Israeli troops were
using ``excessive force against unarmed Palestinians,'' although
some of the protesters, who threw stones and firebombs, were backed
by sharpshooters. The Israeli soldiers targeted chests, abdomens
and necks, and used live ammunition to disperse crowds, the human
rights advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   The violence grew out of street protests on behalf of the 1,650
Palestinian prisoners in Israel, coupled with demonstrations
marking the anniversary of what Palestinians call the ``nakba,''
the ``catastrophe'' that coupled the destruction of Palestine with
the birth of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In a familiar ritual here, some protesters marched to Israeli
guard positions on the outskirts of Palestinian areas and threw
stones and firebombs. The Israeli soldiers responded by shooting
tear gas, rubber bullets and live bullets. And the Palestinian
police were hesitant to place themselves between their own people
and the Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian Authority cannot use brutal measures on its
own people,'' said Nabil Amr, the minister of parliamentary
affairs. ``We cannot deny them the right to express themselves even
if, unfortunately, it leads to violence and more violence.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, however, the Palestinian police prevented most
demonstrations in the West Bank and Gaza from escalating into
violent clashes. In Ramallah, for instance, they set up roadblocks
on all streets leading to an Israeli-guarded junction and then,
using billy clubs, pushed hundreds of stone-throwing demonstrators
away from the fence of a nearby settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, demonstrators began throwing stones t their
own police officers, and some of the officers hid behind a wall and
threw stones back.
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinians said they thought a visit by Sandy Berger,
President Clinton's national security adviser, to Arafat on
Saturday night helped calm the situation. They met in Ramallah.
Saeb Erekat, a senior Palestinian official, said that ``the
Americans affirmed their readiness to hold a trilateral summit''
with Arafat and Barak but insisted that progress in negotiations be
made first.
</P>
<P>
   That would require negotiations to resume. And Berger, who spoke
at Tel Aviv University on Sunday morning, seemed to be urging the
parties to rise above the moment and take the long view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today and in the months ahead, we have a historic opportunity
that we must not allow to slip away _ a chance to resolve the
Israeli-Palestinian problem, the core of the Arab-Israeli
conflict,'' he said. ``The alternative to a peaceful compromise is
not the status quo. It is something very different and, I am
convinced, far worse. For the condition that produced hostility in
the past remains current to this day, as we see in the violence of
the past week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
