<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1607 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRASSAI-EXHIBIT-(1500     05-21 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRASSAI-EXHIBIT-(1500)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRASSAI RETROSPECTIVE REVEALS AN ALL-ROUND ARTIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ With the publication of his first book, ``Paris de
Nuit,'' in 1932, Brassai did more than win immediate acclaim as a
photographer. In what was already a much photographed city, he
created iconic images of nighttime Paris that redefined how it was
seen, almost as if darkness were its natural condition. In the
process he established an artistic trademark that, if exploited,
would have assured him a lifetime of fortune as well as fame.
</P>
<P>
   Brassai, however, was something of a reluctant photographer. He
never had a studio, he never worked on news events or fashion
shoots, he never did commercial portraits, he never considered
photography to be that important. He took up photography almost by
accident, but it was his love of art and literature that shaped his
vision of the world. The idea of endlessly recording Paris by night
was inconceivable to him.
</P>
<P>
   The artists, writers and intellectuals in his circle also
understood that photography was only one of his interests. ``I am
not at all surprised that you are also a good orator _ and a
painter and a sculptor and a writer too,'' Henry Miller, a friend
from prewar days in Paris, told him in a nostalgic letter sent from
California in 1948. ``I'll never forget your speech about Goethe
and Thomas Aquinas in the middle of the night. I'd love to have a
copy in German.''
</P>
<P>
   While remembered as a photographer, then, Brassai was always
reaching beyond photography. He was drawn to Miller and the poets
Jacques Prevert and Henri Michaux _ and photographed them _ because
he was fascinated by the written word. He photographed Picasso,
Matisse, Bonnard and Giacometti, not because they were famous, but
because he identified with them as artists.
</P>
<P>
   This, at least, is the persuasive thesis of the largest ever
retrospective of his work, which is being presented at the Georges
Pompidou Center in Paris through June 26 and which will later
travel to Verona, Florence, London, Tokyo and Berlin. ``Brassai,''
as it is called, naturally focuses on his photography, but it also
exhibits his drawings and sculptures, shows a short film that won
him a prize at the Cannes film festival in 1956 and recalls his
career as a journalist and writer.
</P>
<P>
   This show has a special advantage. ``Brassai: The Eye of
Paris,'' the well-received exhibition organized last year by the
Houston Museum of Fine Arts (and seen during the winter at the
National Gallery of Art in Washington), was built around American
collections of his work. But ``Brassai'' in Paris was able to tap
the archives of both the Pompidou and the photographer's widow,
Gilberte. As a result, 100 of the 450 works on display are being
shown in public for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these offer new insight into how Brassai worked. His
images of Paris night life, of couples in bars or solitary figures
on park benches, earned him the nickname ``pickpocket of reality,''
as if, like Henri Cartier-Bresson, he captured ``decisive
moments.'' But archive photographs in the show demonstrate that,
rather than snapping away surreptiously, Brassai worked slowly and
openly, taking a series of photographs before finding a composition
that pleased him.
</P>
<P>
   Some nighttime series were clearly staged, like those taken of
women in a popular brothel, Chez Suzy, of a prostitute and her
client in a hotel on the Rue Quincampoix and of young hoods hanging
out in the Italian quarter. In all of these he was intent on
creating a mise en scene to suggest a narrative. The man in
overcoat and trilby seen entering Chez Suzy was not ``caught in the
act''; he was evidently a friend who walked up the steps several
times until Brassai was satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Brassai's nude photographs, famous in their own right, become
even more interesting when seen beside his drawings and stone
sculptures of naked women. As a student sketching models in Berlin,
he portrayed women with narrow torsos and exaggeratedly Rubensian
hips, a ``look'' that is echoed in the Cycladic shapes of his
little statues, the photographic poses that emphasize rotund rears
and other nude drawings done 20 years later.
</P>
<P>
   His artist's eye was not accidental. Born as Gyula Halasz in the
then Hungarian (now Romanian) town of Brasso in 1899, he attended
high school in Budapest and served in the Austro-Hungarian Army in
World War I before entering the Academy of Fine Arts in Budapest in
1918. Two years later he continued his studies at the Academy of
Fine Arts at Charlottenburg in Berlin where, just as significantly,
he discovered Goethe. Yet if his purpose was to become an artist,
he was also restless. In 1924 he moved to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   To make ends meet, he became a journalist, covering sports
events for a Hungarian newspaper and writing features for German
magazines. And because these features needed illustration, he began
to meet photographers, among them a fellow Hungarian, Andre
Kertesz. In 1929 Halasz bought his first camera so he, too, could
take photographs for his articles. And, given his Bohemian way of
life, it seemed natural for him to photograph Paris after dark.
``Paris de Nuit,'' with 60 atmospheric black-and-white images, was
the result. It brought him a new career and a new identity:
adapting the name of his birthplace, he became Brassai.
</P>
<P>
   The book's success led to invitations to photograph sculptures
by Picasso in his studio on the Rue La Boetie and to collaborate
with Andre Breton's Surrealist review, Minotaure. He accepted both.
The first led to a lifelong friendship with Picasso and the 1964
book of memoirs, ``Conversations with Picasso.'' (``Read this book
if you want to understand me,'' Picasso said approvingly.) The
second drew him into Breton's circle, although he always rejected
being termed a Surrealist.
</P>
<P>
   ``They considered my photographs `surrealist' because they
revealed a phantasmal and unreal Paris, plunged in darkness and
fog,'' he later wrote. ``But the surrealism of my images was
nothing more than reality rendered fantastic by the way it is seen.
I sought only to capture reality because nothing is more surreal
than that.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   One example of this surreal reality might be the wall portraits
that he called ``Graffiti.'' These were not concerned with words in
the modern sense of graffiti, but rather with the texture and
shapes of crumbling facades eroded by weather or marked by some
amateur artist's knife. Later in life, when Brassai tried his hand
at color photography, these ``Graffiti'' came even closer to
abstract paintings. But, as he liked to point out, they were still
only walls.
</P>
<P>
   After Nazi Germany occupied France in June 1940, Brassai refused
to seek permission to continue working as a photographer or
journalist. Instead, he took up drawing again. (He published a book
of his drawings in 1946, with a preface by Prevert.) He also wrote
a short book, ``Bistro-Tabac,'' about life in occupied Paris. Then,
from 1943, he again accepted Picasso's invitation to photograph his
sculptures, this time in the artist's studio on the Rue des
Grands-Augustins.
</P>
<P>
   After the war resuming a relationship with Harper's Bazaar that
began in 1937, Brassai was free to photograph anything he wished,
with Paris and its artists _ Maillol, Braque, Beckett and Ionesco
were among his new subjects _ favored by the magazine. His own
interests, though, remained eclectic. He wrote a book, ``The Story
of Maria,'' with a preface by Miller, about a humble domestic
servant. He made the film, ``As Long as There Are Animals,'' that
won the prize at Cannes. And while he never returned to Hungary, he
traveled widely.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris show, which is inspired by the 100th anniversary of
Brassai's birth (he died in 1984), is organized around key periods
in his life, with sections dedicated to ``Paris de Nuit,'' his work
for Minotaure, his drawings and sculptures, and his so-called
``Transmutations,'' engravings made on glass plate that already
carry a nude image.
</P>
<P>
   The show also evokes three significant Brassai exhibitions:
``Five French Photographers'' at the Museum of Modern Art in New
York in 1951, which featured Cartier-Bresson, Robert Doisneau,
Izius and Willy Ronis as well as Brassai; ``Language of the Wall:
Parisian Graffiti'' in 1956, also at the Modern; and ``Art Mural''
at the Galerie Recontre in Paris in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising, perhaps, this is the first Brassai
retrospective held in Paris. Yet it achieves its objective. His
photographs of Paris at night have long been part of the city's
visual language, but other Brassais _ the draftsman, sculptor,
writer, filmmaker, even the orator _ were less well known. By
presenting him as the complete artist, this show also uses his life
to make a broader point: that creators are enriched when they avoid
isolation in their own art form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
