<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN'S MOVE ON GOVERNORS WOULD BOLSTER HIS ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It turns out that the most momentous act of Vladimir
Putin's first days as Russia's elected president has not been his
choice of a Cabinet, or the internal debate over a sweeping
economic restructuring plan, or even the approval of two nuclear
arms treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it is Putin's mounting of a swift and stunning crusade
last week to gut the power and political influence of Russia's 89
governors _ and not coincidentally, perhaps, to enhance his own.
</P>
<P>
   If the campaign succeeds _ and that seemed more than possible
this week _ then Putin will have reoriented Russia's federal system
toward the Kremlin. And the governors, arguably the most powerful
and rebellious politicians outside the Kremlin walls, will have
been relegated to truly provincial status.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin says that is what Russia needs to pull itself out of
the slough that is its 9-year history as an independent nation, and
many experts agree. But it will come at the cost of making Putin,
already endowed with czarlike powers by the constitution, an even
more towering figure in Russian politics and government.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Moscow's all-powerful mayor, Yuri Luzhkov, was quick to
attack Putin's plan as arbitrary and potentially illegal. But many
political experts here say Putin is on the right course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general tendency is positive because the major obstacle to
reforms is the influence of the oligarchs and the governors, whom I
call dictators,'' said Sergei Markov, one of the country's top
political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Lilia Shevtsova, a top analyst at the Moscow office of the
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, said, ``The fact that
Putin wants to crush these authoritarian regimes is a very
promising sign.'' She calls the governors robber barons and says
reining them in should be one of the new president's top
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's proposal comes at the peak of his political power now,
while he is blessed with a comparatively prosperous economy and a
clutch of powerful alliances with the major factions in Parliament.
He took quick advantage of it all last week, in effect declaring
war on the governors in two prime-time television speeches.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he proposed to oust, permanently, all 89 governors
and the leaders of their legislatures from their guaranteed seats
in Russia's counterpart to the U.S. Senate, the Federation Council.
The move would wipe out the current membership of the 188-seat
house, replacing it with lesser regional officials.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, Putin said on Wednesday that he would seek legal
authority to personally suspend or fire any governor who flouts
federal law or defies the Russian constitution.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all: Four days earlier, a Putin decree corralled
the governors' 89 provinces into seven new administrative
districts, each overseen by a regional official who is answerable
directly to Putin, and no one else.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the semi-official Interfax news service called the
proposals ``an attack, one may even say storming'' of the
governors' political bastion. Putin is said to have sprung the plan
on top governors last week in a meeting that ran so long that the
president's next appointment _ his new prime minister, Mikhail
Kasyanov _ cooled his heels for more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The governors, still awed by Putin's popularity, have reacted
cautiously. But few Russians expect them to roll over. For taken
together, the proposals have the potential not just to end the
their long run as regional potentates, but to wreak vengeance on
the most disobedient of their lot.
</P>
<P>
   The seven new administrative districts have been billed as a
streamlining of the government, replacing the individual envoys to
all 89 provinces who served under President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   But they are more than that. Under Yeltsin, both the envoys and
many federal agencies became willing captives of the governors, who
supplied them with favors the Kremlin could not or would not
provide. Federal officials were dependent on the provinces for
everything from office space and telephones to jobs for their
families and summer camps for their children.
</P>
<P>
   That will all change under Putin.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The seven new envoys will work from regional capitals with
budgets, housing and offices supplied by the Kremlin, as well as
the power to bestow perks on federal officials in their districts.
The effect, the administration hopes, will be to bring those
officials back under the Kremlin's sway, and thus to bring more
pressure to bear on the governors to follow federal orders.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed reorganization of the Federation Council is
potentially even more far-reaching. While details of the plan were
not clear last weekend, Putin apparently intends to replace the
council members with provincial officials elected by their peers,
diluting the governors' power to control votes on the council.
</P>
<P>
   The governors, however, stand to lose far more than political
power. If they lose their parliamentary seats, they also surrender
one of its most coveted benefits: complete immunity from criminal
prosecution. And more than a few of them have cause to worry about
that.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Russia's governors have lived high for a long time. As a string
of crises and Yeltsin's desultory rule drained Moscow of money and
influence, the far-flung provinces have increasingly made their own
way, and some leaders have become corrupt, autocratic or both.
</P>
<P>
   On the Pacific coast, 5,000 miles from the Kremlin, the governor
of the Primoriye region, Yevgeny Nazdratenko, has taken over
private businesses, seized control of the press and judiciary,
pumped government budgets dry and, according to Yeltsin's Kremlin,
regularly ignored federal decrees.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country on the Black Sea, Krasnodar Province has been
identified by human rights groups as a center of authoritarianism,
anti-Semitism and ``extreme xenophobia'' under Gov. Nikolai
Kondratenko. On the nearby Caspian, Kalmikiya has threatened
secession, veered toward dictatorship and spent lavishly on a
``chess city'' under its chess-obsessed president, Kirsan
Ilyumzhinov.
</P>
<P>
   Some regions have erected trade barriers, treating each other
almost like foreign nations. Putin claims that a fifth of
provincial laws run counter to federal legislation. He need not
look far: The city of Moscow, a federal district, has paid little
attention to warnings that its regulations counter federal law.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In making his argument to clean up the system, Putin argues,
with some justification, that he won election on a platform of
bringing a dangerously undisciplined Russia to heel before it does
itself fatal damage, and that reining in such behavior is the first
step.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just correct today; it is absolutely necessary,''
he said on Wednesday. ``The looseness of power is very costly for
millions of average people. The cost of the lack of discipline in
the state is our personal security, the inviolability of property
and housing and, finally, our own well-being and the future of our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The president stresses that his proposals conform to the
constitution, that they require Parliament's approval, and that he
rejects more draconian options, like arrogating to himself the
power to appoint governors.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is making his case directly to the people, on television,
which suggests that he wants the sort of public mandate that past
leaders, including Yeltsin, rarely bothered to seek.
</P>
<P>
   His chances of getting what he wants seem good. Although the
Federation Council would seem likely to oppose much of the
Kremlin's plan, it appears that the Duma, the lower house of
Parliament, will overwhelmingly approve it. Both the Duma's
Communists and its right-wing party, the Union of Right Forces,
have announced their support.
</P>
<P>
   If the Duma gives Putin 300 of its 450 votes, a constitutional
majority, the Federation Council will be unable to derail the bills
even if it votes against them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
