<HEADER>
A1624 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     05-21 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR HAS LEARNED HIS LESSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Oscar De La Hoya is less than a month away from
one of the biggest fights of his life yet a bout that occurred last
September remains the hottest topic of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya gave away a fight he was winning by running the final
three rounds against Felix Trinidad on Sept. 18, his first and only
loss, which he says changed his approach to boxing as he prepares
to face Shane Mosley on June 17 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the Trinidad fight, De La Hoya said he played
it safe in rounds 10-12 because he believed he had built a
sufficient lead to win.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says there was more to it than that - much more.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, speaking to reporters on the porch of his training-
camp home in Big Bear, said he was dead tired after nine rounds and
lost confidence as a result.
</P>
<P>
   He feared he could be hurt or lose the fight had he engaged the
big-punching Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel I was in condition to stay in there and bang
with him,'' he said. ``In the back of my mind, I'd be thinking,
`I'm gonna get tired, I'm gonna get tired. He might catch me with a
good shot.'
</P>
<P>
   ``... I look back at it now and I realize I should've worked
harder. I should've gone to bed earlier in the training camp, I
should've run a few more miles. These are things I'll always
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if what he says is true, he (begin ital)couldn't(end
ital) run a few more miles.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, along with trainer Robert Alcazar, said the fighter
endured several bad breaks during training camp before the fight.
</P>
<P>
   A left-hand injury bothered him throughout camp, he sprained his
ankle while breaking in new boxing shoes about two weeks before the
fight and came down with flu around the same time, bad breaks that
inevitably will be construed as excuses by some.
</P>
<P>
   Alcazar said De La Hoya did virtually no training in the final
weeks of camp. He and his fighter thought about postponing the bout
but decided the injuries weren't severe enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did almost nothing the last two weeks,'' Alcazar said. ``It
was tough. Even like that, he was able to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you imagine what he could do in better shape? He could
probably fly.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya doesn't plan to do any flying against Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   Alcazar defended the strategy for the Trinidad fight: punch and
move, move, move. He said the objective in this business is to win
and avoid being hurt.
</P>
<P>
   However, the camp also learned several lessons that night.
</P>
<P>
   One, don't leave your fate in the judges' hands even when you're
deemed the house fighter. And, two, do everything in your power to
be in prime condition come fight time.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has said repeatedly that he plans to fight four times
and score four knockouts this year. In part, that decision was made
to stir interest and re-establish him as a force inside the ring.
It also is the result of the judges' scoring, which they and many
others believe was misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to give you nothing,'' Alcazar said. ``He's
going to go into the ring and win by knockout from now on. He's not
interested in decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya claims he has a new outlook on training after the
Trinidad fight.
</P>
<P>
   He says he goes to bed earlier than ever - no later than 9:30 -
and gets up early to run. He and Alcazar say he's stepped up his
mileage and speed and his legs feel stronger than ever as a result.
He also is sparring more than usual.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time in a long time, he says he's 100 percent
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father has always said that if I'm in great shape, no one
can beat me,'' De La Hoya said. ``Now, finally, I'm a believer in
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``... The loss made me realize I'm not unstoppable, I'm human.
If I'm not in shape, somebody is going to beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   All fighters say in one way or another that they're in the best
shape of their lives before big fights.
</P>
<P>
   We'll know whether De La Hoya really has adjusted his regimen
only if the fight with Mosley goes into the late rounds.
</P>
<P>
   No problem: Mosley, although a year older than De La Hoya at 28,
has never had to deal with the media crush he experienced Wednesday
because he's never been involved in a truly big fight.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of newspaper and television reporters and photographers
descended upon his Big Bear training camp to have a word with him.
</P>
<P>
   How'd he do? Handled it like a champ.
</P>
<P>
   He obliged a seemingly endless line of TV reporters there for
one-on-one interviews and then sat with a group of newspaper
reporters and cheerfully answered questions for more than a half
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is fun, what I've worked my whole career for,'' he
said. ``I wanted to be in a spot like this, where if I go out and
have an impressive performance and win, I will be considered the
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure. This is a dream to be in this spot.''
</P>
<P>
   No one who has spent time with Mosley is surprised by his
demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   The Pomona resident isn't taciturn, but he's low-key and seems
to take things in stride.
</P>
<P>
   He's the type of person who will continue to handle the pressure
of a such an event well.
</P>
<P>
   Money matters: De La Hoya will make a guaranteed $8 million but
could clear $15 million depending on pay-per-view buys for the June
17 bout, promoter Bob Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's promoter, Cedric Kushner, is being paid $5 million and
Mosley will get a portion of that. They could make as much as $7.5
million if the fight does well, Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson watch: Politicians and women's rights groups should back
off in their efforts to keep Mike Tyson out of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Few are crazy about the guy and no one condones his despicable
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tyson, scheduled to face Lou Savarese on June 24 in
Glasgow, served his prison term and deserves the right to make a
living.
</P>
<P>
   If he had plans to (begin ital)live(end ital) in Scotland, it
might be a different story. As it is, he'll fight and get out of
town, a town that will benefit financially from the event.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: The Erik Morales-Marco Antonio Barrera rematch -
at 126 pounds - is set for Jan. 20 at Staples Center, Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he would like the winner to face WBO featherweight
champ Naseem Hamed. ...
</P>
<P>
   WBA bantamweight champ Paulie Ayala, who reportedly is near a
deal to face Hamed, has the boxing skills to give the obnoxious
Briton trouble.
</P>
<P>
   However, he probably doesn't have the power to beat him. Ayala
can't punch in his own weight class and will have less power at
featherweight. ...
</P>
<P>
   The sanctioning of a scheduled bout between Kostya Tszyu and
Julio Cesar Chavez is being challenged by the Nevada State Athletic
Commission and National Association of Boxing Commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Some authorities fear for the safety of Chavez, who will be 38
on July 12. ...
</P>
<P>
   Arum said rival promoter Don King is doing all he can to
convince Felix Trinidad to fight De La Hoya at 147 pounds in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it. Trinidad is no longer comfortable at 147 and
De La Hoya won't move up in weight. ...
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya is expected to fight in Japan in February, Arum said.
...
</P>
<P>
   Eric ``Butterbean'' Esch, the 350-pound former Toughman fighter
who hasn't gone beyond four rounds in his pro career, reiterated
this weekend that he wants to fight Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   And he thinks he would win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the Tyson people remember, the Tyson who moves and
punches,'' Bean said. ``He just stands there now like a punching
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too small to stand and bang with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Is a Tyson-Bean fight realistic?
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you pay to see it? That's how realistic it is,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He has a point. Tyson-Bean probably would draw twice the number
of viewers as the Lennox Lewis-Michael Grant fight, which had about
325,000 pay-per-view buys. ...
</P>
<P>
   Tony Ayala Jr. beat Gerald Coleman on Friday to run his
post-prison record to 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's time for him to face a legitimate opponent. Could it
be Fernando Vargas?
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rosenthal's boxing column appears Mondays in the Daily
News. He can be reached at (818) 713-3618 or on the Internet at
boxwriteraol.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
