u i BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-1STLD-WR     05-21 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING AND TAIWAN'S NEW LEADER TESTING EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Corrects Monday to Sunday throughout.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ A day after Beijing hinted at new flexibility
in dealing with Taiwan and its new president, it hastened to
restate that its ``one China'' principle was an absolute
precondition of strengthening ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acceptance or rejection of the one-China principle is the
touchstone to test whether one sincerely wants to improve
cross-straits relations,'' said a commentary by the official New
China News Agency, issued in response to the inaugural speech on
Saturday by President Chen Shui-bian of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who dares insist on splitting Taiwan from China,'' the
press agency said, ``must bear responsibility for all the serious
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech on Saturday, Chen tried to reassure Beijing that
he wanted reconciliation, but he did not satisfy the Chinese
leaders' demand that he unequivocally call Taiwan a part of China.
</P>
<P>
   In an official response on Saturday that was largely repeated in
Sunday's article, Beijing accused Chen of insincerity and
evasiveness. But the statement also emphasized China's desire to
seek closer economic ties across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time since Chen's election in March, Beijing
said negotiations could start under two conditions: if both sides
``express in their own way orally'' that they adhere to the
one-China principle, as China says both did in 1992, and if Taiwan
does not call itself an equal state.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, in his second day as president, Chen offered a potential
plum if the two sides can start talking. He said he hoped to
negotiate an end to what he called Taiwan's outdated ban on direct
trade, shipping and postal links.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has long sought such direct ties, known as the ``three
links,'' not just to save the cost of sending goods and flights via
Hong Kong but as a way to draw Taiwan to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan, professing security concerns, has kept the ban as a
bargaining chip, but its own business leaders, who have invested
billions in China and send it a huge amount of exports, are
increasingly chafing at the costs.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts in China and Taiwan said the varying
statements during the last two days were predictable as the sides
continued to test each other as Chen assumed power. In particular,
Beijing is probing to see how far Chen has moved from his longtime
advocacy of formal independence for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Chen Shui-bian's speech offered something positive,
and we should catch the opportunity,'' said a Chinese specialist in
foreign policy, Shen Dingli of Fudan University in Shanghai. ``But
Beijing will continue to put pressure on him over `one China' to
keep him moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was preparing to run for president, Chen stopped calling
for formal independence, though he emphasized that Taiwan was
already sovereign in practice and intended to stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   China's statement Sunday, compared with Saturday's, included
more emphatic reminders that the one-China principle was a
non-negotiable precondition for talks.
</P>
<P>
   Chen described his goal of relaxing commercial restrictions
today as he visited the outlying Taiwan-controlled island of
Kinmen, or Quemoy, which is near the mainland and would greatly
benefit from direct commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the precondition that national security can be
assured,'' Chen said, ``we are willing to review the outdated,
rigid and inflexible three-links policy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the admission of China and Taiwan to the World Trade
Organization, which could happen as early as September, would
provide a natural forum for discussing such impediments to direct
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Kuo, a political scientist at Soochow University in
Taipei and an adviser to Taiwan's Foreign Ministry, said it was ``a
good sign'' that Beijing had mentioned reviving the 1992 political
formula and its desire to strengthen economic ties.
</P>
<P>
   Kuo warned that rapid progress was unlikely, especially before
China's leaders make crucial decisions about Taiwan at their annual
seaside retreat in August.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said that membership of China and Taiwan in the
trade organization could provide an opportunity to ``sort out
economic issues'' and end the ban on direct commerce. China and
other countries have agreed in principle that Taiwan can join the
trade group on a special, non-state basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
