<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-ELECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS VOTE FOR CLOSER LINKS TO THEIR NEIGHBORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Swiss voters broke with their tradition of isolationism
Sunday, and approved, by a two-thirds majority, a set of agreements
with the European Union that will link their nation more closely
with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The government hopes that the accords are a first step toward
joining the 15-country union. But the seven-part package, which
removes barriers to trade and commerce, bolsters the Swiss economy
without binding it any closer politically, for now, to the rest of
Europe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The package won particularly strong support in areas close to
the borders with France and Germany. Only the Italian-speaking
southern canton of Ticino, and one other of the country's 26
cantons, voted against the agreements. The vote in Ticino, which
abuts Italy, was driven by fears that provisions allowing freer
movement of people would attract cheap labor from northern Italian
areas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foes of closer ties with Europe argued that the accords would
jeopardize Switzerland's historic independence and neutrality, and
lead inevitably to full membership in the European Union _ a step
strongly opposed by a substantial segment. Nationalists and
anti-immigration forces, who criticized the union's treatment of
Austria after Joerg Haider's party entered the national government,
joined to force a nationwide popular vote on the accords. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swiss government, business and trade unions lobbied for the
accords on the ground that they are vital to Switzerland's economic
future, which is built on trade because the landlocked country has
few raw materials. Its biggest trading partner is the European
Union _ with two-thirds of what the country exports going to the
bloc, and 80 percent of imports coming from those 15 countries. The
package increases Swiss access to European markets and opens up the
country's markets in areas like agriculture, aviation, research and
transport. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest winner is likely to be the national carrier,
Swissair, which now has a green light to expand in the union's 15
countries.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government had taken steps to defuse a major voter fear _
that foreigners would take Swiss jobs and drain generous social
benefits by creating new mininum wage floors to protect workers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The accords were worked out in protracted negotiations after
1992, when the country unexpectedly rejected, by a narrow margin, a
plan to join the European Economic Area, which would have tied it
closer to the union than the accords approved Sunday. To overcome
that defeat, the government engaged in years of complicated
negotiations to come up with the package approved Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The head of the ultra-nationalist Swiss People's Party, Ueli
Maurer, said: ``The subject of joining the EU is finally off the
table. EU membership is not an issue at least for the foreseeable
future.'' But spokesmen for other Swiss political parties hailed
the vote as a signal for the government to reignite its campaign to
join the union. National sentiment, though, is so uncertain that
government ministers said they would not apply for membership
before 2004, and that Swiss entry was unlikely before the end of
the decade, if then.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The treaty package has been ratified by the Swiss and European
parliaments, and faces clearance in the parliaments of the union's
15 member states before it can take effect in January 2001, as
planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000521.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1631 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-RAMPAL-2TAKES-NY     05-21 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RAMPAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEAN PIERRE RAMPAL, 78, VIRTUOSO FLUTIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jean-Pierre Rampal, the French-born flutist who was the first
virtuoso on his instrument to enjoy enormous success and celebrity
as a touring soloist and who almost single-handedly took the flute
to new levels of popularity in the decades after World War II, died
Saturday at his home in Paris. He was 78 and had been ill with a
heart condition for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Other important flutists had managed to lift themselves from the
ranks of orchestral and chamber players and achieve success as
soloists, starting with the flutist and composer Johann Joachim
Quantz in the 18th century. Two master French flutists earlier in
the 20th century, Georges Barrere and Marcel Moyse, were also known
for solo work, especially Moyse, who ``opened the door for us,''
Rampal used to say.
</P>
<P>
   But Rampal was the first flutist to attain the kind of
visibility and presence that previously had gone only to virtuoso
pianists and violinists. Rampal regularly filled the world's
largest concert halls, even at times the Hollywood Bowl, for his
recitals and chamber music performances, and in his prime he gave
more than 100 concerts a year.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most-recorded and best-selling classical
instrumentalists in history, he was a proud trailblazer in the
crossover genre. His CBS Masterworks recording of Claude Bolling's
Suite for Flute and Jazz Piano, released in 1975, made the
Billboard chart of top-selling albums for 10 consecutive years,
only the second time the 10-year milestone had been reached, the
first being Pink Floyd's ``Dark Side of the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Rampal's popularity was grounded in qualities that won him
consistent praise from critics and musicians in the first decades
of his career: solid musicianship, technical command, uncanny
breath control, and a distinctive tone that eschewed Romantic
richness and warm vibrato in favor of clarity, radiance, focus and
a wide palette of colorings. Younger flutists assiduously studied
and tried to copy his approaches to tonguing, fingering, embouchure
(the position of the lips on the mouthpiece) and breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing Rampal's performance in Mozart's Concerto for Flute
and Harp with the New York Philharmonic in 1976, the New York Times
critic Harold C. Schonberg wrote: ``Mr. Rampal, with his effortless
long line, his sweet and pure tone and his sensitive musicianship,
is of course one of the great flutists in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in his career, Rampal was often faulted by critics for
resting on his laurels and cutting musical corners, giving
performances that sometimes seemed listless, uninvolved and sloppy.
But when he emerged in the late 1940s and for years thereafter he
was an indisputably major artist.
</P>
<P>
   His entrance into concert life coincided with a revival of
interest in Baroque music, which Rampal championed. Still, much of
his popularity came from his presence and energy as a performer. At
6 feet 1 inch, with a bearlike build and erect stance, he looked
imposing when he walked on stage. But once he started to play, he
seemed the essence of French elegance, taste and poise.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1998, at a concert in Boston's Symphony Hall,
though Rampal was recuperating from knee surgery, fighting a cold
and clearly uncomfortable, his performance moved the Boston Globe
critic Richard Dyer to note that ``the level of Rampal's skill and
the charm of his personality'' had not changed.
</P>
<P>
   Though his background would seem to have preordained him for a
musical career, Rampal was late in his commitment to it. He was
born on Jan. 7, 1922, in Marseilles, France, where his father,
Joseph, was a professor of flute at the music conservatory and his
mother, Andree, badly wanted her son to become a doctor. He began
flute lessons with his father at 12, entering the conservatory but
taking a full course in letters and philosophy at the Lycee Thiers.
In 1937 the conservatory awarded him first prize in a flute
competition. Still, he enrolled at the state college in Marseilles
to study medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, in his third year of medical training, he was called up
for military service by the occupying German forces. But he evaded
the Germans by going to Paris, where he hid out and frequently
changed residencies while studying at the conservatory. Within five
months, he won first prize in a competition there and gave his
first formal performance with an orchestra, playing the Ibert Flute
Concerto with the Orchestre National de France.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1945, with the Germans out of Paris, I was getting happier
every minute,'' he later recalled in his 1989 autobiography,
``Music, My Love,'' which has been translated into four languages.
Accounting for the French penchant for early music at the time, he
further wrote: ``The beat to which the city marched was one dear to
my heart. Baroque music was the sentiment of the day. Bach, Haydn,
Handel, Vivaldi &AMP; Co., with their precise, measured music, gave the
public the security and sense of order that the war had taken away.
You knew where this music was going and what it would do.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, he was invited to join the orchestra of the Paris
Opera. He became its principal flutist in 1958 and held the
position for six years. But he simultaneously pursued his solo
career, starting in 1946 when he began a long association with the
pianist and harpsichordist Robert Veyron-Lacroix. That year he also
made his first formal recording (Mozart's Quartet in D for Flute
and Strings). In 1947, he married Francoise Bacqueyrisse, a
harpist. The security he gained from his marriage, which produced
two children, emboldened him to undertake concert tours as a solo
flutist, at the time an untried idea.
</P>
<P>
   The risk paid off. In 1948, he formed the Ensemble Baroque de
Paris, which enjoyed considerable success. By the 1950s he was
touring Europe as a recitalist. In 1958, he and Veyron-Lacroix made
their first ambitious concert tour of the United States and Canada,
the highlight of which was a performance at Carnegie Hall of works
by Handel, Bach, Beethoven and Prokofiev, as well as a Poulenc
sonata written for him.
</P>
<P>
   Rampal played a large number of contemporary works, including
premieres by Bernstein, Copland, Ezra Laderman, David Diamond and
Krzysztof Penderecki. Though he performed some boldly contemporary
works, including a sonata by Pierre Boulez that was dedicated to
him, Rampal's taste in new music tended toward the conservative.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, he made his conducting debut with the Mostly Mozart
Orchestra at Lincoln Center, and received mixed reviews. Conducting
would never be a notable component of his career.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He was always best known for his performances of Baroque and
Classical works. Yet as the early-music movement grew and the
understanding of historical performance practices increased,
Rampal's work in Baroque began to seem sadly anachronistic. He
unabashedly played Baroque trio sonatas, intended for intimate
settings, in cavernous concert halls. ``It's nice to have a
crowd,'' he explained in a 1992 interview. ``We are all a little
ham, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   In later years many critics found him at times to be more than a
little ``ham.'' Reviewing a 1990 recital at Avery Fisher Hall, the
Times critic James R. Oestreich chided Rampal and the
harpsichordist John Steele Ritter, Rampal's partner since 1982, for
performing Bach's complete flute sonatas without including a
continuo instrument (typically a cello, viola da gamba or bassoon)
to support the bass line of the harpsichord part, which was
standard practice in Bach's day. Rampal showed ``a kind of hubris
seemingly intrinsic in today's superstar events,'' Oestreich wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Rampal's legacy is assured. Audiences will long remember the
gleam and the disarming sound of the 14-karat gold flutes that
Rampal always favored.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Rampal is survived by a daughter,
Isabelle; a son, Jean-Jacques; five grandchildren; and six
great-grandchildren. In a sense, he is also survived by flutists
like James Galway, Carol Wincenc and other virtuosos who have
thriving solo careers in part because Rampal paved the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
