<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ASTHMA-TRACKING-NYT &LR;      05-21 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-TRACKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS MOST STATES LACK SYSTEM FOR MONITORING ASTHMA 
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP J. HILTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the number of asthma cases in the United States rises sharply
and researchers scramble to find the cause, newly released data
from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention shows that most
states have no system to track the number of people with asthma or
monitor what happens to them, and only a few states have any recent
reports on the illness in their jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   The data were reported in a study by Health Track, a new public
health group based at Georgetown University in Washington and
financed by the Pew Charitable Trusts. The study, to be made public
Monday, says that 27 states have no asthma monitoring program, 30
states have no up-to-date information on asthma within their
borders, and more than 40 states have no ``ready access'' to
information on how many people get emergency care or whether
patients have access to good treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rise in the number of asthma cases is a mystery. It
appears to be occurring in many spots around the world, and while
the number of cases had been rising slowly over many decades, the
figures have shot up dramatically since about 1980, said Dr. Lynn
Goldman, a pediatrician with the Johns Hopkins School of Hygiene
and Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The explosive growth has come recently, and it is very
unusual,'' Goldman said. ``There are not many things in medicine
that rise suddenly like that.'' The increase _ ranging from 75
percent to 160 percent in different age groups, with the biggest
jump among children _ has occurred in less than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is the most common chronic disease among children, the
most common medical reason for school absence and the most frequent
cause of trips to hospital emergency rooms, according to statistics
from the National Institutes of Health. The last statistic is
important, doctors say, because treating asthma in the emergency
room is an expensive and inefficient approach that health insurers
would like to reduce.
</P>
<P>
   Various studies have shown that certain factors _ including the
presence of cockroaches, higher levels of ozone and diesel
pollution, and increased smoking among young women _ are associated
with asthma, but it is uncertain why. Dust mites, viral infections
and breast-feeding have also been linked to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   But in looking for the cause of the epidemic, said James O'Hara,
executive director of Health Track, ``We have blindfolded
ourselves, because most states don't have access to one of the
least expensive and most effective tools for preventing the spread
of the disease: information.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said additional information was essential. ``To prevent
and treat the disease, we have to know where to look and what to
look for,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, knowing in what parts of the country and among what
groups the disease is hitting hardest can help public health
officials target prevention and treatment programs. More important
in the long run is the way information on an epidemic can be used
to spot its cause.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have estimated that a national tracking and
monitoring program for asthma would cost about $25 million
annually, O'Hara said. He said the cost of asthma to the national
economy was about $14.5 billion a year and rising.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control began to watch the rise in cases
a few years ago, and in 1998 noted that the increase had reached
epidemic proportions. The agency began to survey states, cities and
territories about their ability to monitor the epidemic, and
finished analyzing the survey results this year.
</P>
<P>
   Health Track, which specializes in environmental issues,
combined the data with reports from the National Institutes of
Health and the Council of State and Territorial Epidemiologists to
produce the current report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
