<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1650 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-PRIESTS-RECRUIT-ART-2     05-21 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIESTS-RECRUIT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ARCHBISHOP HAS AGGRESSIVELY RECRUITED FOR THE PRIESTHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.Y., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Nicholas Pavia, a city councilman and mechanic in Stamford,
Conn., the call to the priesthood was neither an urgent whisper nor
a siren. It was a tugging, always in the background, that stayed
with him as one election followed another. And it was a summons put
off by earthly misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   Until, that is, Pavia met the emissaries of Edward M. Egan, the
bishop of Bridgeport, Conn., soon to become New York's archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt empty, or anything like that,'' said Pavia, a
40-year-old who was ordained Saturday in Bridgeport. ``But I felt I
could be doing something more.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when other dioceses throughout the nation are
struggling through a shortage of priests, Egan has vigorously
recruited men like Pavia for the priesthood, ordaining a higher
proportion of priests than any other diocese in the Northeast. The
bishop's success weighed heavily in his nomination to head the New
York archdiocese, said one church official involved in the highly
secretive process, a sign that the Vatican considers the shortage
one of the most serious problems facing the church.
</P>
<P>
   In his first news conference after he was named
archbishop-designate this month, Egan boasted that his calling card
gave not only his own phone number, but that of his diocese's
recruitment director. The bishop's accomplishment, it seems, lies
in creating the structures that have allowed others to nurture
aspiring priests.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bridgeport's diocese is only one-sixth the size of New
York's, Egan opened a minor seminary soon after arriving there in
1988, modeled on one that Cardinal John O'Connor established in the
Bronx, to embrace men considering the priesthood and to allow them
a year to glimpse the life they would take on.
</P>
<P>
   But the bishop also created a full-time recruitment team, headed
by the Rev. Christopher Walsh, whose stated purpose was to
aggressively recruit candidates for the priesthood. They keep track
of men who express an interest in becoming priests, following those
who enter the seminary the bishop created, St. John Fisher in
Stamford, at every step of their preparation. The diocese also
adapts the seminarians' training to accommodate each candidate's
interests and circumstances, and, like many other dioceses hard
pressed for new priests, it readily accepts older men into the
ranks of seminarians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord is calling, but there's a lot of static out there,''
Walsh said. ``My job is to reduce the static. To create the
environment where the call can be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   While Egan has aggressively courted men for the priesthood, he
has not done so by softening or popularizing the church's stands,
but rather by stressing the orthodox view of the clergy's role. It
remains to be seen how Egan's approach to training men for the
priesthood will influence relations between the church and the New
York archdiocese's 2.4 million Roman Catholics. Nor is it clear
whether he will seek to have a political voice in New York, or how
his decision will play out in the hurly-burly world of local
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the priests Egan has ordained say his emphasis on
restoring the traditions of the church was one of the reasons they
chose to serve in Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said that some of the seminarians seemed nostalgic for a
church steeped in rituals they had imagined, but not known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them are not into getting all excited about guitar
Masses and Masses on the beach,'' Walsh said. ``They're, to be
honest, more attracted to the tradition, to the liturgical
tradition, to some of the devotions of the church, rosaries,
novenas and eucharistic adoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, the generation that's coming up now have been
deprived of that tradition; they're the children of the baby
boomers who discarded much of that,'' Walsh added. ``I don't see it
as an ideological fixation on the past, but as a longing for the
tradition that they've missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the priority he sets on building up the priesthood,
Egan _ officially not New York's archbishop until his installation
on June 19 _ ordained this year's graduates of St. Joseph's
Seminary at St. Patrick's Cathedral Saturday. The priests
prostrated themselves on the cathedral's marble floor as the
congregation prayed over them. Egan closed his hands over theirs
while the men swore lifelong respect and obedience to the
archbishop-designate and his successors.
</P>
<P>
   But there were only five of them. Over the last year, considered
an average one, more than a score of priests have died in the New
York archdiocese. And a declining enrollment of candidates for the
priesthood at St. Joseph's suggests the number of new priests will
slide even further in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not limited to New York. With fewer and fewer
young men choosing a life of celibacy and sacrifice, many priests
across the nation must serve at more than one parish. While the
Roman Catholic population in America has grown 30 percent over the
last 35 years, to 59.2 million from 45.6 million in 1965, the
number of priests has dropped 21 percent, to 46,352 from 58,632.
</P>
<P>
   Dean R. Hoge, a professor at Catholic University and the author
of ``The Future of Catholic Leadership,'' said that a generally
rising standard of living had given young men today more career
options, making the cost of the priesthood's demands _ particularly
celibacy _ seem higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come to a crossroads in Catholic history,'' Hoge said.
``There's not enough candidates. We have a problem producing
high-quality product.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Katarina Schuth, author of the 1999 book ``Seminaries,
Theologates, and the Future of the Church Ministry,'' said strict
traditionalists were having an increasing influence in seminaries,
though they might not represent a greater share of students. Nearly
half of today's seminarians, she found, begin their studies for the
priesthood after a religious conversion. One out of four speak
English as a second language.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In such an atmosphere, even Walsh wonders why Bridgeport is
succeeding where others are struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the newer priests or those soon to be ordained chose the
Bridgeport diocese because it was their home. But others selected
Bridgeport from a number they had considered, attracted by Egan's
reputation for orthodoxy and for fostering an esprit de corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the diocese or priests in the diocese are being
hypercritical, or saying Rome is way off base, that doesn't attract
young men,'' Walsh said. ``You aren't going to get young men to
give their lives to an institution if you're criticizing that
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Bridgeport diocese, like New York's, is home to a
large number of Hispanics, none of the young men graduating from
the seminary this year are Hispanic. ``It's sort of a fluke this
year,'' said Walsh, noting that five of the 30 seminarians
considering the priesthood at St. John Fisher are Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who are joining the Bridgeport diocese are Robert
Kinnally, the 39-year-old dean of admissions and financial aid at
Stanford University, who will enter St. John Fisher this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas W. Powers, 35, the priest at St. Theresa's in
Trumbull, Conn., left a promising job at a global consulting firm
to join Egan's diocese.
</P>
<P>
   Powers calls Egan ``an impressive man, the kind of guy you want
to follow,'' and he does so with an absence of reservations that
can be striking in an age of skepticism. ``I trust him,'' Powers
said. ``He's been a spiritual father to me. He inspires me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do God's will by obeying my bishop.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining the diocese not only meant giving up a successful job
but, in a sense, erasing his ego so his sense of God could take
over, Powers said. ``We really must die to ourselves,'' he said.
``He must increase, while I must decrease.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers said he was drawn to Egan's ``orthodoxy'' and
``holiness.'' Staunchly anti-abortion, Powers sometimes prays the
rosary outside abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnally, an organist who once worked as musical director of St.
Augustine's Cathedral in Bridgeport, said Walsh's encouragement
played an important role in his decision to return to the diocese.
He also considered applying to the diocese in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an openness to guys like me who are coming at this a
little later, and the sense that what we bring to it can enrich the
priesthood,'' Kinnally said. ``Bridgeport is doing so well. The
simple way to say it is, they're doing something right.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pavia's case, the diocese tackled his misgivings head on. It
even allowed him to keep his full-time job as a mechanic in the
maintenance department of Stamford Hospital while he attended St.
John Fisher, until he was sure about committing to the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   While priests ordained in the 1960s and '70s generally do not
describe the ritual of their ordination as something they gave much
thought to beforehand, seeing it mostly as a necessary step to
becoming the spiritual shepherd of Catholics, Pavia was awed by the
moment he was to deliver his personal will to the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holy Spirit at that time is coming over you,'' Pavia said.
``Everyone, from saints in heaven to the people in the pews, are
praying for you. My life is now totally in God's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   As a newspaper boy long ago, Pavia would get so wrapped up
talking to his customers that he sometimes forgot to collect their
money. Now, he sees the essence of his new life in the Masses,
baptisms and confessions ahead. He envisions going door to door
once again, visiting nursing homes and hospitals, seeing to the
needs of his parishioners with Bible in hand. The impulse to do for
others, he said, will probably never leave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the calling and we all have it,'' he said. ``We
just respond to it in different ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
