<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANE SAWYER SCHEDULED AFTER `MILLIONAIRE'  
 NEW YORK POST PLANS A SPORTS WEEKLY  
 A POLITICAL EXCHANGE COURTESY OF GANNETT  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, Diane Sawyer received some very good news.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives announced she would be a co-host a new news
magazine program, ``Prime Time Thursday,'' starting in the fall. It
will be preceded by ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' the ratings
blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely believed that by moving Sawyer's prime-time duties
from Wednesday to Thursday nights after ``Millionaire,'' executives
have given her good leverage in the highly competitive race to win
interviews with sought-after newsmakers. If the game show can
maintain its popularity, Sawyer can guarantee potential subjects
extra-large audiences.
</P>
<P>
   But what is good for Sawyer does not necessarily make for smooth
office politics.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Walters, who won fame for her interviews with newsmakers
long before Sawyer came along, had been pushing for an installment
of ``Millionaire'' before her Friday night edition of ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, programmers scheduled a new sitcom in the time slot.
Called ``Madigan Men,'' it stars Gabriel Byrne as a divorced
architect living in New York. Walters is said to be relieved that
she will no longer have to follow the network's Friday night
programming block tailored for youngsters, which is being
dismantled for the fall. But she has expressed deep disappointment
about not following ``Millionaire,'' said executives close to the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   They added that they expected Walters to raise that
disappointment again when she renegotiates her contract in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer, it should be noted, played the good soldier last year in
agreeing to be a co-host of ``Good Morning America,'' a grueling
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Neufeld, who is executive producer for all of the ABC
news magazine programs, said: ``All this has to do with is how the
network saw the schedule working out for the best.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK POST PLANS A SPORTS WEEKLY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the age of 24-hour sports television networks, sports
talk radio stations, countless sports Web sites, the continued
dominance of Sports Illustrated and the immediate availability of
game scores on wireless devices (and so on). So do sports fans,
particularly in the New York area, need more sports coverage?
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post thinks so. Beginning June 1, it will publish a
separate weekly newspaper covering local teams.
</P>
<P>
   The editors of the tabloid think a good portion of its readers
just cannot get enough of its particular brand of sports coverage
and will be willing to spend an extra $1.50 a week for the new
publication, to be called New York Post Sports Week.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is in keeping with the strategy of Rupert Murdoch, the
chairman of The Post's parent company, the News Corp., to
capitalize on avid sports fans' passions for their favorite teams
and players. His television sports network, Fox Sports Net, for
instance, creates regional programming for fans in 19 different
markets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Chandler, The Post's publisher and editor in chief, said his
editors came up with the idea for the paper and saw it as a good
chance to extend The Post's brand. In a similar vein, earlier this
year the newspaper began a separate Web site for its gossip column,
Page Six (Pagesix.com).
</P>
<P>
   This will not be a major rollout. The initial print run will be
75,000 to 100,000, a fraction compared with the circulation of The
Post (436,544 daily; 358,545 on Sundays). The publication, which
will carry 48 to 52 pages at first, will be supported by newsstand
sales, with some advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But Chandler said the news articles would be original, not
recycled. Six new reporters will write exclusively for the weekly
newspaper, but the entire sports staff will contribute to it in
return for more money, including The Post's columnists, like Steve
Serby, Phil Mushnick and Peter Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   While The Post follows the sports news of the day, Chandler said
Sports Week would be filled with long features, investigations and
deeper statistics. It will feature color on its cover and on some
inside pages.
</P>
<P>
   Can it work?
</P>
<P>
   ``Between The Sporting News, Sports Illustrated and the
Internet, the dailies, it's kind of interesting that they think
there's an opportunity there,'' said Jared Weiss, a partner at
Steiner Sports Marketing. ``I don't see it from the surface.''
Nevertheless he said he is discussing promotions with the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler was confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's based on the assumption that our readers love our sports
coverage and no matter how much we give them in the paper, they
always seem to want more,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A POLITICAL EXCHANGE COURTESY OF GANNETT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for reporters to complain that candidates do
not hold enough debates. In New Jersey, however, where the
Democratic contenders for the U.S. Senate have been debating about
debates for months, editors from Gannett papers around the state
found an unusual way to initiate at least one additional
face-to-face encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett, which owns seven papers in New Jersey, invited Jon S.
Corzine to meet with members of its editorial boards at 1 p.m. last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to Corzine, who has been reluctant to debate his
opponent, Jim Florio, the papers also invited Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Like Corzine, Florio said he was stunned when he arrived and
found his rival in the room. Both men were even more surprised when
the editors told them that instead of the individual interviews
they had expected, the candidates were expected to engage in a
debate.
</P>
<P>
   When the impromptu encounter ended, both campaigns complained
that they had been misled.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Ingle, Gannett's Trenton bureau chief, said the papers
had decided months ago to save time by holding just two editorial
board meetings, one for the four Republicans and one for Corzine
and Florio. Ingle, who was in charge of setting up the encounters,
said that both campaigns were fully informed of the arrangements,
although he could not recall whom he spoke with at either campaign.
If Corzine was misled, it was by his own people, Ingle said.
</P>
<P>
   And was Florio misled, in precisely the same way, by his aides?
``Well, who else would it be?'' Ingle asked.
</P>
<P>
   With less than three weeks remaining until the primary, neither
campaign wanted to antagonize a newspaper chain by complaining
publicly, so their spokesmen tried to laugh off the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School of
Communications at the University of Pennsylvania, said that a
newspaper can harm its own credibility if it is not candid and
complete in its dealings with political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The protocol is that it's the newspaper's responsibility to be
absolutely clear about who will appearing at a forum and what the
format will be,'' she said. ``Otherwise, it sounds like the
candidates were blindsided.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
