<DOCNO> NYT20000521.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BROCK-PROFILE-ART-NYT     05-21 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROCK-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO RECAST THE MAKING OF PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. _ At 69, the former senator, cabinet officer and
party chairman is enjoying what would be for some the pleasures of
retirement, like a power boat on the Severn River or an afternoon
walk around the colonial era streets of Maryland's capital _ not to
mention cheering the Naval Academy's football team.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Brock is anything but retired. For several years he had
been working quietly, as chairman of Intellectual Development
Systems Inc., on a program to help school systems overcome learning
problems. For the last few weeks he has been working noisily to
rebuild the current presidential nominating system.
</P>
<P>
   Although he concedes that ``every reform I ever voted for has
come back to bite me,'' Brock is leading an effort among Republican
leaders to begin the primary season with the smallest states and
put the biggest states, like New York and California, last.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, if adopted at the Republican convention this summer
and implemented by the states, is intended to enable people in
every state to feel involved in the choice of presidential
nominees, and thereby in the system generally. This year, for
example, Republicans had high turnout in early states, through the
March 7 primary. Then, ``It was just like falling off a cliff, in
terms of participation,'' Brock said. ``Nobody came from then on.''
</P>
<P>
   By starting with small states, the system would encourage
lesser-known candidates without lots of money. ``You place your
primary emphasis on retail politics, face-to-face campaigning in
small settings, small groups where people can ask questions looking
the candidate in the eye and hear his response or her response. The
candidates can get a much, much clearer sense of what is bothering
Americans by walking their neighborhoods than they can by standing
in front of a television camera _ or reading a poll.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, who holds the party chairmanship that Brock
occupied from 1977 to 1981, put him in charge of reinventing the
primaries last summer, creating a commission of several party
elders.
</P>
<P>
   Brock represented Tennessee in the House and the Senate, and
after his time as party chairman, when he rebuilt the machine that
Ronald Reagan led to victory, he served in the Reagan
administration as trade representative and secretary of labor. In
the Senate, he cast some votes for what he thought was reform. He
supported encouraging the development of political action
committees. He voted for the 1974 Federal Election Campaign Act,
which imposed a $1,000 limit on campaign contributions, which he
said worked pretty well for the 1976, 1980 and 1984 elections,
before the blossoming of soft money.
</P>
<P>
   He does not argue that the new primary system would solve all
the problems in the system. Changes in campaign financing are
essential, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think soft money is an abomination. I think what has
happened to PACs has dismayed all of us who thought it was a reform
when we voted for them in the early 70s after Watergate. Obviously,
the $1,000 limit is a problem because it is worth less than $300
now in real terms. So that is ridiculous. And all of these are
pieces of the whole. All of these are parts of the problem, and if
you try to deal with one aspect and not the complete package, you
are not going to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   The urgency of acting soon settled on the commission, Brock
said, when ``we saw this whole thing come to a crashing halt,
effectively, on the 7th of March. People began to realize that it
is not just the financial side, it is the whole process that
requires remedy.'' He added, ``Doesn't it scare people that we have
elections in America where nobody comes? That is a terrifying
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Many leaders from big states oppose the plan because they think
the nominating contest would end before it reached them. And even
if Brock gets his proposal through the Republican National
Committee and the convention, he knows it won't be very effective
unless Democrats agree.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like the Republicans must make the first move. Their
current party rules can only be changed by the convention. The
Brock plan would ask the convention to allow the national committee
to change the rules between conventions. Then a deal could be
struck with the Democrats, who can change their rules between
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Brock speaks kindly about the Democrats who are watching to see
if he will succeed. ``The Democrats have a particular problem,'' he
said. ``Their rules are very difficult to change'' because it takes
a ``two-thirds majority. It effectively allows almost any
significant group of opponents to block reform. That's the
challenge they face. I'm very sympathetic to their problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bill Brock who came to Washington in 1963, or even the one
who beat Al Gore Sr. for the Senate in 1970, would not have been
tolerant of Democrats. But he changed in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in riding my white horse with my armor burnished, ready
to slay the dragons of the left,'' he said. ``It was amazing how
little I thought of Hubert Humphrey until I got to know him, and
then how much I loved him. We didn't have to agree on issues. You
know, viewed from afar, people don't look as good as they can look
up close. It's really hard to hate somebody that you have to live
with and work with. You begin to have an appreciation for and a
respect for the process. The system works, and you have to pay
attention to it and make sure it continues to work because the
world does change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
