<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1661 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      05-21 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: AFTER GIULIANI'S WITHDRAWAL, RETOOLED CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It had become a race about celebrity and personality: Hillary
Rodham Clinton attacking New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as harsh
and temperamentally unsuited for a place in the U.S. Senate, and
Giuliani portraying Clinton as opportunistic and untrustworthy,
unsuited to represent New Yorkers in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But as Clinton and her new opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio of Suffolk
County, set out across New York Sunday, laying out their divergent
ideologies and themes, it was clear that the new candidate lineup
had prompted the first lady, and to a lesser extent the
Republicans, to retool their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   This has become a contest that is slightly less about who the
participants are, and slightly more about what they stand for. And
it is a development that appears to be welcomed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   In the old lineup, Clinton had sought to attack Giuliani on both
his temperament and his ideology. But she kept returning to his
jagged personality, in no small part because depicting the moderate
mayor as too conservative was ``a stretch,'' as one of her advisers
conceded Sunday with a sudden candor that surfaced with Giuliani's
exit from the race.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has now flipped. Attacking the temperament of
Lazio _ with his Boy Scout grin and telegenic good looks _ seems
even more improbable than attacking Giuliani as hard-right
conservative. But Lazio stands to the right of Giuliani, which
means that Clinton may now be able to draw on the ideological
differences with Lazio that had proved so elusive with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``We no longer have the hard-edged personality to pivot off,''
one of Clinton's senior advisers said Sunday. ``Now we really are,
in a large measure, in a campaign of issues. I think that issues
and ideology are going to play more importantly going forward than
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if Giuliani at times sought to resist Clinton's attempt
to draw ideological distinctions between them, Lazio seemed Sunday
to be encouraging them, in the calculation that he would benefit
from the contrast more than Clinton. At every turn, he belittled
his new opponent as a liberal, reprising the play book that
Republicans have used in every state election in New York and
throughout the country for the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   To a certain extent, one of Lazio's advisers said, the new
candidate, who won the formal endorsement of the state Republican
chairman, William D. Powers, Sunday, will carry on with some of the
more personality-driven attacks that Giuliani offered. In an
interview on Sunday, for example, he described Clinton as an
opportunist, and he has repeatedly labeled her a carpetbagger, a
line of attack that his aides said would be central to his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While a series of polls has suggested that the issue of
Clinton's new residency has receded in the minds of many New
Yorkers, it is the kind of topic, one of Lazio's advisers said,
that could help the Republicans paint Clinton as ``not one of us,''
to use the shorthand favored by consultants. One Republican
suggested that that could prove easier for the easygoing Lazio than
for the hard-driven Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani was the opponent, there was some disagreement
among Clinton's advisers about the extent to which they should go
after the mayor's personality rather than his ideology, because the
two held such similar views. The question now, one aide said, is
determining how aggressively Clinton should move to show Lazio as
ideologically extreme.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Clinton's advisers were described as divided
Sunday night over whether they should quickly wheel out television
advertisements attacking Lazio's positions, in particular his
support for much of Newt Gingrich's ``Contract With America'' in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   To date, it has been Clinton's surrogates (Sunday, it was her
press secretary, Howard Wolfson, on ``Meet the Press'' on NBC)
rather than the candidate who has carried the attack, reflecting
the concern among Clinton's advisers that she remains too
polarizing a figure to carry out the assaults herself.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it was Clinton's aides who first attacked Lazio, a
point that Lazio made over the last two days. Still, Clinton
presented herself as something of the victim in an appearance in
Albany, the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little disappointed yesterday that my latest opponent
has already started hurling insults instead of offering ideas about
what we can do to improve the lives of New Yorkers,'' she said. ``I
am sorry that my opponent couldn't even get through his
announcement speech without going on the attack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
