<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-NASCAR-BRIDGE-COLLAPS     05-21 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-BRIDGE-COLLAPSE0522-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``It was an amazing sight; everyone disappeared. . . . For a
split second, I was thinking I was going to die, and then I
realized I was going to live.''
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell and Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C._ With dark sunglasses hiding the circles around
his eyes, H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler on Sunday once again was forced to
discuss tragedy at Lowe's Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler, the track's president and general manager, had rested
only a couple of hours since the collapse of a pedestrian bridge at
11:15 p.m. Saturday, moments after The Winston stock-car race.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that 107 people were injured when
an 80-foot section of the walkway above the south-bound lane of
U.S. 29 collapsed. As many as 13 were listed in critical condition
on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The concrete bridge, constructed in 1995 by Lowe's Motor
Speedway at the cost of $1 million, was a shortcut from the race
facility to the parking lots and campground. It consists of four
80-foot sections. Each is 16 feet wide and is enclosed by a tall
chain-link fence that arches at the top to discourage people from
throwing debris on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second tragedy in 13 months at the Charlotte track.
Three fans were killed in May, 1999, when debris from an open-wheel
car flew into the stands during a wreck. A bomb threat was called
to the track at last October's Winston Cup event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we are concerned (about the track's image) after
the three incidents that happened here,'' Wheeler said. ``This is
the worst thing you go through with one of these things when
spectators get hurt. It's very much a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not concerned about the safety of this place. We've
had excellent architects, excellent engineers and have a tremendous
maintenance crew of full-time staff who do constant inspections of
everything in the (track). I feel like it is a very safe place.''
</P>
<P>
   In a press briefing on Sunday, the assistant bridge engineer for
the North Carolina Department of Transportation said that, ``rusty
or eroding'' steel cables could have contributed to the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make any generalizations or conclusions from
this,'' said Don Idol of the N.C. DOT, ``(but) I did observe what
appeared to be corrosion on some of the (steel cables) at the
failure point. You can make your own judgement from that. Tests and
all will confirm or deny whether that was the real mechanism of
failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 40 steel cables run through the two sections of the
bridge. The cables cannot be seen from the outside and are supposed
to be sealed. According to Idol, only water and oxygen can cause
erosion of the cables. When the steel rusts, the bridge weakens.
</P>
<P>
   The section that collapsed was the highest, about 20 feet,
officials said. It cracked in the center, leaving two pieces that
gave way under the weight of shoulder-to-shoulder people leaving
the race, said state traffic engineer Rich Mason, who witnessed the
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses reported two loud pops, following by a mass of people
sliding down the broken sections. It was as though the ends of two
sliding boards were coming together in the highway, said David
Hampton, assistant director of Cabarrus County Emergency Management
Services.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked, watching his feet to avoid running into people in
front of him, Gus Lejano, of Huntersville, N.C., said, ``I saw the
concrete open up and crack open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, all of a sudden,'' Lejano said, ``when you saw all those
bodies and all those people in front of you, in an instant I could
see all the way across to the other side of the bridge because they
all fell down.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the injured who returned to the speedway Sunday to
get their cars and return to their homes had cuts and scrapes.
Their arms and legs were bandaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amazing sight; everyone disappeared. . . . There was
a mass of people, and then they were all gone,'' said Mike Aquino,
41, of Atlanta, who was treated for minor injuries. ``For a split
second, I was thinking I was going to die, and then I realized I
was going to live.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a surreal scene outside the track after The Winston for
more than three hours. U.S. 29 was crowded with ambulances, police
cars, and rescue vehicles with flashing lights. Thousands of fans
watched helicopters transport the seriously injured spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a freak thing,'' driver Sterling Marlin said.
``That doesn't make it any easier for the folks who were hurt, but
still something no one could have expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The Winston was the first of two consecutive race weekends at
Lowe's Motor Speedway. Wheeler said Wednesday night's qualifying
for Sunday's Coca-Cola 600 will proceed as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about 170,000 people who have already made their
commitments to be here,'' Wheeler said. ``A lot of them are here
now, and we're going to go on. This is not to take us away from our
concern for the people who are injured. This is not going to take
away from what we can do for those people, nor is it going to take
away from the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
