<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1666 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-A     05-21 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12,000 TO PAY TRIBUTE TO THE MASTER FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make one-time purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Wednesday night, President Clinton will headline
the most lucrative political fund-raising event ever, collecting at
least $25 million from 12,000 donors packed into the MCI Center
here.
</P>
<P>
   The record-setting gala, a salute to Clinton and Vice President
Al Gore, will draw thousands of small donors who bought $50
tickets, but also a large number of mega-givers, including 15 to 20
people who have raised or pledged at least $500,000 each. Some of
these big givers will share a private dinner with the president and
vice president the night before the gala at the BET Jazz club in
downtown Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion cements the president's legacy as the most
prodigious political fund-raiser ever. Democratic fund-raisers and
the White House estimate that Clinton is responsible for raising at
least $500 million and perhaps as much as $1 billion since 1992 for
his own campaigns and for Democratic candidates. He is also helping
Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton collect millions of dollars for
their campaigns and is also soliciting money for his presidential
library.
</P>
<P>
   The $500,000 donors to the gala represent a new level of giving
in the arena of soft money, the large, unrestricted contributions
to the political parties. Among those who have given or pledged to
raise this amount are S. Daniel Abraham, the chairman of Slim-Fast
Foods Co.; Claire Dwoskin, the wife of a northern Virginia property
developer, and Vinod Gupta, an Internet entrepreneur from Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has devoted an extraordinary amount of time to cajoling
cash from Democratic donors, speaking at 350 fund-raising events
just since January 1997, an average of one every three days. That
total includes only the events that appear on the president's
official calendar; it does not even capture countless private
sessions that have brought additional millions of dollars into
Democratic accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Clinton has also embarked on a campaign to raise $200
million for his presidential library in Little Rock, Ark., a
project that just last year was projected to cost $125 million.
Multimillion-dollar pledges to the library have been made by
wealthy Clinton friends like David Geffen, the movie mogul and
co-founder of DreamWorks SKG.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike contributors to federal candidates and parties, donors to
the library do not have to be disclosed and so far the White House
has refused requests from the news media to make public the names
of library contributors. The president has been criticized for
raising these large, undisclosed contributions for his library
while he is in office, although previous presidents have also
engaged in similar fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's success in raising money astonishes even those who
have closely watched him do it over the years. ``I don't know how
you count it,'' said Mark Weiner, a financier from Rhode Island, a
friend of Clinton's and treasurer of the Democratic Governors'
Association. ``I would think Clinton has raised $1 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, said that Clinton
had certainly raised hundreds of millions of dollars and that the
figure was probably approaching $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not even close to debatable that he has raised more money
than any other figure in American political history,'' a senior
Democratic party official said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some of Clinton's more brazen tactics, especially
inviting big donors to sleep at the White House and to fly on Air
Force One, have drawn criticism, as well as scrutiny from federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his sheer effort at cultivating wealthy donors from
Hollywood to Wall Street, what is the secret of Clinton's success?
His admirers and his critics both said that he combined the
celebrity and charisma of a polished entertainer with the power and
gravitas of the presidency, a formula that left potential donors
energized.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the givers also strongly agree with the president's
agenda and want to see Gore and other Democratic candidates
continue his policies.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been tireless in his fund-raising duties,
Clinton seldom directly asks his audiences for cash, leaving that
task to others, most notably Terry McAuliffe, who is one of the
president's closest friends. McAuliffe estimated that he had raised
at least $300 million for Clinton and Democratic causes, including
the 1997 inaugural, the White House millennium celebration, the
president's legal defense fund and the campaigns of Gore and
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the years that I've known Bill Clinton, I've never
known him to ask someone for a contribution,'' McAuliffe said. ``He
doesn't like it. He'd rather have someone else do it, like me.''
</P>
<P>
   From his first campaign for the White House in 1991-92 until
this year, Clinton has voiced support for changing the current
campaign finance law, including a ban on soft money. In October
1997, for example, Clinton appeared with congressional advocates of
campaign finance revisions to demand action on legislation to
tighten the laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tide of reform is coming in,'' he said at an appearance in
the White House. ``I will fight as hard as I can for as long as I
can'' for passage of reform legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he did not forswear the raising of soft money, which
led to the scandals and investigations of his 1996 re-election
campaign, Clinton said: ``I'm not sorry that I did what was
available under the existing system. But I have always been for
changing the system. I'm just not for unilateral disarmament.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gore has asked Gov. George W. Bush of Texas to join him in
eschewing soft money, but the offer was rebuffed and the soft money
race has continued unabated. The two political parties have raised
$160.5 million in soft money for the 2000 election, a record for
this point in an election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Clinton could have devoted his charisma and the
power of the presidency to achieving significant changes in the
political money game. Instead, they say, he used his skill to
stretch it to the breaking point while feeding public
disillusionment with politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton's presidency on campaign finance has been one of
the great squandered promises and missed opportunities of all
time,'' said Scott Harshbarger, the president of Common Cause and a
former Democratic attorney general of Massachusetts. ``He has
eliminated any sense of shame or outrage from the system of
money-raising in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's fund-raising prowess has generated envy and spawned
imitators in the Republican Party, Harshbarger said. ``The
smoothness, the ingenuity, the almost sheer gall _ people saw what
was happening, and now everyone has just copied him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to calculate with precision how much money
Clinton has raised since he announced his candidacy for president
in 1991. He collected about $30 million in relatively small
donations for his own primary campaigns in 1992 and 1996. But he
also helped the Democrats raise $123 million in soft money for the
1996 campaign and is committed to helping the party surpass that
number this year.
</P>
<P>
   He has also raised untold millions of dollars for Democratic
candidates for the House and Senate, for mayors and governors and
candidates for state legislatures. He raised $10 million for the
millennium celebration. The president's friends and supporters also
donated $8 million to two of his legal defense funds.
</P>
<P>
   He was the host of more than 100 White House coffees in 1995 and
1996, each of which had a fund-raising goal of about $400,000. And
he has tirelessly traversed the country in aid of virtually any
Democrat willing to share a stage with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went into Indiana and did an Evan Bayh dinner in 1996 and
we raised $1 million,'' said Weiner, the treasurer of the
governors' association. ``He'd show up at the Democratic Governors'
Association and we'd raise $5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Clinton says he does not relish the job of raising
money, he offers no apologies for the aggressive way that he and
McAuliffe have taken to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry and I have never been of the school that believed that
we ought to act embarrassed because we ask people in the system we
have to contribute so that we could get our message across,''
Clinton said at a tribute to McAuliffe last June.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe sees Wednesday's gala as the crowning achievement of
his and the president's fund-raising career and a fitting send-off
for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who doesn't love it?'' McAuliffe said. ``This is a perfect
ending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
