<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-HAITI-ELECTION-ART-     05-21 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-HAITI-ELECTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAITI HOLDS A LONG-DELAYED ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 16, 17, 18, 19 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ Overcoming fears of violence, Haitians
crowded into chaotic polling places Sunday to elect thousands of
legislators and local officials with the hope that their country
would finally escape its political paralysis of the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The vote had been postponed three times since its original
November date because of political fights and logistical setbacks.
Voters initially encountered confusion and long lines Sunday when
they tried to cast ballots. Polls opened late in many places as
officials scrambled to deliver ballots or voter lists. Nonetheless,
there was a widespread expectation that perhaps Haiti had a chance
to have a fully functioning democracy and recover from its
turbulent past and impoverished present.
</P>
<P>
   ``These elections are important because this is the only weapon
the people can use to struggle against all that is bad,'' said
Jean-Claude Augustin, a candidate for mayor in Petionville, a
Port-au-Prince suburb. ``This is our chance to vote for the people
who can do something for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishing that in a country where decades of dictatorship
under the Duvalier family and a succession of military juntas has
been the norm proved trying Sunday. Postponements and delays,
combined with 15 politically related killings in the past six
weeks, had created a climate of insecurity and fears that voter
turnout would be low.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the streets were calm and bustling with people early
Sunday, and turnout was initially estimated at more than 45 percent
of the four million registered voters. More than 29,000 candidates
were vying for 7,500 posts from senators and deputies to mayors and
local delegates. Final results were not expected until later in the
week. Civic leaders were buoyed by the turnout because the current
political stalemate stemmed from disputes over the validity of the
last legislative elections in 1997, when only 5 percent of the
electorate voted.
</P>
<P>
   Voters said they went to the polls because the country had no
other option if Haiti ever hoped to for the international community
to recognize it as having a legitimate government and finally have
access to $500 million in foreign aid that had gone untouched
because the government was in a political standoff. Since last
January, the country has had no constitutionally appointed prime
minister and no parliament. Its fortunes have steadily worsened
with crumbling roads, insufficient police and increased crime. Drug
trafficking has soared, making Haiti a major transshipment point
for drugs headed to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a change,'' said Venel Esteve, as he waited to vote.
``I want people to have a life where they can put their children in
school and put food on the table.``
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of emerging from the paralysis of recent years
was enough to make some voters willing to confront even the worst
memories of the past. Alexis Metalome waited to cast his vote at
the Argentine Bellegarde National School, a place that had been a
bloody memory since November 1987 when thugs linked to the military
massacred more than 30 people trying to vote in the first
post-Duvalier elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not afraid to vote today,'' said Metalome, who
recalled how he fled the school in 1987 when he saw gunmen jump out
from two cars and start shooting. ``The violent people are now more
afraid than we are. Nothing can stop the vote today.''
</P>
<P>
   But many things delayed it. Voters from the middle class suburb
of Petionville to the teeming slums of Cite Soleil complained that
they arrived at the polls at 6 a.m. only to wait for six hours or
more because electoral officials showed up without ballots or voter
lists. Tempers flared in Cite Soleil when voters could not find
where they were supposed to vote. While there were few reports of
violence, observers said a local electoral official in Cite Soleil
fled when intruders burst into a polling place, grabbed the ballots
and marked them for the candidates of Family Lavalas, the party of
former President Jean-Bertrand Aristide.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's vote was seen as a crucial test for Aristide's power
and popularity in anticipation of his run for the presidency in
November. In the months before the election, roving bands of people
claiming to be Lavalas supporters had violently forced cancellation
of a voter-education campaign. In April, those roving bands of
``chimeres'' burned down one party's headquarters while the police
did nothing to stop them. The violence ebbed in recent weeks but
created a climate of fear that sent some candidates into hiding.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers and civic leaders feared that Lavalas wanted
to derail the elections, or at least wear down the opposition's
patience and campaign funds to assure that their candidates would
win. Some people suggested that the multiple delays in scheduling
the vote were part of an attempt to combine the presidential and
legislative elections so that Lavalas candidates could ride to
victory on Aristide's coattails.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing Aristide certainly does not want is to find
himself with a parliament he could not control,'' said a diplomat
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Lavalas officials insisted that they had been ready for
elections all along. Aristide has also said that he wanted to make
sure that calm prevailed during the elections. They accused their
opponents of trying to tear them down because they cannot match
Lavalas' popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the source, the fear as well as the numerous logistical
glitches and delays took their toll on candidates who barely
campaigned after running out of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was there time enough for elections? Yes,'' said one
businessman who was active in a civic coalition that urged
candidates to resume campaigning. ``Was that time used properly?
No.''
</P>
<P>
   Confusion and fatigue were evident among those Haitians who
decided to sit it out altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not have money or a job,'' said Gerard D'Liscard, as he
fixed fishing nets on a rickety pier the day before the election.
``I'm not going. I voted before and nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said they saw the problems leading up to the elections as
the inevitable result of a country that is tottering towards
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All countries pass years and years before establishing a
certain real democracy,'' said Raoul Denis, a businessman. ``It's a
perpetual fight. Even in France, from 1789 to now they have
problems. It's difficult for us. It's nobody's fault. It's
history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
