u i BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-U.S.     05-21 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-U.S.(1300)2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DID LITTLE TO DETER BUILDUP BY ETHIOPIA AND ERITREA FOR WAR  

</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton annointed the leaders of
Ethiopia and Eritrea as princes of an African Renaissance two years
ago, he and three of his aides took a special interest in trying to
head off one of the continent's biggest and costliest wars.
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes courting of the Ethiopian Prime Minister,
Meles Zenawi, and the Eritrean president, Isaias Afewerki, ended in
bitter disappointment 10 days ago when Ethiopia rolled into Eritrea
with tanks and artillery and launched trench warfare reminiscent of
World War I.
</P>
<P>
   The latest offensive was taken after two years in which both
countries, among the poorest on earth, spent more than $1 billion
on arms. But in trying to forge a peace settlement, the
administration never sought economic or arms sanctions. Nor did it
seek to slow down more than $1 billion in World Bank loans in the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it focused on an intensive, and sometimes highly
personal diplomatic maneuver. At times, the diplomats involved
said, Clinton himself phoned the two leaders and wrote them letters
trying to coax them away from battle and into peace talks that
could have been held in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A last-second maneuver this month by a team of United Nations
ambassadors who knew the fighting was imminent because blood plasma
had just been shipped to the front also failed.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons pouring into the region _ fighter planes and
helicopters, tanks, howitzers, shoulder-to-air missiles, and
ammunition from Russia, Ukraine, Bulgaria, Romania, China and North
Korea _ were easy for Western intelligence agencies to see as they
entered Eritrea by sea and Ethiopia overland from Djibouti, by
rail.
</P>
<P>
   But the three Clinton Administration diplomats who headed the
peace effort _ Anthony Lake, a former National Security Agency
adviser to Clinton; Gayle E. Smith, the director for Africa at the
agency; and Susan E. Rice, the assistant secretary of state for
African affairs _ acknowledge that they were reluctant to chastise
the two African leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Former guerrilla leaders who once fought together, Zenawi and
Afewerki were seen as friends of the United States, men who had
promise as reformers, despite their drive to fight each other. They
led countries at the bottom of the economic ladder: it seemed
heartless to be too tough. And they were considered useful in the
administration's efforts to curb the power of the Islamic regime in
Sudan, a government that Zenawi and Afewerki opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as 10 days of fighting have dislodged hundreds of thousands
of people from their homes in Eritrea and killed unknown numbers of
front-line conscripts, the United Nations Security Council has
approved a weapons embargo at the urging of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As the Ethiopians step up their assault by bombing targets near
Eritrean Red Sea ports, the diplomats say they are still talking to
both sides. But they are also considering more severe sanctions,
like limiting the ability of the Eritreans to collect remittances
from friends and relatives in the United States and restricting
international flights of Ethiopian Airlines, a major revenue
earner.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Rice said ``different sanctions'' were
considered at different points.
</P>
<P>
   But she said, ``It was our view given the disposition and the
psychology of the two governments and the two peoples that external
pressure was more likely to drive them in the opposite direction
than the desired direction.'' It was decided to ``resort to those
pressures only in extremis.''
</P>
<P>
   Last October, as the weapons buildup became impossible to
ignore, Lake said there were suggestions to seek an arms embargo.
But Lake said he remained convinced that an arms embargo would have
thrown the two countries into war. Zenawi and Afewerki had asserted
that an arms embargo would bring about a collapse of the peace
talks, making war much more likely, Lake said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the policy say that it was much too soft. ``We should
look them in the eyes and growl,'' said Chester A. Crocker, a
former assistant secretary of state for African affairs. ``They
would blink if they thought we were going to shut them down with
the World Bank. We have the power to come down hard on the
leadership. No one laid our glove publicly on either of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the poverty _ and now the shortage of food that has struck
both countries _ the governments have spent staggering amounts of
money on weapons in the last two years, according to figures from
the Institute for International Strategic Studies in London.
Ethiopia, a country of 60 million, spent $480 million on arms in
1999; Eritrea, a nation of 3 million, spent $306 million. They
spent slightly smaller amounts in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Ethiopia's defense budget is set to rise to $533
million. Yet before the first outbreak of war in 1998, Ethiopia's
defense budget was a little more than $100 million, the Institute
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years, Ethiopia received $924.9 million from
the World Bank, more than two-thirds of it in 1998 after a first
round of fighting, according to the World Bank. Eritrea, a much
smaller country, received less.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank never threatened to stop the money, bank
officials said, although Ethiopia lost its program with the
International Monetary Fund because of excessive military spending.
</P>
<P>
   As well, the Eritrean leader, Afewerki has been able to
complement the foreign aid money by raising funds from the very
loyal Eritrean diaspora in the United States. In early March,
Afewerki addressed more than 10,000 Eritreans at the Equestrian
Center in Upper Marlboro, Md., and many of them gave generously to
his war machine.
</P>
<P>
   The three negotiators who squared off with the African leaders,
who turned out to be less princes of reform than warriors for
personal honor, were eclectic, each with a point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Lake, 61, who specialized in Africa as a university student and
wrote his doctoral dissertation on Rhodesia, carried the weight of
a professional diplomat. Smith, 44, once a freelance journalist who
was on friendly terms with the two leaders from the 1970s and 1980s
when she wrote about them from behind the lines, conveyed intimate
knowledge of the region's clans and personalities. Rice, 35, an
African-American who has the confidence of Secretary of State,
Madeleine K. Albright, carried the authority of that office.
</P>
<P>
   The current fighting represents the third and most expansive
phase of the battle between the two countries. The State
Department's best guess is that 50,000 to 60,000 people were killed
in the first two rounds in the last two years, officials said. The
death toll this time could be even higher, they said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the dispute is about territory around a
border between Eritrea and Ethiopia. Eritrea says it was reclaiming
its own land when it marched over the line in May 1998; Ethiopia
says it must have the territory back before it will agree to a
comprehensive peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   As both leaders amassed their huge arsenals and conscripted wave
upon wave of peasants, teachers, engineers and doctors, they were
summoned to negotiations in Algiers earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   There, the talks were convened under the umbrella of the
Organization for African Unity, but atmospherics were sour. The two
men walked away, determined to go to war, just as they had been at
various points all along, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When a group of United Nations ambassadors, including the
American envoy, Richard C. Holbrooke, heard that the countdown for
war was under way, they rushed from central Africa northward to see
if they could make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   But the envoys found Meles and Afewerki impervious to arguments
about how they risked the lives of tens of thousands of their
citizens and the viability of their fledgling countries.
</P>
<P>
   As the ambassadors left, war broke out, making clear that
Clinton's speechwriters, who chose to compare Meles and Afewerki to
Renaissance leaders, may have unwittingly been correct. The
Renaissance, several Africa hands noted, ended in bloody wars too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
