<HEADER>
A1675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PA-PLANE-CRASH-NYT &LR;      05-21 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PA-PLANE-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
19 DIE IN PENNSYLVANIA PLANE CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A charter plane carrying 19 people from Atlantic City, N.J., to
Wilkes-Barre, Pa., apparently developed engine trouble Sunday
morning as it approached its destination and crashed, killing
everyone aboard, federal and local officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane, a twin-engine turbo prop carrying 17 passengers
and two crew members, had made one failed approach at
Wilkes-Barre/Scranton International Airport and was trying another
approach when it crashed at 11:48 a.m., said George W. Black, a
federal National Transportation Safety Board member. The plane fell
in Bear Creek Township, a hilly, wooded area in northeast
Pennsylvania about nine miles southwest of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Fire, police and ambulance crews found the burning wreckage in
the Poconos Mountains nearly an hour later, at 12:45 p.m. ``They
found the crash site, and there were no survivors,'' said Ron Rome,
spokesman for Luzerne County 911, which coordinated emergency
services.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots of the Jetstream 31, an aircraft owned by Executive
Airlines of Farmingdale, N.Y., had reported engine trouble as the
plane made its first approach through cloudy skies and mist,
prompting airport officials to dispatch fire and ambulance crews.
The aircraft was unable to land and continued around for a second
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some indication on the air traffic control tapes that
they were encountering engine problems during the first approach
and those continued into the second attempt,'' Black told reporters
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On a portion of the tape played on ABC News, one pilot can be
heard saying ``tell him we lost both engines.'' The other pilot
replies: ``We lost both engines.''
</P>
<P>
   Wy Gowell, the assistant director of the Wilkes-Barre airport,
said that low cloud cover and rain required the pilots to try an
instrument landing. The pilots were in contact with air traffic
controllers through the first landing attempt, Gowell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was apparently going around for another approach,'' Gowell
said. ``And then he apparently experienced some difficulty, and the
tower and radar approach lost contact with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gowell said the passengers, all or most of them from the
Wilkes-Barre area, had left on Saturday for Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Maguire, 37, who lives two miles from the crash scene,
said she was gardening when she heard an aircraft motor revving
overhead. ``I realized that it wasn't a lesson, that it was a plane
in distress,'' she said. ``I looked up but I couldn't see it
because of the clouds. Then the motor quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said investigators would analyze the cockpit voice
recorder to determine what problems the pilots believed they were
encountering as they approached the airport. But he said the
Jetstream 31, like many planes its size, is not required to carry a
flight data recorder, which tracks altitude, air speed, engine
performance and other details that help investigators determine
what may have caused a malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Black said the plane, which was manufactured by British
Aerospace, does not have a history of malfunctions. According to a
Federal Aviation Administration database, the plane that crashed
was built in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Accidents, though, have happened. On Dec. 13, 1994, a Jetstream
31 operated by American Eagle crashed on approach to Raleigh-Durham
International Airport in North Carolina, killing 15 of the 20
people aboard. The cause was pilot error. In January 1991, another
Jetstream 31 operated by American Eagle crash-landed at Beckley,
W.Va., starting a cabin fire. No one was killed but 16 people were
hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
