<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YES, RANDY JOHNSON IS HUMAN  

</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Major League Baseball officials can find time when
they are not probing the baseball or brushback pitches or
intemperate speech, they need to investigate a claim that arose
Sunday at Shea Stadium in the aftermath of the Mets' battering of
Randy Johnson. Johnson, several members of the Arizona Diamondbacks
asserted, is human.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Connor, the team's pitching coach, said it. So did Damian
Miller, who was Johnson's catcher. Even Jay Bell, one of the wiser
members of the Diamondbacks, offered that view. ``Randy's human,''
Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Before his 7-6 loss, certainly, they or anyone else would have
been hard pressed to substantiate that claim. But if they are
right, their revelation may be most helpful to their opponents and
most destructive to themselves. If Randy Johnson is indeed human,
it creates the possibility of an entirely different outcome when he
pitches every fifth day.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson approached Sunday's start against the Mets as the
National League leader in victories, strikeouts, shutouts, complete
games, innings pitched, lowest opponents' batting average, overall
earned run average and earned run average at home and on the road,
at night and in daylight. His season ERA read 0.97, and that really
doesn't suggest a human species, not in today's game when the
composite league ERA is five times greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy obviously has set a very high standard for himself, one
that's very tough to meet,'' Buck Showalter, his manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   So, if the Diamondbacks were to be believed, this was the human
Randy the Mets swatted around the ballyard Sunday. ``Even Randy
Johnson can't go out every fifth day and be unhittable,'' Miller
said. ``This is the big leagues, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   It was presumably the alien form of Johnson that struck out
batters for 13 of the 20 outs he recorded. It was the mere human
who gave up eight extra-base hits for the eight hits he allowed:
five doubles and three home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Slugging percentage is computed by dividing total bases by times
at bat. In Johnson's first nine starts, teams compiled a .268
slugging percentage against him. The Mets amassed 22 total bases in
27 at-bats. Those figures produce an .815 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Location,'' Connor said, explaining the reason for Johnson's
problems. ``A lot of the balls were in the middle. He was behind in
a lot of counts.'' Was this the first time this season the
left-hander has had trouble with location? The coach said
emphatically, ``Oh, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson especially had trouble with the location of a pitch to
Mike Piazza in the third inning. The location when the ball reached
the plate was bad enough; when it landed, it was oh-so-much worse.
``It was a pitch up and over the plate,'' Miller said. ``The slider
didn't do much, just kind of hung up there about belt high right
down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   And the location when the ball reached its final resting place?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably still circling the stadium right now,'' Johnson
said. The ball landed in the third-highest of four tiers of seats,
the ones painted green near the orange pole separating fair from
foul at the end of the left-field line. The Mets, using their
computerized chart, estimated the distance at 492 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some mistakes,'' Johnson said, offering no apologies or
excuses, ``and when you make mistakes to good hitters, hang
pitches, then they hit them a long ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had cracked three doubles when their first inning was
only eight pitches old. Joe McEwing, a .190 hitter, who had
previously managed only two hits in 12 at-bats against Johnson,
produced the first double, rapped another in the fifth inning as
the climax of a 12-pitch confrontation, then heaped injury upon
insult in the seventh by smashing a home run.
</P>
<P>
   The home run, which cut the Mets' two-run deficit in half,
followed a 1-1 pitch that Johnson thought was a strike but Umpire
Tim Timmons called a ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you feel like you throw strikes, you want them to be
called,'' Johnson said, refusing to say anything more about the
call or link it to the ensuing development. Miller offered more of
an insight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when he doesn't get that pitch,'' the catcher said,
``he'll get a little bit more erratic instead of just saying, `OK,
it's a ball, I have to make a quality pitch right here.' When he
doesn't, he gets in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson struck out Derek Bell after McEwing connected, but then
Edgardo Alfonzo tied the score with another home run. ``Alfonzo's a
hitter that has a history against us,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first game of their division playoff series last October,
Alfonzo started Johnson on his way to a loss by whacking a
first-inning home run against him. After the Mets loaded the bases
against Johnson in the ninth inning of the 4-4 game, Alfonzo
crushed a grand slam against Bobby Chouinard.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo hit Sunday's home run on the second pitch Johnson threw
to him. In the first inning, he swung at the first pitch and
doubled just after Bell had done the same thing. Piazza hit his
monstrous home run on the third pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was surprising how they came out and swung the bat right
away,'' Miller said. ``I think their plan was to get him early,
before he got two strikes on them. They were swinging at a lot of
first pitches. If I was facing Randy Johnson, that's what I would
do. I'd swing early in the count.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had not discussed a plan, Piazza said, but they were
aware that some hitters had had success against Johnson by swinging
at an early pitch. If that word gets around, Johnson may become
permanently human. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
