<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GIULIANI'S CHANGE OF HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The weather was miserable. A cold rain, whipped by
strong winds, had laced the city for the better part of two days.
Some of the reporters and politicians making their way to City Hall
on Friday had been soaked.
</P>
<P>
   The media crush was so great the press conference had to be held
in the Public Hearing Room, instead of the elegant and more
intimate Blue Room, where most mayoral press conferences are held.
</P>
<P>
   The 107th mayor of New York, looking nervous and weary, walked
into the hearing room a little before 4 p.m. and announced that he
would not run against Hillary Rodham Clinton for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   And then Rudolph Giuliani proceeded for the next half-hour to
present himself as some kind of suddenly changed man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen in life for reasons that sometimes you only
figure out afterwards,'' he said. ``And there is something good
that comes out of this. A lot of good things come out of it. I
think I understand myself a lot better. I think I understand what's
important to me better.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor tried in his inexperienced way to express a sense of
warmth and compassion. He seemed to say that he would like to
establish some bridge of understanding between himself and ethnic
minority groups in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people in the city have felt a big change, a great sense
of optimism,'' he said. ``They've gotten a lot of help and they've
gotten a lot of benefits, and they feel very differently. But it
hasn't reached everyone in this city. And there are a lot of people
who haven't felt that. And I'm going to dedicate myself to trying
to figure out how we can get them to feel that, too, including
maybe changes I have to make in the way I approach it, the way I
look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is going through a period of extended agony and most
New Yorkers feel he deserves a break and our best wishes. I hope he
defeats the cancer that threatens him and finds the personal
happiness he seeks.
</P>
<P>
   But with all due respect, he comes a little late to the table of
fair play and brotherhood. Too late.
</P>
<P>
   This instantaneous conversion from the man who wielded the whip
to the tender and ultrasensitive soul concerned about the blacks
and the downtrodden, the people without health insurance and those
who have to face the dark night of grave illness alone _ well, it's
a little tough to take seriously. This sudden abstract embrace of
all things humane is conveniently timed to cast a helpful glow on
Giuliani's image of himself as he does battle with his own grave
illness.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's all about him.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks that I've talked to over the past couple of days have
tended to point out rather dryly that it took an encounter with a
potentially fatal illness for the notion of empathy, compassion and
real fairness to even dawn on Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never cared about us,'' said Lucie Greene, a black woman
who lives on the East Side of Manhattan. ``His whole thing was to
show that he could discipline us. So let him get his treatment and
get on with his life. I don't wish him any more bad luck. But don't
try to sell me any stories about he cares about me, because he
doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's career, even more than most politicians, has been
about power and control. He ruled by fear, ruthlessly, and created
a carefully calculated image of powerhouse strength and
invulnerability. Most of the city and much of the nation bought
into that image.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the cancer diagnosis and the feelings of fear,
sadness and vulnerability that inevitably accompanied it. And it
turned out that Rudolph Giuliani was just a man, after all.
</P>
<P>
   He will be helped by the many good wishes of the ordinary people
of New York, which is to say, the kindness of strangers. The city
has always been kinder than he's ever been.
</P>
<P>
   No one is holding the mayor to his impulsive promises in his
hour of need. We've heard them before. On election night, 1997, in
the victory speech televised to the city, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do a better job of serving all of you. We have to
reach out to all of you. And if we haven't, I apologize. I'm sorry,
and it is my personal commitment that we will try, endlessly and
tirelessly, to bring all of you into the kind of success and
optimism we have in this room.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Maybe he meant it when he said it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
