<HEADLINE>
KOBE LEARNS TO PLAY IT COOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Boxed into a corner, trapped on the baseline, with
somewhere between four and six arms criss-crossing in his face,
Kobe Bryant showed Saturday how much his game has evolved.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was harassed repeatedly by multiple Portland defenders,
but he handled the double- and triple-teams with the finesse of a
veteran as the Lakers defeated the Trail Blazers to take a 1-0 lead
in the Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the first time I ever faced a double-team that
aggressive on the post consistently,'' Bryant said Sunday. ``It was
fun. I enjoyed it, because it's another aspect of the game that I
want to master. And I want to learn, as far as double-teams, where
the double-teams are coming from, where your teammates should be,
that type of stuff. It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time that such defensive pressure would prompt
Bryant into forced shots and bad decisions. But he committed just
one turnover in 38 minutes, and his patience was evident in his
shooting - 4 for 9 from the field - and his six assists.
</P>
<P>
   It was the deft passing of Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal that got
the Lakers' role players clicking in the second quarter, when the
Lakers outscored the Blazers 37-16. The bench, led by Robert
Horry's 12 points, scored 20 points in the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played well,'' O'Neal said of Bryant. ``We had orders to
get everybody else involved. Me and Kobe can't do it by ourselves.
... If everybody's scoring, and Kobe and I just get our average,
we'll be a hard team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said he didn't mind the low-scoring day, but he did enjoy
the few occasions that Portland left 5-10 Damon Stoudamire to guard
him one-on-one. ``He can't guard me,'' Bryant shouted to fans
sitting courtside after Stoudamire fouled him late in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves the Blazers with difficult decisions to make
heading into Game 2 tonight: continue doubling both Bryant and
O'Neal and watch Horry and Rick Fox shoot 3-pointers, let
Stoudamire handle Bryant solo or perhaps move Scottie Pippen onto
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be kind of difficult, because their biggest
strength is having Scottie roam the field, especially with this
offense and with this system,'' Bryant said. ``They like to have
him disrupt things, so either way they're going to be giving us
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson said the Blazers' wealth of tall, athletic
players allows them to double-team two players at once, but said,
``We think we can survive that. We've handled it a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Still hacked: Portland's failed hack-a-Shaq tactics put O'Neal
at the foul line for 25 fourth-quarter attempts, but O'Neal said
he's not concerned about a Game 2 encore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even worried about other people's strategic
planning,'' he said. ``We just have to go out and play our game.
... You know, if they want to play against the odds, the odds
haven't worked all year. So I don't think they're going to work
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Portland coach Mike Dunleavy perhaps trying to psyche out
O'Neal for the series?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't mess with my mind. Impossible,'' he said. ``I think
they're just paying homage to my game. That's all. Just call me the
Big Homage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into the back-and-forth thing'' with
Dunleavy, O'Neal said. ``I'm not going to get into the
confrontations. ... I remember the old days when it was blood and
blood, sweat for sweat. That's the kind of basketball I like. All
this strategic Internet planning, playing the odds and playing the
lottery, that does not work.''
</P>
<P>
   He also took another shot at Portland center Arvydas Sabonis,
who failed to keep O'Neal (41 points) in check and went scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's a shame that a 7-foot-3 guy can't play a 7-
foot-1 guy one-on-one. That's a shame,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
