<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-COLUMN-     05-21 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TRIPLE CROWN DREAM DIES AS RIVALRY IS BORN  

</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Well, he is no Secretariat. And, at least for the
moment, he is not even Red Bullet.
</P>
<P>
   In something less than two minutes, Fusaichi Pegasus fell from
his pedestal on Saturday when Red Bullet outran him in the
homestretch of the 125th Preakness and, just like that, racing lost
its chance that the &QC; $4 million flying horse would continue flying
toward the Triple Crown. Racing people had joined the public in
almost conceding the crown to Fusaichi Pegasus, acclaiming him as a
superhorse, hailing him as the horse who would rescue the sport
from its steep decline.
</P>
<P>
   But if this is the end of the dream, it is likely the start of a
new rivalry that may achieve the same goals. Fusaichi Pegasus and
Red Bullet, first and second in the Wood Memorial in April, second
and first in the Preakness in May. Both were destined for New York,
where the Belmont Stakes will be run on June 10, and will most
likely meet again, perhaps then and there.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Orseno, who trains Red Bullet for Frank Stronach of Austria
and Canada, put his horse on a van for New York Sunday and said,
``They will be facing each other again.'' And Neil Drysdale, who
trains Fusaichi Pegasus for Fusao Sekiguchi of Tokyo, said that his
horse would ``temporarily go to New York on Monday morning, and he
seems suited to the Belmont because he's a big, long-striding
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing can mourn its beaten favorite after the Preakness, but
two horses may still turn out to be better than one. Affirmed and
Alydar. Easy Goer and Sunday Silence. You play the hand that is
dealt, and right now fate has dealt two aces with dramatic
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Racing has waited 22 years for a horse who could withstand the
rigors of winning the Kentucky Derby, the Preakness and the Belmont
in five weeks' time. In each of the last three years, it looked
imminent. But Silver Charm, Real Quiet and Charismatic all were
thwarted in the final yards of a race that took them a mile and a
half. And since Pegasus captured the Derby with classical power and
a kind of majesty, racing sensed that the superhorse had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he has. But as Stronach put it, ``Horses are not
machines.''
</P>
<P>
   How did it happen? You can find four elements to the equation,
starting with the fact that Fusaichi Pegasus ran in the Kentucky
Derby two weeks ago and Red Bullet did not.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when they did meet, they raced on a heavy track that
Drysdale described as greasy. Still, as Orseno said, ``We all had
to run over it.'' But that is where the fresh horse had the edge.
Red Bullet had been biding his time for five weeks since the Wood.
And even superhorses may lose a step along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the gate opened for the Preakness, the favorite was
squeezed between the horses alongside him and lost some momentum.
Drysdale does not use that as an excuse. In fact, after flying to
Hollywood Park overnight, he said by telephone this morning: ``He
pulled up well after the race and was quite bright and playing in
the test barn. He wasn't tired. He came up with a tiny cut under a
knee, which indicates he got hit by some horse. But that didn't
really mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, most of the credit has to go to Red Bullet, who got
hooked into a duel with Fusaichi Pegasus in the homestretch and
simply outran him by three and three-quarter lengths. Red Bullet
was a legitimate challenger, too, despite his four-length loss in
the Wood. Since then, he had been training sensationally at
Pimlico. And in the Preakness, he had the extra advantage of having
Jerry Bailey on his back, providing a flawless ride and making sure
that Red Bullet would not beat himself.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the cast are generally tossing in the
towel. High Yield has made 14 starts, and shows it: 15th in the
Derby, 7th in the Preakness. His trainer, D.Wayne Lukas, said he
would look through his deep stable for another Belmont horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably Commendable,'' he said. ``He's a fresh horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, eighth in the Derby and fourth in the Preakness,
was headed home to California with Snuck In and Hugh Hefner. Cash
Asmussen, the rider on Snuck In, said, ``When Red Bullet went by
us, it was like, whoosh.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal's Hope tired badly to finish 8th and last after running 16th
in the Derby. ``He hasn't done any good since we left Florida,''
said Harold Rose, his 88-year-old owner and trainer.
</P>
<P>
   But Impeachment, third in the Derby and third in the Preakness,
was booked into the Belmont. Also listed as probable candidates
were seven horses who did not run in the Preakness, namely
Aptitude, Wheelaway, Tahkoda Hills, Unshaded, Chief Seattle, Curule
and Globalize.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest ones were the horses who dueled down the stretch
in the Preakness: Red Bullet and Fusaichi Pegasus. And the best is
yet to come. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
