<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-ART-N     05-21 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS FOLLOW THE SCRIPT AND ELIMINATE THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT10,11,12,13,14,15 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The players from both teams dispersed after a tense
timeout, but a frantic Coach Jeff Van Gundy was still standing on
the court, cupping his hands and directing the Knicks until the
official Dick Bavetta raked him back toward the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   There were just 12.4 seconds on the clock, and all his team
needed was one last defensive stop to leave the Miami Heat in
pieces once again. Van Gundy wanted the choreography to be perfect.
As the next 10.3 seconds unfolded inside the queasy air of American
Airlines Arena, he watched as the ball went to Alonzo Mourning,
but, on cue, Patrick Ewing and Larry Johnson sealed him off like
gates at a railroad crossing.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't going to let Mourning end their season. Anyone but
him. So Mourning had to pass, found an open Jamal Mashburn, but too
timid to shoot, he ditched the ball to Clarence Weatherspoon. A
reserve, a misfit on a Miami Heat team filled with them, was forced
to take the Heat's last shot of the deciding Game 7 and final shot
of their season.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon's jumper in the lane arched over the wingspan of
Marcus Camby and fell horribly off the rim. As the loose ball
bounded away, Latrell Sprewell darted between two Heat players and
hugged the ball as his feet danced dangerously near the baseline
with 2.1 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   For an instant, there was confusion. Had Sprewell called a
timeout? Had he stepped out of bounds? At first, the official
Bennett Salvatore rewarded the ball to the Heat. A conference took
place, Bavetta overruled Salvatore, and the ball went back to the
Knicks as another tortured grimace registered on Heat Coach Pat
Riley's face.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, it was over. Charlie Ward inbounded the ball to
Chris Childs. Then the confident bit player, who emerged as the
Knicks' stars vanished Sunday, hoisted the ball into the rafters
before the Heat could foul him. In another addition to the lore of
this rivalry, the Knicks eliminated the Heat on Miami's home court
for the third year in a row, 83-82, and advanced to the Eastern
Conference finals to play the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   `'I don't think you're surprised by how a game goes,'' Van Gundy
said. `'It came down to a last possession and Sprewell's rebound.
We feel very proud of our accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat players didn't want to leave the floor. As cups and
plastic noisemakers pelted the court, Tim Hardaway was barking at
the officiating crew, as Mashburn was in the ear of Bavetta while
security led the referees away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they call him `Knick Bavetta,''' a wounded Hardaway
said. `'It's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't have to come down to the officials. In the end, the
Heat weren't as mentally strong as the Knicks. They couldn't come
up with an X factor like Childs, who scored the Knicks first 10
points of the fourth quarter to keep his team in the game. They
couldn't find a way to get the ball to Mourning, who scored 29
points but couldn't get off a shot in the last 5 minutes of the
game. They couldn't capitalize on their chances at the free-throw
line, where the Heat missed 5 of 7 in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks kept themselves together because Childs wouldn't let
his team fall apart. All around him, he saw his teammates
disappear. A limping Allan Houston (2 for 10) was only a decoy on
the floor. A hot Sprewell scored 20 in the first half but made just
1 of 8 shots in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   `'I just kept attacking,'' Childs said. `'I was just trying to
make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He did just that near the 9-minute mark of the fourth quarter.
With the Heat ahead, 71-68, Childs seized on the misstep Anthony
Carter made on his dribble, stripped the ball from him and then
raced down the floor and connected on a fastbreak layup that drew a
foul and created a 3-point play.
</P>
<P>
   The lead for the Heat was 6 points again when Childs penetrated
again and drew a foul with 4 minutes left. Coolly he hit both free
throws. At this point, he had scored the Knicks only 10 points of
the fourth quarter. Help would come soon. Ewing began asserting
himself. With 1:20 left in the game, Mourning darted toward Ewing
for a steal. Ewing sidestepped his Georgetown protege and went in
for a dunk that gave the Knicks a 83-82 lead. That's how it stood
with 12.4 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   `'At that point, it was all about getting the ball out of
Mourning's hands,'' Van Gundy said. `'We were willing to live with
any other shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat have to live with another devastating outcome, one that
ended on a wild last possession and controversial call.
</P>
<P>
   `'I have Sprewell calling timeout but I wasn't sure if his foot
was out,'' Salvatore said after the game. `'I didn't believe he was
out of bounds but I wanted to check with my partner. He was not out
when my whistle blew. He confirmed that there was no question that
the timeout came before he went out of bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for one thing. Sprewell said after the game that he never
called a timeout. Was it a phantom voice? Whatever it was, it will
haunt the Heat through another season filled with Knicks demons.
But a somber Riley did not use the officials as an excuse. He cited
all the missed opportunities, instead. In the end, the Heat just
could not come up with the kind of miracles that have worked so
well for the Knicks over the span of this playoff rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   `'You have to wonder what will happen to them,'' said Marcus
Camby who helped give the Knicks a, 46-43 rebounding edge with 13
boards. `'Riley might break it up. But as long as he is the coach
here, it will always be an intense rivalry. This was something,
wasn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
