<DOCNO> NYT20000521.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HEAT-ANGER-ART-NY     05-21 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-ANGER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUNNED BY DEFEAT, MIAMI BLAMES OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10,11,12,13,14,15 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In the Miami Heat's defining moment Sunday, a reserve
took the pivotal shot. And then, with the game to the Knicks
freshly lost _ and the Heat's season suddenly in ashes _ one of its
most frustrated players ran after a referee, berating him.
</P>
<P>
   With the Heat losing, 83-82, in the fading seconds at American
Airlines Arena, it was left to the backup small forward Clarence
Weatherspoon to decide the game. His high-arcing 12-foot jump shot
hit off the side of the rim and signaled an end to Miami's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm driving the ball and I'm seeing 4 seconds on the clock,''
said Weatherspoon, in the game because the starter P.J. Brown had
fouled out. ``Who else you throw it to? I wanted us to have a
chance of rebounding the ball, and I didn't want the clock to run
out.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened after the defeat showed the depth of Miami's
despair. Small forward Jamal Mashburn, who thought the officiating
likely cost Miami this victory so crucial to its psyche, cornered
one of the game referees.
</P>
<P>
   What did he say?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they stink,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mashburn thought in particular that a foul should have been
called on a drive to the basket he made with two and a half minutes
to play and the score tied at 79.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was contact,'' he said. ``If you're going to let us
play, let us play throughout the whole game. Don't sway one way or
another. Be consistent with it. I don't think they were very
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashburn, who had largely exorcised the demons of his previous
failures against the Knicks with his play in this series, had a
nightmarish game to carry into the offseason. He made just 3 of 15
field-goal attempts, shot no free throws and had 2 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   In the game's final 7 minutes 42 seconds, he had the ball last
on a shot-clock violation, launched an out-of-control shot with the
Heat up by 4 points, missed on the drive in which he thought he was
fouled and misfired on a medium-range jump shot with the Heat
trailing by a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't win and I didn't make the shots,'' he said,
blanching at the idea that his play through the stretch might have
been a liability. ``If you want to put that on me, that's cool.
That's fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashburn said there was a feeling of shock in the locker room.
This was the third straight season that the Knicks have eliminated
the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for the people in this locker room,'' he said.
``I feel their pain. Everybody had a little tear in their eye or
something, Coach was pretty broken up.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that no one realizes what a work schedule the Heat
submitted to in order to have a chance at National Basketball
Association title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a lot of work into it _ a whole lot more than any other
NBA team will ever even think about,'' he said, his head now up and
defiant.
</P>
<P>
   About then, someone asked him whether he thought the NBA's
hierarchy had ordained a Knicks-Los Angeles Lakers final to capture
television ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if they are going to do that, then they need to send us
a memo before the season,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Around the locker room, the Heat echoed Mashburn's sentiment
about inconsistent refereeing. Center Alonzo Mourning thought a
chintzy ``touch foul on the perimeter'' had been allowed to settled
Game 6, and that Mashburn had clearly been fouled late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Tim Hardaway even called for a league investigation
into the officiating, before abruptly ending his post-game
critique.
</P>
<P>
   Heat Coach Pat Riley was a little more contrite, but not much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have won in spite of it,'' he said. ``There were
four fouls where our players just played hard. This is a very
difficult loss for my team to take _ we were at home. With as much
as we were attacked going to the basket, there was a disparity in
the foul calling. It is hard to lose that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning thought the officials plainly erred after
Weatherspoon's missed field-goal attempt with 2.1 seconds left. The
Knicks' Latrell Sprewell retrieved the rebound and was granted a
timeout. Mourning complained, to no avail, that Sprewell never
requested it and, in fact, stepped out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the better team,'' Mourning said. ``No one will be
able to convince me otherwise. But sometimes things happen. It's
tough to take.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
