<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK SUSPENDS PEACE TALKS WITH PALESTINIANS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak suspended peace talks with
the Palestinians Sunday, ordering his negotiators home from
Stockholm amid continued violent demonstrations in the West Bank
and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   A 2-year-old Israeli girl was on life-support Sunday after being
critically burned late Saturday when Palestinians hurled firebombs
at her family's car in Palestinian-ruled Jericho, where a casino
often draws Israeli patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's move raised fears that the peace process could be
derailed just as the two sides are engaged in multiple negotiating
tracks in an attempt to come up with the frequently delayed final
peace agreement by the new deadline of Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's spokesman said in a statement that Barak
recalled Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami and lawyer Gilad
Sher, who have been conducting a second track of negotiations in
Stockholm with Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had already canceled a trip to Washington to meet with
President Clinton, citing the ongoing clashes between Palestinians
and Israeli soldiers and the upsurge in fighting in south Lebanon,
which is taking place just a month before Israel's planned
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   He also barred Israelis and foreign tourists Sunday from
entering the Palestinian-ruled areas.
</P>
<P>
   The recall of the negotiators was condemned by the Palestinian
Authority, which now controls some 40 percent of the West Bank and
most of Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   One Palestinian official said Barak's decision was an attempt to
cover up the fact that negotiations were not going anywhere. The
two sides are negotiating over how much more land the Palestinians
should have for an independent state, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like these negotiations didn't achieve anything, and
Barak is using the incident as a pretext for bringing the
negotiations to an end,'' said Yasser Abed Rabbo, the Minister of
Information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any connection between the incidents in
the West Bank and Barak's decision,'' said Abed Rabbo, who this
month resigned from a different negotiating team, saying he had not
been informed about the talks in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Six Palestinians have been killed and more than 1,000 wounded in
the violence that escalated sharply on May 15, the annual
Palestinian day of mourning marking Israel's creation in 1948, when
hundreds of thousands of Palestinians either fled or were forced
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40 Israeli soldiers have been wounded, including one
seriously, in the clashes that last week spun out of control when
Palestinian police and Israeli soldiers shot at each other with
live ammunition. Twenty-two Israeli civilians have also been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The West Bank and Gaza have since been rocked by pockets of
violence between Palestinians hurling stones and Israeli soldiers
firing tear gas and rubber-coated metal pellets, but there has been
no repeat of the large-scale gunbattles that erupted last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But while the demonstrations have grown smaller, they continue
to reflect long-simmering Palestinian anger over the slow-moving
peace process and Israel's refusal to release more Palestinian
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   While some Israeli officials have charged that Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat may have lost control of the demonstrators,
the clashes have given Arafat an important boost in popularity just
as criticism was growing, Palestinian political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the violence could not have come at a worse time for
Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations began the day Barak's Cabinet narrowly
approved transferring three Jerusalem suburbs to full Palestinian
rule, a move that has mixed support from the public but has been
promoted by Barak as an important step in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Since the vote Barak has been fighting to keep his coalition
government intact. Two coalition partners, one representing Jewish
settlers in the West Bank and Gaza and the other Russian
immigrants, have threatened to withdraw when the land is handed
over.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he will delay handing over the three suburbs of
Jerusalem until the Palestinian Authority reins in the
demonstrators, some of whom are said to be part of an opposition
group within Arafat's Fatah party.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the clashes, coupled with the increased violence in south
Lebanon, including Hezbollah rocket attacks on Israel's northern
border over the past few days, have led to complaints from some
Israelis that Barak is making concessions and getting only violence
in return.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a sign that Arafat may be trying to limit further
violence, his Fatah party Sunday called for five days of peaceful
protests on behalf of the 1,650 Palestinians imprisoned by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians say that Israel should release the prisoners,
particularly those who committed violent acts before the 1993 peace
accord was signed. Israel has released some as part of the peace
process but said most should serve out their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The Fatah decision to organize new protests was clearly designed
to get the demonstrations back under control and reduce the tension
that has gripped both Israelis and Palestinians since clashes
began.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians stage demonstrations to remind Israelis why
they should withdraw from the West Bank and Gaza, while Barak's
hesitation over transferring more land is a reminder to Arafat that
Israel is not free to give in to all demands, one Israeli analyst
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each case the leadership is showing that it is not coming
to the negotiating table with absolute freedom, that it has limited
powers,'' said political analyst Yaron Ezrachi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
