<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON IS NO MATCH FOR METS' MCEWING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe McEwing is one foot shorter than Randy Johnson,
the 6-foot-10-inch pitcher who Bobby Valentine said looks 8 feet
tall while he is lurking menacingly on the mound. When you see
Johnson at a baseball game, you figure he is a powerful athlete.
When you see McEwing, you feel like asking for two with mustard.
McEwing would probably fetch the hot dogs, too.
</P>
<P>
   But there was McEwing talking softly and ever so humbly about
conquering Johnson and helping the Mets burst past the Arizona
Diamondbacks, 7-6, to complete the three-game sweep at Shea Stadium
Sunday. Derek Bell lined a single off Byung-Hyun Kim in the ninth
inning that enabled McEwing to hustle in from second base with the
winning run and complete his own extraordinary day in style.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday, Johnson had dominated the National League with his
ferocious fastball and an intimidating disposition. Until 10 days
ago, McEwing was playing, but hardly dominating, with Class AAA
Norfolk in the International League. But on a raw, rainy day,
McEwing, the 28-year-old who is called Super Joe by his teammates,
aggravated the Diamondbacks with a home run, two doubles, a walk, a
crucial stolen base and three runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the ultimate challenge for us to face a guy like
him,'' McEwing said of Johnson. ``As professionals, that's what we
strive for. We went out and battled all day. We came from behind
four times and didn't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Valentine mused that at least one person surely
speculated that the game was over when the Diamondbacks went ahead,
1-0, in the first inning. But the Mets opened up with three
consecutive doubles off Johnson to erase the first of three
deficits against him. Johnson gave up five earned runs on three
homers and five doubles in six and two-thirds innings, as many
earned runs as he had allowed in his previous six starts over 472/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets struck out 13 times against Johnson, including one
stretch in which he fanned 11 of 14 batters. But the Mets pelted
Johnson by being aggressive, by trying to avoid two-strike counts
in which he could unleash his slider and by viewing the reigning Cy
Young award winner as a mortal pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just showed that none of our guys played that game before
it started,'' Valentine said. ``They came out and had a little
determined look in their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes after the victory, McEwing still had his cap
pulled tight over his brow while he did a radio interview. There
were bloodstains on the right knee of his white uniform pants and
dirt stains splashed across the backside. McEwing, who had his
first major league hit off Johnson while with the St. Louis
Cardinals last season and who is now 5 for 16 off the left-hander,
looked like a kid who had been frolicking in a puddle. That is how
he wants to look.
</P>
<P>
   McEwing started the first rally with a double, he finished a
memorable 12-pitch at-bat that featured seven two-strike fouls with
another double, he lined a homer to spark another rally and he
began the winning rally with a walk on a 3-2 pitch. In five times
at bat, McEwing, the leadoff hitter, squeezed 34 pitches out of
Johnson and Kim.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what he lacks in pure size and ability, he makes up with
his gutsy play,'' Mike Piazza said. ``He's fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   After McEwing, Bell and Edgardo Alfonzo doubled on three
straight pitches in the first inning to put the Mets ahead, 2-1,
Arizona clipped Rick Reed for two runs in the third to make it,
3-2. But Piazza belted a majestic homer, estimated at 492 feet,
into the left-field mezzanine section to even the score.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Lee's two-run homer off Reed in the sixth gave Arizona a
5-3 lead, the third time the Mets trailed Johnson. No problem, the
Mets thought. McEwing lumbered to the plate an inning later,
holding his bat high above his shoulders and hammered a fastball
over the left-field fence. Alfonzo went deep one batter later to
tie the score, 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley homered off Dennis Cook in the eighth to push
Arizona ahead, 6-5, but once again the Mets displayed resilience.
Robin Ventura, who did not start for the second straight game
because of a strained left thigh muscle, was healthy enough to
smack a pinch-hit homer off Mike Morgan and tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth game drifted to the ninth, and it was a nice
omen for the Mets when McEwing led off the inning. McEwing walked
against the submarine-throwing Kim and quickly stole second. He
scored the decisive run when a diving Lee missed snaring Bell's
liner to right by a few inches. The Mets sprinted out of the dugout
to mob Bell and McEwing, who, fittingly, was the last player to
leave the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very humble person, so I'm not going to brag about
myself, but I'm also a confident person and I believe in my
abilities,'' McEwing said. ``You just got to go out and battle.
That's what I do every day. I play hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
