<DOCNO> NYT20000521.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1700 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-HAITI-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      05-21 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAITIAN ELECTION INITIALLY HAILED AS A SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ In an election marked by long lines,
disorganized poll workers, and voters possessing reservoirs of
patience, Haiti's landmark vote Sunday went off without reports of
major trouble, an apparently successful step toward rebuilding the
destitute nation.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, in direct contrast to elections held over the last 13
years of topsy-turvy democracy, was notable for its absence of
fear. It was social, and it also was miserable for those waiting
five, six, seven hours in the sun. But for many, voting was their
duty. For some, it was pure joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I scored!'' yelled a young woman as she danced out of a voting
place in Leogane, about 20 miles south of the capital, known for
its boatbuilders who helped launch thousands of desperate
boatpeople toward America in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted!'' she shouted. ``For the first time!''
</P>
<P>
   The long-delayed elections will fill Haiti's now-vacant
parliament seats as well as an astounding 7,300 local offices. The
ballots _ some of them being carried by donkey over roadless hills
and mountains _ aren't expected to be tallied for a week or two, or
three.
</P>
<P>
   The seating of a parliament alone carries major benefits for
Haiti, which has been without a legislature for 17 months and
without a truly functioning government for more than three years.
Once a parliament is sworn in this summer, about $500 million in
frozen international assistance becomes available. After scheduled
presidential elections in November, more donor aid is expected.
</P>
<P>
   For the poorest country in the Western Hemisphere, one with
illiteracy long stuck at 80 percent, Sunday's vote was seen as a
possible turning point to end its relentless downward political and
economic spiral.
</P>
<P>
   With only incomplete reports coming in to Port-au-Prince, the
vote wasn't free of crisis. In Croix des Bouquets, a supporter of
an arrested candidate shot and wounded a policeman, who returned
fire and killed him, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In two southern areas of Grand-Anse and Nippes, elections were
postponed late Saturday because of poor preparation, frustrating
335,000 registered voters, or about 8 percent of the electorate.
And in voting centers throughout the country, thousands of polls
opened several hours late _ including the center where former
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide cast his vote. Polls were kept
open an extra hour because of the late start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, overall, it's looking quite positive so far,'' said
Mary Durran, spokesperson for the Organization of American States'
210-member electoral observer mission. She ticked off a list of
problems, including the late poll openings, disorganized poll
workers, some violations of secrecy of the vote, and crowd control
problems in Port-au-Prince, Gonaives and Cap Haitien.
</P>
<P>
   Representative William Delahunt, a Quincy Democrat who was part
of a congressional delegation here, said, however, the most
surprising and encouraging part was the calm mood and high turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary estimates from international observers put the
turnout in the capital _ where intimidation and despair had kept
most voters at home in previous elections _ at 40 to 60 percent,
and as high as 80 percent in many northeastern towns.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt said that election officials should move quickly to
reschedule the postponed vote in the two southern areas. He also
foresaw potential difficulties with the compilation of the
balloting, given the massive undertaking _ 11,000 voting stations
and 29,000 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``To borrow someone's line, I'd call these free, fair and flawed
elections,'' Delahunt said.
</P>
<P>
   At polling center No. 9711 in Port-au-Prince's Fontemara
section, a group of young men waited five hours to vote _ and then
didn't want to leave afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at us,'' said Jean Jean-Robert, 33, who sells medicine in
the streets. ``The fact that in 1987 nobody was able to hang around
a polling station because we feared getting shot, and that we are
staying here today, shows that things are much better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was worth staying in line for five hours,'' said Olivier
Bonnet, 26, who is studying to be an electrician. ``We know where
we came from. We know where we want to go. And without this vote,
we can't get there.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Port-au-Prince school where gunmen killed about 20 people
lined up to vote in 1987, Metilhomme Alexis, 56, also drew upon the
past to explain why he was voting. He had arrived at 6 a.m., the
official time to begin voting. Voting didn't begin until after 8
a.m., but Alexis didn't complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the massacre in 1987, I was watching from across the
street. I saw a jeep drive in. It was a jeep of death. These guys
with guns jumped out and started shooting at us. We escaped,'' he
said. ``I have no fear whatsoever today. If we didn't vote, I see
nothing happening in this country. I see no escape.''
</P>
<P>
   The day wasn't without its frustrations, small and large. When a
polling station finally opened at the National Theater in the
capital at 7:57 a.m., security officials opened a metal gate and
hundreds tried to shove their way in, causing screaming and pushing
for several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In Leogone, moments after the young woman publicly expressed her
happiness, an opposition party leader screamed his displeasure
inside the voting place. Jean Marie Mariel said election officials
unfairly kicked out a representative of the opposition Espace party
because he didn't have the right stamp on his documents.
</P>
<P>
   And in a tiny schoolroom-turned-polling place in Grecier, south
of the capital, one man began telling his wife how to vote. ``Stop
that!'' said one election official.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make a mess here,'' the man said. ``I'll blow this place
up!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Want us to call the police?'' said the official.
</P>
<P>
   The man left everyone alone, his wife included.
</P>
<P>
   But such anger seemed rare Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Most people, their faces stoic, approached voting as their
solemn national duty _ even if many knew none of the candidates or
needed help deciphering the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voting is your right and your work,'' said Carmen Rose, 26, of
Nancolin.
</P>
<P>
   Next to her was Fort Stenley, 29, straddling his bicycle.
``We're not going to solve this in one shot, one vote,'' Stenley
said. ``It's going to be day by day, and little by little it's
going to get better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
