u s BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-COLUMN-N     05-21 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE DEVILS TAKE STOCK AS ELIMINATION LOOMS  

</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Among personalities in the coaching
profession, there are the fire-breathers and the cool breezes.
Bobby Knight, the Indiana basketball coach, is often among the
first group. Larry Robinson, the Devils' coach, is usually among
the latter. Robinson is unlikely to put his hands on an athlete's
throat or to insult people gratuitously or to scream at his team in
the dressing room. He prefers to offer positive reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson, with exasperation and in desperation, yelled quite
a bit Saturday night after the Devils fell to the brink of
elimination in the Stanley Cup playoffs. After a 3-1 Flyers victory
in Continental Arena, Robinson kicked over a trash can and
addressed his players in shouts that could be heard in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regret anything I said,'' Robinson said Sunday
afternoon, in measured tones, before the team boarded its bus to
Philadelphia. ``However, my voice regrets it and my head regrets
it. I felt it was the right place and the right time. They had to
know exactly how I felt. At least I know I've done what I could.''
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a performance for a man whose first grandchild was
born over the weekend, and it might not be enough. The Devils trail
by 3-1 in the four-of-seven-game Eastern Conference finals, which
resume Monday night at First Union Center. A Flyer victory would
put Philadelphia into the Stanley Cup finals against either Dallas
or Colorado, who are tied at two victories apiece in the West.
After winning Game 1, the Devils have lost three consecutive games
to a similar team that may be a little bigger, tougher and more
skilled.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said Sunday that he thought his team had become
undisciplined when the score was 1-1 in the third period. He said
his players needed to maintain their positions and trust in the
game plan. He said his forwards needed to push to the net and try
for more rebounds. He said that some players were giving full
effort but that not everyone was trying hard enough. So he wanted
more energy, execution, focus and finish. The message seemed to
have reached its intended receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he's going to get it through our thick skulls what
he wants,'' Scott Stevens, the captain, said. ``You never see him
mad. I was shocked. It was very upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur, the goalie whose play improved Saturday despite
another costly turnover that led to the first goal, said it was not
wrong for Robinson ``to lose it like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If he doesn't, it would have proved he doesn't
really care.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Gomez, the rookie center, said Robinson's loud words
``showed us how much he cares about us and how much he believes in
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was one of two veteran defensemen praised by Robinson
for their effort. The other was Ken Daneyko. When prompted to cite
a few more positives Sunday Robinson instead chose to stress
negatives. ``Philadelphia has scored probably 90 percent of their
goals going to the net and getting rebounds,'' he said. ``We have
yet to score off a rebound. That's what the New Jersey Devils have
been noted for, going to the net and being hard to move in front of
the net. We haven't been in front of the net. You don't have to
move anything that's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of those big forwards are Bobby Holik and Randy McKay. Holik
scored the only Devil goal Saturday and McKay assisted. Referring
to Robinson's outburst, McKay said: ``It better have the desired
effect because he was right. We didn't play smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his teammates, McKay said: ``It wasn't from lack of trying.
Everyone in here cares. I'm not questioning anybody's character.''
</P>
<P>
   Holik added that Robinson's words had an effect. ``If a man of
that stature says something, everybody in the room had better
listen,'' Holik said.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes what is unspoken is also important. The Flyers can
be an intimidating team around their net. Dan McGillis, a big
defenseman, is having a good series. Rick Tocchet and Keith Jones,
rugged forwards, are punishing people who turn their backs to them
in pursuit of the puck. And forwards like Mark Recchi, John LeClair
and Keith Primeau are breaking free for rushes going the other way,
putting defensemen like Stevens and Daneyko on their heels.
</P>
<P>
   While Philadelphia will probably advance, a Devil comeback is
not totally far-fetched. In a tournament this long, teams can fall
into slumps and come out of them. The Devils showed signs of it
Saturday. The stylish attacking tandem of Gomez and Alexander
Mogilny, despite being on the ice for Philadelphia's winning goal,
had several close chances. Mogilny rang a crossbar behind goalie
Brian Boucher. Gomez charged to the net and ended up in it after
Boucher stopped his low backhander. Claude Lemieux was aggressive
and nasty and inspired fans and teammates with his penalty killing.
</P>
<P>
   But, with Robinson's words ringing in their ears, do the Devils
have enough time, grit and skill to recover?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' Brodeur said. ``It's up to us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
