</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES FRUSTRATED IN ROOKIE'S FINE DEBUT  

</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Paul Rigdon has been a big-league pitcher for one
day and he can tell friends he gets standing ovations every other
inning. He can say those world champion Yankees aren't that tough
if you just throw strikes. He can say he outduels pitchers like
Orlando Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Rigdon can say his record is perfect, after he allowed just two
hits in pitching shutout ball for seven innings Sunday, as
Cleveland dumped the Yankees, 6-1. The Yankees' only run came in
the ninth; they have not scored a run with Hernandez (4-4) in the
game since May 3, a span of 24 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lost two of three games to Cleveland this weekend.
It was the first time they dropped a series at Jacobs Field since
June 20-22, 1997, when the Indians also took two of three games.
Because Boston lost two of three to Detroit, the Yankees (24-16)
did not lose any ground in the American League East: they are one
game behind the Red Sox (25-15). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rigdon, 24, was promoted to the majors in the wake of the rash
of devastating pitching injuries suffered by the Indians last week.
In one day Cleveland placed three pitchers _ the starters Jaret
Wright and Charles Nagy and the reliever Ricardo Rincon _ on the
disabled list. All the Yankees knew about Rigdon before he pitched
Sunday was contained in a few lines of a scouting report. He throw
sinkers, it was written, and sliders, and he throws lots of
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams said later that the report did not mention the
changeup that Rigdon threw. Nor did it mention that Rigdon blew out
his elbow in 1996 and had to have the joint rebuilt, or that he
missed the entire 1997 season, or that he was among the first
players cut in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees learned about Rigdon mostly by watching him pitch
Sunday. They could see he was a tall right-hander, and aggressive.
He was nervous facing the Yankees, he said afterward, so he just
pretended he was not facing the Yankees, but just an ordinary team.
</P>
<P>
   He just kept pumping strikes, ``kept getting ahead in the
count,'' Manager Joe Torre said. ``He wasn't overpowering,
obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees kept getting healthy swings against Rigdon, putting
the ball in play, but Chuck Knoblauch did not collect the Yankees'
first hit until there were two out in the third inning. After
Rigdon retired the side in the top of the fourth, striking out
Jorge Posada to close the inning, fans at Jacobs Field _ accustomed
to seeing the Yankees destroy Cleveland pitching _ gave the rookie
a standing ovation. They stood again for him after the fifth and
sixth innings. ``When there are 40,000 on their feet cheering for
you,'' Rigdon said, ``it sends chills down your spine.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (23-17) scored in each of the first three innings,
building a 4-0 lead with rallies that included an inside-the-park
home run. Two outs into the second inning, Enrique Wilson lifted a
high drive toward right field. Paul O'Neill retreated, staring
upward. O'Neill felt the hard rubber surface of the warning track
beneath his feet, and as he continued to follow the flight of the
ball, he anticipated he would reach the fence.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill did not know he had drifted into the jaws of an angle,
where one part of the wall meets another and creates a little extra
space on the warning track. O'Neill was not as close to the wall as
he thought. Rather than back up another step or two, he jumped,
falling backward, and the ball glanced off his glove, ricocheted
off the fence and bounded toward the infield. O'Neill lay against
the base of the wall, helpless.
</P>
<P>
   As Williams ran over from center field to retrieve the ball,
Wilson charged around the bases, waved around third by the base
coach Jim Riggleman. It appeared the second baseman, Knoblauch, the
relay man, had a reasonable chance of cutting down Wilson at the
plate, but his throw sailed high over the catcher Posada's head
while Wilson belly-flopped across the plate, exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got kind of lost and I missed it,'' O'Neill said. ``It
got in the sun and I lost it. But it hit my glove, and any time it
hits your glove, you should catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had his hands on his hips frequently, his pose of
frustration, and after Jim Thome ripped a high curveball for a
two-run homer in the third, Hernandez looked at Posada and tapped
himself on the chest: my fault. Manny Ramirez's two-run homer in
the seventh finished the scoring against Hernandez, who allowed
nine hits, three walks and six runs in six-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   Posada lined a one-out double off Rigdon in the seventh and the
Indians' bullpen came to life, as if the Indians could not believe
how much they were getting out of Rigdon. But Jim Leyritz smashed a
grounder that shortstop Omar Vizquel gloved to begin an
inning-ending double play _ the second of three Cleveland double
plays _ and fans were on their feet again. Later, Knoblauch and
Scott Brosius estimated that they have received two standing
ovations at Yankee Stadium; Rigdon had four on his first day.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored an unearned run in the ninth before Posada
flied out to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez flipped his batting gloves onto the dugout and
other Yankees tossed balls and other items as if to rid themselves
of mementos from this frustrating day against a rookie pitcher they
could not hit. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
