u a BC-COLLEGE-CLOSING-NYT &LR;      05-21 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-CLOSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE COMMENCEMENT DOUBLES AS A WAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVERHILL, Mass. _ Bradford College, a small liberal arts school
that had been struggling to find a niche since it became a
four-year coeducational institution a generation ago, died Saturday
after a bittersweet commencement ceremony that drew hundreds of
alumni from around the country. It was 197 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the cause was a simple failure to find enough
students to cover operating costs, though many blame mismanagement
and weak marketing. Bradford's demise was sealed when enrollment
fell short of expectations last fall by just 31 students, but it
probably had been inevitable at least since the college decided in
1996 to borrow $18 million to build new dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to change to survive,'' said Karen M. Shugrue, a 1970
graduate who heads the board of trustees. ``Bradford has always
done that _ has always somehow managed, until now, to change and
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   With its grand red-brick buildings around a grassy quad and a
wooden bridge arcing over Tupelo Pond, Bradford is the
quintessential picture of a New England college campus and has long
been the cultural heart of this historic working-class community,
35 miles northeast of Boston. It was founded in 1803 as one of the
first girls' schools in New England and, in 1932, became a two-year
college serving the daughters of the well-to-do. Four decades
later, at the height of the Vietnam War, Bradford admitted men and
began granting bachelor's degrees; since then, the college has been
on the cutting edge of liberal arts education, offering tiny
student-faculty ratios, innovative teaching and an emphasis on
internships and community service.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, amid the increasingly competitive college
market, Bradford has been in a seemingly endless process of
self-reinvention, catering to artists, international students, the
learning disabled. But with fewer than 600 full-time students, the
bulk of them lured to campus with generous discounts off the
$25,000 sticker price, the college ran yawning deficits.
</P>
<P>
   While elite liberal arts colleges like Amherst in Massachusetts
and Oberlin in Ohio are thriving, higher education has shifted its
overall focus to professional training, leaving smaller,
lesser-known schools, like Bradford, in danger. In 1960, about half
the nation's students were at liberal arts colleges; today, about
17 percent are. Since 1986, more than 40 such institutions have
shut their doors, but none was as old or respected in academic
circles as Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's profoundly sad for all of us,'' Arthur C. Levine,
president of Teachers College at Columbia University and a former
president of Bradford, said in the final commencement address
Saturday. ``For our nation, it's a tragedy, when small colleges,
which know their students by name and character, give way to
megaversities and online campuses that know them by Social Security
numbers or URLs.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's ceremony was more Irish wake than funeral, as
graduates celebrated their successes through tears and alumnae from
a half-century ago joked about reconvening if the college is
converted into a retirement home. The 25-acre campus, which has 19
buildings _ from the 17th-century tavern where the school was
conceived to the new complex of town houses that brought it to the
brink of bankruptcy _ is on the market, and though schools have
come shopping, none has made a bid.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford's e-mail network and mailing address will be defunct by
month's end, its transcripts sent to nearby Merrimack College, the
$20 million endowment in the hands of the state attorney general.
The fate of other assets _the 36-foot mural of Bradford's history
painted a decade ago; the trowel used to lay the cornerstone of
Academy Hall, the campus centerpiece, in 1870; countless old bows
and arrows, snowshoes, tennis rackets and posture trophies in the
former gym _ remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mourn the 200-year tradition, obviously,'' said David
Crouse, a 1990 graduate who returned to teach writing five years
ago. ``But a lot of my mourning is about the possibilities. We were
on the verge of great things.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the closing was announced on Nov. 23, the campuswide
strategic planning process has been replaced with talk of transfer
applications and job interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Students and faculty have cycled through the stages of grief:
angry protests under desperate ``Save Bradford'' banners; a futile
effort to raise $20 million, which netted several thousand in
pledges; a steady march of farewell parties; and throughout, an
attempt at teaching and learning, tests and projects, even the
annual faculty-senior softball game, as the college ran out of
basic supplies like light bulbs and paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like purgatory,'' Marc Mannheimer, an art professor for
the past 21 years, said in an interview the day after classes
ended. ``Every day, I say to myself, `This is the last time I'll do
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford is survived by 6,711 alumni, 497 students (131 of whom
received diplomas Saturday), 33 full-time professors and 121 staff
members. It was preceded in death by the renowned writer Andre
Dubus, who taught at the college for 18 years, and Portia Marshall
Washington Pittman, the daughter of Booker T. Washington, who
graduated in 1905.
</P>
<P>
   As they milled about outside the white commencement tent,
generations of former students reminisced about gooey chocolate
Bradford cake (which was served at the alumni reception), singing
holiday songs by candlelight on the steps of Academy Hall, jumping
in the pond when classes were canceled on the annual Spring Day.
Singing the alma mater for an institution founded when Thomas
Jefferson was president, they wondered what it would mean to have a
diploma from a place that no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Jordan Gabrielson, a 1945 graduate who lives in
Philadelphia, said Dorothy M. Bell, Bradford's president for 27
years, always told her ``the one thing you can count on in life,
that's change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't expect it here,'' said Gabrielson's classmate,
Muriel Horne Weldon, who wore her monogrammed green Bradford scarf
around her neck. ``That is, not in this form. They changed their
thinking. They added buildings, added students. But it was still
supposed to be here forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2226EDT &QL; 
