u s BC-BKN-DRAFT-LOTTERY-NYT     05-21 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-LOTTERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NETS SCORE A BIG VICTORY: THE NO. 1 PICK  

</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SECAUCUS, N.J. _ The Nets do not have a coach, a director of
basketball operations or much of a history of good fortune. But
they do now have the No. 1 pick in the 2000 National Basketball
Association draft and a chance to begin to reverse their struggles
after coming up as the winners of the draft lottery Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who finished with the league's seventh-worst record,
had 44 chances out of 1,001 to obtain the top overall selection,
but the Ping-Pong balls fell their way. The organization, which has
been undergoing an overhaul with Coach Don Casey being let go and
the team's president, Michael Rowe, being reassigned since the end
of a disappointing season, suddenly finds itself in an enviable
position for once.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Katz, the principal owner of the Nets, sat on the podium
listening as the June 28 draft order was called off. After the Nets
had passed by the No. 7 spot where their record would have placed
them, and it came down to the final two spots, Katz sat nervously
mouthing silent words to himself.
</P>
<P>
   When the announcement came that the Vancouver Grizzlies were No.
2, leaving the Nets as the winners, Katz pumped his fist and
shouted, ``Yes, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so unbelievable,'' Katz said. ``You start out at 40 out
of 1,000, and you're thinking, `I want to be at No. 7, I don't want
to lose my position.' Then when you hit 7, it's like, `I'd like to
be No. 3.' And then, all of the sudden, it's like you're at the
Academy Awards. It's you.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Nets, it's absolutely phenomenal. It's an up for a
tough season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzlies, who had the fourth-worst record in the league,
moved up to No. 2, and the perennially struggling Los Angeles
Clippers dropped to the third pick despite having the worst record.
Chicago moved down to No. 4 and also picked up the seventh pick
from the Washington Wizards, who owed the pick as a part of a trade
if they did not get one of the top three spots.
</P>
<P>
   With no clear choice for the first overall selection, the Nets
must decide whether to use the pick themselves or to trade it away.
The thought has been that Kenyon Martin, a 6-foot-9-inch power
forward from the University of Cincinnati, would be the top pick in
this draft. But Martin is coming off a broken leg and torn
ligaments in his ankle and also plays the same position as Keith
Van Horn. So the Nets could consider another player, such as Chris
Mihm, a 7-foot center from the University of Texas, or Stromile
Swift, a 6-8 forward from Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could field offers, such as the one that came, jokingly
at this time, from Orlando General Manager John Gabriel. As the
Nets celebrated the pick, Gabriel leaned over to Nets General
Manager John Nash and offered up the No. 5 and No. 10 picks that
the Magic wound up with Sunday. The Magic also has the No. 13 pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is a decision that is going to be made by a
number of people who aren't currently with us,'' Nash said. His
status remains a question with the Nets having begun interviewing
candidates for a director of basketball operations, including John
Thompson, who was interviewed on Friday. ``It's going to be an
organizational decision,'' he said. ``I think it would be
inappropriate until the organization is fully intact to be making a
decision as important as this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets had the top pick in the draft once previously, in 1990
when they selected Derrick Coleman. Coleman was more of a sure
thing than Martin as a talent, but never delivered the lift to the
organization that his ability had promised, and he was finally
dealt away as a disappointment. This time, the Nets bring back a
far more talented roster than the 17-65 team that Coleman joined,
but one still with needs. With Jayson Williams' health a question
mark and all three of the small forwards from the past season's
roster potential free-agent departures, the Nets' most glaring
needs are center and small forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we can fill a major void,'' Nash said. ``The
question is, can we improve the team even more if we opt to trade
the pick? Right now, I wouldn't be predisposed to trading the pick,
but as I say, we're going to have some new key management and
coaching people in place over the next couple of weeks and I think,
in fairness to them, they're going to have significant input.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
