<HEADLINE>
WALKING THE STREET TO CRUISE THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a typical New York street fair in many ways:
cotton candy, silly balloon hats, rock band, stock-option raffle.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it was a little different. With 60-odd Internet companies
hawking their wares at the Silicon Alley Street Fair, creativity
ruled the day. And the 30-somethings at Asktherobot.com, a
job-recruitment company, perhaps best captured the spirit of the
day by raffling 500 shares of their soon-to-be-public stock to the
winners of a basketball toss.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Internet,'' explained Michael Vogel, the chief
executive of the company, which started nearly four months ago and
plans to go public in a year or so. ``The big calling card to the
world is stock options. This is what the Internet is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogel estimated the potential value of the stock at $25,000,
depending on the selling price at the initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, hyperbole ruled the day as well.
</P>
<P>
   The fair, after all, was intended in large part to promote
Silicon Alley, the concentration of technology and Internet-related
companies that have cropped up in and around Manhattan, said Janet
Stites, the publisher of Alleycat News, which organized the fair at
Union Square Park with the marketing firm MarketMatch Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``People read about Silicon Alley, they hear about it, but they
don't come face to face with it,'' Stites said. ``It's an economic
development issue and a curiosity issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiosity seemed to be winning. Droves of people, despite a
chilly drizzle, massed under white tents for demonstrations of all
manner of Web sites, brought through a T-1 high-capacity telephone
line set up just for the event. And of course they filled plastic
bags with all manner of freebies: T-shirts, flying discs, caps and,
of course, software.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Kimmel, 59, who lives nearby, toted a bag filled with
goodies, a powerful lure for her. But she also recently bought an
Internet-only computer after months of surfing the Web at a
library, so anything ``dot-com'' would have brought her out. ``I'm
very obsessed with the Internet now,'' she said. ``I'm just
thrilled with it. I have so much clutter and thousands of pieces of
paper, so I can get rid of it all because all the information is on
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Cohen of Brooklyn picked up a CD-ROM for a
financial-services Web site, infogate.com, and was amazed at the
variety of companies. Many were start-up firms like
Asktherobot.com, but mainstays like IBM and United Parcel Service
also got in on the action, as did out-of-towners like mall.com, a
retail site based in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wider range of companies than I thought,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet service providers, or portals, and companies offering
online shopping seemed most abundant. Or at least made the most
noise. ``Come on, lonely Matt here is waiting for somebody to
e-mail him!'' cried a worker for juno.com, an Internet service
provider, as another employee, Matt Daly, sat checking his empty
in-box.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at cyberrate.com, a retailing site, beckoned passers-by
by flashing a strobe light and throwing T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Mariolene Jeanbaptiste, dressed as a big red bean, passed out
temporary tattoos for beenz.com, an electronic commerce site.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll try anything,'' said Marion Rodgers, turning away from
the big bean with a handful of tattoos. ``It's like when you go to
the mall and all these people come up to you. I don't know why I
would be surprised that Internet companies would be any different.
Maybe because you never see real people on the Internet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Certainly the paradox at hand _ that everybody there had left
his home to visit a fair whose companies promise you won't have to
because of the Internet _ was not lost on some people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be interesting to see if they can have a virtual
street fair some day,'' said Adrian Marsh, a sophomore at New York
University majoring in English who is thinking more and more of
majoring in computer science. ``At least that way they would not
have to worry about the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe next year, though organizers have more modest goals _ like
using wireless modems next time, and of course drawing more
companies. Laura Sabia of MarketMatch said she is working on
creating similar fairs for other high-tech cities like Boston and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   New York's fair was enough for Alan Barnes, 33, of Brooklyn.
``This place was as crowded and jumbled as the Internet,'' he said
as he left empty-handed and walked into that century-old portal,
the subway.
</P>
</TEXT>
