<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-CHIPSPEED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 IBM TO UNVEIL BREAKTHROUGH IN CHIP SPEED  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ IBM on Monday will unveil the first products
containing a breakthrough semiconductor technology that is
considered likely to spread across the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Called silicon-on-insulator, or SOI, the technology increases a
chip's speed and reduces its power consumption. It involves putting
a thin layer of silicon, then an insulating layer, under the
millions of tiny metal-oxide transistors, or switches, that do the
work inside the chip.
</P>
<P>
   The net effect is to make it possible to turn these switches on
and off with less electricity and therefore faster _ about 20 to 30
percent faster, according to IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal,'' said Fred Zieber, an analyst at Pathfinder
Research in San Jose, Calif. ``They're probably a couple of years
ahead of everyone else, but eventually everyone will have to adopt
SOI if they want to keep moving to higher clock speeds.''
</P>
<P>
   The products IBM is announcing today are additions to its AS/400
series of big business servers. In the long run, however, SOI could
have its greatest impact in battery-powered mobile computers
because it can reduce a chip's power requirements by as much as a
factor of three, according to IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Because IBM doesn't currently make Intel-compatible chips, SOI
won't show up in Windows notebooks until the company decides to
license its process to other manufacturers, or other companies
manage to come up with their own equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   But an IBM spokesman said the technology will be available to
Apple, which already uses IBM-made PowerPC chips in its laptops.
While declining to provide details, he said SOI will appear in a
portable device this year.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at IBM and elsewhere have been studying SOI for
almost 30 years, but until 18 months ago, when IBM first announced
the technology that led to today's products, no one had managed to
implement it in a way that could be applied to high-volume
commercial production.
</P>
<P>
   The advance is the latest in a string of recent technology
firsts for IBM. It has led the industry in shifting from aluminum
to copper for the internal wiring inside its chips, another
innovation that increases processor performance. Last month, it
announced major progress in another critical area of processor
technology known as ``low-k dielectrics.''
</P>
<P>
   These advances have bolstered the company's status as a leader
in microprocessor technology. Both Hewlett-Packard and Sun
Microsystems _ competitors with IBM in the server market _ have
recently contracted with IBM's microelectronics division to
manufacture some of their cutting-edge processors.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to the combination of copper wiring and SOI, the
AS/400 servers IBM is announcing today are up to 3.6 times faster
than their predecessors, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   They include the AS/400e 250, a small business server that
starts at $7,500 without memory or disk storage; the AS/400e 270, a
line designed for Web serving, e-business and Java applications,
which will be priced between $10,000 and $50,000; and the AS /400e
820, 830 and 840, a series of ``mid-market enterprise servers''
priced between $30,000 and $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
