<SLUG> BC-INTEL-XEON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INTEL TO INTRODUCE XEON PROCESSORS TODAY  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Intel Corp. will announce new versions of its
high-end Pentium III Xeon processors Monday, boosting the
performance of the server-oriented chips by 13 to 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The new Xeons, running at a clock speed of 700 megahertz, will
feature 1 or 2 megabytes of performance-enhancing ``Level 2 cache''
memory built into the chip. The company already offers versions of
the Xeon that run at speeds up to 866 megahertz, but those chips
have only 256 kilobytes of cache; until this week, the larger-cache
versions were available only at speeds of 550 megahertz or less.
</P>
<P>
   The new 700-megahertz version with 1 megabyte of cache will sell
for $1,177 in quantity; its 2-megabyte sibling will be $1,980.
</P>
<P>
   The chips, each of which has 140 million transistors, are
intended mainly for servers with four or more processors. Servers
are used not only to store data and run major business applications
inside corporations, but also to deliver Web pages and host
e-commerce programs.
</P>
<P>
   Companies expected to announce servers with the new chips in the
next few weeks include Compaq, Dell, Fujitsu-Siemens, Gateway,
Hewlett-Packard and IBM, which on Wednesday will unveil what it
calls ``the world's largest Intel-based server.''
</P>
<P>
   According to International Data Corp., 78 percent of all servers
in use worldwide are now based on Intel chips. Most of those are
low-end models, by server standards, but over the past five
quarters, the Xeon's market share in servers priced above $10,000
has climbed from 40 to 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
