<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHILDS LEAVES THE HARD ROAD BEHIND HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ He hoisted the basketball toward the rafters, a long
heave that ended another heirloom of a game and left Chris Childs
defiantly shaking his head. Standing there as his teammates stormed
the middle of American Airlines Arena and hugged and laughed and
lifted each other off the floor, Childs resembled the park ranger
who instructed the tourists not to feed the bears.
</P>
<P>
   Hadn't Miami Coach Pat Riley and his team learned anything from
this surreal seven-game odyssey? Whether it was Anthony Carter
dropping in an impossible shot over the backboard in Game 2 or
Bruce Bowen calmly downing a 3-pointer to seal Game 5, it became
understood.
</P>
<P>
   Do not leave players who took the long road to the National
Basketball Association open. You cannot give them the lane to
drive, an inch behind the arc or two free throws in the final
minutes. They worked too hard to get here.
</P>
<P>
   Childs thought long about this after the game was over, this
83-82 thriller won by the unshakable Knicks and their backup point
guard. He scored 10 straight Knicks points to begin the fourth
quarter, keeping them in a game they were about to throw away.
</P>
<P>
   Until the most confident role player in America morphed into the
Knicks' go-to guy, maneuvering his 6-foot-2-inch frame past Alonzo
Mourning and the Miami front line, scoring on driving layups and
drawing the foul, knocking down important jump shots. Who did he
think he was playing for, Quad City?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that CBA guys have unbelievable heart,'' Childs, a
five-year veteran of the Continental Basketball Association, said
after another demoralized Heat crowd had filed out into the Miami
sunlight, cursing his existence. ``Nobody has seen the hotels we
stay in, the money we make. What we had to do to even make the NBA.
You can't really describe unless you live that life. We have a
passion for the game nobody could understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody. Not a No. 1 draft pick whose bags have been carried to
and from the team charter plane since he was 22 years old. Not a
most valuable player candidate with a $105 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost fitting for Childs to help end the madness. It
began when Riley gave players like Carter and Bowen and _ at the
bitter end for Miami _ Clarence Weatherspoon the ball with the game
on the line. Either Mourning was covered or Tim Hardaway was
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what a person has done to get here,'' Kurt
Thomas said afterward in the Knicks' locker room. ``A lot of people
thought Anthony Carter would never play in this league. He ended up
having a big series. When you look at it, it was just 24 guys who
suited up, willing to give everything they had.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Knicks-Heat has never been about ego, multimillionaires
or franchise players. It is about hard-core ball, gym rats and hoop
junkies, trading shots like two youngsters in a pillow fight who
can't seem to get the other one to go groggy and drop.
</P>
<P>
   With the season in the balance, Childs' gumption, his coolness
amid the calamity, sent the Knicks to Indiana and the conference
finals for the second straight season.
</P>
<P>
   You could not believe the decibel level in this building when
Mourning blocked Allan Houston's driving runner with less than 10
minutes left. Miami had a 71-65 lead, and for the first time in two
weeks it seemed that someone would end the dance, pull away from
the other for good.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat had the ball and a chance to go up by 8 points. With
bedlam about to ensue, Childs stole a Jamal Mashburn pass and raced
upcourt. He bore down, went hard to his right and attacked the
basket. He was not taking on Mourning and P.J. Brown and
Weatherspoon as much as he was taking on the venom in the arena,
the people who would die happy if his layup was rejected into the
stands as he raced toward the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Bucket. And a foul on Weatherspoon. Three-point play.
Three-point game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest plays of the game,'' Riley said. ``Chris
drove down to our basket and got a 3-point play. Chris Childs
played really big for them.''
</P>
<P>
   There is something about Childs that embodies this Knick team
like no other player. The constant feuding with referees. The way
he hip-checks everyone who is guarding him as he dribbles down the
floor. The way he squared off against Kobe Bryant two months ago in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The little bully, unbent and unbowed, ready to trade genuine
blows with every player who challenges him, cocksure enough to
guarantee a Game 6 victory _ and back it up.
</P>
<P>
   For 9 minutes 12 seconds Sunday, the people who are paid more
than anyone else to fill Madison Square Garden and deliver the
Knicks a championship either could not make a shot or were
blanketed by their defender. Patrick Ewing, Latrell Sprewell and
Houston _ all current or past All-Stars _ were stifled by this
suffocating Heat defense.
</P>
<P>
   Childs scored 13 straight at one juncture, beginning with a
3-pointer at the end of the third quarter and ending with two free
throws with four minutes left. With the noise at a deafening pitch
and Mourning about to decide the series defensively, Childs took on
the Heat and Dade and Broward Counties all at once.
</P>
<P>
   The irrepressible Quad City kid, going back to the Eastern
Conference finals, heaving the ball toward the rafters, leaving the
hard road behind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
