r f BC-BBQ-E-TAIL-SFCHRON &LR;      05-21 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBQ-E-TAIL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LEAN TIMES FOR WEB STORES AS INVESTORS LOSE INTEREST  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ So you want to be an Internet entrepreneur?
</P>
<P>
   One day you see that a terrific domain name _ BBQ.com _ is for
sale, and you decide to build an Internet store around it, selling
$3,300 Lynx gas grills, bacon-wrapped Omaha steaks, electric bug
zappers.
</P>
<P>
   You quit your six-figure job. You line up seed money, hire
staff, build a Web site. You sell your first grill 30 seconds after
the site is up. Within half a year, business starts doubling
monthly. You add people. You build a bigger, better Web site. You
gear up for summer, barbecue's equivalent of Christmas. Now you
need more capital to fuel your growing business.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one problem.
</P>
<P>
   The same people who last year threw bundles of cash at online
pharmacies, pet food and cosmetics stores now say that investing in
e-tailers is dumber than pouring lighter fluid on flaming coals.
</P>
<P>
   By now, you realize you're playing out a drama being repeated
all over the e-tailing landscape: A cast of factors _ Nasdaq
gyrations, big-name debacles like Drkoop.com and CDNow, IPOs that
turned into penny stocks _ have created a downward spiral effect
for Internet stores.
</P>
<P>
   You give your pitch to 20 venture-capital firms, explaining the
barbecue market's allure: a huge, fanatical following who spend $18
billion a year; no dedicated stores online or offline; high margins
and, surprisingly, year-round traction. Some kinda like the idea,
but no one wants to take the lead in financing your company.
</P>
<P>
   The money's almost gone. You lay off most of your staff. Some
are so loyal they continue to show up at work for a few hours every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Now you have just days to see if you can find a deep-pockets
backer and pull a success out of the mesquite embers of your dream.
</P>
<P>
   So it's gone for Anthony Johndrow, chief executive and
co-founder of San Francisco's BBQ.com.
</P>
<P>
   After raising $1.68 million last summer to purchase the BBQ.com
domain name and launch the site, Johndrow went back to the well two
months ago only to find that it had run dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, I could have raised $30 million, but now VCs are
hiding under their desks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in May should hit $75,000 and could double in June, he
said _ if the site is still around.
</P>
<P>
   Johndrow and co-founder Fred Karem said they're talking to six
``very interested parties'' who might cough up the money to rescue
BBQ.com by investing or acquiring it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly the bottom of the ninth, two outs, a man on first
and second. If we don't knock something home this week, then that's
probably it,'' said Matthew Poole, the site's editor.
</P>
<P>
   BBQ.com's story exemplifies that of many little guys on the Web.
For every well-known Internet store that streaks across the night
sky like a comet, there are probably a dozen that don't attain much
more than the luminescence _ or life span _ of a firefly.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the recent flops have been huge. Europe's Boo.com, a
clothing site that aspired to a global market, burned through $120
million in months and last week went kaput.
</P>
<P>
   But many failures have been of small, specialty firms.
Violet.com, a San Francisco clothing site, shut down last month.
Connecticut's Craftshop.com, an arts-and-crafts e-tailer backed by
CMGI Inc., this month said it plans to file for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Targeting a niche market can mean a company is thinking smart _
or that it's consigned to have a trifling business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to go national with a boutique,'' said David
Cooperstein, research director for online retail at Forrester
Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``You need demand, a way of tapping
into it, a business strategy sound enough to execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Some three-quarters of all e-business startups are destined for
failure, according to a recent Gartner Group study. But that
doesn't mean that the whole idea of e-tailing is a bust, just that
the market can't support hundreds of little players.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, too many companies are doing (e-tailing), there's
too much hype, some companies are not well-managed. But if you look
past that, there's a huge market, growing really fast,'' said Barry
Parr, director of consumer e-commerce research, at International
Data Corp. in Mountain View, pointing to an expected $42 billion in
consumer spending on the Internet this year, up more than 50
percent from 1999.
</P>
<P>
   VCs have clearly lost their taste for e-tailing, but they're
still putting money in the sector. In the first quarter of 2000,
funding for e-commerce firms dropped in half from the previous
quarter, while overall funding went up almost 25 percent, according
to VentureOne, a VC research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Still, e-commerce drew $744.19 million in backing, although that
includes companies creating business exchanges as well as those
selling to consumers. Some e-tailers scored major bucks: Food.com
landed $80 million in private placement; eZiba, which sells
hand-crafted goods, got $68 million in VC; and home-improvement
products site OurHouse.com got $62.4 million in VC.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Fram, a professor of marketing at the Rochester (N.Y.)
Institute of Technology, offers a historical perspective on the
current Darwinian struggle.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, a brand-new industry sprang up in America,
generating incredible hype and excitement. More than 400 companies
fiercely competed to meet its demands. Eventually, only three
remained.
</P>
<P>
   A total flop, just like some say e-tail will be?
</P>
<P>
   The three players that survived the carnage _ Ford Motor Co.,
Chrysler Corp. and General Motors _ managed to do pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
