 REALNETWORKS UPGRADES INTENDED TO FIGHT MICROSOFT CHALLENGE  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Trying to head off a strong charge by Microsoft,
RealNetworks Inc. has reworked its Internet video and audio
playback software to become an all-purpose online entertainment
center.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle company Monday will unveil its latest upgrades of
its RealPlayer video and audio programs and the RealJukebox digital
music software as a prelude to the company's fourth-annual
developer's conference later this week in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The new RealPlayer 8 and RealJukebox 2 will still be available
separately and for free, although they now have more common,
integrated features and will be promoted as part of a suite of
programs called the Real Entertainment Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Microsoft Office model for digital
entertainment,'' said Rob Grady, product manager for RealNetworks'
consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks is trying to keep its lead over Microsoft's
competing Windows Media Player audio and video technology, which is
being shipped with Microsoft's Windows 98, Windows 2000 and
forthcoming Windows Millennium operating software.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks says it has about 125 million registered users of
its RealPlayer streaming video software and 34 million RealJukebox
users. Microsoft, meanwhile, says it has more than 100 million
registered users of its Windows Media Player.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which was built on software that allowed audio and
video to be streamed across the Internet, hopes to capitalize on
the increasing use of the Web as an entertainment medium, from MP3s
to video, with products that will work on computers and wireless
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the improved RealPlayer and RealJukebox, along
with a new file downloading manager, should help RealNetworks keep
its lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their technology is still well ahead of Microsoft's,'' said
Larry Gerbrandt, a senior analyst with Paul Kagen Associates in
Carmel, Calif. ``The government may complain about a lack of
competition, but we're certainly seeing the benefits of competition
in the streaming space.''
</P>
<P>
   Both RealNetworks and Microsoft are trying to build all-purpose
media players that do more than just play streaming video, but play
music converted into the MP3 or other audio formats, store and
catalog music files in a computer database and transfer the files
into separate digital audio devices.
</P>
<P>
   The RealNetworks upgrades are for the first time able to read
HTML code like a standard Web browser to better tie into the
company's Real.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Zaballos, director of systems marketing, said the company
is trying to stay abreast of the rapid consumer-driven changes in
digital entertainment, which will shift even more this summer when
major record labels like Sony and BMG begin selling downloadable
top hit songs through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not using this as a feature to move operating systems,''
Zaballos said. ``We're looking at the complete transformation of a
communications medium. This is not about computers _ this is about
the way people communicate. It's about to explode in ways
completely independent of the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerbrandt said the Real Entertainment Center can better take
advantage of forthcoming Internet devices, such as wireless phones
and Web-connected stereo system components.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually moves the player to become a central entertainment
manager, not only for your streaming media but your MP3 files, your
CDs, and it really makes porting music from the desktop to other
devices much simpler,'' Gerbrandt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take too much vision to look down the road and see
Real moving into the consumer electronics space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
