<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-ABATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SCIENTISTS WAGER ON THE EXACT NUMBER OF HUMAN GENES  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Playful scientists have given a whole new
meaning to the term ``gene pool.''
</P>
<P>
   At a five-day conference last week on the Human Genome Project,
microbiologists took time out from their headache-inducing lectures
to create the scientific equivalent of an office pool.
</P>
<P>
   The event brought several hundred of the world's brainiest
biologists to Long Island, N.Y.'s Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory,
headquarters of James Watson, who shared a Nobel Prize for the 1953
discovery of the structure of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   At this august gathering, 27-year-old European computer whiz
Ewin Birney walked around with a notebook soliciting opinions on
the hottest topic in DNA research _ just how many genes there are
in the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   The genome is a stretch of 3 billion chemical letters. After 10
years of work, scientists are on the verge of putting together the
entire sequence from one end to the other.
</P>
<P>
   But more than 95 percent of those chemical letters have no
apparent purpose. Only 5 percent of the letters are thought to
encode genes, which are the bodily equivalent of blueprints that
instruct cells how to make the proteins and enzymes that make our
bodies work.
</P>
<P>
   Previously published estimates of the gene count have gone from
35,000 to 150,000, a range that only serves to illustrate
humankind's collective ignorance about the body's basic software.
</P>
<P>
   Birney collected $1 from each of the 228 participants, who
contributed their own best guesses on the final gene count, which
should be hashed out over the next two years. Birney's collection
of estimates ranged from 27,462 to 200,000. Being a scientific
sort, Birney calculated the mean (62,598), the median (53,700) and
posted the distribution curve on the Web
( &LR; www.ensembl.org/genesweep.html &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Francis Collins, director of the National Human Genome Research
Institute in Bethesda, Md., and chief U.S. scientist on the Human
Genome Project, got into the spirit of things.
</P>
<P>
   At his speech closing the conference, Collins proposed that, in
addition to the handsome purse, the winner should get an
autographed, leather-bound version of ``The Double Helix,''
Watson's hilarious book about how he and Francis Crick defied
authority and hoodwinked colleagues in order to beat famed American
scientist Linus Pauling to the finding that transformed biology.
</P>
<P>
   Providing that research proceeds on schedule, and scientists
actually agree on the gene count by then, the winner will be
selected at the Cold Spring conference in 2003 _ the 50th
anniversary of the Watson-Crick discovery.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER WATCH: Cancer has become the single largest sector of the
biotechnology industry, and many biotech stocks will rise or fall
this week depending on the research presented at the American
Society of Clinical Oncology meeting in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day event, which began Saturday, gives drug and biotech
firms a chance to share their latest findings with thousands of
oncologists who treat cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 years after President Richard Nixon declared war on
cancer, science may finally see a light at the end of the tunnel.
Although victory still seems distant, patients are living longer
and suffering less, thanks to new treatments that target cancer
cells more directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that things going through clinical trials today
will cut the death rate in half within five years,'' said Jim
McCamant, editor of the Medical Technology Stock Letter in
Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies presenting research will be Matrix
Pharmaceutical of Fremont, Calif., which is in the final stage of
testing a new chemotherapy agent. Instead of being administered
intravenously and roaming the blood stream, causing hair loss and
other side effects, Matrix's IntraDose is injected into a tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Matrix hopes this will confine the cancer-fighting effects to
the diseased tissues. This morning, the company will take the wraps
off a scientific study that will show whether this is true.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech Inc. will use the conference to unveil the results of
three studies that test a new cancer-fighting theory called
anti-angiogenesis.
</P>
<P>
   Angiogenesis is the term for blood vessel formation, and the
Genentech experiment is meant to show whether it is possible to
slow tumor growth by restricting new blood vessel formation.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Genentech released findings from a Phase II study
suggesting that its anti-angiogenesis agent lengthened the life
span of patients with advanced colorectal cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The trial tested 104 patients divided into three groups. One
group received chemotherapy alone. The other two groups received
chemo plus a low or a high dose of the anti-angiogenesis drug.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the low-dose drug plus chemo seemed most
effective. Of the 35 patients in that group, more than half were
still alive after 17.3 months. Of the 36 patients in the chemo-only
cohort, the median survival rate was just 13.8 months. The 33
patients who got the high dose of the Genentech drug fell in
between, with a 16.1 median month survival rate.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Emily Bergsland, an oncologist at the University of
California at San Francisco who worked on the colorectal study,
said the study marks ``the first time an agent designed to block
blood vessel growth has proven effective in a random clinical
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be even greater interest in the data Genentech will
present tomorrow from a study of the same anti-angiogenic compound
used against lung cancer. Of the 67 patients enrolled in the lung
cancer study, six had such severe blood-coughing episodes that four
actually died. So oncologists will likely focus on the safety of
anti-angiogenesis in lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   THE SANTA CLAUSE: Speaking of Genentech, the South San
Francisco, Calif., firm held an uneventful annual meeting last
week. I showed up just to meet Franz Humer, chief executive of
Roche, the Swiss drug firm that owns 59 percent of Genentech. We
exchanged pleasantries during a brief conversation as Humer exited
the public gathering on his way to the private board meeting that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   The only meaningful business conducted during the open session
was the ratification of the new six-member board of directors that
includes Humer and another Roche executive, Jonathan Knowles, in
addition to two Genentech old-timers _ CEO Art Levinson and company
co-founder Herb Boyer _ plus two outside board members.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-votes were overwhelming for all six candidates, but
there was noticeably less enthusiasm for the two men from Roche.
The other four board members registered 245 million yeas, to a
couple of hundred thousand nays. Humer and Knowles got a lower
positive vote total and far more ``votes withheld'' _ 4.8 million
and 6.9 million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   A mere blip, insisted Genentech public relations, not even worth
mention. Perhaps, but there seems to be a molecule or two of
resentment out there in Genentech-land against the company's Swiss
overlords.
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley resident Herb Solomon, a longtime Genentech
shareholder, e-mailed me to complain that Roche was dumping so many
Genentech shares onto the market that it was depressing the stock
price. ``Their corporate greed seems to know no bounds,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But in a follow-up note, Solomon saw the bright side. Last year,
the U.S. government forced Roche to pay a $500 million penalty for
fixing vitamin prices. The sale of Genentech stock, which has
netted Roche over $5 billion dollars, has allowed the Swiss firm to
pay its ``price fixing almost 10 times over,'' Solomon quipped.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
