<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DSL-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DSL COMPETITION EXPECTED TO HEAT UP  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Flashcom touts its superfast Internet service
with a cartoon turtle, happily sporting aviator's glasses and a
rocket strapped to its back.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, EarthLink, Telocity and more than a dozen other
rivals also are peddling digital-subscriber lines, which offer
speedy access to the Net over telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Taback didn't have a hard decision when he ordered
DSL three months ago. He picked Pacific Bell, th local phone
company. It was the only name he knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have probably heard some ads and read some ads,'' said
Taback, an information systems consultant from Berkeley, Calif.,
``but none of the names (of the other DSL providers) has stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pacific Bell has been steamrolling the competition in
the race to offer DSL to Bay Area consumers, despite complaints
about poor customer service, installation glitches and slow e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell has installed roughly 100,000 lines to residential
customers in California as of March 31 _ with probably more than
50,000 in the Bay Area alone. That's more than the largest
independent DSL providers have installed nationwide combined.
</P>
<P>
   But Yankee Group analyst Fritz McCormick said rivals could soon
become more aggressive because of something called ``line
sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Pac Bell competitors usually have to install a
separate phone line for DSL, which costs more and is more
cumbersome to set up, discouraging them from signing up consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell, by contrast, can simply use the line already used for
voice calls for little extra cost. But starting June 6, the Federal
Communications Commission has ordered local phone companies to let
DSL competitors piggyback on the lines as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Line sharing will have a terrific effect'' on competition,
McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   But rivals have a lot of catching up to do. Less than a third of
consumers even know there are alternatives to the Baby Bell,
according to national research collected by Northpoint
Communications, a San Francisco DSL wholesale supplier.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Pacific Bell talks about competition, it normally
points to AT&AMP;T, which offers equally fast Internet access over
cable television lines for roughly the same price _ $40 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell spokesman Shawn Dainas said the company believes it has
a narrow lead over AT&AMP;T in the Bay Area. AT&AMP;T, which has well over
50,000 local cable modem customers, isn't sure who is ahead. ``It's
a horse race, that's for sure,'' said spokesman Andrew Johnson.
Neither company will divulge specific figures.
</P>
<P>
   But cable modem service isn't available in many cities,
including Oakland, San Jose and nearly all of San Francisco _
except the Bernal Heights neighborhood. Johnson says it will take
three years to upgrade the coaxial cable lines throughout the
cities. And even where AT&AMP;T says it covers the entire city, like
Berkeley, the company often cannot serve specific homes or
apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, DSL isn't available everywhere either, largely
because it works a short distance from a central switching office,
normally 3 miles.
</P>
<P>
   But since DSL is available in many places where cable isn't,
where are all the other DSL companies?
</P>
<P>
   Experts cite three reasons for Pac Bell's domination:
</P>
<P>
   -- Bigger brand. Think Pacific Bell Park. Think 8.5 million
residential phone customers. Plus, Pac Bell is spending millions
specifically promoting DSL, running radio and TV commercials, print
ads, employing telemarketing and inserting leaflets in local phone
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Even Flashcom's rocket turtle can't keep up. Most DSL providers,
including Telocity and Flashcom, are tiny upstarts with limited
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   And Internet behemoths have done little to promote DSL. America
Online, which carpet-bombed America with computer disks and CD-ROMs
to build a base of 22 million dial-up customers, has signed up only
a few thousand DSL customers. Spokeswoman Marta Grutka said the
company has done only limited telemarketing and online promotion to
get its feet wet before marketing the service more aggressively.
``We don't want to give our users a bad experience,'' Grutka said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rivals have focused on the corporate market. The three
largest DSL wholesalers, Northpoint, Covad Communications and
Rhythms NetConnections, all estimate that between 80 and 85 percent
of their customers are nonresidential. (Wholesalers provide DSL
service to Internet service provides like Flashcom, Telocity and
others.) Covad Vice President Rich Wong said the company targeted
business customers first because they ``generate higher revenues
and profit margins.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Local phone companies have a big advantage. Pac Bell already
owns the phone lines, so it can charge its Internet arm nothing or
a nominal fee to use them for DSL.
</P>
<P>
   But Pac Bell rivals have traditionally had to install a second
phone line, and then pay $22 per month just to use the copper wires
between the home and the telephone switching office.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rhythms estimates it must spend $200 to $300 more
on installation costs because it has to dispatch technicians to
install the second line.
</P>
<P>
   The extra costs are so steep that Northpoint has mostly avoided
the consumer market because it couldn't make money selling lines
for $40 per month, said Northpoint CEO Liz Fetter. ``We are very
much loath to go beyond our costs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals also accuse Pac Bell of sabotaging their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Covad executives say the company usually has to wait several
weeks, and sometimes longer than a month, for access to a phone
line that should be available in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   An arbitration board just ordered Pac Bell to pay a $27 million
fine last week for dragging its feet providing lines and space in
its offices for Covad equipment. Pac Bell vowed to appeal and said
the judgment was based on old complaints that it has since
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Pac Bell competitors say they'll soon be on a more
even playing field when line sharing begins next month.
</P>
<P>
   How significant is line sharing? A month after the FCC ordered
it to begin this summer, Rhythms announced plans to target
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fundamentally changed the economics of DSL,'' said Mike
Calabrese, Rhythms' vice president of product management. ``We
wanted to position ourselves in the marketplace to be ready to go
when it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Northpoint has teamed up with Radio Shack and MSN,
Microsoft's giant Internet service, to offer DSL to consumers this
summer, after line sharing begins.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Northpoint and Rhythms' costs are coming down. Late
last year, the California Public Utilities Commission slashed the
price of leasing a line for DSL to between $11 and $16. And with
line sharing, a PUC judge tentatively ruled this month that Pac
Bell rivals should be able to share a voice line for less than $6.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the PUC cut the price rivals must pay Pac Bell to
ready a new line to about $40 from $88. It could be lowered
further.
</P>
<P>
   Now DSL competitors are pushing for even lower prices. Rhythms
just signed agreements with Bell Atlantic and US West to rent the
lines for free, because those phone companies do not charge their
Internet operations extra to use the lines for DSL.
</P>
<P>
   They want Pac Bell to do the same. (Pac Bell argues that since
it invested the money to install and maintain the phone lines, it's
absurd to hand it over to competitors for free.)
</P>
<P>
   Rhythms and others also say line sharing will make installation
faster and easier for consumers, who often gripe about having to
wait for DSL technicians who sometimes show up late or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Pac Bell started letting customers in the Bay Area
install DSL themselves. Now with line sharing, rivals say they will
be able to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   And as the playing field becomes more even, several Pac Bell
competitors say they plan to market DSL lines more aggressively to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Cupertino, Calif.'s Telocity, for instance, just started service
in the Bay Area last month and has started using radio and direct
mail to recruit customers. Covad has initiated a $40 million
national ad campaign with its partners.
</P>
<P>
   The added competition could help consumers by keeping prices
down and putting pressure on Pac Bell to improve its service.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell already says it is hiring hundreds more technicians and
support staff, beefing up its computers and going toward
self-installation to help customers. ``We know that customers have
a choice,'' spokesman John Britton said recently.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, other DSL companies have also sparked complaints.
</P>
<P>
   While Pac Bell rates among the worst DSL companies, according to
customer reviews collected on  &LR; www.dslreports.com &LR; , Flashcom, the
company with the happy turtle, is listed as dead last. Several
other DSL companies targeting local consumers are also rated worse
than Pac Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's early in the race, analysts say. Only about 3
percent of Americans have either cable modem service or DSL today.
Cahners In-Stat predicts the number will soar to roughly half by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Pac Bell ahead? I guess,'' said Covad's Wong. ``But we are
running hard on their tail.''
</P>
<P>
   But others are betting Pac Bell and other local phone companies
will retain their lead. Telocity executive Joe Harris likens it to
the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two decades after Ma Bell was busted up, AT&AMP;T still
claims 58 percent of the market. But rivals like Sprint and MCI
have become telecommunications giants. And countless smaller
companies have found a niche.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt the (local phone companies) are going to have a large
share of the DSL market,'' said Harris, Telocity's senior director
of market development. ``But that doesn't mean there's nothing for
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
