<SLUG> BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH 21: IN PURSUIT OF EVER-SMALLER CIRCUITS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000. The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some of the smartest people in the technology
world are in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not talking about the cops who hunt for pedophiles on AOL or
the D.A.s chasing scam artists on eBay. I'm referring to the
scientists and engineers who enforce Moore's Law, the principle
that the number of transistors that can be packed into a given area
of silicon doubles every 18 to 24 months. It's the technical basis
for the exponential increases in processing power and memory
capacity that have made high tech as we know it possible.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Moore's Law isn't really a law at all, in the
jurisprudential or even the scientific sense. It's simply an
empirical observation _ more like Murphy's or Parkinson's laws than
Ohm's or Boyle's _ first formulated 35 years ago by Intel
co-founder Gordon Moore as he traced the early history of memory
chips.
</P>
<P>
   It's turned out to be an amazingly accurate predictor of
progress since then (see the chart at  &LR; www.intel.com/intel/museum &LR; 
 &LR; /25anniv/hof/moore.htm &LR; ). But compliance with this law doesn't
just happen _ it has always required intense effort and sustained
innovation, not to mention billions of dollars in investment for
R&AMP;D and capital equipment.
</P>
<P>
   That's all the more true as the industry looks to the future.
Some features on today's state-of-the-art chips are only .18 of a
micron wide _ about one-500th the thickness of a human hair. Next
year, .13-micron equipment will go into production, then .1 micron.
</P>
<P>
   By 2005, to keep up with Moore's Law, the industry will have to
be capable of putting features on chips that measure only .07
micron, or 70 nanometers. (A micron is a millionth of a meter; a
nanometer, which for obvious reasons will soon be the standard unit
of measure in this context, is one-billionth of a meter.) And
before the end of the decade, when microprocessors should be
operating at clock speeds somewhere between 5 and 10 gigahertz, the
leading edge will be down to 30 nanometers.
</P>
<P>
   You don't learn to make circuits that small just by parroting
Moore's dictum. Keeping pace depends on a host of breakthroughs not
just in electronics, but also in optical and mechanical
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the industry needs new lithographic technology.
Circuits are etched on chips by shining light through a mask _
essentially, a negative _ at photosensitive material coating the
chip. The industry does that now with something called ``deep
ultraviolet'' (DUV) light, which is beamed through a sequence of
lenses that reduce its image by a factor of four.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the wavelength of DUV, even after optical
reduction, is simply too big to draw circuits as minuscule as will
be needed by mid-decade. So several years ago, the industry
embarked on a search for an NGL _ ``next-generation lithography.''
Companies and trade groups around the world have been exploring and
debating a variety of technologies.
</P>
<P>
   That assessment process is still going on. IBM and Nikon are
promoting a solution called electron-projection lithography. By
most accounts, though, a technology called extreme ultraviolet
(EUV), originally considered a dark horse, has emerged as the clear
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Intel seems to be EUV's chief proponent, but rivals Advanced
Micro Devices and Motorola joined Intel in forming a consortium to
pursue it way back in 1987. This spring, Micron Technology and
Infineon, formerly the semiconductor division of German giant
Siemens, also signed on, and others are expected to enlist soon.
</P>
<P>
   Because several of the U.S. Department of Energy's national labs
in the Bay Area _ Sandia, Lawrence Livermore and Lawrence Berkeley
_ had already done preliminary research on the technology, the
industry consortium turned to them, agreeing to provide 100 percent
of the funding for a multiyear R&AMP;D program. The three labs in turn
decided to form a new entity to run the program; they call it the
Virtual National Lab.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the consortium and the virtual lab held a
briefing on their progress. I got there a little late, having been
delayed by some low-tech troubles (my car caught fire and burned to
the bare metal along Interstate 580!), but I managed to catch most
of the presentations and get a look at some of the prototype
machinery the labs are developing.
</P>
<P>
   While the leaders of the effort focused, understandably, on the
progress they've made, what impressed me most was the challenges
they face. In effect, as they put it, what they're trying to do is
equivalent to etching a quarter on the surface of the Earth from a
space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve such resolution, the equipment has to be almost
totally isolated from vibration. And EUV isn't exactly easy to work
with: Because it's absorbed by air, the lithography process has to
occur in a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   And because EUV's wavelength is so narrow, it won't work with
lenses; to focus and reduce it, lab engineers, building on work
done earlier at Stanford, are developing reflective coatings that
are only 12 to 15 atoms thick and flat to less than the thickness
of a single atom.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they say they're well on their way. They're now building
an ``alpha tool'' _ a prototype EUV lithography machine _ which
they expect to complete next year. A follow-up beta machine is
scheduled for 2003 or 2004. Commercial semiconductor equipment
companies will have access to the prototypes, so they can learn to
build their own versions.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, such machines will go into production in 2005 or 2006
_ and Moore's Law will stay on the books for at least another few
years.
</P>
<P>
   HUNT FOR ET _ ON PC AND MAC: Now that your average desktop
computer has more processing power than whole corporations and
governments did just a few decades ago, and most of that horsepower
sits idle most of the day, wouldn't it be nice if we could put it
to some constructive use _ something more useful than displaying
flying toasters or Windows logos?
</P>
<P>
   Several nonprofit groups are attempting to take advantage of
that opportunity by using extra cycles on ordinary computers to
take on tasks that would otherwise require expensive supercomputer
time.
</P>
<P>
   I've tried several of these ``distributed computing'' schemes,
all of which work roughly the same way: You go to the project's Web
site, sign up and download a chunk of data and a small application
that processes it. The programs are set up to kick in when your
system has been idle for a specified interval; as soon as you move
your mouse or tap a key, they get out of the way. When the program
has finished processing one chunk of data, it sends its results
back to the Web site and grabs another block of data.
</P>
<P>
   These programs also share another attribute: extreme nerdiness.
One, called PiHex, is currently calculating the quadrillionth bit
of Pi, according to its Web site ( &LR; www.cecm.sfu.ca/pr4ojects/pihex &LR; 
 &LR; /pihex.html &LR; ). Another, which calls itself Distributed.net
( &LR; www.distributed.net &LR; ), has run a variety of projects, but mostly
focuses on cracking encryption schemes. (It says its participants'
computers add up to the equivalent of more than 160,000
266-megahertz Pentium II PCs working 24 hours a day, 7 days a week,
365 days a year.)
</P>
<P>
   The best-known distributed-computing initiative, however, is
SETIathome, which recently enlisted its 2 millionth participant.
Based at the University of California at Berkeley, the project
invites users to help analyze data collected by a large radio
telescope in Arecibo, Puerto Rico, in hopes of finding hints of
intelligent life elsewhere in the universe. (The raw data is first
snail-mailed, on tape, from Puerto Rico to Berkeley, according to
the project's Web site,  &LR; setiathome.ssl.berkeley.edu &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   None of these goals is very high on my personal priority list,
but for want of something better I've recently loaded the latest
version of the SETIathome software on my home machines.
</P>
<P>
   No sign of extraterrestrial life yet, but the effort has
generated some new fuel to throw on an everlasting fire _ the
PC-versus-Mac debate. After 48 hours of work time, my 450-megahertz
Power Mac G4 had completed eight full SETIathome ``work units''
plus 44.5 percent of another. In the same time, a Hewlett-Packard
Pavilion 1G, powered by a 1-gigahertz Intel Pentium III, finished
only five units plus 27.6 percent of another.
</P>
<P>
   Between SETI searches, I've also been doing additional Adobe
Photoshop performance testing on the two machines, and on a
500-megahertz G4 Apple just lent to me, as a follow-up to a sidebar
on the subject I did last month. The results are interesting, and
they don't quite match my original findings, but I'll have to save
the details for another week.
</P>
<P>
   DUMB MISTAKES DEPARTMENT: In last week's column, I referred to
the new laser chips developed by Novalux as ``silicon lasers.''
That's wrong _ they're semiconductors, all right, but they're made
of gallium arsenide, not silicon. In addition, I jumped the gun in
suggesting that Novalux will be in production by the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company says, its Sunnyvale, Calif., fab will go
into full operation this month, but for now it'll be producing only
beta-test chips. Testing probably won't be complete until around
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
