<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A FAST START BY LAZIO 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, May 22:
</P>
<P>
   With a quick announcement of his candidacy, rapid-fire attacks
on Hillary Rodham Clinton and a sprint across New York state on
Sunday, Rep. Rick Lazio has gotten off to an energetic start in his
race for the Senate. All but anointed for the Republican
nomination, he has not left any time for Republican leaders to
wring their hands over Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's withdrawal. Five
months before the election, the little-known Long Island
congressman must be rated the underdog. But Clinton faces a
challenge in having to adjust to his intensity, and to his strong
drive toward establishing his stature as a credible candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton should also expect an effort to revive the issue of her
not being from New York. By campaigning hard upstate while Giuliani
stayed home, she has overcome some skepticism but may find that
voters outside New York City will see Lazio as a more comfortable
figure than the mayor. Common sense suggests the GOP will find the
money to help Lazio close the gap in the polls. For all the
freshness of the race, there was a certain familiarity to its
themes and politics. Lazio describes himself as a centrist, but in
1995 he voted fairly regularly with Speaker Newt Gingrich in the
budget battles against President Clinton. Mrs. Clinton is certain
to accelerate her attacks on his record of deep cuts in education,
Medicaid, Medicare and environmental programs. On the talk-show
circuit yesterday, Lazio tried to dismiss these actions as not
relevant, but his record will surely be thrown back at him.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking on Sunday of repairing New York's roads and
empowering its average citizens, Lazio was casting himself in the
Republican populist mold of his fellow Long Islander, Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato. But he could draw fire because of his prodigious record of
fund-raising among those interests that have business before him on
the Commerce and Banking Committees.
</P>
<P>
   The other familiar feature to the race is its reliance on the
traditional building blocks for electoral success in New York.
Against Giuliani, who was likely to get at least a third of the
vote in traditionally Democratic New York City, Clinton was under
tremendous pressure to build up support in traditional Republican
areas of the suburbs and upstate. She can now probably count on
winning the city at least three to one and may not have to do as
well outside it. Upstate, Clinton has presented herself as a kind
of Daughter of the Great Lakes and has made great inroads,
according to opinion polls. Ironically, Giuliani has always had his
greatest popularity in the New York suburbs, where Lazio should
also do his best.
</P>
<P>
   Although New York and the nation relished a Giuliani-Clinton
showdown, the focus on the mayor's health and personal life had, in
a curious way, diverted attention from the electoral competition.
Lazio's weekend blitz seemed likely to reignite voter interest in a
race that will still be one of the most watched in the country. Its
new dynamics will test Lazio's ability to adjust to a broader arena
and test Clinton's resilience and flexibility. New Yorkers are
fortunate to still have a lively contest of issues, ideas and
personalities.
</P>
</TEXT>
