<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO CAMPAIGN TRIES TO MAKE UP FOR LOST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick A. Lazio raced through the first half
of a two-day Senate campaign fly-around Sunday, scrambling to
present himself to voters here and in Rochester, Syracuse and
Binghamton as a viable statewide alternative to his richly funded
and well-traveled opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But less than 48 hours after Mayor Rudolph Giuliani withdrew
from the race because of his prostate cancer, Lazio had already
accomplished two things the mayor had never done: He had officially
announced his candidacy, and he had embarked on an extensive,
multi-city upstate tour with his wife and two young daughters that
is to take him to Elmira, Watertown, Utica, Albany and Westchester
County on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio family stayed overnight in the Holiday Inn in Elmira.
In his infrequent trips upstate this year, Giuliani always returned
in the evening to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be here so often, I'm going to be sweating
Buffalo wings,'' Lazio told a modest but lustily cheering crowd in
a terminal of the Buffalo International Airport. Moments before, he
had stepped off a seven-seat, two-engine jet, which was hastily
chartered for the trip. ``This campaign has been a 40-hour
miracle,'' said Lazio's freshly hired political consultant, Mike
Murphy, who three months ago was advising Sen. John McCain on the
``Straight Talk Express.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio then introduced his wife, Patricia, and daughters Molly
Ann, 7, and Kelsey, 6, to the crowd. ``We're here because we're a
family operation, because we believe in family values,'' Lazio
said. It was a pointed contrast to Giuliani, who never once
campaigned in this race with his family and who announced this
month that he had a ``very good'' female friend and was seeking a
separation from his wife, Donna Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   At every stop, Lazio presented himself as the wholesome,
earnest, fresh-faced stand-in, without the irritability of the old
Giuliani or the philosophical soul-searching of the new. What he
lacked in star quality or moody complexity, he made up for in
energy. Even before he began his four-city upstate swing about
noon, Lazio gave a commencement speech on Long Island and
interviews to six morning news programs in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Lazio said he would accept the
Independence Party endorsement, even if Pat Buchanan was at the top
of the ticket. Both Clinton and Giuliani, at varying times, have
called Buchanan anti-Semitic and divisive.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's first upstate stop was Buffalo, where he was happily
greeted by the very same party leaders who only three weeks ago had
rallied around Giuliani on his first upstate trip since announcing
he had prostate cancer. For anyone who had been to both events, the
sudden change in candidates was disorienting, like watching a play
where the lead had been switched. But the overriding reaction of
party leaders, who had agonized while the mayor agonized, was
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``As every day went by and there was no decision, I thought he
was staying in,'' Robert E. Davis, the Erie County Republican
chairman, said of Giuliani. ``I'm glad it's over; I'm glad that the
decision was made.'' Although Lazio is a virtual unknown outside
his Suffolk County home base, Davis added, he is confident that
that will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a couple of weeks, he's going to be pretty close to
being a household name,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   At each stop Sunday, Lazio introduced himself to New Yorkers,
without the aid of a Clintonesque biographical video, as ``the son
of a guy who came back from World War II without a dime in his
pocket.'' His parents' first date, he told the crowd, was at Ebbets
Field, and his father built a business from scratch by borrowing
$700. Over and over, Lazio described himself as ``a home-grown''
boy, the kind who ``never needed an exploratory committee to find
western New York.''
</P>
<P>
   But as his last-minute tour made clear, Lazio faces enormous
challenges upstate _ territory that traditionally should be his
against a Democrat, but where Clinton was recently running even
with Giuliani in several polls. For nearly a year, Clinton has
campaigned extensively upstate, and seems to genuinely like it
here. Recently she proudly told reporters accompanying her one
early morning to see a waterfall in Wyoming County: ``You travel
with me, and you see New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also has $9 million in the bank compared with Lazio's
$3.5 million. One big question is whether he will be able to
harvest campaign contributions as prodigiously as Giuliani; the
mayor's advisers say his campaign was grossing $1 million a week
before he announced he had prostate cancer. (After the
announcement, the advisers say, the gross weekly contributions were
$600,000 to $750,000.)
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said repeatedly Sunday that he was up to the challenge.
``I know this is not just going to come to me,'' he told the crowd
in Buffalo. ``I know I have to earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   At each stop, Lazio presented himself as a moderate, despite his
alliance with Newt Gingrich, the former speaker of the House. He
said that he favored abortion rights but was against a form of
late-term abortion that opponents call ``partial birth.'' He also
said that he was in favor of ``reasonable measures to support the
rights of sportsmen,'' meaning that he was against gun
registration.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also frequently attacked Clinton, echoing the language of
his speech announcing his candidacy on Saturday. He said that she
is ``on the far left-wing of the Democratic Party,'' that she is
``no more a New Democrat than she is a New Yorker'' and that ``I
can't call on Air Force One whenever I need a ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton responded that ``I was a little disappointed yesterday
that my latest opponent has already started hurling insults instead
of what we can do to improve the lives of New Yorkers.'' Howard
Wolfson, Clinton's press secretary, added that ``it sounds like the
Rick Lazio statewide insult tour, day two.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gov. George Pataki nor the state Republican Party
chairman, William D. Powers, accompanied Lazio across the state
Sunday, but Lazio did take a call from the governor during his stop
in Buffalo. As a practical matter, there was no room on the plane.
Lazio and his family took up four seats, Murphy took a fifth, and a
press aide and a staff aide took up the remaining two.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said that the campaign's biggest short-term challenge is
``mechanically, we're just trying to deal with the explosive growth
of the campaign.'' He added that Lazio ``knows he's the underdog,
he knows he's going to be outspent, he knows he's going to be
behind for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel A. Giambra, the Erie County executive, said that he is
excited about Lazio, and that even though the candidate does not
have the ``star quality'' of Giuliani, he is the person ``who can
take on the 800-pound gorilla.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
