<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-21 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ONCE AND FOR ALL, THE HEAT FALLS  

</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Sunday was the final day in a battle of cliches. Pat
Riley, emperor and coach of the Miami Heat, exhorted his team with
``once and for all.'' After being eliminated by these Knicks the
previous two seasons, Miami could break this spell once and for
all. Jeff Van Gundy, the Knicks' coaching prince-in-waiting,
challenged his team to get to the ``ultimate game.'' Get the ball
and get to the ultimate game, Game 7
</P>
<P>
   Once and for all. The ultimate game. Somehow in the alchemy of
great competition, the teams came close to achieving their goals:
the Knicks got to their ultimate game; Miami very nearly exorcised
that New York ghost. In the end, Miami lost, 83-82, and its season
was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' victory was so enthralling that even Van Gundy, the
latter-day Lonesome George Gobel, could not hide his satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so proud of what this team has accomplished,'' Van Gundy
said. ``To come in here and win three times is something special.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Van Gundy's ultimate game; in a basketball sense, it
was Riley's most disastrous hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is tough to take,'' Riley said. ``This is a familiar
feeling; I didn't think it would happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   From start to finish in these Eastern Conference semifinals,
each game was like a civil war for the teams, who are part of the
same basketball nation: Riley, the former coach of the Knicks, who
pulled the franchise from the ashes and then left in an ugly
dispute; Van Gundy, who was once Riley's assistant and took over,
building a team in Riley's general image. Riley even has Van
Gundy's younger brother, Stan, on his bench.
</P>
<P>
   After yesterday's loss, Riley appeared with face reddened and
eyes downcast, though Miami brought this on itself. On Friday, the
Heat squandered an 18-point lead and lost. Yesterday's loss was a
slow roast.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat started so strong, with Alonzo Mourning dominating and
Tim Hardaway showing flashes of his old brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   But this game had such rapidly changing currents. The Heat led
by 9 points at the end of the first quarter; by intermission
Latrell Sprewell had caught fire and ignited a push that gave the
Knicks the lead. The currents continued to change until Miami was
knocked out of the playoffs by the Knicks for the third consecutive
year.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was as compassionate as an opponent could be without
conceding the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for them,'' he said. ``I want to win, but I feel for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy challenged his team the last two weeks as he watched
the Knicks get pushed around, outhustled, beaten, it seemed, to
every loose ball. The Heat and Knicks went about this second-round
series in peekaboo fashion: lose a game, win a game; lose a game,
win a game; lose a game, win a game.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday he challenged the Knicks to have the guts to play for
the ultimate game, Game 7. They did, and yesterday the Knicks
pulled off a harrowing victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell surged in the second quarter and Chris Childs in the
fourth, and Ewing, playing his second dominating game in less than
48 hours, floored the Heat with a crushing dunk. He was the
exclamation point on a whip-around series of passes that went from
Childs to Sprewell to Larry Johnson to Ewing, who caught, stepped
and dunked the Heat out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   All the loose balls the Knicks lost, they got; the rebounds that
got away, they grabbed. Where before they had unwittingly fallen
into the Heat's defensive trap, yesterday the Knicks attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Someone said this was the greatest early-round series of all
time. Who knows? Better than those knockdown, drag-out series with
Baltimore in 1970 when the Knicks won, 4-3? Better than the 1971
series with Baltimore that they lost, 4-3?
</P>
<P>
   All Pat Riley knew was that this was the best one he had been
involved with, and he has been a coach and a player in the National
Basketball Association for almost 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in 13 world championships finals and I've never been
part of a finals that's had as much intensity and as much effort,
as much caring, as much everything as something prior to getting to
the finals,'' he said. ``You have to understand that this was a
very unique matchup. One team just ran out of clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley complained that the game had been determined by the
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been part of a game when officials were deciding
games on perimeter fouls,'' he said. ``It's hard for a team to
take. It just is.'' He said they were not shooting fouls, ``just
touch fouls and bailout fouls.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult, Riley said, ``for a team that has worked hard to
lose that way. I'd rather lose on what happened with Patrick with a
blatant dunk.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Heat made just 11 of 21 foul shots; the Knicks were 28
of 31. ``You got to step up and knock those down,'' Riley
conceded.''
</P>
<P>
   A third knockout loss to the Knicks made it that much worse.
``There's not much more we can learn from it,'' Riley said,
``because we've been here already a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   The future is just beginning for Van Gundy. Last year he played
with a team whose makeup was not necessarily to his liking, in a
truncated season, and reached the NBA. finals. This team, this
style is Van Gundy's from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Now for all the talk beforehand, the Knicks have to forget this
game and move on to Indiana. For one day, however, the Knicks did
play an ultimate game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
