<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLAZERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS AREN'T CONVINCED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When is a 15-point Lakers victory not convincing?
</P>
<P>
   When you're the Portland Trail Blazers, you were on the wrong
end of that 109-94 score, and you've had all night to sort out the
excuses - Rasheed Wallace's ejection and the Lakers' unconscious
shooting though not the Blazers' questionable hack-a-Shaq tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning the Blazers awoke, went back to Staples Center to
practice, and sounded confident of taking away the Lakers'
home-court advantage by winning Game 2 of the NBA Western
Conference Finals tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a must-win, but it's a win that we want,'' guard
Damon Stoudamire said. ``We feel we can play with those guys. We
feel we just ran into a team (Saturday) that had about 10 guys get
hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoudamire thought he knew how to prevent a recurrence of the
second-quarter burst in which the Lakers made five 3-pointers to
expand a 30-28 lead to 52-30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were (the kind of uncontested) shots you get when you're
playing shooting games before practice. If we can get a hand in
their face, it can be different,'' Stoudamire said. ``I just think
Robert Horry, Rick Fox, those kind of players, if you give them
those shots, you give them a little confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers (those kind of players) plan some changes
tonight. Among the obvious:
</P>
<P>
   -Tighten their defensive rotations.
</P>
<P>
   -Keep Wallace in the game. The power forward earned his second
technical foul with 6:43 to play in the third quarter, having
scored 11 points in 16 minutes, after defying referee Ron
Garretson's order not to ``stare'' at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the answer to it, but I do know the result I'd
like, I'd like Rasheed to stay on the court,'' Blazers coach Mike
Dunleavy said, while Wallace was refusing interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy ridiculed Garretson's charge, picked up by an NBC
microphone, that Wallace was ``trying to intimidate me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the officials got intimidated,'' the coach said.
``They're the ones who have all the power. ... I think you (a
referee) need to have a little more leeway in certain situations,
and I think yesterday was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq's probably not going to get thrown out of a game for
staring, and Shaquille O'Neal is a lot more intimidating than
Rasheed Wallace, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stoudamire: ``He's so emotional, that's how he plays the
game. He's just got to not let the refs beat him. Because if the
refs don't, the Lakers don't have anyone who can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   -Get Arvydas Sabonis involved early. The center wasn't involved
at all in Game 1, totaling 0 points and 1 rebound in 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As for the adjustment fans everywhere would like to see: No, the
Blazers don't intend to abandon their strategy of fouling the weak
free-throw-shooting O'Neal in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was ugly Saturday, and it didn't help the Blazers, who
trailed by double figures before and after. Fouled 12 times in the
closing 5 minutes, O'Neal sank 12 of 24 free throws, right on his
season stats.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's called for, we'll do it,'' Dunleavy said.
``Basically it's somewhat of a high-percentage play. ... You try
for 2 (points) for (the Lakers') 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until (O'Neal) shows he can make free throws, it's going to
continue to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
