<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NRA-NYTT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TAKING ON THE NRA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, May 22:
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association's annual convention over the
weekend in Charlotte, N.C., drew nowhere near the massive crowd
that took part in last week's Million Mom March for more stringent
gun control laws. But the NRA's power has never depended on
rallying vast numbers of people or even favorable opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the mothers' march itself was largely an expression of
frustration over the NRA's ability to block gun control in Congress
and the state legislatures even in the face of surveys showing that
many more Americans endorse gun control than oppose it _ as well as
the depressingly frequent outbreaks of gunfire in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control leaders are now considering how best to channel the
energy of the Mother's Day event into a sustained grass-roots
political movement. Their first order of business is to focus on
why their opponents are so successful. The NRA's dominance rests
mainly on intensity and intimidation. It says it has 3.6 million
dues-paying members, a figure seven times larger than the
contributors list of the leading gun control advocacy group,
Handgun Control Inc. More important is the NRA's relatively small
core of super-dedicated members, who can be relied upon to blanket
Congress with letters, phone calls and e-mail on a moment's notice,
making it appear that the pro-gun constituency is larger than it
really is.
</P>
<P>
   To reinforce the pressure on Congress, the NRA raises millions
of dollars that it then spreads around as campaign contributions to
its loyal supporters. It also has a long track record of punishing
those who dare deviate from the NRA line by making direct donations
to their opponents, and by running ``issue ads'' attacking them _
sometimes disguising the NRA's sponsorship by raising an issue
other than gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA also employs a large number of lobbyists who use their
knowledge of how laws are written and their close ties to key
legislators to water down popular gun control proposals when
outright opposition would be politically impossible. Promoting
weaker alternatives, and hiding behind calls for stricter
enforcement of existing laws _ something everybody supports _ the
NRA has succeeded in tying up the modest gun control package that
passed the Senate after the Columbine High School massacre last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the gun control side, NRA leaders have a
tendency to say offensive things that undermine their
organizational and monetary advantages. An example was the
suggestion in March by the group's executive vice president, Wayne
LaPierre, that President Clinton was ``willing to accept a certain
level of killing to further his political agenda.'' The recent
boast by the NRA's first vice president, Kayne Robinson, that the
NRA would have an office in George W. Bush's White House was not a
whole lot smarter.
</P>
<P>
   The gun control movement needs to be ready to take advantage of
these flubs _ much as Handgun Control recently did by running a
television commercial publicizing Robinson's indiscreet bragging.
But that is obviously not enough. For too long, the NRA has gotten
away with shoddy arguments unsupported by empirical evidence, like
the assertion that keeping a loaded handgun handy to use against a
possible intruder makes homes safer when, in fact, the opposite is
true.
</P>
<P>
   If it is to succeed, the gun control movement must be prepared
to step up its own public education efforts and to counteract the
NRA's lobbying efforts. That, in turn, means raising more money and
building a professional staff. But mostly it means putting pressure
on lawmakers using the movement's best asset _ the huge
constituency of voters in districts all around the country,
including a large number of suburban women, who are fed up with
gridlock on gun control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
