<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAST-HYPERMART-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAL-MART'S REMAINING HYPERMART STORE TO BECOME SMALLER
SUPERCENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sam Walton's trip to Kansas City in February
1990 was one of triumph.
</P>
<P>
   The Wal-Mart founder who started his retail empire with a small
store in a small town had come to Kansas City to open his magnum
opus: the Hypermart USA on Hillcrest Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited I can hardly stand it,'' Walton said that day
inside the giant ``mall without walls,'' a concept touted as one
that would change the way Americans shop.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, the experiment is over and Hypermarts are dead.
And a Kansas City councilman may have played a role in knocking off
the final one.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. announced last week that it would spend
$4.9 million to convert Kansas City's Hypermart USA to a Wal-Mart
Supercenter.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly 270,000 square feet, the store was the largest of the
company's four Hypermarts. The others have already been converted
or closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hypermarts were too big and too inconvenient for customers,''
said Wal-Mart spokesman Nef Garcia. He could not provide
information on store sales and profits.
</P>
<P>
   As for what Sam Walton, who died in 1992, would think of the
demise, Garcia speculated, ``I think he would be proud that we
responded to what our customers wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The hypermarket concept, which sells practically every consumer
product short of cars and major appliances, was more of a European
style of retail.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Wal-Mart, the world's largest retailer, to
abandon the style probably means it will be awhile before Americans
again see such massive stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Wal-Mart can't break into the hypermarket line, I don't
think other retailers would even try,'' said Bruce Van Kleeck, vice
president of retail operations for the National Retail Federation,
a trade association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean Wal-Mart did anything wrong _ they do their
homework. It may mean American shoppers just weren't ready for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an irony, Van Kleeck said: In an effort to be so convenient
as to offer everything under one roof, the Hypermart was
overwhelming to the shopper.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City 6th District Councilman Chuck Eddy put a different
spin on the story.
</P>
<P>
   He said his office received so many complaints about
deteriorating conditions at Hypermart that he pressured Wal-Mart
officials to make improvements at the store.
</P>
<P>
   And, Eddy said, he used leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart wants to build a new store on State Line Road just
north of 135th Street. The project, which requires approval from
Kansas City officials, is opposed by neighbors in that area.
</P>
<P>
   According to Eddy, he told Wal-Mart officials that the
likelihood of getting approval for the new store would be greatly
enhanced if improvements were made at Hypermart, which is east of
Interstate 435 between 87th Street and Bannister Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want you going in there (to the new site) and doing
the same that you did at Hypermart,'' Eddy said he told Wal-Mart
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about Hypermart included trash in the parking lot,
dirty restrooms and overall messy conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very disappointed in the company for letting it get to
that point,'' Eddy said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, the Wal-Mart spokesman, declined to comment on Eddy's
leverage, but did acknowledge that Eddy approached the company with
concerns about conditions at Hypermart. He said the company has
brought in a new manager to oversee the improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation is set to begin in July, Garcia said. Company
officials haven't decided on all the changes, but the plan
generally calls for the store's layout to be similar to other
supercenters, though larger.
</P>
<P>
   The red, white and blue facade will be replaced by the softer
blue shade seen on other Wal-Mart stores.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible Sam Walton wouldn't be surprised at the
changeover. That day a decade ago when he toured the new Hypermart,
he tempered his glee with caution.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City shoppers were not used to buying jeans, garden
fertilizer and a pot roast in one stop. And they certainly weren't
used to a store of more than a quarter-million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The new Hypermart opened with 850 employees and 53 check-out
stands.
</P>
<P>
   Then 71, ailing and the richest man in America, Walton said the
store on Hillcrest would be the last Hypermart for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing his trademark Wal-Mart hat, he said: ``We'll see how
this one goes and then we'll decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart never built another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000521.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1844 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-SHEPARD-FRIENDS-KAN &LR;      05-21 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEPARD-FRIENDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY A STOP ON THE ROAD TO HEALING FOR FRIENDS OF SLAIN GAY
STUDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Alex Trout and Walt Boulden moved to Kansas
City seeking refuge.
</P>
<P>
   They needed time to trudge the emotional path of grieving.
</P>
<P>
   The men were close friends of Matthew Shepard, the 21-year-old
Wyoming college student whose death became a symbol of violence
against gays after he had been pistol-whipped, hung on a rural
fence and left to die in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City was a good place to hunker down and do the healing
I needed to do,'' said Boulden, who has friends in St. Joseph, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The city also is where the two friends have begun to make sense
of a senseless death, to find a positive outcome for their loss.
</P>
<P>
   HELIOS-KC, a project to train police to better deal with gay and
lesbian people, is their answer. The acronym stands for Human
Equality Through Legislation, Innovation, Organization and
Sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   They have finished two-hour sessions with recruits from the
Kansas City, Kan., Police Department and with about 80 workers at
the Johnson County, Kan., Juvenile Detention Center. Other
departments are considering the training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our recruits to be sensitive to all citizens,'' said
Lt. Randall Murphy, director of training for the Kansas City, Kan.,
academy. ``And we have zero tolerance for any kind of same-sex
harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   HELIOS discussed stereotypes of gay people and coached the
recruits on how to differentiate between an assault and domestic
abuse in a homosexual relationship, especially if the people are
not openly gay.
</P>
<P>
   HELIOS' efforts are grass-roots. There is no budget, no staff.
</P>
<P>
   Trout, 23, sandwiches his efforts around work as a hotel clerk.
Boulden, 47, fits in the work between remodeling his 1908 Northeast
home and writing a book.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have no criticism of how police in Wyoming handled the
Shepard case.
</P>
<P>
   It was an incident here that sparked the idea for HELIOS.
</P>
<P>
   Trout was assaulted last June while talking with friends early
one morning in Penn Valley Park. A man grabbed him from his car and
beat him in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Trout reported the attack but said a police officer told him,
``That is known as fag park so unless you are a fag you shouldn't
be up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Trout filed a complaint. But he didn't think police would follow
up, so he began to focus on having them handle such incidents with
more sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget Alex Trout,'' said Kansas City police Maj.
Anthony G. Ell, whom Trout called after the incident. ``I'll never
forget how passionate he is in his thoughts and ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Trout persuaded Ell to push for changing a police discrimination
policy so it would include gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Ell said he did not think the department had a problem with
homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``But because it is not specifically in our policy, that wasn't
the perception Alex was able to draw because everyone else was
covered but his group,'' Ell said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Office of Citizen Complaints finished its
investigation. The officer was disciplined for making the slur and
the office recommended sensitivity training to help police serve
gay and lesbian people, said I. Pearl Fain, director of the office.
</P>
<P>
   Trout, who calls himself a ``reluctant activist,'' is buoyed by
local departments' willingness to listen.
</P>
<P>
   And Boulden said HELIOS was a fitting tribute to Shepard, who
wanted to work on human-rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   Boulden is one of the last people who spoke with Shepard. The
two friends planned to see a movie to celebrate Boulden's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard canceled, saying he wanted to study at a bar students
used as a hangout.
</P>
<P>
   The next day Boulden was called by Shepard's parents, who were
living in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard had been found by bicyclists, his skull crushed, his
face pistol-whipped and his body left hanging like a scarecrow on a
wooden fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear was his murder wouldn't be reported for what it was, a
hate crime,'' Boulden said.
</P>
<P>
   Boulden thought the Laramie newspaper would downplay the story
to prevent bad publicity. Boulden and Trout called friends working
for larger Wyoming newspapers, urging them to cover the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing I knew, I was being contacted by The Washington
Post, The New York Times, `20//20,' everybody,'' Boulden said.
``Every time I would hang up the phone, it would ring again.''
</P>
<P>
   The story and its horrible details continued to spread. Two men
were convicted of Shepard's death after they lured him under the
pretense they were also gay.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard stayed alive, breathing with a respirator, for several
days. Reporters staked out the hospital. Boulden and Trout sneaked
up back staircases to visit their friend privately.
</P>
<P>
   They also began to lobby for increased acceptance of gay and
lesbian people, speaking on the steps of the nation's Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Gay and lesbian advocates credit outrage after Shepard's murder
with legislative efforts in 35 states to ensure homosexuals are
protected by hate- crime laws. Missouri is one of seven states
where the legislation passed. Kansas has no such laws.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Boulden nor Trout wanted to attend the trial. Boulden
had just finished the research for his social work dissertation,
``How Can You Be Gay and Live in Wyoming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After the murder, every time I picked it up to go through the
research, it had a completely different meaning,'' he said of the
doctoral work.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard had read through the interviews and encouraged Boulden
to study college-age people, too. Friends in St. Joseph encouraged
Boulden to move. He had a job at a local college, but a hiring
freeze thwarted the position.
</P>
<P>
   Trout tagged along, also needing a place to find solace from the
media attention in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised that it is not OK to cry,'' Trout said. ``So it
took me awhile to actually deal with the fact that he was dead.
Even to this day I don't know that I have come to terms with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
