<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1846 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-COURT-INTERPRETERS-KA     05-21 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-INTERPRETERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE SPEAKS MANY LANGUAGES _ WHICH CAN BE A CHALLENGE FOR
COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ The island of Pohnpei is a long way from Olathe.
Only about 33,000 people inhabit the speck of volcanic rock in the
Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, one of them ended up at the Johnson County
Courthouse in 1998 needing an English-Pohnpeian interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   The case illustrates the growing challenge for court officials
to provide _ and pay for _ translators for an increasingly diverse
immigrant population.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in Johnson County, court officials had to find
interpreters who spoke Arabic, Bengali, Cantonese, Farsi, German,
Hmong, Japanese, Korean, Laotian, Mandarin Chinese, Polish,
Punjabi, Russian, Serbian, Somali, Spanish, Thai, Tigrinya, Turkish
and Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   The court is required by law to provide interpreters for any
non-English-speaking person who requests it _ even if that person
speaks Pohnpeian. (It took several days and a long-distance
telephone link to California, but officials found their Pohnpeian
interpreter.)
</P>
<P>
   The county spent $82,200 last year to provide interpreter
services for court proceedings. That was up from $59,000 in 1998.
And so far this year, the county has spent 33 percent more than in
the same period last year, according to Cynthia Bricker, purchasing
coordinator in the court administrator's office.
</P>
<P>
   Once a minor chore, arranging for interpreters now takes up
about 20 percent, or one work day, of Bricker's time every week.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County, Mo., Circuit Court officials said they also had
seen an interpreter increase, but their costs were roughly the same
for 1998 and 1999. Jackson County spent $17,000 to $18,000 each of
the last two years, according to the court administrator's office.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County's costs may be lower than Johnson County's
because Jackson County pays interpreters only for the time they
work, not for the two or three hours the interpretation services
often set as their minimum charge. Jackson County also does not pay
for mileage and other expenses as Johnson County does.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Castillo is the dean of Johnson County court interpreters.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, of Overland Park, has worked for more than a decade in
the county's courts, as well as in federal and municipal courts.
The workload, he said, is now ``much, much, much more.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Yolanda Bustamante, also of Overland Park, provide the
bulk of Spanish interpretation services in Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   It takes more than just being able to speak two languages to be
a good interpreter, said Castillo, who grew up in New Mexico and
once worked in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people who claim to be bilingual are just semiliterate in
two languages,'' Castillo said.
</P>
<P>
   The job requires a thorough knowledge of courtroom procedures
and legal terminology.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante, a lawyer in her native Peru, said she once listened
to an interpreter explain a court diversion program by using a
Spanish word for ``party.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Castillo and Bustamante do when they meet new
clients is find out what country they are from and how much
schooling they have had. The interpreters adjust their language
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Many of their clients come from countries where there is extreme
mistrust and fear of the legal systems, Castillo said. When
attorneys explain to clients what options they have in the United
States, many ask the interpreters for their advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are surprised and have a hard time believing that they
have choices,'' Castillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante and Castillo said they could earn more providing
interpreting services in business, but courtroom work is
satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest service Bustamante has provided occurred
last year in the case of a man charged in several burglaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He swore from the beginning that he hadn't done anything,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Mendoza was on his way to prison until Bustamante was
asked to translate a video recording of another burglary suspect's
statement to police.
</P>
<P>
   She was struck by how similar the two cases were.
</P>
<P>
   of operation), the same area, the same time,'' she said. ``It
was eerie,'' she said. ]
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante talked to Mendoza's attorney the next day, and he
contacted prosecutors. Investigators then found the second man's
fingerprint at the scene of one of the break-ins that Mendoza was
accused of committing.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors dropped the charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bustamante, Kansas City resident Mira Mdivani is a lawyer
who branched out into court interpreting.
</P>
<P>
   She has seen a huge increase in calls for interpretation
services since starting her company, Vertex Corp., four years ago.
There has been a 30 percent increase in the past year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Johnson County, her company works in Jackson County,
Clay County, Mo., Franklin County, Kan., and in cities such as
Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Vertex often turns to colleges and universities to find
interpreters but maintains a group of regulars, she said.
</P>
<P>
   One man the company employs speaks five languages. At least
that's what Mdivani thought until Johnson County court officials
called looking for someone who could speak the east African
language of Tigrinya.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the man spoke six languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge was very happy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, a lawyer will subpoena one of her interpreters to
testify as a witness in a case. She fights such efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interpreters are impartial,'' she said. ``They don't take
sides, and they should not be used as witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Mdivani's company provides training, but there are no standards
or procedures concerning the qualifications or quality of
interpreters that the courts can rely on. That can be a problem
with languages for which the local pool of speakers is small.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Johnson County domestic violence case, the first
interpreter hired tried to talk the victim out of testifying. The
interpreter turned out to be a cousin of the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Bricker of the court administrator's office is doing research to
set up formal guidelines for the use of interpreters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ultimate goal is to establish a code of procedure and have
everybody follow the same rules,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
