Institute of Technology at the Old Westbury Campus in Long Island,
N.Y. Lazio hit the ground running Sunday, appearing on six
television talk shows, giving the commencement address at a Long
Island college and flying to four upstate cities to rally support
for his nascent Senate campaign. It was a whirlwind tour by a man
determined to overcome the biggest immediate obstacle in his quest
to beat Hillary Rodham Clinton: His own obscurity. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) FAIRFAX, Va. -- May 21, 2000 -- GORE-BIO-2 -- Though Vice
President Al Gore's political opponents have successfully portrayed
him as a pure-bred Washington creature, with only photo-op moments
in the heartland, he did have a life there, on the family farm, and
by all accounts a more intense emotional connection to that place
than to the nation's capital. Gore peers into a hiding place for
his toys under a stairway leading to the roof of the Fairfax Hotel
in Fairfax, Va., where the Gore's lived while in Washington and
where Gore spent much of his youth. (Stephen Crowley/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FAIRFAX, Va. -- May 21, 2000 -- GORE-BIO-1 -- Vice
President Al Gore's real childhood was in Tennessee; in Washington,
he spent his time with adults, important adults, in whose presence
he was expected to behave beautifully, and did. Tennessee was, at
the very least, where Gore wished he had grown up. Gore returned to
the Fairfax Hotel, where the Gores lived while in Washington, and
as a boy he would play pranks on guests, like dangling a toy duck
on a string from the roof. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOISE, Idaho -- May 21, 2000 -- SERVICE-PROVIDERS --
Brian Bertlin, right, information services director at Morrison
Knudsen, the large construction company, says using outside
providers has been an efficient way to handle e-mail and other
services for the company. Morrison Knudsen handed off operation of
its online travel booking a few months ago to Unisys and is about
to let Unisys take on the company's travel expense accounting
system. ``The aim,'' Bertlin says, ``is to reduce costs in areas
that do not directly generate revenues for the company.'' (Glen
Oakley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 21, 2000 -- BOOK-DEAL-MEDIA -- Mary
Higgins Clark, 72, the blockbuster mystery writer, signed a
five-book, 64 million dollar contract in April. At five books for a
total advance of $64 million, the contract made her the
highest-paid female author in the world, per book, according to
most industry estimates. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
