<P>
   (NYT19) LEOGANE, Haiti -- May 21, 2000 -- HAITI-ELECTION-4 --
Braving threats of violence, Haitians lined up by the thousands
Sunday for a vote to restore democracy and in the process free a
half-billion dollars in desperately needed foreign aid. An election
moderator counts blank ballots in a polling station in Leogane,
Haiti, approximately 20 miles south of Port-Au-Prince, Sunday.
(Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NANCOLIN, Haiti -- May 21, 2000 -- HAITI-ELECTION-3 --
Overcoming fears of violence, Haitians crowded into chaotic polling
places Sunday to elect thousands of legislators and local officials
with the hope that their country would finally escape its political
paralysis of the past three years. The vote had been postponed
three times since its original November date because of political
fights and logistical setbacks. Haitians wait in line to cast their
ballots in Nancolin, Haiti. (Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NANCOLIN, Haiti -- May 21, 2000 -- HAITI-ELECTION-2 --
Haitians' strong determination to vote, not seen since 1990
elections brought Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power in Haiti's first
democratic vote, were frustrated by hours-long delays throughout
the country on Sunday for a vote to restore democracy and in the
process free a half-billion dollars in desperately needed foreign
aid. The elections would restore a working legislature after
President Rene Preval disbanded Parliament in 1999 and appointed a
new premier by decree. Haitian citizens wait, identification in
hand, to cast their vote in Nancolin, Haiti, Sunday. (Jonathan
Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- May 21, 2000 --
HAITI-ELECTION-1 -- Braving threats of violence, Haitians lined up
by the thousands Sunday for a vote to restore democracy and in the
process free a half-billion dollars in desperately needed foreign
aid. The Haitians' strong determination to vote, not seen since
1990 elections brought Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power in Haiti's
first democratic vote, were frustrated by hours-long delays. A
elderly man on crutches makes his way to a polling station in
Port-Au-Prince, Haiti, Sunday. (Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MIAMI -- May 21, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-6 -- As the New
York Knicks begin to celebrate yet another victory over the Miami
Heat, 83-82 on Sunday, the Heat's Alonzo Mourning must begin to
wonder what if anything his team must do to defeat New York in the
playoffs. The Knicks knocked the Heat out of the playoffs for the
third straight season. The victory sends the Knicks into the
Eastern Conference finals against the Indiana Pacers. Game 1 is
Tuesday night in Indianapolis. (Barton Silverman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MIAMI -- May 21, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-5 -- The New
York Knicks Latrell Sprewell grabs a rebound that the Miami Heat's
Clarence Weatherspoon put up for a 12-footer, as referee Bennett
Salvatore, right, stops the clock with 2.1 seconds left after
ruling that Sprewell had called a timeout. The Knicks went on to
defeat the Heat 83-82, Sunday. The Heat argued that Sprewell never
signaled for a timeout, an argument apparently backed up by
television replays although a player doesn't have to signal with
his hands to get a timeout. (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MIAMI -- May 21, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-4 -- The Miami
