<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-595&AMP;ADD-N     05-21 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR WANTS TO OFFER SYMPATHY TO SLAIN MAN'S FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who upon ending his campaign
for the U.S. Senate intimated that he would work to improve his
relationship with minority residents, said in an interview
broadcast Sunday that he had ``sympathy, concern and compassion''
for the family of a Haitian-American man killed by the police in
March.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor made the remarks on Saturday in an intensely personal
interview with Tim Russert for broadcast Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the
Press.'' Giuliani also said he had no regrets about his decision to
drop out of the Senate race, given that he now realized politics
was ``not the most important thing in life.''
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour interview touched on a broad range of topics, from
Giuliani's thoughts about his political future to his prostate
cancer and what he acknowledged might have been bad advice that his
father once offered him, suggesting that it was more important to
be respected than to be loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, fathers make mistakes and fathers are human beings,
and I tend to think now that love is more important than I
thought,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani first acknowledged on Thursday that he did not respond
properly to the fatal shooting in March of Patrick Dorismond, the
Haitian-American man, by a plainclothes police officer who had
tried to solicit marijuana from him. Dorismond, a security guard
who was standing outside a midtown bar, was unarmed and was not
carrying drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said in the ``Meet the Press'' interview that he
intended ``to find a way'' to let Dorismond's family know about his
regrets, including possibly a visit to his parents. But the mayor
again defended his decision on the day of Dorismond's shooting to
release his juvenile arrest record.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I should have done is to do a lot more to express
sympathy, concern, help, assistance, compassion for a situation
where, whether justified or unjustified, whatever it turns out, was
still a tragic situation,'' the mayor said. ``I think that is where
I made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also spoke at length with Russert about his desire,
first expressed on Friday, to try to extend the benefits of New
York City's current economic boom to more disaffected communities
in the city. The mayor said he had not yet decided how he would do
that, but he said he was committed to finding a way ``to break down
the barriers that I've created'' as a result of his own sometimes
abrasive personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people in the city who feel that they haven't been
reached,'' by the progress in the city in recent years, the mayor
said. ``There are people that feel that I don't care about them,
there are people who feel that I don't take them into equal
consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside predominantly African-American churches in Harlem and
Queens on Sunday, city residents said they would be watching the
mayor to see if he lived up to his vows. Many said they were
skeptical that the mayor, who has been criticized for increasing
tension between the city authorities and New York's ethnic
communities, would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it is like a leopard changing his spots,'' said
Douglas K. Henderson, 65, outside the Abyssinian Baptist Church in
Harlem. ``It has got to be some sort of a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Many said they wanted to see him talk with black leaders like
the Rev. Al Sharpton and visit in black neighborhoods, and then act
on what he has heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to lend people of color an ear,'' said Sharon
McClarty, 44, a computer technician from Queens. ``He has been
talking, but he doesn't listen.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Andrea Summers, a mother of two who said she was cut from the
welfare rolls as part of the mayor's workfare program, said the
mayor needed to soften his harsh stance on welfare. She said she
worked at two jobs but could not earn enough to pay the rising
rents in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   She dismissed the mayor's comments about breaking down barriers.
``He never comes to our parades, never comes meet the people, he is
never here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As the mayor's remarks were televised Sunday, founders of the
group 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who Care challenged him to
compensate the Dorismond family by settling a lawsuit that it has
filed against the city.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond's parents, Marie and Andre Dorismond, could not be
reached for comment Sunday. But on Saturday, Dorismond's father
dismissed the mayor's recent offers of sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it doesn't make sense for him to apologize,'' he said.
``It's been two months since my son died. It's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   During the ``Meet the Press'' interview, the mayor, who said he
was still struggling to decide on which cancer treatment to choose,
appeared relaxed, laughing and joking with Russert at times, even
offering him one of his trademark Godfather impersonations.
</P>
<P>
   He called the decision to drop out of the Senate race the most
difficult of his life, a choice he said he made entirely because of
his cancer and not because of the controversy surrounding his
recently revealed relationship with an East Side woman, Judith
Nathan, and his decision last week to separate from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for the cancer and the timing of the cancer, I would have
gone ahead and done it,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, 55, who has 18 months left in office, deferred
questions about his own political future, not indicating whether he
might make a run for governor or accept an appointment to the
cabinet of George W. Bush, if Bush wins his bid for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love politics,'' the mayor said. ``The thing I felt good
about as I made the decision'' to leave the Senate race is ``I
finally figured out that politics is not my life. My life is about
things that are closer to you and deeper than that.''
</P>
<P>
   And Giuliani said he had not yet decided what he would do with
the approximately $9 million in unspent campaign contributions he
had amassed, noting only that he intended to do as much as he could
to support Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to try to do everything I can to help'' Lazio in
his bid against Hillary Rodham Clinton, the mayor said, ``if it is
advertising, if it's an appearance, if it's figuring out how to
make sure they're able to raise money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
