<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SEARCH FOR SHORTSTOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE WERSTINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ With Gary DiSarcina out of the lineup with a
sore left shoulder and contemplating season-ending surgery, the
Angels are searching for a replacement at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Backup Benji Gil, who has started 31 games at short after
playing at Triple-A Calgary in the Florida Marlins' system last
year, seemed to be the logical choice, but he's struggled to say
the least.
</P>
<P>
   He is hitting just .224, but manager Mike Scioscia certainly
would be happy just to find a shortstop who is solid defensively.
However, Gil hasn't been that either.
</P>
<P>
   Gil's error Saturday, his team-leading ninth of the season, led
to four unearned runs in the top of the seventh inning in the
Halos' 8-7 come-from-behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   So, on Sunday, the Angels opted to give Keith Luuloa (pronounced
lew-oo-lo-uh) his first major-league start at shortstop. But
manager Mike Scioscia insisted the move was made to Gil a day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just to let Benji have a rest, give him a breather,''
Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Luuloa, who made his first big-league appearance Wednesday as a
pinch runner in the eighth inning and finished the game, sees this
as a solid chance to establish himself in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I'm here as a utility infielder, a backup... until
Mike feels I can play two-three times a week,'' Luuloa said. ``I
understand that. My day will come.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Honolulu, Luuloa, who was challenged just three
times in the field and went hitless - if not for a diving grab by
Royals third baseman Joe Randa, is one of three Hawaiian-born
players currently in the major leagues, the others being the
Dodgers' Onan Masaoka and the Mets' Benny Agbayani.
</P>
<P>
   Line Drives
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson's third-inning grand slam was the sixth in the
majors Sunday, setting a new MLB record. ... As expected, reliever
Mark Petkovsek was not in uniform Sunday, still recuperating from a
fever caused by a viral illness. ... Sunday's pregame festivities
were highlighted by the annual Little League Parade. Nearly 12,000
youth baseball players took part in the march that last almost an
hour. ... The Angels' next home game begins interleague play, when
the Dodgers come to Edison Field on June 2 to open a three-game
series. The San Francisco Giants are in town the for three games
June 5-7 before the Halos get back to the American League. ...
Three years ago Sunday, the Angels set a record, scoring a
club-high 18 runs at home in an 18-3 victory over the Seattle
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Advance Box
</P>
<P>
   Monday: idle
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday at Minnesota, 4 :05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Schoeneweis (4-2, 5.46) vs. Joe Mays (1-5, 5.14)
</P>
<P>
   TV: None.......Radio: KLAC/570, XPRS/1090
</P>
