<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREFEARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF CASH HIKES FIRE
 RISK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY MARK SHAFFER 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Flagstaff, Ariz.) _ In U.S. Forest Service vernacular, they're
called doghair thickets _ spindly, sickly looking pine trees, dark
gray, only 6 inches or less in diameter yet grow up to 20 feet
tall.
</P>
<P>
   Left to their own devices, as many as 2,000 of them can grow per
acre. Timber cutters say they aren't mar ketable enough to cut.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of providing shelter for some wildlife, the only notable
role the trees play is serving as fuel in forest fires, dangerous
match sticks that burn bottom up and tag bigger trees, generating
crown fires the likes of which roared into Los Alamos this month.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with drought conditions, the thickets turn forests into
catas trophes-in-wait-of-ignition. This has forest and park service
officials in Arizona fretting.
</P>
<P>
   A group of area fire agencies re leased a report in late March
in which they concluded that about 40,000 acres of the dense
ponderosa pine forest around Flagstaff and about half of the 60,000
people living within city limits are at high risk from catastrophic
wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   The Ponderosa Fire Advisory Coun cil and Grand Canyon Forest
Part nership also said that legal maneuvers by environmental groups
and shortages of money for the Forest Service for tree thinning and
controlled burns had allowed only 3 percent of that area to receive
fire-protection measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Pinetop-Lakeside and Show Low areas are almost as
vulnerable, said Ed Collins, district ranger for the Lakeside area
of Apache-Sit greaves National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said tree thinning had been done in only 20 percent of
the district's 115,000 acres and that the only industry in the area
that cut the smaller trees _ a pulp and paper mill in Snowflake _
got out of that business last year. Timber cutting has pretty much
disappeared from the state's public lands because of legal action
by environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly critical is a 15,000-acre area southwest of Show
Low, from where the prevailing winds blow in the spring and summer.
That part of the forest has had very little treat ment against
fires and funding limi tations have turned it into a project that
will last 10 years, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the state, park and forest service officials are in a
state of alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire conditions this year are as tough as we have ever
seen,'' said Rod Hoibakk, fire manager of Pres cott National
Forest. ``The bulk of the chaparral in tinderboxes like Hassayampa
Canyon hasn't burned in 70 years. The only question is when it's
going to go off.''
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service workers have been using a machine to cut and
grind the manzanita and chaparral near Pres cott subdivisions in an
effort to carve a mile-wide fire break between trees and the
thousands of homes on the south and east sides of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The state also has taken note.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull declared a ``wildfire emergency'' in Arizona on
Thursday, freeing up $3 million in state money to fight and prevent
wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's forests haven't always been so susceptible to
undergrowth such as doghair thickets.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1800s, the state's high country had open ponderosa
pine forests with few trees and large spreads of grass in between.
In those days, fires seldom burned more than ground cover.
</P>
<P>
   But increasing herds of cattle did a number on the grass. Then,
during a five-year period about the time of World War I, a
combination of wet years and abnormally high seed production by the
trees led to dense stands of small pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   That, plus the federal government's policy of immediately
suppressing all forest fires until the 1980s, led to the
proliferation of the thickets, so named because they are as thick
as dog's hair.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Farnsworth, fire management officer for the Coconino
National Forest in Flagstaff, knows more than he wants to about the
effects of doghair thickets.
</P>
<P>
   There was the ``Radio'' fire in 1977, which burned Mount Elden
to the nub. There were the ``Hochderffer'' and ``Horseshoe'' fires
four years ago that burned 25,000 acres of the west and north
flanks of the San Francisco Peaks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 10 largest fires in the Flagstaff area's history
all have occurred since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Farnsworth casts a wary eye to the forests south and west of
Flagstaff from where, as in Show Low, the winds blow at this time
of year.
</P>
<P>
   It's in these areas, near the caldera of Dry Lake, the U.S.
Naval Observa tory and Flagstaff's Arboretum, that Farnsworth has
funneled much of his $80,000 annual budget in thinning trees and
doing controlled burns on the likely route of any large fire that
would head toward Flagstaff. That kind of money doesn't buy much
these days, Farnsworth concedes, noting that he and his staff can
thin only about 500 acres and control burn about 3,000 acres
annually while tens of thousands of acres are at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Farnsworth stops his pickup at the base of A-1 Mountain, near
where a small fire 10 days before had almost taken off up the
mountain because of 60 mph winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all that junk in there,'' Farnsworth said, pointing
into the doghair thicket of hundreds of small pine trees curling
grotesquely toward the ground with dead pine needles and vegetation
about a foot thick on the ground. ``One lightning strike and,
whoosh, the fire would be out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the forest is in this condition, Farnsworth said, noting
the checkerboard ownership of the land among state, federal and
private entities. State lands tend to have worse conditions for
fire. With pri vate land, it depends on the owner, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But federal fire managers have their owns problems trying to do
con trolled burns.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said state agencies like the Department of Environmental
Qual ity and Game &AMP; Fish Department and federal agencies like the
Fish and Wildlife Service and Corps of Engi neers have control over
what he does because of clean air, endangered species and clean
water consider ations.
</P>
<P>
   And, because one of the best times to do controlled burns is in
the fall, after the summer monsoon rains, when temperature
inversions trap the smoke close to the ground, Collins said he
often runs afoul of DEQ.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few people call them and cough and I'm shut down,'' Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the only problem, Collins said. ``It's costing
upward of $600 an acre to do these treatments because of all the
trees,'' Collins said. ``There's not enough money in Fort Knox to
do what we should do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
