<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-21 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1863 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-PRIESTS-RECRUIT-ART-2     05-21 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIESTS-RECRUIT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: second language. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In such an atmosphere, even Walsh wonders why Bridgeport is
succeeding where others are struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the newer priests or those soon to be ordained chose the
Bridgeport diocese because it was their home. But others selected
Bridgeport from a number they had considered, attracted by Egan's
reputation for orthodoxy and for fostering an esprit de corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the diocese or priests in the diocese are being
hypercritical, or saying Rome is way off base, that doesn't attract
young men,'' Walsh said. ``You aren't going to get young men to
give their lives to an institution if you're criticizing that
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Bridgeport diocese, like New York's, is home to a
large number of Hispanics, none of the young men graduating from
the seminary this year are Hispanic. ``It's sort of a fluke this
year,'' said Walsh, noting that five of the 30 seminarians
considering the priesthood at St. John Fisher are Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who are joining the Bridgeport diocese are Robert
Kinnally, the 39-year-old dean of admissions and financial aid at
Stanford University, who will enter St. John Fisher this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas W. Powers, 35, the priest at St. Theresa's in
Trumbull, Conn., left a promising job at a global consulting firm
to join Egan's diocese.
</P>
<P>
   Powers calls Egan ``an impressive man, the kind of guy you want
to follow,'' and he does so with an absence of reservations that
can be striking in an age of skepticism. ``I trust him,'' Powers
said. ``He's been a spiritual father to me. He inspires me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do God's will by obeying my bishop.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining the diocese not only meant giving up a successful job
but, in a sense, erasing his ego so his sense of God could take
over, Powers said. ``We really must die to ourselves,'' he said.
``He must increase, while I must decrease.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers said he was drawn to Egan's ``orthodoxy'' and
``holiness.'' Staunchly anti-abortion, Powers sometimes prays the
rosary outside abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnally, an organist who once worked as musical director of St.
Augustine's Cathedral in Bridgeport, said Walsh's encouragement
played an important role in his decision to return to the diocese.
He also considered applying to the diocese in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an openness to guys like me who are coming at this a
little later, and the sense that what we bring to it can enrich the
priesthood,'' Kinnally said. ``Bridgeport is doing so well. The
simple way to say it is, they're doing something right.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pavia's case, the diocese tackled his misgivings head on. It
even allowed him to keep his full-time job as a mechanic in the
maintenance department of Stamford Hospital while he attended St.
John Fisher, until he was sure about committing to the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   While priests ordained in the 1960s and '70s generally do not
describe the ritual of their ordination as something they gave much
thought to beforehand, seeing it mostly as a necessary step to
becoming the spiritual shepherd of Catholics, Pavia is awed by the
moment he will deliver his personal will to the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holy Spirit at that time is coming over you,'' Pavia said.
``Everyone, from saints in heaven to the people in the pews, are
praying for you. My life is now totally in God's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   As a newspaper boy long ago, Pavia would get so wrapped up
talking to his customers that he sometimes forgot to collect their
money. Now, he sees the essence of his new life in the Masses,
baptisms and confessions ahead. He envisions going door to door
once again, visiting nursing homes and hospitals, seeing to the
needs of his parishioners with Bible in hand. The impulse to do for
others, he said, will probably never leave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the calling and we all have it,'' he said. ``We
just respond to it in different ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
