<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA SCHOOLS CHIEF SUPPORTS STATE MONITOR FOR L.A. DISTRICT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID R. BAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 EDITORS: Staff Writer Rick Orlov contributed to this story.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Even as Los Angeles Unified moves forward with
reforms and choosing a new superintendent, momentum is building in
Sacramento for state intervention in the long-troubled school
district.
</P>
<P>
   The latest to join the movement is Delaine Eastin, state
superintendent of public instruction. In an interview, Eastin
backed a bill by state Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles, that
would appoint a watchdog over the Los Angeles Unified School
District and break up the district if student achievement doesn't
improve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Eastin said the first step to reforming the district should
be assigning someone to assess its status now and track its future
progress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``It's a great help to know where all the bodies are
buried,'' said Eastin, who under Polanco's bill would appoint the
watchdog. ``We don't want the district to go further downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Sacramento's sudden willingness to dive into the district's
affairs has alarmed Los Angeles school board members. They have
spent the last year making sweeping changes that they say should,
given time, turn the ailing district around.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For interim Superintendent Ramon Cortines, the state's rush to
get involved ignores the work he and the board have done. He was
hired by the board in late fall to implement reforms and will leave
office next month after a new superintendent is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``It's like I didn't need to come,'' he said. ``You want a
district to take corrective action, and the district does that, and
then you want to penalize them?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Mayor Richard Riordan said through a spokesman that he
continues to have confidence in the school board majority he helped
elect.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The mayor has indicated the legislation could be improved,
and he wants to work with Sen. Polanco on it,'' spokesman Peter
Hidalgo said. ``The mayor has been encouraged with the LAUSD's
reform Board of Education and Superintendent Cortines, who are
working to enact purposeful changes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But legislators say they've heard Los Angeles beg before for
more time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``At some point, there comes a time when you have to say we
can't wait any longer; we have to step in,'' said state Sen.
Deirdre ``Dede'' Alpert, D-San Diego, who chairs the Senate's
Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Alpert's committee is scheduled to vote on a heavily amended
version of Polanco's bill this week. The changes in large part
reflect the current mood in Sacramento toward Los Angeles Unified.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  While many legislators want to give the state greater
oversight, few want to take the next step of making day-to-day
decisions for the immense district. Accordingly, Polanco has
removed language that would have given the watchdog or monitor veto
power over Los Angeles Unified's administrative or policy
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  And while the idea of dismantling the district has gained
ground in Sacramento, many legislators want to wait several years
to see whether the changes wrought by Cortines and the board can
boost student achievement. The current version of Polanco's bill
calls for breaking up the district if it doesn't substantially
raise test scores and make other improvements in the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``I don't want to doom those efforts to failure before they
really get going,'' said Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, one
of the district's toughest critics. ``Setting a definite time line
is what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Nor is Polanco's bill the only effort by state lawmakers to
involve themselves in Los Angeles Unified's fate. State Sen. Martha
Escutia, D-Montebello, has a bill that calls for a study of
removing several southeastern Los Angeles County cities, including
Bell and Cudahy, from the massive district.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Some school board members question why lawmakers have chosen
to jump into the fray now. Where were they two or three years ago,
the board members said, when previous district officials often
dismissed suggestions that their low-scoring, overcrowded school
system had serious problems?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; And even if the monitor doesn't obtain veto power, many Los
Angeles Unified officials fear the end result will be the same: a
shadow superintendent operating hundreds of miles from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``This is a move away from local control,'' board member
Caprice Young said. ``This is just more bureaucracy and, after a
while, the bureaucracy becomes stifling.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Eastin and many legislators disagree with Young. Eastin added
that Cortines would make an excellent monitor were he interested in
the job. Cortines said he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  While remaining neutral on the move to break up Los Angeles
Unified, Eastin said she doubts it would work. Schools in some
parts of the district are so overcrowded that they must send their
students to distant neighborhoods to find room for them. Breaking
the district into smaller pieces might make that impossible, Eastin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could build some nice new schools in Pacoima or Pico
Union (heavily populated areas in the San Fernando Valley and
downtown, respectively), you could make the case that the district
could be broken up,'' she said. ``Otherwise, it would be a civil
rights disaster, and I think it would lose in court.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-00 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
