<HEADLINE>
ROYALS END ANGELS' WIN STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE WERSTINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ With their starting pitching depleted due to
injuries and having taxed the bullpen rather heavily because of it,
the Angels were hoping Kent Bottenfield would carry them deep into
the game Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't happen as the Kansas City Royals battered
Bottenfield around early and often to beat the Angels, 10-6, and
put an end to their season-best three-game winning streak at Edison
Field before a crowd of 28,052.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels (22-22), who finished a 12-game homestand - their
longest of the year - with a 6-6 mark, are idle today before
beginning a 10-day, nine-game trip that starts in Minnesota on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking all things into consideration, like our starting
pitching situation (Jason Dickson, Tim Belcher, Ken Hill and Kent
Mercker all on the disabled list), and looking back, things could
have been much worse,'' said Anaheim manager Mike Scioscia, whose
starters were 1-5 during the homestand while the bullpen went 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other side of it, you are looking to make up some
ground (in the standings),'' Scioscia added. ``But we are still
there ... a couple of games off the pace.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first career start against the Royals (22-21),
Bottenfield, who has pitched six-plus innings in each of his
previous six outings, could only carry the Angels 4 1/3 innings
while getting pounded for nine runs on 10 hits, including three
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like Bottenfield was a pitch short in every situation
where he allowed runs.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, he retired the first two batters but gave
up a double to Mike Sweeney and a run-scoring single by Mark Quinn
on two-strike counts. Carlos Beltrans homer leading off the second
came on a full count, and Joe Randa's took a 2-2 offering and
smacked a three-run homer in the third inning to make it 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't have good command today,'' Scioscia said. ``He
left the door open and they took advantage of his mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind back-to-back homers by Garret Anderson, who slugged his
fourth career grand slam, and Troy Glaus off Kansas City starter
Chris Fussell, the Angels tied the score at 5-5 in the bottom of
the third, giving them - and Bottenfield - new life.
</P>
<P>
   But it was shortlived, as the Royals, who gave up a
fourth-inning run to the Angels on Mo Vaughn's RBI single off K.C.
reliever Jason Rakers, came back to score two runs in the fourth
and two more in the fifth, on David McCarty's homer, to take a 9-6
lead and chase Bottenfield (3-5).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bad game,'' Bottenfield said of his
second-shortest start of the season. ``I made more mistakes than
good pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels reliever Mike Fyhrie, who allowed just one hit in 1 2/3
innings of work, closed out the fifth inning without any further
damage and got the Royals in order in the sixth, the first time
Kansas City failed to put up at least one run.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Weaver followed with a 1-2-3 seventh inning, before working
out of danger in the eighth to keep the Angels within striking
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never think we are out of it,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   But their would be no Angels come-from-behind victory this time.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, who have won their last six games via the comeback,
were ineffective against K.C. reliever Jose Santiago (4-1), who
worked the final three innings to earn the victory and kept Anaheim
without a hit after Vaughn's single in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, who put runners on first and second against Brett
Hinchliffe, added an insurance run on McCarty's single off of Mike
Holtz in the ninth inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
